SUP0506.Description: The catalog file in the selected repository is corrupt or compressed in an unsupported format.
SUP0506.Resolution: Select a repository with a valid catalog file, and retry the operation.
SUP0506.Message: Unable to decompress the catalog file.

TMP0106.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0106.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

STOR312.Description: The firmware package being used to update the physical disk drive is not valid for the drive model identified in the message. The firmware package contains the drive component id in the list of supported drives, but the firmware image is not valid for the drive model identified in the message.
STOR312.Resolution: Acquire the correct firmware image file for the drive model identified in the message, and then retry the operation. The correct image file can be found by using the drive model information and searching the support site for related firmware.
STOR312.Message: Unable to update the firmware of the physical disk drive %1 because an incorrect firmware image file is used.

SYS190.Description: The OS-related data cannot be collected because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installed on the server does not support this feature on the version of Operating System installed.
SYS190.Resolution: Install a iDRAC Service Module (ISM) supported OS, and then retry the operation.
SYS190.Message: Unable to collect the operating system (OS)-related data because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) installed on the server does not support this feature on the version of Operating System installed.

CMC8603.Description: CMC cannot read the information about the FRU, because of an internal issue with the CMC and the server. Some information such as model number may not be reported. The server may not power up if the server planar FRU cannot be read.
CMC8603.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the server. The Chassis Management Controller will retry the read operation of the FRU information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8603.Message: Unable to read the FRU information from the server %1, status %2.

AMP0312.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0312.Message: System level current is less than the lower warning threshold.

SWC8612.Description: The profile identified in the message does not contain boot device information in a usable format.
SWC8612.Resolution: Recreate the profile identified in the message or use a different profile.
SWC8612.Message: Unable to fully extract boot device information from profile: %1.

RAC0153.Description: Power redundancy is typically used to protect equipment from unexpected power disruption that could cause data loss or hardware damage.
RAC0153.Resolution: It is recommended to use power redundancy
RAC0153.Message: Non-redundant power mode: Check the system hardware manual for implications.

CMC8527.Description: CMC is unable to obtain the memory information from the server specified in the message. This occurs if there is no communication between CMC and iDRAC.
CMC8527.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC. 2) Reset CMC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8527.Message: Unable to retrieve the server-%1 memory information.

SWC0129.Description: Racadm tool was not able to send a test email for the configuration.
SWC0129.Resolution: Check for the parameters mentioned in the message.
SWC0129.Message: Unable to send test email. Please make sure that your email alerts have been configured correctly and connectivity to the SMTP server exists.

UEFI0146.Description: Unable to verify the chassis type via iDRAC and CMC. System configuration may be incorrect as a result.
UEFI0146.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware and then restart the system. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0146.Message: Unable to verify the chassis type via iDRAC and CMC. System configuration may be incorrect as a result.

RAC0694.Description: Unable to configure the attributes of the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0694.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0694.Message: Unable to configure the attributes of the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

PSU0912.Description: Status from the power supply indicates a power supply exception occurred. The power supply will try to operate in a degraded state. System Performance and power redundancy may be degraded or lost.
PSU0912.Resolution: Check input power. Re-install the power supply. If problem persists contact support.
PSU0912.Message: A failure detected on power unit %1.

SWC0042.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation.
SWC0042.Resolution: Exit the Import Server Profile wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0042.Message: Unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation.

SWC0070.Description: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully copied to the USB drive.
SWC0070.Message: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully copied to the USB drive.

PWR8544.Description: Insufficient power is available for the server identified in the message to function. The server will be turned off until there is sufficient power available.
PWR8544.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis.
PWR8544.Message: Chassis Management Controller turned off the Server %1 because of insufficient power at inventory.

CMC8566.Description: The KVM mapping is disabled for the server slot specified in the message. The KVM cannot be mapped to this server slot.
CMC8566.Message: KVM mapping is disabled for the server slot %1.

RED010.Resolution: Correct the target information and retry the operation.

CPU0802.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0802.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0802.Message: A predictive failure detected on CPU %1 voltage regulator module.

RAC0708.Description: Previous reboot was due to a firmware watchdog timeout.
RAC0708.Message: Previous reboot was due to a firmware watchdog timeout.

VFL0007.Description: The operations could not be completed because a vFlash SD Card is not detected.
VFL0007.Resolution: Confirm an SD Card is present in the vFlash SD Card reader slot. Otherwise, insert an SD Card and retry the operation.
VFL0007.Message: No vFlash SD card is present.

LC034.Description: The As-Shipped from the factory Hardware Inventory information is not present on the system.
LC034.Message: Unable to retrieve As-Shipped Hardware Inventory from the system.

CMC8526.Description: CMC is unable to obtain the CPU information from the server specified in the message. This occurs if there is no communication between CMC and iDRAC.
CMC8526.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC. 2) Reset CMC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8526.Message: Unable to retrieve the server-%1 CPU information.

FAN0012.Description: The device is not performing optimally. The device may be installed improperly.
FAN0012.Resolution: Remove and re-install the device at the next scheduled service. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0012.Message: %1 RPM is less than the lower warning threshold.

PWR8564.Description: The server identified in the message was not turned on because the available power is less than the requested power.
PWR8564.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller web interface to check the System Input Max Power Capacity Power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, retry the operation. Otherwise, increase the System Input Power Cap value.
PWR8564.Message: Unable to turn on the Server %1 because the power request exceeded the System Input Power Cap.

UEFI0264.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot because the iSCSI initiator name is invalid.
UEFI0264.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the iSCSI Initiator Name field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0264.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot because the iSCSI initiator name is invalid.

SYS073.Description: The import of system configuration XML file operation completed with errors because the Lifecycle Controller State was disabled in the input XML. Configuration changes requiring a system reboot were not applied.
SYS073.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller State setting and retry the operation.
SYS073.Message: Unable to apply changes that require system reboot because the Lifecycle Controller State setting is disabled in the configuration XML.

SWC8606.Description: The server identified in the message never reported that remote services were ready.
SWC8606.Resolution: Make sure that the iDRAC on the server identified in the message is operating properly and that Lifecycle Controller is enabled, then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform a virtual reseat of the server and retry the operation. The server can be virtually reseated by using the CMC Web UI interface and selecting Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components and then select Virtual Reseat from the drop down operation for the server identified in the message.
SWC8606.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Timeout exceeded while waiting for remote services ready on Server %1.

JCP027.Description: An install or configuration job is successfully created on iDRAC.

RAC006.Description: The attribute value cannot be changed because it is of read-only type.
RAC006.Message: The attribute value cannot be changed because it is of read-only type.

SYS1003.Description: System is performing a CPU reset because of system power off, power on or a warm reset like CTRL-ALT-DEL.

CPU0817.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is operating normally.

BAR048.Description: The server motherboard does not have a Service Tag assigned, the operation cannot continue.
BAR048.Resolution: Perform a System Profile import from a previous backup file. If no backup file is available, contact your service provider.

UEFI0175.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.
UEFI0175.Resolution: Quad Rank and Octal Rank DIMM modules cannot be mixed on a channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0175.Message: A Octal Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Quad Rank DIMM module.

HWC4013.Resolution: Check presence, re-install or reconnect, then re-attempt the update. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC4013.Message: Hardware unsuccessfully updated for embedded NIC.

OSD10.Description: Installation for the selected operating system is not supported. Make sure that the correct operating system name was entered.
OSD10.Resolution: Recheck the operating system name with the output of GetDriverPackInfo().
OSD10.Message: Installation not supported for the selected operating system.

SEL1507.Message: Communications restored with Chassis Group Member %1.

MEM1209.Message: Memory spare redundancy is degraded. Check memory device at location %1.

RAC977.Description: The configuration XML file import operation was initiated.
RAC977.Resolution: Use the racadm jobqueue view i <Job ID> command to view the status of the operation.
RAC977.Message: Import configuration XML file operation initiated.

BIOS008.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. To create a configuration job, at least one attribute should be changed.
BIOS008.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes and then create a configuration job.
BIOS008.Message: No pending data present to create a Configuration job

USR0023.Description: The user privilege is invalid. This may be due to invalid combinations of privileges given to the user.
USR0023.Resolution: Request the administrator to assign appropriate user privileges to the specific user.
USR0023.Message: The current user privilege is not valid.

SWC0055.Description: Unable to load the View Current Version page due to an internal error.
SWC0055.Resolution: Retry the operation. If problem persists, update the iDRAC firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
SWC0055.Message: Unable to load the View Current Version page.

PR12.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference and would apply firmware. However, user settings indicate that Part Replacement should perform the upgrade only and not a downgrade to an earlier firmware version.
PR12.Message: Firmware update setting allows version upgrade only and will not be performed.

UEFI0156.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license in three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor and the Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup options are being reverted to default because of the absent license.
UEFI0156.Resolution: If the absence of license is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0156.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license in three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor and the Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup options are being reverted to default because of the absent license.

RED073.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the parameter identified in the message.
RED073.Resolution: Verify the value for the parameter identified in the message is valid and retry the operation.
RED073.Message: The input value entered for the parameter %1 is invalid.

PWR8523.Description: The chassis power cycle operation was completed.

RAC941.Description: A system configuration profile export operation may take several minutes to complete depending on the system configuration.
RAC941.Resolution: Monitor the job status using "racadm jobqueue view -i <Job ID>".
RAC941.Message: Successfully initiated the export operation. This operation may take several minutes to complete.

IOV005.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is not ready to run commands because the chassis must be turned on.
IOV005.Resolution: Turn on chassis and retry the command.
IOV005.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is not ready to run commands.

VDR3.Description: Data redundancy has been restored to a virtual disk that previously suffered a loss of redundancy.
VDR3.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SUP022.Description: JobStore file has exceeded the size limit. Delete all unneeded JobIDs from the job store.
SUP022.Resolution: New JobId cannot be stored. Manually delete the failed jobs and retry the operation.
SUP022.Message: Job store has reached the maximum storage limit.

PSU8510.Description: The firmware for the PSU identified in the message is successfully updated to the version displayed in the message
PSU8510.Message: PSU in slot %1 FW updated successfully to version %2

MEM1010.Message: Memory device at location %1 is off-duty.

VF041.Description: The remote share could not be mounted.
VF041.Resolution: Try the operation again. If this problem persists, check your login credentials and network.

RAC0236.Description: vFlash image upload failed because the image is not valid.
RAC0236.Resolution: Image may be corrupt. Try uploading a valid vFlash image.

RAC0272.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0272.Resolution: Disable NIC only if remote access is undesired.
RAC0272.Message: Disabling NIC will prevent the user from accessing the iDRAC remotely through Web GUI, Remote Racadm, Ssh, and Telnet. Local Racadm and serial interface will continue to work.

SWC8537.Description: The add key operation did not complete successfully for the slot identified in the message due to the key being too long.
SWC8537.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8537.Message: Unable to add key for slot %1 of service account, due to the key being too long.

SWU8538.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation was not successful.
SWU8538.Resolution: Retry the Update operation. If the issue persists, reinsert the iKVM and retry the operation.
SWU8538.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware. Reason = 0x%1.

JCP023.Description: One of the job ID values specified as input to the operation is a duplicate. The duplicated Job ID is indicated in the message.
JCP023.Resolution: Use the correct job ID and retry. Use the GetAllJobs method to retrieve all open jobs.

RAC967.Description: The configuration XML file can only be exported to a remote share while using Firmware RACADM.
RAC967.Resolution: When using Firmware RACADM, make sure to export the configuration XML file to a remote share only.
RAC967.Message: Exporting the configuration XML file to a local share is not supported when using Firmware RACADM.

CTL91.Description: The controller identified in the message is unable to communicate with its peer. This can be because of a cabling issue.
CTL91.Resolution: Check the cabling between the PERC cards and the expanders. If this does not resolve the issue then contact your service provider.
CTL91.Message: %1 is unable to communicate with its peer.

ISM0026.Description: The iDRAC Hard Reset operation is performed by system OS user identified in the message from the operating system (OS) on the day-date-time-year identified in the message.
ISM0026.Resolution: The iDRAC may take up to 2 minutes to fully restart. Wait until the iDRAC is fully restarted before performing further operations with the iDRAC.
ISM0026.Message: The iDRAC Hard Reset operation is performed by system OS user %1 from the operating system (OS) on %2.

PCI3001.Message: Device option ROM on embedded NIC was successfully updated.

OSD47.Description: Unable to access the network share using the credentials specified or the firewall might be enabled and is preventing access to the share.
OSD47.Resolution: Make sure that the firewall is disabled, and that the credentials (username, password) are correct.

SYS090.Description: The configuration XML Input file contains XML DOCTYPE tags which may contain injection security threats. The XML DOCTYPE tag is not supported in configuration XML files.
SYS090.Resolution: Check the input XML file for DOCTYPE XML tags and remove them before retrying the operation.
SYS090.Message: The configuration XML input file contains unsupported DOCTYPE tags.

LC008.Description: The parameter value is not supported.
LC008.Resolution: Confirm that the parameters provided are correct. For a list of parameters for this method refer to the Lifecycle Controller User Guide.

BAR012.Description: Lifecycle Controller data collection and export has failed.
BAR012.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Download and apply the Dell Update Package (DUP) for USC. 2) Run System Services to update the database if CSIOR is not enabled. 3) Reboot the system and retry. If the issue persists after performing these operations, download the Field Service Repair software and repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download and install all the DUPs for USC, diagnostics, driver packs, and device firmware of all the devices of the host system.
BAR012.Message: Unable to collect Lifecycle Controller data.

STOR051.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the specified StartingLBA and Size value combination is greater than allowed by the physical disk size.
STOR051.Resolution: Specify the Size value only and allow the instrumentation to calculate the StartingLBA value then retry the operation.
STOR051.Message: StartingLBA and Size value combination is greater than allowed by the physical disk size.

STOR2.Description: A SCSI device experienced an error, but may have recovered.

HWC1104.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message that is inserted in the slot identified in the message is not supported by the chassis or the current CMC firmware version.
HWC1104.Resolution: Make sure that the peripheral sled identified in the message is supported by the chassis and the CMC firmware. For information about the supported sleds and firmware versions, see the System Manual available at the support site.
HWC1104.Message: The %1 installed in slot %2 is not supported by the chassis.

PWR8669.Description: The server identified in the message could not be successfully turned on because of incompatibility between the chassis PCIe components and mezzanine card.
PWR8669.Resolution: Make sure that the chassis PCIe components and mezzanine card are compatible. For information about compatibility of hardware components, see the Modular System Chassis Hardware Manual available at the support site.
PWR8669.Message: Unable to turn on the server %1 because of an inconsistency between the chassis and server components.

CMC8543.Description: The CMC specified in the message has reset because of thermal issues.
CMC8543.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Review the Hardware Log and check if there are fans that are not functioning properly. 2) Replace the fans that are not functioning properly. 3) If all the fans are functioning, check the chassis temperature in the CMC Web Interface or by using RACADM. When the fans are functioning properly and the chassis temperature is too high, the ambient air temperature is too high or the air inlets are not receiving sufficient air.
CMC8543.Message: The CMC %1 has reset because the thermal threshold was exceeded.

TMP0107.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0107.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

CMC8542.Description: The CMC specified in the message was manually restarted.
CMC8542.Message: The CMC %1 was restarted because of a manual reset.

RAC0400.Description: iDRAC is running low on memory.

CTL97.Description: The controller identified in the message has been changed to a new personality mode (HBA or RAID).

RED012.Description: Unable to create a Lifecycle Controller update task. The related job status is marked Failed.
RED012.Resolution: Retry the update operation after one minute.
RED012.Message: Unable to create Lifecycle Controller update task.

LIC011.Description: License Manager does not allow the replacement of a non-evaluation license with an evaluation license.
LIC011.Resolution: To replace a non-evaluation license, first delete the non-evaluation license, then import the evaluation license.
LIC011.Message: A non-evaluation license cannot be replaced with an evaluation license.

RAC0718.Description: Remote File Share service is busy with the previous connection.
RAC0718.Resolution: Stop the Remote File Share session and retry the operation.
RAC0718.Message: Remote File Share service is busy with the previous connection.

PCI1306.Resolution: Reboot the system and update the component drivers.
PCI1306.Message: A software error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

PWR8545.Description: Incorrect power inventory information reported by the iDRAC for the server identified in the message.
PWR8545.Resolution: Invalid power inventory information could be due to outdated iDRAC firmware or server BIOS firmware versions. Update the components to their latest versions.
PWR8545.Message: Chassis Management Controller turned off the server %1 because of incorrect power data retrieved from iDRAC at inventory.

CTL2.Description: You have changed the controller rebuild rate. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SYS048.Description: The operation expected a valid XML that is compliant with the system configuration schema. However, the system configuration file does not contain valid XML content.
SYS048.Resolution: View the file in any Web browser to check for invalid characters. Remove the invalid characters and make sure that the file is a valid XML and is compliant with the system configuration schema published on delltechcenter.com/lc in the LC XML Schema Guide.
SYS048.Message: System configuration XML input file contains invalid characters, %1 at line %2.

LOG003.Description: The log entry with the specified InstanceID does not have any associated configuration results.
LOG003.Resolution: Verify the ConfigResults availability for the InstanceID through enumeration of the LogEntry class and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
LOG003.Message: ConfigResults not available for log entry specified.

RAC970.Description: The import operation cannot continue if the value specified for the end power state of the system option (-s) is incorrect. The supported values are "On" and "Off".
RAC970.Resolution: Make sure to specify either "On" or "Off" for the end power state (-s) option.
RAC970.Message: Incorrect value specified for the end power state option.

RAC0761.Description: The system inventory cannot be retrieved because the maximum number of inventory collections allowed is reached, or because of an internal issue where the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.
RAC0761.Resolution: The total number of hardware inventory instances might have exceeded the maximum limit. Wait for the operation to complete and retry the operation. If no other system inventory operation is in progress, enable the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature, restart the system, and then retry the operation.
RAC0761.Message: Unable to retrieve the system inventory because the maximum number of inventory collections allowed is reached, or because of an internal issue where the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

ISM0028.Description: The iDRAC Hard Reset operation cannot be performed either because of an unsupported CPLD firmware version or the iDRAC Hard reset feature is currently disabled on iDRAC.
ISM0028.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the CPLD vesion by using iDRAC graphical user inteface (GUI). 2) To enable the iDRAC Hard Reset feature by running RACADM command, enter the following at the command line interface (CLI): "racadm set idrac.servicemodule.idrachardreset enabled".
ISM0028.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC Hard Reset operation either because of an unsupported CPLD firmware version or the iDRAC Hard Reset feature is currently disabled on iDRAC.

CMC8561.Description: Unable to send the email alerts to the destination.
CMC8561.Resolution: Make sure to use a valid email address.
CMC8561.Message: Unable to send the email to %1 after trying %2 times.

PWR8554.Description: This situation occurs if the iDRAC is found to be turned off after power allocation information is sent by the CMC or if the communications between the CMC and iDRAC is non functional.
PWR8554.Resolution: Perform a Virtual Reseat of the component identified in the message. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components, and then select slot for the component identified in the message and apply the Virtual Reseat.
PWR8554.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to send power allocation information to %1-%2 at priority %3.

PDR20.Description: A disk has received a SMART alert (predictive failure) after a configuration change. The disk is likely to fail in the near future.
PDR20.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk will cause the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.

TMP0123.Message: The system inlet temperature is within range.

RED015.Description: The download protocol specified is not supported.
RED015.Resolution: The supported protocols include NFS, CIFS, HTTP, FTP, TFTP
RED015.Message: The download protocol specified is not supported.

SWC8525.Description: Unable to add member because the maximum number of Chassis Group members indicated in the message has been reached.
SWC8525.Resolution: Try removing an existing member and retry the operation.
SWC8525.Message: Unable to add member to Chassis Group. Maximum members supported is %1.

LC064.Description: The maximum number of characters allowed for the parameter is displayed.
LC064.Resolution: Reduce the number of characters to the maximum length allowed for this parameter.
LC064.Message: The value exceeds the maximum length of %1 characters for %2.

CPU0004.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is inserted correctly, if the processor is removable.3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

OSD38.Description: There was an error while copying the ISO from the network share.
OSD38.Resolution: 1) Make sure the network connection is functional. 2) Make sure the Dell VFlash doesn't have hardware issues by accessing it through the iDRAC GUI.
OSD38.Message: Copying the ISO image from the network failed.

CPUA0023.Resolution: Verify processor installation. If present, reseat the processor.

UEFI0176.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slots.
UEFI0176.Resolution: Only a single Quad Rank DIMM module can be installed on a channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0176.Message: Multiple Quad Rank DIMM modules are installed on a DDR channel. Refer to DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

PDR97.Description: The controller detected drives that require security keys for access. Without providing security keys, the drives are unstable.
PDR97.Resolution: Provide the security key required to unlock the secure encrypted drives.

RAC0221.Description: The Destination E-mail Address can contain upto 64 characters.
RAC0221.Resolution: Enter an email address that contains upto 64 characters.
RAC0221.Message: The Destination E-mail Address is too long. The maximum length is 64 characters.

UEFI0012.Description: A CPU page fault (type 0x0E) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment. A program accessed a page mapped in the virtual address space, but not loaded in physical memory.
UEFI0012.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

CTL93.Description: The controller identified in the message has been changed to operate as part of a fault tolerant pair.
CTL93.Message: %1 has been successfully changed to operate in Fault Tolerant mode.

ISM0019.Description: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS), because checksum verification did not succeed for some files.
ISM0019.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the OS Collector on the iDRAC to the most recent version available, and then retry the operation.
ISM0019.Message: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because checksum verification did not succeed for some files.

RAC1170.Description: Unable to find the SSL library. This can be because, the library is not installed in the default path or no SSL library is installed.
RAC1170.Resolution: If a SSL library is not installed, install one and retry the operation. If a SSL library is installed, create a soft-link of the installed SSL library to "libssl.so" using the linux "ln" command and retry the operation.
RAC1170.Message: Unable to find the SSL library in the default path.

SWC0272.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0272.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0272.Message: Invalid syntax. The -g option is only valid with -o, -i, and -c.

PWR8507.Description: The system Input Power Cap was changed from the value to the value indicated in the message.
PWR8507.Message: System Input Power Cap changed from %1W AC to %2W AC.

UEFI0177.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.
UEFI0177.Resolution: Only a single Quad Rank DIMM module can be installed on a channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0177.Message: A DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Quad Rank DIMM module.

ENC14.Description: There are too many enclosures attached to the controller port. When the enclosure limit is exceeded, the controller loses contact with all enclosures attached to the port. This is an unsupported configuration.
ENC14.Resolution: Remove the extra enclosures. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for maximum number of enclosures that can be connected.
ENC14.Message: The number of enclosures connected on %1 has exceeded the maximum limit supported by the controller.

RAC969.Description: The import operation cannot continue if the value specified for the shutdown option (-b) is incorrect. The supported values are "Graceful" and "Forced".
RAC969.Resolution: Make sure to specify either "Graceful" or "Forced" for the shutdown (-b) option.
RAC969.Message: Incorrect value specified for the shutdown option.

CMC8541.Description: The CMC specified in the message was reset by a watchdog event.
CMC8541.Message: The watchdog has reset the CMC %1.

VDR5.Description: The controller removed a virtual disk. This is due to a delete virtual disk operation, a reset configuration operation, or the removal of every physical disk that was a member of the virtual disk.

SWC0013.Description: The operation to save the front panel security settings encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0013.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0013.Message: Unable to save the front panel security settings.

BOOT005.Description: One or more of the invoked methods required parameters are missing.
BOOT005.Resolution: Check documentation for the method in question and try again.

PST0208.Description: System BIOS has halted and is unable to continue.
PST0208.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) If new hardware has been added, remove the new hardware and restart the server, 2) Turn server off and back on using the power button, or 3) Remove and reapply server input power. If the problem persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

LC059.Description: The attribute specified is read only and the value cannot be changed.
LC059.Message: Cannot set read only attribute specified in AttributeName %1.

RAC953.Description: The comment was added to the specified entry in the Lifecycle Log.
RAC953.Resolution: View the added comment using the racadm lclog view q <seq. no> -n 1 command.

VLT0102.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0102.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0102.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

PWR218.Description: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) the feature because the Fresh Air (FA) mode is enabled.
PWR218.Message: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature because the Fresh Air (FA) mode is enabled.

PSU0043.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0043.Message: An output under current fault detected on power supply %1.

RFM1027.Message: Removable Flash Media is operating normally.

BAT1014.Description: Diagnostic event for service to determine if there is an ambient temperature problem.

IOV006.Description: The Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard firmware is not at the correct version..
IOV006.Resolution: Run the command "racadm fwupdate -g -u -a <TFTP server IP Address> -d mainboard.bin -m main_board" to upload the latest firmware version to the Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard.
IOV006.Message: Incorrect Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard firmware version.

VFL0004.Description: The requested vFlash media operation could not be performed, because some of the iDRAC services are busy.
VFL0004.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation. If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
VFL0004.Message: Unable to perform the vFlash media operation.

RAC037.Description: There are no pending configurations to delete.

RAC0631.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid network file share name is entered.
RAC0631.Resolution: Enter a valid network file share name, and then retry the operation.
RAC0631.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid network file share name is entered.

FAN907.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already enabled.
FAN907.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already enabled.

RAC1036.Description: Successfully cleared pending values for attributes in the group specified.
RAC1036.Resolution: To verify, run the RACADM command "racadm get group".
RAC1036.Message: Successfully cleared pending attribute(s) for the group specified.

SEC0601.Message: A secure mode violation was corrected.

BAR020.Description: The Lifecycle Controller data is being imported from the backup file.

UEFI0231.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Configuration Read phase.
UEFI0231.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0231.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RED055.Description: A reboot job for applying one or more update packages has been created. The server will reboot at the specified start time.

SWC0040.Description: The location of the backup Server Configuration Profile image file provided is incorrect.
SWC0040.Resolution: Enter the correct location of the backup Server Configuration Profile image file and retry the operation.
SWC0040.Message: Unable to complete the Import operation.

SWC1924.Description: The server configuration cannot be modified by using Quick Sync because issues were found with the configuration information.
SWC1924.Resolution: Review the server configuration operation results and correct any issues detected, then retry the operation.
SWC1924.Message: Unable to modify the server configuration by using Quick Sync.

IPA0002.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.

RAC972.Description: Configuration XML import and export operations require the specified username to have administrator role privileges.
RAC972.Resolution: Run the same command with a username that has an administrator role privileges.
RAC972.Message: Insufficient privileges to run the configuration XML file import or export operations.

BAR028.Description: The component restoration on the host system has completed, but there were errors. The Host System will shutdown.
BAR028.Resolution: View configuration data and request attributes update for the components or retry system profile import.
BAR028.Message: Host System Component Restore completed with errors, shutting down Host System.

CPU0005.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.
CPU0005.Resolution: Review product documentation for supported CPU configurations.

RAC026.Description: Unable to set DNS Domain Name because "Domain Name From DHCP" is Enabled.
RAC026.Resolution: Disable "Domain Name From DHCP" to set values for DNS Domain Name.
RAC026.Message: Unable to set DNS Domain Name because "Domain Name From DHCP" is Enabled.

VF030.Description: The specified hash type is not a valid type.

CTL96.Description: The controller identified in the message has an issue as displayed in the message.
CTL96.Resolution: To resolve this issue, see Troubleshooting section in the Dell Shared PowerEdge RAID Controller (SPERC8) documentation.
CTL96.Message: %1 has entered safe mode with limited functionality due to %2

STOR0506.Description: The physical disk is unreadable or the RAID controller is not responding.
STOR0506.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, replace the physical disk or update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version, and retry the operation.

RAC065.Description: The iDRAC reset operation was not successful. This may be due to IPMI communications issues.
RAC065.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, remove AC input power from the server and re-apply AC power to the server and retry the operation. 3) If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
RAC065.Message: iDRAC reset operation was not successful.

RAC0288.Description: All characters entered must be alphanumeric or valid symbols.
RAC0288.Resolution: Enter all alphanumeric characters and valid symbols.
RAC0288.Message: Invalid entry: Entry must be exclusively alphanumeric characters and valid symbols.

CTL24.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL24.Message: Abort CC on Error and Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.

DH009.Description: An unexpected internal problem has occurred and the operation did not complete successfully.
DH009.Resolution: Remove AC power from the system and re-apply AC power to the system. After the server restarts, retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
DH009.Message: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unexpected internal problem..

CTL68.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL68.Message: Attempted to import Virtual Disk with missing Physical Disk on %1.

PWR8656.Description: CMC could not successfully turn on the component identified in the message, because of insufficient power available.
PWR8656.Resolution: Make sure there is sufficient power available, and then retry the operation. To increase available power, add more PSUs, use PSUs with higher voltage inputs or a higher power rating, remove unused components from the Chassis, or change the redundancy policy to Redundancy Alerting Only or Non-redundant.
PWR8656.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the component %1-%2 because of insufficient power.

PCI3000.Description: Either the BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, or LOM firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3000.Resolution: Update BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, and LOM firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3000.Message: Device option ROM on embedded NIC failed to support Link Tuning or FlexAddress.

BAR103.Description: System branding data is being collected and copied to the backup Server Profile.

PDR1002.Description: The controller received a SMART error from the drive. The drive is operational but needs replacement.
PDR1002.Resolution: The drive will need replacement at the next service window.
PDR1002.Message: A predictive failure detected on drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

SYS122.Description: The operation to collect OS and Application Data is successfully completed.
SYS122.Message: OS Collector: The operation to collect OS and Application Data is successfully completed.

HWC5035.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure fans are installed and working correctly. 2) Check the temperature sensor status for the chassis and make sure it is within the chassis operating temperature range. 3) Reseat the I/O module to clear the over-temperature condition. If the problem persists, contact the service provider.
HWC5035.Message: An over-temperature event detected on I/O module %1.

SEL1506.Description: The primary CMC has lost communication with the indicated member CMC.
SEL1506.Resolution: Check network cable and network connections.
SEL1506.Message: Lost communications with Chassis Group Member %1.

RAC0616.Description: iDRAC was unable to continue with the operation after the PKCS#12 file was uploaded, because it is not able to extract the custom signing certificate and private key.
RAC0616.Resolution: Make sure to upload the PKCS#12 file that contains a valid custom signing certificate and private key.
RAC0616.Message: Error while extracting custom signing certificate and private key from the PKCS#12 file.

RAC0609.Description: The import or export system configuration operation with the job ID indicated in the message was successfully added to the Job Queue.
RAC0609.Resolution: No response action is required. The status of jobs can be viewed on the Job Queue page.
RAC0609.Message: The job %1 has been successfully added to the job queue.

RED011.Description: Current USC version does not support this component. Check InstanceID
RED011.Resolution: Use the latest version of USC available if possible.

SYS186.Description: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server OS is turned off.
SYS186.Resolution: Turn on the server and wait until the OS finishes booting, and then retry the operation.
SYS186.Message: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server is turned off.

RAC030.Description: This attribute is dependent on a related attribute that has an incorrect value. The related attribute is the parent in a parent-child value dependency relationship and has an affect on what values the child attribute can have.
RAC030.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller - Remote Services User Guide or the DCIM iDRAC Card Profile to determine the required values for the related attribute and retry the operation with the appropriate value.
RAC030.Message: This attribute is dependent on a related attribute that has an incorrect value.

LOG302.Description: The Chassis Log file header is corrupted. The Chassis Log will be recreated and all current log entries will not be preserved.
LOG302.Message: The Chassis Log file header is corrupted.

RAC1010.Description: The power cap cannot be set if the object Power.Cap is disabled.
RAC1010.Resolution: Enable Power Cap setting using "racadm set System.Power.Cap.Enable < 1 | Enabled >", and retry the operation.
RAC1010.Message: Unable to set the power cap value.

BOOT004.Description: An invalid number of source arguments was passed to the method.
BOOT004.Message: Invalid number of Boot Source arguments

SWC0308.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0308.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0308.Message: The -d option requires -g to also be specified.

SWC0113.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0113.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0113.Message: The -6 option can only be used in combination with the -d or -s option.

SEC0002.Description: The I/O card area is open. I/O cards may be added or removed. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0002.Resolution: Close the I/O card area. Check system logs.
SEC0002.Message: The I/O card area is open.

RAC0680.Description: The USB Configuration XML feature is not available if the iDRAC user credentials and BIOS passwords are not set to default values.
RAC0680.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC user credentials and BIOS passwords to default and retry the operation.
RAC0680.Message: Server iDRAC user credentials and/or BIOS passwords are not currently set to default credentials. The USB Configuration XML feature is not available unless default credentials are set.

SWU8526.Description: The firmware update operation of iDRAC identified in the message is initiated.
SWU8526.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is initiated.

FAN0006.Description: The fan may be required for optimal performance.

BAT1028.Description: The controller battery voltage is low. This may indicate that the battery is no longer protecting the controller cache.
BAT1028.Resolution: The battery needs to recharged. Wait 24 hours to see if the charge is restored.
BAT1028.Message: The battery voltage on %1 is low.

RAC0620.Description: Lifecycle Controller is currently busy performing tasks. The selected jobs cannot be deleted until the following: 1) The Lifecycle Controller tasks are completed. 2) The system completes all the Power-on-Self-test (POST) operations.
RAC0620.Resolution: Wait until Lifecycle Controller completes the current tasks and the system completes Power-on Self-test (POST).
RAC0620.Message: Lifecycle Controller is unable to delete the selected jobs.

IOV009.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) runs this function only when the chassis is turned off.
IOV009.Resolution: Turn off the chassis and retry the operation.
IOV009.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to reset to factory default or pre-factory default settings.

ASR0106.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. No action was taken. (IPMI sensor type code 23h - offset 00h event 3:0 - 4h)
ASR0106.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.

VDR101.Description: Indicates the Virtual Disk to Virtual Adapter Mapping for audit purposes.
VDR101.Message: Virtual Adapter mapping reported for %1. Virtual Adapter 1 is now %2. Virtual Adapter 2 is now %3. Virtual Adapter 3 is now %4. Virtual Adapter 4 is now %5

PWR8584.Description: If power redundancy is lost and the server Performance Over Power Redundancy feature is disabled, the server turn-on will not be allowed.
PWR8584.Resolution: To enable the server to be turned-on, on the Power Configuration page in the Web UI, enable the server Performance Over Power Redundancy option . Using the RACADM utility, run the following command "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPerformanceOverRedundancy 1". Then retry the operation.
PWR8584.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because the power supply redundancy is lost and Performance Over Power Redundancy feature is disabled and the power required is less than the available power.

RAC054.Description: The user account attributes cannot be reset to default values due to an internal error.
RAC054.Resolution: Make sure the configuration XML file contains valid values for user account attributes and retry the operation.
RAC054.Message: User account attributes cannot be reset to default values due to an internal error.

CPU0010.Description: The CPU is throttled due to thermal or power conditions.
CPU0010.Resolution: Review system logs for power or thermal exceptions.

RAC1135.Description: The RACADM command could not be run because the internal instrumentation components are either busy or have stopped functioning.
RAC1135.Resolution: Wait for a minute for the internal instrumentation component to respond, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for 15 seconds, wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting, and then retry the operation. If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
RAC1135.Message: Unable to run the RACADM command because an internal instrumentation component has stopped functioning.

SEC0101.Description: The Storage disk tray in the slot identified in the message has been open for an extended period of time. The tray should be closed as soon as any service action is completed. Leaving it open for extended period may result in drives overheating.
SEC0101.Resolution: Close the Storage disk tray as it may affect the system performance or may cause hard drives to overheat. Check system logs .
SEC0101.Message: The %1 in slot %2 is opened for more than 3 minutes.

ISM0025.Description: The NVMe device cannot be prepared for removal from (the PCIe slot identified in the message because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) NVMe device is busy, 2) NVMe device is not present or 3) NVMe driver is not present.
ISM0025.Resolution: Make sure of the following: 1)That the NVMe device identified in the message is not in use, 2) the NVMe device is present, and 3) NVMe device drive is installed.
ISM0025.Message: Unable to prepare the NVMe device %1 for removal from the PCIe slot %2 because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) NVMe device is busy, 2) NVMe device is not present or 3) NVMe driver is not installed.

SWU8550.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful.
SWU8550.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8550.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Standby CMC and Active CMC.

UEFI0277.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection number identified in the message because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv6 server is invalid.
UEFI0277.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reconfigure the DHCPv6 server boot file URL option, and note that server name must be specified. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable Target Info via DHCP and configure the parameters manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0277.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv6 server is invalid.

RAC0605.Description: There are no jobs to be displayed.
RAC0605.Message: There are no jobs to be displayed.

STOR075.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because there is an operation pending to change the enclosure configuration mode (Split or Unified). This operation is exclusive because it involves changing the RAID backplane topology.
STOR075.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending enclosure mode change request operation, allow the job to complete, restart the server, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR075.Message: The operation cannot be performed because the enclosure configuration mode (Split or Unified) change request is pending.

BIOS018.Description: The BIOS password specified in the operation is not valid. A valid BIOS password must be made from the following: 0 to 32 characters in length, numbers 0 to 9, lowercase letters a to z, special characters <>|-,+./;[\]'.
BIOS018.Resolution: Retry the operation with a BIOS password that conforms with system BIOS password requirements.

SEL0002.Description: This message appears when event logging of a specific type is disabled by the user. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 01h)

STOR0109.Description: No power supply unit data to display. The system is powered off, no power supply unit is present in the system, or the power supply unit is not connected to the enclosure.
STOR0109.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosure power supply unit is available, and power supply unit is connected to the enclosure.
STOR0109.Message: Power supply unit is not connected to the enclosure or data about power supply unit is unavailable.

PWR8666.Description: The iKVM power cycle operation is initiated.
PWR8666.Message: The iKVM power cycle operation is initiated.

RAC0658.Description: The iDRAC Service Module service can now be started on the server operating system. This service needs to be started manually on the server operating system.
RAC0658.Message: The iDRAC Service Module service can now be manually started on the server operating system.

RAC0707.Description: Primary Firmware image is invalid. Currently booted from backup image. To restore primary image, update the firmware.
RAC0707.Resolution: Acquire an iDRAC firmware image of the version desired. Using the latest version available is recommended. Update the iDRAC firmware.
RAC0707.Message: Primary Firmware image is invalid. Currently booted from backup image. To restore primary image, update the firmware.

CMC401.Description: Changing the Reserved QuickDeploy IP Addresses setting to <number of IP address> may create an issue in the future if higher density server nodes are inserted in to the Chassis (for example, quarter-height servers).
CMC401.Resolution: Select a higher number to accomodate future higher density server node additions, otherwise no response action is required.
CMC401.Message: Changing the Reserved QuickDeploy IP Addresses setting to %1 may create an issue in the future if higher density server nodes are inserted in to the Chassis (for example, quarter-height servers). Press OK to continue.

VF039.Description: The detaching partition operation did not complete successfully.
VF039.Message: Detach partition operation did not complete successfully.

RAC1150.Description: The export operation did not be complete successfully.
RAC1150.Resolution: Retry the export operation after five minutes.
RAC1150.Message: Unable to complete the export operation.

UEFI0041.Description: Unable to turn on the TXT feature because the Virtualization Technology (VT) feature is not enabled on the processor.
UEFI0041.Resolution: From System Setup, enable VT, and then enable TXT. If the issue persists, update the system BIOS firmware.
UEFI0041.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the Virtualization Technology (VT) feature is not enabled on the processor.

ENC13.Description: An unsupported configuration was detected. The SCSI rate of the Enclosure Management Modules (EMMs) are not the same.
ENC13.Resolution: Replace one of the EMMs with the matching SCSI rate EMM.

PDR10.Description: This message is generated after a rebuild starts on a physical disk.

RAC1157.Resolution: Verify whether or not the entered FQDD is valid. Run the command 'racadm gethostnetworkinterfaces' for the list of valid FQDDs.
RAC1157.Message: Unable to find the specified FQDD.

CPU0012.Resolution: Review System Event Log and Operating System Logs. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0012.Message: Correctable Machine Check Exception detected on CPU %1.

UEFI0282.Description: One or more graphics processing unit (GPU) adapters are not operating correctly because the power cables between graphics processing unit (GPU) adapters and motherboard are not correctly connected.
UEFI0282.Resolution: Make sure that the cable connections between GPU adapters and motherboard are correct and retry the operation.
UEFI0282.Message: One or more graphics processing unit (GPU) adapters are not operating correctly because the power cables between the GPU adapters and motherboard are not correctly connected.

STOR5.Description: A virtual disk or enclosure has lost data redundancy. In the case of a virtual disk, one or more physical disks included in the virtual disk have failed. Due to the failed physical disk or disks, the virtual disk is no longer maintaining redundant (mirrored or parity) data. The failure of an additional physical disk will result in lost data. In the case of an enclosure, more than one enclosure component has failed. For example, the enclosure may have suffered the loss of all fans or all power supplies.
STOR5.Resolution: Identify and replace the failed components. To identify the failed component, select the Storage object and click the Health subtab. The controller status displayed on the Health subtab indicates whether a controller has a failed or degraded component. Click the controller that displays a Warning or Failed status. This action displays the controller Health subtab which displays the status of the individual controller components. Continue clicking the components with a Warning or Failed status until you identify the failed component. See Storage Health for more information. See the enclosure documentation for information on replacing enclosure components and for other diagnostic information.

STOR092.Description: The requested configuration operation cannot be run because a foreign configuration import operation on the controller is already in progress.
STOR092.Resolution: Wait for the import process to complete before running any configuration operation.
STOR092.Message: Unable to run the configuration operation on the controller because foreign configuration import operation is in progress.

SYS146.Description: Starting secure erase-capable drive erase operations because of a System Erase operation request.
SYS146.Message: Starting secure erase-capable drive erase operations.

PWR8664.Description: The power configuration property dynamic power supply engagement feature is disabled or enabled as identified in the message.
PWR8664.Message: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature is %1.

VLT0220.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0220.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0220.Message: The %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

SYS138.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server OS is turned off.
SYS138.Resolution: Turn on the server and wait until the OS finishes booting, and then retry the operation.
SYS138.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server is turned off.

RED089.Description: A Chassis firmware update operation is in progress. Any attempt to update Chassis firmware during this period will be unsuccessful.
RED089.Message: A Chassis firmware update operation is in progress.

NIC024.Description: The attribute specified in the operation is currently read only and the value cannot be modified.
NIC024.Resolution: For more information on the attribute, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
NIC024.Message: The set operation did not complete successfully as the attribute is read-only.

HWC7002.Description: Server health changed to a warning state from a normal state.
HWC7002.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7002.Message: Server %1 health changed to a warning state from a normal state.

SUP013.Description: The update process is underway and cannot be deleted.
SUP013.Resolution: Do not try to delete the job when the update process is underway. To revert to the previous version of the update, download and update the firmware to the version desired or run the rollback command to go back to the previous version.

BAR106.Description: Unable to import system branding data from the backup Server Profile.
BAR106.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
BAR106.Message: Unable to restore system branding data.

DKM1001.Message: The key management service is operating correctly.

IOV111.Description: Unable to successfully update Chassis Infrastructure firmware.
IOV111.Resolution: Refer to the release notes of the Mainboard update package for recommended action. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
IOV111.Message: Unable to update Chassis Infrastructure firmware.

MEM1206.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed.
MEM1206.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>
MEM1206.Message: Memory mirror redundancy is degraded. Check memory device at location %1.

UEFI0252.Description: The watchdog timer is armed before the BIOS boot manager invokes an UEFI boot option. The watchdog is set to a period of 5 minutes. The Operating System boot loader from the boot option is required to disable the watchdog timer after it is successfully loaded, otherwise the system will reset if the timer expires.
UEFI0252.Resolution: Check the boot option image and boot loader. Update them to the latest version if possible.
UEFI0252.Message: Unable to boot a boot option because the watchdog timer has expired. System will reset.

CMC8551.Description: The message is displayed if the chassis health is not OK (non-critical or critical). The message after this message in the log indicates cause for the issue.

VDR15.Description: The initialization operation could not be completed. This may be due to a user action or a physical disk failure.
VDR15.Resolution: If a physical disk failed, then replace the physical disk. Restart the virtual disk initialization.

RRDU0002.Description: Either one of the SD card or both the SD cards are not functioning properly.
RRDU0002.Message: Internal Dual SD Module redundancy is lost.

SWU8503.Description: The specified Lifecycle Controller operation is successfully submitted and the operation will be executed on the basis of scheduling criteria.
SWU8503.Message: A reinstall/rollback request was submitted to the Lifecycle Controller on server %1.

PSU0040.Description: The power supply output voltage is insufficient to keep system operating at a normal levels.
PSU0040.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0040.Message: An output under voltage fault detected on power supply %1.

SWC0280.Description: The group is indexed and an index needs to be specified.
SWC0280.Resolution: Enter the command with a valid index for the group.

PWR8540.Description: The interval for remote logging of power information is set to the value identified in the message
PWR8540.Message: Power Remote Logging Interval set to %1

UEFI0049.Description: The NMI button cannot be enabled because either the NMI button is stuck or iDRAC firmware is not updated.
UEFI0049.Resolution: Correct the NMI button if stuck or update iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0049.Message: Unable to enable the Non-maskable Interrupt (NMI) button because either the NMI button is stuck or iDRAC firmware is not updated.

OSD14.Description: iDRAC was unable to expose the drivers as a USB device for the OS installation to proceed.
OSD14.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD14.Message: Unable to expose the USB device that contains the operating system drivers to host system.

RAC0275.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0275.Resolution: Disable NIC only if remote access is undesired.
RAC0275.Message: Click OK to disable the NIC. Click Cancel to keep the setting unchanged.

SEC0042.Description: TXT CPU microcode boot cannot be completed because system configuration may have changed.
SEC0042.Resolution: Check system hardware inventory for TPM presence, clear and reconfigure TPM and TXT in BIOS setup menu.
SEC0042.Message: Processor detected a problem while performing an Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) operation.

TMPS0101.Description: <font face="Calibri">Inlet temperature has been above the critical  threshold for duration of 0.8% or more for the operational time during the last one year.</font>
TMPS0101.Resolution: This condition will occur if the ambient temperature is high. Make sure the ambient temperature of the environment is in normal range.
TMPS0101.Message: Inlet temperature is above critical level for extended duration.

MEM0024.Message: Memory device at location %1 is no longer spare memory.

ISM0005.Description: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully restarted communication with iDRAC.
ISM0005.Message: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully restarted communication with iDRAC.

PWR8512.Description: Power configuration data in memory cannot be accessed due to synchronization issues.
PWR8512.Message: CMC rebooted, because the power configuration data could not be accessed.

DIS101.Description: The AutoConfig operation is started by iDRAC using the AutoConfig import file specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS101.Message: The execution of AutoConfig operation is started.

UEFI0135.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This issue is caused by LC partition attach issues.
UEFI0135.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0135.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

IOID110.Description: The virtual address of NIC port identified in the message is configured.
IOID110.Message: The virtual address of %1 Port %2 is configured.

HWC3002.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-insert

STOR047.Description: Unable to change the value of the attribute identified in the message because it is ReadOnly.
STOR047.Message: Unable to change the value of attribute %1 because it is ReadOnly.

VFL0019.Description: The requested vFlash media partition is already detached from the host operating system.
VFL0019.Message: The vFlash media partition is already in detached state.

RAC0762.Description: Unable to perform a firmware update because a valid catalog file is not available on the network share.
RAC0762.Resolution: Make sure that a valid catalog file is available on the network share and retry the operation.
RAC0762.Message: Unable to perform a firmware update because a valid catalog file is not available on the network share.

IOID111.Description: The virtual address of the NIC port identified in the message could not be successfully configured because either the network port connection is not enabled or the NIC is not capable of Virtual Addressing.
IOID111.Resolution: Verify that the network port is enabled and that the port has Virtual Addressing capability and then retry the operation.
IOID111.Message: Unable to configure the virtual address of %1 Port %2.

PWR2260.Description: The iDRAC experienced an IPMB communication issue with the Intel Management Engine and was not able to recover IPMB communications. The server thermal failsafe state is activated.
PWR2260.Resolution: Disconnect power from the server and reconnect power. Turn on the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR2260.Message: The Intel Management Engine is unresponsive and the server thermal failsafe state is activated.

RED088.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because an update operation is already in progress.
RED088.Resolution: Wait until the current update operation is completed, and then retry the operation.
RED088.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware because an update operation is already in progress.

PSU8506.Description: When the Server Power Management mode is enabled the Power cap cannot be set.
PSU8506.Resolution: To enable the ability to set the power cap, switch to external Power Management and disable the Server Based Management Mode in the CMC Web interface.
PSU8506.Message: Unable to change power cap because Server Based Power Management Mode is enabled.

IOID118.Description: The iDRAC has applied I/O Identity Configuration on NIC and FC HBA devices. One or more of the setting configuration operations did not complete successfully.
IOID118.Resolution: Review the previous log entries and identify the devices that did not successfully complete configuration operations. For the identified devices, do the following and then restart the server: 1) Make sure the device is installed properly. 2) Make sure the device has latest firmware installed. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
IOID118.Message: Unable to configure some or all I/O Identity settings based on current persistence policy settings.

STOR073.Description: The iDRAC Service Module version present on the server OS does not support the requested PCIe SSD (NVMe) device operation.
STOR073.Resolution: Update the Dell iDRAC Service Module (ISM) to the version that supports the requested operation on the PCIe SSD (NVMe) device.
STOR073.Message: The iDRAC Service Module version present on the server OS does not support the requested PCIe SSD (NVMe) device operation.

RAC0301.Description: User will be unable to connect to Remote File Share.
RAC0301.Resolution: Make sure proper connectivity exists between the client and the remote file share before using this feature.
RAC0301.Message: Remote File Share connection is unavailable. Check the settings and try again.

OSD41.Description: VFlash does not contain the ISO Image because either the image was deleted, or it was never copied.
OSD41.Resolution: Download the ISO Image to the VFlash again using the DownloadISOToVFlash method.
OSD41.Message: ISO Image not found on VFlash.

RAC0206.Description: Certificate upload failed because this is not a certificate file.
RAC0206.Message: Certificate upload failed: Not a certificate file.

RSI0001.Description: The Lifecycle Controller Remote Services instrumentation is available.
RSI0001.Message: The Lifecycle Controller Remote Services is available.

PDR28.Description: A physical disk that was assigned as a hot spare has been unassigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically unassigned by Storage Management. Storage Management unassigns hot spares that have been used to rebuild data. Once data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, the hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. Assign a new hot spare to maintain data protection in this situation.
PDR28.Resolution: Although this alert is provided for informational purposes, you may need to assign a new hot spare to the virtual disk. Refer to product documentation and see the section Protecting Your Virtual Disk with a Hot Spare for more information.

SWC8521.Description: Unable to modify the timeout for the session.
SWC8521.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have chassis config administration privilege, 2) The session timeout given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8521.Message: Unable to modify timeout for session: %1: %2-%3

IOV001.Description: The operation or operation parameter sent to the Chassis Manager is invalid or not supported.
IOV001.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to Chassis Manager product documentation to determine the contact method for the service provider.
IOV001.Message: The operation contains an invalid request or argument.

SUP0518.Description: The specified firmware for the component was successfully updated.
SUP0518.Message: Successfully updated the %1 firmware to version %2.

TMP0124.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0124.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

RAC1048.Description: The Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings must already exist in order to be cleared.
RAC1048.Message: Unable to clear the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings because there is currently no configuration.

SYS062.Description: The input file for the import configuration operation does not contain a valid XML root element.
SYS062.Resolution: Open the input file in any Web browser to check for invalid content before the expected root element. Correct the invalid content and make sure that the XML file is compliant to the system configuration schema before retrying the operation.
SYS062.Message: Input file for import configuration operation is invalid. The expected XML root element was not found.

RAC019.Description: The submitted job did not complete successfully.
RAC019.Resolution: Examine source of the errors by inspecting the results from the job execution, and after resolving the issues, retry the operation. Job results can be retrieved from the Lifecycle Log or the WSMan API.

BAR027.Description: The component restoration on the host system is complete. The Host System will shutdown.
BAR027.Message: Host System Component Restore complete, shutting down Host System.

OSD71.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'Password' is missing.
OSD71.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "Password" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD71.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'Password' is missing.

RAC1137.Description: Remote unattended diagnostic results export operation initiated.
RAC1137.Resolution: Using the RACADM command line interface, run the "racadm jobqueue view -i <job id>" command to view the status of the operation.
RAC1137.Message: Remote unattended diagnostic results export operation initiated.

RAC0503.Description: Out-of-band controllers cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, or controllers are removed or disconnected.
RAC0503.Resolution: Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown.
RAC0503.Message: There are no out-of-band capable controllers to be displayed.

BAR046.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) is preparing to switch over to the recently loaded firmware. During this switch over, the connection to iDRAC is lost. The server will startup after iDRAC restarts.
BAR046.Message: Host System will power up approximately 10 minutes after Integrated Remote Access Controller Restore (iDRAC).

RED019.Description: Reinstall or Rollback cannot be performed since no applicable firmware was found on the Lifecycle Controller.
