RED019.Resolution: Directly update to the desired version.
RED019.Message: Reinstall or Rollback cannot be performed since no applicable firmware was found on the Lifecycle Controller.

SUP0126.Message: Firmware update in progress. Please wait...

BAT0012.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may have failed because of thermal exceptions.
BAT0012.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation for the associated bay.2) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.
BAT0012.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 has failed.

SEL1502.Description: An action or failure has taken place that degrades CMC redundancy. This includes firmware mismatch between CMC's and a CMC missing SD card.
SEL1502.Resolution: Chassis management controller (CMC) redundancy is degraded.
SEL1502.Message: Chassis management controller (CMC) redundancy is degraded.

HWC6004.Description: Information and status from the controller is unavailable.
HWC6004.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

LC025.Resolution: Make more space available on the network share and try the operation again.

OSE1008.Description: The system OS has successfully booted from the CD-ROM.

TMP1001.Resolution: Check whether the thermostat setting is too low and whether the room temperature is too cool.
TMP1001.Message: %1 has crossed the minimum warning threshold.

RAC0629.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested job type is not supported.
RAC0629.Resolution: Enter a correct job type, and then retry the operation.
RAC0629.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid job type is entered.

BIOS006.Description: A configuration job is already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job succeeds or the job is cancelled.
BIOS006.Resolution: Wait for the job to complete. To continue with more set operations on the specified target, cancel the job and proceed.
BIOS006.Message: Configuration job already created, cannot set attribute on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled

CMC8512.Description: The Extended Storage feature is not activated if the removable flash media SD card on the secondary CMC does not respond within 90 seconds after activation is initiated.
CMC8512.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration, and verify if the SD card on secondary CMC displays errors. 2) If errors are displayed, execute the following racadm command: "racadm cmcchangeover". 3) Repair the removable flash media SD Card by selecting the Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration > Repair Active Controller Media in the CMC Web interface. Repairing is only allowed on the SD card of the primary CMC. If the problem persists, replace the card.
CMC8512.Message: The Extended Storage feature activation timed out. The feature is not active.

RAC0668.Description: This setting will be applied during the next server restart. If the setting is not compatible with the RAID Controller, then LED status indicators on all the associated hard disk drives (HDDs) stop functioning.
RAC0668.Message: This setting will be applied during the next server restart. If the setting is not compatible with the RAID Controller, then LED status indicators on all the associated hard disk drives (HDDs) stop functioning.

PST0141.Description: Quick Path Interconnect failed during system POST. Reboot the system. If problem persists, remove input power and reseat processors. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.
PST0141.Resolution: Reboot the system. If problem persists, remove input power and reseat processors.

SWC4007.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between system BIOS in slot %1 and CMC.

PWR8577.Description: A virtual reseat operation is initiated on the Sleeve or Sled identified in the message. A virtual reseat is the same as removing and inserting a Sleeve or Sled.
PWR8577.Message: A virtual reseat operation is initiated on Sleeve or Sled %1.

RAC0689.Description: Unable to create a virtual disk on the selected disk drives, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0689.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0689.Message: Unable to create a virtual disk on the selected disk drives, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

LIC212.Description: The features are updated because the license was imported or deleted, or the license has expired.

SYS097.Description: The Lifecycle Controller State has been set to disabled by the configuration XML import operation. Further changes to the system configuration require the Lifecycle Controller State to be enabled before the changes are processed.
SYS097.Resolution: If further configuration changes are required for the system, the Lifecycle Controller State must be enabled prior to attempting the configuration change. To enable the Lifecycle Controller State, run the racadm command "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState Enabled".
SYS097.Message: The state of Lifecycle Controller is disabled by the configuration XML import operation.

TST103.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the operation are missing.
TST103.Resolution: To provide the correct parameters, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

LIC019.Description: A leased license may not be imported prior to the actual start date of the license.
LIC019.Resolution: Import the license on or after the license start date.
LIC019.Message: A leased license may not be imported prior to its start date.

VDR56.Description: This message occurs when a physical disk in the disk group was removed or when a physical disk included in a redundant virtual disk fails. Because the virtual disk is redundant (uses mirrored or parity information) and only one physical disk has failed, the virtual disk can be rebuilt. Typically, the virtual disk (E.g. RAID 6) has multiple redundant disks and there is a problem with one of them.
VDR56.Resolution: Replace the missing or failed physical disk.

JCP028.Description: An install or configuration job status is successfully updated on iDRAC.

LOG501.Description: The command cannot be run because a general issue occurred.
LOG501.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the CMC, and then retry the operation.
LOG501.Message: Unable to run the command because of a general issue.

SUP0534.Description: The catalog file cannot be found in the specified location.
SUP0534.Resolution: Specify the correct repository location and retry the operation.
SUP0534.Message: Unable to locate the catalog file.

RAC0108.Description: A non-specific error is detected when accessing the Smart Card.
RAC0108.Resolution: Review the error message preceding or following this message.
RAC0108.Message: An internal error is encountered. Insert a valid Smart Card and try again. (Does this and preceding messages show up in the SEL?)

SYS185.Description: The Tech Support Report job that was running has been cancelled by user request.
SYS185.Resolution: To start another Tech Support Report job, wait until the current job that is being cancelled completes and then retry the operation.
SYS185.Message: The Tech Support Report job has been cancelled.

RED081.Description: The requested operation was not successful because an Automatic Update schedule already exists.
RED081.Resolution: Delete the existing Automatic Update schedule operation before retrying the operation.
RED081.Message: The Automatic Update schedule already exists.

PDR111.Description: The volatile memory backup device on the PCIe solid state device identified in the message is no longer functional. Data loss is possible.
PDR111.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.
PDR111.Message: The volatile memory backup device on %1 is no longer functional.

RAC915.Description: The auto-negotiation property for the iDRAC NIC can be changed only if the NIC is in dedicated mode. To change the NIC mode to dedicated, an iDRAC Enterprise license is required.
RAC915.Resolution: Change the NIC mode to dedicated mode by using "racadm set idrac.nic.selection <1 | Dedicated>", and retry the operation.
RAC915.Message: Unable to change auto-negotiation property for the NIC.

LC013.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. At least one attribute should be changed to create a configuration job.
LC013.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes before creating a configuration job.
LC013.Message: A configuration job cannot be created because there are no pending values to change.

NIC008.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. To create a Configuration job, at least one attribute should be changed.
NIC008.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes and then create a configuration job.
NIC008.Message: No pending data present to create a Configuration job

PST0137.Description: System BIOS detected a parity error during post This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code 89)
PST0137.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

RAC0118.Description: The SD card is not a valid vFlash SD card. The use of non-Dell media prevents the use of some extended capabilities and functions.
RAC0118.Resolution: Insert a supported vFlash SD card.

LOG300.Description: The system recovered from Chassis Log file corruption. Some log entries may not be recovered.
LOG300.Message: The system recovered from Chassis Log file corruption.

SEC0605.Message: A setup password violation was corrected.

SWC0047.Description: The passphrase specified is not correct.
SWC0047.Resolution: Enter the valid passphrase and retry the operation.
SWC0047.Message: Incorrect backup Server Configuration Profile file passphrase provided.

SWC8603.Description: The selected profile cannot be applied to the server identified in the message, because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature on the server is disabled.
SWC8603.Resolution: Make sure that CSIOR on the server identified in the messages is enabled and retry the operation. For 11th generation servers, to enable CSIOR, restart the server, and select the Ctrl-E setup. Select System Services, and enable CSIOR. For 12th generation servers, to enable CSIOR using Lifecycle Controller GUI, restart the server, click <F2> when the companys logo is displayed. On the iDRAC Settings page, click Lifecycle Controller, and enable CSIOR.
SWC8603.Message: Unable to apply profile to server %1 using Quick Deploy feature, because the CSIOR feature on Server %1 is disabled.

CTL49.Description: The NVRAM has corrupted data. This may occur after a power surge, a battery failure, or for other reasons. The controller is reinitializing the NVRAM.
CTL49.Resolution: No response action is required as the controller is taking the required corrective action. However, If this message is generated often (such as during each reboot), then replace the controller.
CTL49.Message: The NVRAM has corrupted data on %1.

LC046.Description: The DownloadServerPublicKey operation is in progress. The operation may take a few minutes to complete before the operation can be attempted again.
LC046.Resolution: Wait a few minutes before retrying retry the operation.
LC046.Message: An instance of DownloadServerPublicKey is already running.

SWC8535.Description: Public Key (PK) SSH Authentication key file upload did not complete successfully because Chassis Management Controller is unable to access the configuration database.
SWC8535.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8535.Message: Unable to add key for slot %1 of service account, due to problem saving key file.

CMC8510.Description: This happens during promotion of extended storage feature from single CMC to dual CMC. If the media on Standby CMC is not healthy, this message is displayed and the feature returns to single CMC state.
CMC8510.Resolution: Do one of the following, and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration and verify if the card on the secondary CMC displays some errors. 2) Do a failover and then reprovision the card from the same GUI page. Reprovisioning is only allowed on the card of primary CMC. However, if both the options 1 and 2 fail, the card may be no longer functional.
CMC8510.Message: Unable to activate the extended storage feature on the secondary CMC: %1. The feature will return to single CMC mode.

LC010.Description: The communications encryption certificate was imported successfully.

HWC2004.Message: The system board %1 cable or interconnect is connected.

HWC0001.Description: The error is caused due to iDRAC failure.
HWC0001.Resolution: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord and turn on the system.
HWC0001.Message: Unable to complete the operation as there is no response from iDRAC.

VDR25.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PDR1122.Message: Drive %1 is no longer in the failed array.

RAC0238.Description: vFlash is unable to service the request at this time. Try again later.
RAC0238.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes.
RAC0238.Message: vFlash is currently in-use by another process. Try again later.

LIC018.Description: The license is already imported on the system and does not need to be reimported.

CPU0816.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0816.Resolution: if removal was unintended, check presence and re-install .
CPU0816.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is absent.

SWC0319.Description: The syntax for the getraclog command is invalid.
SWC0319.Resolution: Refer the help text for getraclog command.
SWC0319.Message: The -i option is not valid with any other options.

PWR8546.Description: A chassis shutdown was already in progress, when the additional shutdown request was received.

NIC006.Description: A configuration job already exists for the specified target. No further configuration operation is allowed until the existing job completes or the job is cancelled.
NIC006.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Wait for the existing configuration job to complete and retry the operation, 2) To continue with a configuration change, cancel the existing job and retry the operation.
NIC006.Message: A configuration job already exists, Cannot set attribute on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled

PWR8565.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate with the iDRAC service processor for the Server identified in the message and the Server could not be turned off. This situation may occur when iDRAC is rebooting.
PWR8565.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Wait for a few minutes for the iDRAC service processor to complete startup. 2) Retry the operation. 3) If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and wait a few minutes for the iDRAC startup to complete before retrying the operation.
PWR8565.Message: Unable to turn off the Server %1 due to iDRAC communication issue.

RAC1151.Description: The export operation did not complete successfully.
RAC1151.Resolution: Run the RACADM techsupreport collect command again and then retry the export operation.

BAR044.Description: Waiting for the host system to successfully get turned off.
BAR044.Message: Waiting for the host system to successfully get turned off.

SWC8505.Description: The description for the Profile identified in the message was edited.

LOG008.Description: The complete Lifecycle Log was successfully created for a requested export operation.
LOG008.Message: The complete Lifecycle Log was successfully created for an export operation.

SYS033.Description: The staged component configuration update performed in the UEFI environment on the host system has completed, but there were errors.
SYS033.Message: Staged component configuration completed with errors.

PST0004.Description: System BIOS has started memory configuration.

CPU0701.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.
CPU0701.Resolution: 1) Check system and operating system logs for exceptions. If no exceptions are found continue. 2) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 3) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 4) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

RED021.Description: The component InstanceID specified could not be located on the system.
RED021.Resolution: Ensure the component specified for updates is present in the system. Restart the system with Collect System Inventory on Restart enabled and verify that the component is represented by an instance of DCIM_SoftwareIdentity.
RED021.Message: The component InstanceID specified is not present on the system.

SWC0087.Description: The Public IP access feaure in iDRAC is disabled by the Integrated Data Center solution. The iDRAC can no longer be accessed via the public IP interface.
SWC0087.Message: The Integrated Data Center Public IP mode is disabled.

RAC1072.Description: The maximum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is less than or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.
RAC1072.Resolution: Check the minimum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the minimum critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1072.Message: Unable to set maximum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is less than, or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.

SEL1205.Message: The unknown system hardware failure was corrected.

VF008.Description: Creating a partition with an image did not complete successfully.
VF008.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes, 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
VF008.Message: Image partition creation did not complete successfully.

BAR105.Description: Importing system branding data from the Server Profile backup file.

TMP0136.Description: The system is automatically turned off because of insufficient cooling.
TMP0136.Resolution: Replace the fans that have stopped functioning, or add the minimum number of fans recommended. For more information, see the system Owner's Manual available at the support site.
TMP0136.Message: The system is automatically turned off because of insufficient cooling.

SYS095.Description: Unable to unmount an iDRAC internal storage partition.
SYS095.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issues persists, reset the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and then retry the operation after the iDRAC has finished restarting.
SYS095.Message: Unable to unmount an iDRAC internal storage partition.

POW001.Description: Host failed to power up because chassis cover is open. This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2251
POW001.Message: Power on permission error, chassis cover open.

RAC0500.Description: Batteries cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off or there is a bad or disconnected cable for batteries connected to the controller.
RAC0500.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Verify that the batteries are connected properly.
RAC0500.Message: There are no batteries to be displayed.

CBL0001.Description: A backplane signal cable was detected, but the accompanying power cable was not present.
CBL0001.Resolution: Reconnect or replace the power cable. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

UEFI0024.Description: The Management Engine firmware is not responding to the BIOS via the HECI interface.
UEFI0024.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0024.Message: The Management Engine is not responding.

LC039.Description: Lifecycle Controller is locked by another instance of the As-Shipped Inventory export process. Allow the process to complete before attempting another export operation.
LC039.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
LC039.Message: An instance of As-Shipped Inventory export is already in progress.

UEFI0157.Description: The request to reset BIOS to default settings is successfully completed.
UEFI0157.Message: The iDRAC request to reset BIOS to default settings is successfully completed.

RAC0634.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid username is entered.
RAC0634.Resolution: Enter a valid network file share username, and then retry the operation.
RAC0634.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid network file share username is entered.

SWC0307.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0307.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0307.Message: The -d option requires -p or -g to also be specified.

FAN0009.Description: The fan may be required for optimal performance.

RAC0266.Resolution: Enter a valid VLan ID. Expected range: 1-4094.

RAC047.Description: The event action selected is not supported for the event filter specified.
RAC047.Resolution: Refer to the iDRAC User Guide and Lifecycle Controller documentation and retry the operation with a valid event action selection on the specified filter.
RAC047.Message: Unsupported event action for the specified event filter.

TMP0114.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0114.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0114.Message: The %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

STOR0509.Description: The controller does not have the minimum number of initialized disks to create a virtual disk.
STOR0509.Resolution: Connect required number of initialized physical disks to the RAID controller and retry the operation.

CTL54.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation.

RAC0255.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv4 Subnet Mask does not conform to the required format.
RAC0255.Resolution: Enter a valid Subnet Mask. Expected ranges are: 255.XXX.0.0 [Class A], 255.255.XXX.0 [Class B], 255.255.255.XXX [Class C], and XXX.0.0.0 [others], where XXX must be valid (0,128,192,224,240,248,252,254).
RAC0255.Message: The Subnet Mask is invalid. Expected ranges are: 255.XXX.0.0 [Class A], 255.255.XXX.0 [Class B], 255.255.255.XXX [Class C], and XXX.0.0.0 [others], where XXX must be valid (0,128,192,224,240,248,252,254).

FAN0015.Description: The cooling device is not performing optimally. The cooling device may be installed improperly.
FAN0015.Resolution: Remove and re-install the cooling device. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0015.Message: %1 RPM is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PWR8537.Description: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is disabled.
PWR8537.Message: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is disabled.

TMP0200.Message: CPU %1 temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

RAC937.Description: The configuration XML file import operation was successfully initiated after it was invoked by the user specified in the message.
RAC937.Message: Successfully initiated configuration XML file import operation that was invoked by the %1.

SWC0119.Description: The syntax of the sslcertview command is invalid.
SWC0119.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertview subcommand.
SWC0119.Message: Invalid certificate type specified with -t option.

PDR46.Description: The Patrol Read task has encountered an error that cannot be corrected. There may be a bad disk block that cannot be remapped.
PDR46.Resolution: Backup your data from the disk. Start disk initialization and wait for it to complete, then restore the data from the backup to the disk.
PDR46.Message: Patrol Read found an uncorrectable media error on %1.

SUP0123.Resolution: Re-connect to the iDRAC after a minute.
SUP0123.Message: Firmware update completed successfully. The RAC is in the process of resetting. Your connection will be lost. Please wait up to a minute before starting a new session.

PWR216.Description: Unable to enable Extended Power Performance, because redundancy policy is set to Grid Redundancy or No Redundancy.
PWR216.Resolution: Configure Redundancy Policy to Power Supply Redundancy and retry the operation. Using the CMC Web GUI, click Power > Configuration. From the Redundancy Policy drop-down menu, select Power Supply Redundancy.
PWR216.Message: Unable to enable Extended Power Performance, because Redundancy Policy is set to Grid Redundancy or No Redundancy.

PWR8591.Description: Before inserting hard disk drives, always make sure the Chassis has enough available power. Otherwise operating servers may be turned off.
PWR8591.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Go to, the Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field, view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis.
PWR8591.Message: Servers are turned off to allocate power to the newly inserted hard disk drives.

PWR2202.Message: The system is sleeping with lost processor context.

PR31.Description: All the tasks in the Job were attempted, but some did not complete successfully.
PR31.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log for more details associated with this warning then retry the operation if appropriate.

RAC0241.Description: SD Card does not have enough free space available.
RAC0241.Resolution: Delete existing data or insert a SD card of greater size and retry.
RAC0241.Message: The specified size exceeds the maximum size of %1 MB.

RAC0670.Description: Deleting the virtual disk will remove the virtual disk from the controller's configuration. If the specified virtual disk is a boot device, the server will not boot unless another boot device is selected in BIOS.
RAC0670.Resolution: If the specified virtual disk is a boot device, the server will not boot. Press OK to continue.
RAC0670.Message: Deleting the virtual disk will remove the virtual disk from the controller's configuration.

ISM0001.Description: The iDRAC Service Module detected a OS to iDRAC Pass-through mode as identified in the message. iDRAC Service Module will automatically connect to iDRAC after the OS to iDRAC Pass-through is configured to the USB NIC mode.
ISM0001.Resolution: Configure OS to iDRAC Pass-through to the USB NIC mode by running the commands: 1) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.PTMode usb-p2p 2) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.UsbNicIpAddress <ip address> 3) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.adminstate enabled
ISM0001.Message: The iDRAC Service Module detected a OS to iDRAC Pass-through in the %1 mode. Switch the OS to iDRAC Pass-through to a USB NIC mode.

UEFI0160.Description: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit.
UEFI0160.Resolution: Check the total number of ranks in the channel to make sure it does not exceed the maximum allowed limit. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0160.Message: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit on memory slots: %1.

MEM0000.Description: The memory is operational. This is an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0000.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0000.Message: Persistent correctable memory errors detected on a memory device at location(s) %1.

RAC028.Description: The attributes "DNS Domain Name From DHCP" and "DNS From DHCP" are dependent on the attribute DHCP being Enabled. Currently DHCP is configured as Disabled.
RAC028.Resolution: Set DHCP attribute to Enable to be able to Enable DNS Domain Name From DHCP or DNS From DHCP.
RAC028.Message: Unable to Enable "DNS Domain Name From DHCP" or "DNS From DHCP" because DHCP is Disabled.

PSU8505.Description: Unable to set the chassis redundancy policy to AC Redundancy.
PSU8505.Resolution: Retry the operation using the CMC command line interface or CMC Web interface. To set the chassis redundancy policy using the command line, enter "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisRedundancyPolicy 1". To configure the chassis redundancy policy using the Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration. From the Redundancy drop-down menu, select AC Redundancy.
PSU8505.Message: Unable to set the chassis redundancy policy to AC Redundancy.

PWR8586.Description: The Chassis does not support the server identified in the message.
PWR8586.Resolution: The server inserted is not supported in the Chassis. Remove the server from the Chassis.
PWR8586.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because it is not supported in the VRTX chassis.

VDR94.Description: This message occurs if the controller pinned cache is recovered.
VDR94.Message: Controller preserved cache was recovered for %1.

LIC005.Description: The maximum number of installed licenses has been reached.
LIC005.Resolution: Delete one of the currently installed licenses and retry the import.
LIC005.Message: Import failed: The maximum number of licenses are installed.

SWC4008.Description: FlexAddress is not implemented in one of the versions of firmware. Please update the firmware.
SWC4008.Resolution: Check firmware versions. Update CMC 1 and CMC 2 firmware to match.
SWC4008.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility detected between CMC 1 and CMC 2.

RAC960.Description: The configuration XML file specified for import cannot be located in the specified repository.
RAC960.Resolution: Make sure the specified file name is correct and is located in the specified repository, and retry the operation. For more information about the syntax, run "racadm help set" to view RACADM help.
RAC960.Message: Unable to find the specified configuration XML file for import.

CMC8567.Description: The DVD drive is mapped to the server slot specified in the message.
CMC8567.Message: The DVD drive is mapped to the server slot %1.

UEFI0066.Description: A PCIe Link failure is observed in the device identified in the message and device link is disabled. The system will be halted.
UEFI0066.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Turn off the input power to the system and turn on again. 2) Update the PCIe device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0066.Message: A PCIe link training failure is observed in %1 and the link is disabled. The system has halted.

SWC0014.Description: Unable to apply the changes to the date and time settings because an internal error occurred.
SWC0014.Resolution: Exit the Date and Time wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation.
SWC0014.Message: Unable to set new date and time.

RAC1139.Description: The requested file can be exported from the firmware racadm only to a remote file share.
RAC1139.Resolution: Create a remote file share to export the file or use remote or local racadm to export to the file system that is accessible by the racadm executable.
RAC1139.Message: The entered option is not supported by the interface.

TMP0125.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0125.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

UEFI0015.Description: The BIOS is unable to access the Lifecycle Controller firmware. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0015.Resolution: Perform the following actions: 1)Reboot the system. 2) Press F2 during boot to enter System Setup. 3) Select iDRAC Settings then Lifecycle Controller. 4) Change Lifecycle Controller back to Enabled. If subsequent failures occur, press and hold the system ID button down for 15 seconds to reset the iDRAC. For more information on how to reset iDRAC, see iDRAC User's Guide.
UEFI0015.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible and is therefore in Recovery mode.

RED042.Description: The necessary user access rights for performing the operation identified in the message are not available for the username used to access the iDRAC.
RED042.Resolution: Use a username that has the necessary access rights and retry the operation.
RED042.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was not created because the necessary user access rights are not available.

UEFI0258.Description: An issue is observed on the Hard-drive/SSD backplane.
UEFI0258.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Make sure the correct type of Hard-drive/SSD backplane is installed. 2) Check the configuration of Hard-drive/SSD backplane and make sure its power cable is connected. Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0258.Message: An issue is observed on the Hard-drive/SSD backplane.

BAT0002.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0002.Message: The system board battery has failed.

SUP002.Description: Could not create a new job because of a network error or an unresponsive iDRAC.
SUP002.Resolution: Retry the action. If this fails, reboot the iDRAC.

SYS178.Description: Unable to retrieve TTY log data because no storage controllers are detected in the server.
SYS178.Resolution: Make sure that at least one storage controller is present in the server, and then retry the operation.
SYS178.Message: Unable to retrieve TTY log data because no storage controllers are detected in the server.

SWC0151.Message: RAC configuration saved to file successfully

CTL1.Description: This event is retrieved from the controller when iDRAC storage monitoring was not running. Such events which are generated in the past are logged as informational severity.

PSU0034.Description: This failure may be the result of an electrical issue with cables or subsystem components in the system.
PSU0034.Resolution: 1) Remove and re-install the power supply.2) Check cables and subsystem components in the system for damage. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0034.Message: An under voltage fault detected on power supply %1.

BAT0000.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0000.Resolution: Check the system board battery at the next service window.
BAT0000.Message: The system board battery is low.

ASR0008.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC) within the timeout period. The BMC invoked a system interrupt. (IPMI sensor type code 23h - offset 00h)
ASR0008.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0008.Message: The watchdog timer interrupt was initiated.

BAR018.Description: A system profile backup file validation request has completed.

FC003.Description: An invalid number of arguments was provided to the method.
FC003.Resolution: Enter required input parameters and retry. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide or the FC HBA Profile specification.

UEFI0039.Description: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Keyboard Controller Style (KCS) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI). Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as remote out of band access, active power management, thermal management, inventory collection, LCD, or system error reporting.
UEFI0039.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0039.Message: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Keyboard Controller Style (KCS) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).

RED046.Description: The operation identified in the message was disabled and the iDRAC was unable to create the next job in the sequence.
RED046.Resolution: Enable the operation identified in the message and retry the operation. To enable the Automatic Server Profile Backup operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoBackup 1". To enable the Automatic Update operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoUpdate 1".
RED046.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was unable to create a job because the task type is now disabled.

STOR015.Description: A new virtual disk cannot be created because the maximum number of virtual disks are already created.
STOR015.Resolution: A new virtual disk cannot be created until one is deleted.
STOR015.Message: Maximum virtual disks allowed for this controller has been reached.

PWR8663.Description: The server identified in the message could not be successfully turned on because of incompatibility between the I/O module and mezzanine card.
PWR8663.Resolution: Make sure that the I/O module and mezzanine card are compatible. For information about compatibility of hardware components, see the Modular System Chassis Hardware Manual.
PWR8663.Message: Unable to turn on the server %1 because of an inconsistency between the I/O module and mezzanine card.

SWC8549.Description: The status of Media Access Control (MAC) address identified in the message is not valid. Possible MAC address status values are unassign, assign and active. The value is "unassigned" if the MAC address is not used in any profile. The value is "assigned" if the MAC address used in a profile. The value is "active" if used in a profile applied to a server. The status must be same for all Virtual MAC addresses if assigned to a profile.
SWC8549.Resolution: Edit the Virtual MAC Address Pool to correct the MAC address status. Possible MAC address status values are unassign, assign and active. The value is "unassigned" if the MAC address is not used in any profile. The value is "assigned" if the MAC address used in a profile. The value is "active" if used in a profile applied to a server. The status must be same for all Virtual MAC addresses if assigned to a profile.
SWC8549.Message: The status of Media Access Control (MAC) address %1 is not valid for Boot Identity profile operations.

BAR057.Description: The configuration import was completed, but some of the imported values were not set correctly.
BAR057.Resolution: The system event log captures the values that were not set, and they must be reset manually.
BAR057.Message: Some of the configuration values not applied to Device: %1

UEFI0223.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Receive Buffer Per Bit Deskew Training phase.
UEFI0223.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0223.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

TMP0132.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0132.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0132.Message: The control panel temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

CMC8577.Description: The Remote Access Controller (RAC) Kerberos Keytab is changed.
CMC8577.Message: The Remote Access Controller (RAC) Kerberos Keytab is changed.

LOG004.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in iDRAC firmware.
LOG004.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.

PR24.Description: The specified job was cancelled. This could be due to user action or system error. This message is no longer in use in Lifecycle Controller 2.0 as the job control functionality handles this operation.

SYS193.Description: A configuration change is detected in the component identified in the message.
SYS193.Message: A configuration change is detected for component: %1.

SYS091.Description: Unable to complete the operation because the method is not supported.
SYS091.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the method is not supported.

VFL0010.Description: Another operation is currently in progress on the SD card.
VFL0010.Resolution: Wait until the current operation is completed, and then retry the requested operation.
VFL0010.Message: An operation is in progress on the SD card.

PWR8524.Description: The redundancy was lost because the power requirement of the chassis exceeds the current redundant policy.
PWR8524.Resolution: No response action is required. Review the power requirements and determine if more PSUs are needed to restore redundancy.
PWR8524.Message: Redundancy was lost, while Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is enabled.

FC008.Description: No changes are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration. To create a Configuration job, change at least one attribute.
FC008.Resolution: Change the configuration of one or more attributes and retry creating the Configuration job.
FC008.Message: No pending data present to create a Configuration job.

SUP0537.Description: Unable to continue the firmware update due to an internal error.
SUP0537.Resolution: Reboot the system and retry. If the problem persists, contact your service provider for the latest Update Package.
SUP0537.Message: Unable to continue the firmware update.

MEM0016.Message: Memory device at location(s) %1 is operating correctly.

LOG508.Description: The network share may be read-only or it may not have sufficient space for the export operation.
LOG508.Resolution: Verify the network share is not read-only and has sufficient space for exporting, then retry the operation.
LOG508.Message: Unable to write to the network share.

RED008.Description: The firmware payloads in the Update Package cannot be extracted. This may be because the file is not valid or the security signature cannot be verified.
RED008.Resolution: Re-acquire the Update Package from the service provider.
RED008.Message: Unable to extract payloads from Update Package.

VF017.Description: The SD card is not initialized.
VF017.Resolution: In order to perform this operation, first initialize the SD Card.

BOOT014.Description: The system's SD card has been removed or is in use.
BOOT014.Resolution: Verify that the SD card is inserted and that another operation is not in progress, and try again.

STOR050.Description: The controller is in Local Key Management mode.
STOR050.Message: Controller is in Dell Key Management mode.

FAN0016.Description: The cooling device is not performing optimally. The cooling device may be installed improperly.
FAN0016.Resolution: Remove and re-install the cooling device. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0016.Message: %1 RPM is outside of normal operating range.

OSD18.Description: Unable to find the ISO file specified in the network share. Make sure that the correct ISO file path was entered into the command and that all other user credentials are correct.
OSD18.Resolution: Rerun the command with the correct ISO file path.
OSD18.Message: Unable to locate the ISO image on the network share point.

CTL14.Description: The storage controller memory identified in the message is not operating correctly.
CTL14.Message: Single-bit ECC error limit exceeded on the %1 DIMM.

BAT0003.Message: The system board battery is present.

DIS008.Description: iDRAC IP address change in progress with Provisioning Server.
DIS008.Message: Notification of iDRAC IP address changed to %1 from %2 sent to Provisioning Server.

SUP0539.Description: Update Packages are missing from the specified repository.
SUP0539.Resolution: Enter another repository location that contains the desired Update Packages and retry the operation.
SUP0539.Message: Update Packages missing in the repository.

STOR046.Description: Unable to complete the create virtual disk operation because the StartingLBA and Size value combination results in an overlapping virtual disk.
STOR046.Resolution: Refer to the users guide to provide the correct StartingLBA and Size combination values.
STOR046.Message: The specified StartingLBA and Size values combination result in an overlapping virtual disk.

STOR024.Description: Configuration changes for the specified device are already scheduled.
STOR024.Message: Unable to create a configuration job because a configuration job for the device already exists.

SYS131.Description: Unable to communicate with the OS IPMI service because the service is not running.
SYS131.Resolution: For more information about checking whether the IPMI service is running, see the iDRAC8 User's Guide.
SYS131.Message: OS Collector: Unable to communicate with the OS IPMI service.

SYS120.Description: The OS Collector application did not complete its task within the maximum allowed time and the operation is cancelled. This may be because the server OS is not supported by the OS Collector application and the application is unable to function correctly.
SYS120.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure that the OS Collector application supports the OS installed on the server. If the OS is not supported, the OS Collector may not function correctly. 2) Reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation. To install the OS Collector using the iDRAC Web UI, get the latest OC Collector update package and then select the Update and Rollback link from the iDRAC Web UI home page and upload the install package. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SYS120.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the OS Collector is taking too much time. The operation is cancelled.

PDR100.Description: The controller is not able to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a dedicated hot spare. The disk may have been removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.
PDR100.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and that it has not been removed. Check the cables. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the dedicated hot spare.
PDR100.Message: Dedicated Hot Spare %1 no longer useful for all arrays.

BIOS017.Description: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration.
BIOS017.Resolution: Remove AC power from system and after restoring AC power, retry the operation.
BIOS017.Message: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration

LC063.Description: All jobs must be completed before creating a new job.
LC063.Resolution: Retry after all the existing jobs are completed or deleted.
LC063.Message: Cannot create new jobs until the existing running jobs are completed or deleted.

CTL55.Description: The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation. This text is from events in the controller event log that were generated while Storage Management was not running.
CTL55.Resolution: If there is a problem, review the controller event log and the Server Administrator alert log for significant events or alerts that may assist in diagnosing the problem. Verify the health of the storage components. See the hardware documentation for more information.

FC102.Description: The FC controller port link identified in the message is not functioning either because the FC cable is not connected or the FC device is not functioning.
FC102.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure that the FC port is enabled. 2) Make sure the Activity/Speed LEDs are lit if the physical port has LEDs. 3) Check the FC cable and FC cable connections for proper installation. 4) Check that the attached FC switch is functioning.
FC102.Message: The %1 port %2 link is not functioning either because the FC cable is not connected or the FC device is not functioning.

PDR1001.Description: The controller detected a failure on the disk and has taken the disk offline.
PDR1001.Resolution: Remove and reseat the failed drive. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PDR1001.Message: Fault detected on drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

LC054.Description: The network share may be read-only or it may not have sufficient space for the export operation.
LC054.Resolution: Verify the network share is not read-only and has sufficient space for exporting, then retry the operation.
LC054.Message: Unable to write to the network share.

PDR37.Description: The physical device may not have a supported version of the firmware or the physical device may not be supported.
PDR37.Resolution: If the physical device is supported, then update the firmware to a supported version. If the physical device is not supported, then replace the physical device with one that is supported.

VFL0016.Description: The requested vFlash media partition is already attached to the host operating system.
VFL0016.Message: vFlash media partition is already in attached state.

BIOS012.Description: No changes to BIOS attribute data are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration.

CTL100.Description: The Patrol Read operation running on the controller was stopped by user request or an issue was detected by the controller.
CTL100.Message: The Patrol Read operation was stopped and did not complete for %1.

BAR019.Description: A system profile backup file validation is in progress.
BAR019.Message: Validating Restore operation, allow several minutes for this to complete.

VLT0103.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0103.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0103.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PSU0800.Description: Lists the complete status of the power supply unit.
PSU0800.Message: Power Supply %1: Status = 0x%2, IOUT = 0x%3, VOUT= 0x%4, TEMP= 0x%5, FAN = 0x%6, INPUT= 0x%7

RAC0757.Description: The requested operation using the USB Management Port cannot be completed because the port is disabled in BIOS configuration.
RAC0757.Resolution: Enable the USB Management Port in BIOS configuration to use this feature
RAC0757.Message: USB Management Port is currently disabled in BIOS configuration.

RAC0129.Description: No status response was returned after completing the initialization request.
RAC0129.Resolution: Try reinitializing the card again in a few minutes.
RAC0129.Message: An error has occurred while initializing the SD card.

RAC0247.Description: This message is displayed when trying to format or download to an attached vFlash partition.
RAC0247.Resolution: Detach this partition and try again.

UEFI0184.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Load Reduced DIMM (LR-DIMM) buffer initialization.
UEFI0184.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0184.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

UEFI0142.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was unable to complete a requested task or function.
UEFI0142.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0142.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was unable to complete a requested task or function.

STOR012.Description: One or more of the specified physical disks cannot be used for the operation requested. Physical disk protocol and media type, along with other physical disk characteristics like Secure Encryption and T10 protection, need to match the requirements of the requested operation.
STOR012.Resolution: Make sure the specified physical disk has the appropriate protocol and media type for the requested operation. Specify a different physical disk with a state appropriate for the requested operation and retry the operation.
STOR012.Message: Provided Physical disk not valid for this operation.

POW000.Description: Host failed to power up because chassis infrastructure is not ready. This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2250
POW000.Message: Power on permission error, chassis infrastructure not ready.

VFL0015.Description: The request could not be successfully completed, because the vFlash SD Card partition is in read-only mode. Write operations cannot be performed on the card partition.
VFL0015.Resolution: Change the partition access type to read-write by running the command 'racadm set idrac.vFlashPartition.<index>.accesstype 1'.
VFL0015.Message: vFlash media partition is of read-only type.

SYS137.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
SYS137.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller by pressing F2 during server startup and select iDRAC Settings > Lifecycle Controller and then enable the Lifecycle Controller. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
SYS137.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

SWC8542.Description: The Profile identified in the message is exported.

UEFI0067.Description: A PCIe link failure is observed in the PCIe device identified in the message and device link is disabled.
UEFI0067.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Turn off the input power to the system and turn on again. 2) Update the PCIe device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0067.Message: A PCIe link training failure is observed in %1 and device link is disabled.

BAR014.Description: Unable to access the server profile Backup file and the operation cannot continue. This can be due to a media error or loss of connectivity.
BAR014.Resolution: If using vFlash media replace media and try again. If a network share, make sure there is connectivity to and existence of the destination.
BAR014.Message: Backup file or partition access error.

RAC0745.Description: There are no pending operations on the selected component group.
RAC0745.Message: There are no pending operations present on the selected component group.

PWR207.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.
PWR207.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR207.Message: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.

UEFI0054.Description: Debranding process is completed. The system is being restarted.
UEFI0054.Message: Debranding process is completed. The system is being restarted.

SYS121.Description: The operation to collect OS and Application Data was cancelled using iDRAC Web UI.
SYS121.Message: The operation to collect OS and Application Data was cancelled using iDRAC Web UI.

VF024.Description: The partition is locked by another operation.
VF024.Resolution: Wait for the partition to be unlocked and check the partition status to see if it is attached.

SWC0244.Description: The specified Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDDs) system component name is invalid.
SWC0244.Resolution: Verify that the correct Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) system component name is specified. See the help text (The help text for the get subcommand can be obtained by running "racadm help get") or documentation for valid FQDD system component names.

PDR1008.Message: Rebuild was aborted for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

SWU8532.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation is not successful, because an invalid parameter is entered.
SWU8532.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because an invalid parameter is entered. ErrorCode=0x%1.

HWC1105.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message is removed from the unsupported slot identified in the message.
HWC1105.Message: The %1 is removed from the slot %2.

RAC0644.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'year', while scheduling a job.
RAC0644.Resolution: Enter a correct value, and then retry the operation.
RAC0644.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid 'year' value is entered.

BAR066.Description: The system profile export destination is not enabled.
BAR066.Resolution: Enable the vFlash media and retry the operation.

MEM9000.Description: An issue is detected in the propagation of signals between the processor and the memory.
MEM9000.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

PDR93.Description: The physical disk firmware update operation has completed.

PWR1002.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1002.Resolution: Review system configuration and system logs for thermal or environmental failures and warnings.
PWR1002.Message: The system performance degraded because of thermal protection.

CTL46.Description: The Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) is malfunctioning. Data loss or data corruption may occur..
CTL46.Resolution: Replace the DIMM immediately to avoid data loss or data corruption. The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM.
CTL46.Message: Single-bit ECC error. The %1 DIMM is critically degraded.

SWC0157.Message: User certificate successfully uploaded to the RAC.

VDR16.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk failed or there is an error in the parity information. A failed physical disk causes errors in parity information.
VDR16.Resolution: Check that all the physical disks of the virtual disk are in a healthy condition. Replace any disks that are not healthy and restart the operation. If this is not the problem, delete the virtual disk and restore the data to the disk from a backup copy.

UEFI0150.Description: The system has detected a storage backplane that is not supported in this system or configuration. The backplanes functionality may be degraded or disabled.
UEFI0150.Resolution: Install a supported backplane configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0150.Message: The system has detected a storage backplane that is not supported in this system or configuration. The backplanes functionality may be degraded or disabled.

RDU0017.Description: The storage system has redundant power lines. One of power lines is no longer available.
RDU0017.Resolution: Turn system off and remove AC input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. If the issue still persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
RDU0017.Message: The storage power redundancy is no longer available.

UEFI0114.Description: The Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) operating mode cannot be enabled because of mismatches in DIMM channel configurations.
UEFI0114.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0114.Message: Unable to enable the Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) operating mode because of mismatches in DIMM channel configurations.

LC005.Description: The value provided for the update mode parameter is invalid.
LC005.Resolution: Verify that the correct firmware update mode was entered. The choices are: 1) Disable (default) 2)Allow version upgrade only 3) Match firmware of replaced part.

SUP0529.Description: The selected USB drive is disconnected.
SUP0529.Resolution: Make sure the USB drive is connected and retry the operation.

CTL44.Description: A diagnostics test failed. The text for this message is generated by the tool that ran the diagnostics and can vary depending on the situation.
CTL44.Resolution: Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information on the diagnostic test.

RED009.Resolution: Verify if Lifecycle Controller is installed on the system by pressing F10 on boot up. If the Lifecycle Controller application is not present, use the update package to reinstall it.

JCP024.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage due to use by another application or operation. This job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.
JCP024.Resolution: Wait for current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is: 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs.
JCP024.Message: Lifecycle Controller is in use. This job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.

SWU8553.Description: The firmware update operation of Active CMC was not successful. The firmware Image file could not be accessed.
SWU8553.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware Image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8553.Message: Unable to update the Active CMC firmware. The Image file was not accessible.

PWR204.Description: Object value is successfully modified. Max Power Conservation Mode will deactivate the Extended Power Performance feature.
PWR204.Message: Object value is successfully modified. Max Power Conservation Mode will deactivate the Extended Power Performance feature.

IOID115.Description: The target settings properties of the NIC port identified in the message could not be configured, because either iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is not enabled; or, the network controller is not functioning.
IOID115.Resolution: Make sure that the iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is enabled. Check whether or not the network controller is working.
IOID115.Message: Unable to configure the target settings properties of the %1 Port %2.

RAC1055.Description: The Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings must already exist in order to be cleared.
RAC1055.Message: Unable to clear the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings because there is currently no configuration.

PCI2002.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI2002.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device.
PCI2002.Message: A fatal IO error detected on a component at slot %1.

PWR8547.Description: The chassis was already turned off, when the power off request was received.

RAC949.Description: The specified work note was added to the Lifecycle Log.
RAC949.Resolution: View the work notes using the racadm lclog view c worknotes command.
RAC949.Message: Successfully added a work note to the Lifecycle Log.

BOOT010.Description: The provided vFlash partition index could not be found on the system.
BOOT010.Resolution: Verify that a vFlash partition with the desired index exists on the System.
BOOT010.Message: Could not locate vFlash partition index

DIS109.Description: The server could not be configured because the End Host Power State value specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC is incorrect.
DIS109.Resolution: In the DHCP scope option field where VendorID=iDRAC, enter a end-host-power-state (-e <0 or 1>) where 0 = Powered Off and = Powered On, and then retry the operation.
DIS109.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because an invalid End Host Power State value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

STOR034.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because an invalid value is specified for RebootJobType.
STOR034.Resolution: Enter a valid RebootJobType value and retry the operation. For more information about the RebootJobType parameter, see the RAID Profile specification.

SWC0058.Resolution: Reboot the system and retry the operation.

SWC0161.Message: PK SSH Authentication operation completed successfully.

FC002.Description: Unable to allocate memory required to perform the operation.
FC002.Resolution: Perform an AC power cycle and retry Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC firmware update.

RAC0754.Description: Reset iDRAC to complete custom SSL certificate deletion action. A manual reset of iDRAC is needed for the action to take effect.
RAC0754.Resolution: Click the Reset iDRAC link to reset iDRAC.
RAC0754.Message: Reset iDRAC to complete the deletion action of the certificate.

SYS079.Description: The Preview operation indicates the input file for system configuration XML is not compliant with the configuration XML schema.
SYS079.Resolution: Make sure that the input file is compliant with the system configuration XML schema published on www.delltechcenter.com/lc.
SYS079.Message: The Preview operation indicates the input file for system configuration XML is not compliant with the configuration XML schema.

SWC8512.Description: Unable to add user name identified in the message. The reason for this issue is described with the error code in the message.
SWC8512.Resolution: Correct the error described in the message and retry the operation after a few minutes.

PWR8580.Description: The power on request for the server identified in the message was not successful because the Chassis is turned off.
PWR8580.Resolution: Turn on the Chassis, and then retry the operation. To turn on the Chassis using the Chassis Management Controller Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Control, select the Power On System option, and then click Apply.
PWR8580.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because the Chassis is not turned on.

SWC8547.Description: Some or all of the Media Access Control (MAC) addresses cannot be added to the pool because they are already present in the MAC address pool.
SWC8547.Message: Unable to add some of the Media Access Control (MAC) addresses because the MAC addresses are already present in the MAC address pool of Boot Identity profile operations.

ASR0001.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC) within the timeout period. The system was reset per the configured setting.
ASR0001.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0001.Message: The watchdog timer reset the system.

HWC8504.Description: The control panel is not functioning normally. This could be because the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) cannot communicate with the control panel or because of a problem with the control panel hardware.
HWC8504.Resolution: Remove and reapply chassis input power. If problem persists, contact your service provider.
HWC8504.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) cannot communicate with the control panel.

STOR308.Description: The Controller is in HBA mode, RaidAction CreateAuto value is not supported.
STOR308.Resolution: In order to perform a RAID configuration operation, change the controller mode to RAID and retry the operation. For switching to RAID mode using the F2 System Setup utility, go to Device Settings > "RAID Controller "> Controller Management > Advanced Controller Management > Switch to RAID mode.
STOR308.Message: Controller is in HBA mode, RaidAction CreateAuto value is not supported.

SUP0505.Description: The catalog file in the selected repository is corrupt.
SUP0505.Resolution: Select a repository with a valid catalog file, and retry the operation.

VFL1016.Description: The SD card is not detected or not installed.
VFL1016.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
VFL1016.Message: Media not present for Removable Flash Media %1.

SWC0108.Description: The Service Tag string is empty.
SWC0108.Message: The service tag is not currently populated.

RFLA2001.Description: The SD card module is not detected or not installed.
RFLA2001.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the SD module.
RFLA2001.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is absent.

PST0195.Description: The current processor configuration is unsupported or encountered a fatal exception during POST. Check the processor configuration. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code C3).
PST0195.Resolution: Review system processor configuration and reduce the system to the minimum configuration.

HWC1009.Description: The backplane may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC1009.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

TST106.Description: The email alert being tested is not properly configured.
TST106.Resolution: Configure the email alert and retry the operation. If the failure persists, reset iDRAC.
TST106.Message: Email alert destination address not configured.

SWC0235.Description: All public keys stored on the iDRAC have been deleted.

RED003.Resolution: Schedule the job if it is not already scheduled.

STOR0701.Description: There are no RAID controllers, physical disks or virtual disks discovered by instrumentation that can be configured.
STOR0701.Resolution: Storage objects are unavailable in the current system configuration. Make sure that the storage devices are installed in the system, and then retry the operation after the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature has updated the system inventory. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
STOR0701.Message: Storage objects are unavailable in the current system configuration.

SYS144.Description: Starting controller hardware cache data erase operations because of a System Erase operation request.
SYS144.Message: Starting controller hardware cache data erase operations.

VDR31.Description: The controller is getting disconnected from its virtual disk, while Input Output (IO) is in-progress.
VDR31.Resolution: Try importing foreign disks, if any. Check if the enclosure containing the Virtual Disk is disconnected from the controller. Insert any disks that are reported missing or failed. If the enclosure or disks were removed intentionally, the preserved cache can be discarded. See storage hardware documentation for more information on performing these steps.
VDR31.Message: Controller cache is preserved for missing or offline %1.

PST0088.Description: System BIOS is preparing to boot the system.

USR104.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in iDRAC.
USR104.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
USR104.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

MEM8501.Description: A low memory condition was detected. If this condition continues, a failover or a reset may occur.
MEM8501.Resolution: If multiple resets occur, contact your service provider.

SUP0538.Description: Unable to update firmware due to one the following:1) Update Package is not supported. 2) Trusted Platform Module feature is enabled in BIOS settings.
SUP0538.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Download the latest Update Package from your service provider. 2) Disable the Trusted Platform Module feature in BIOS settings. 3) Update the Lifecycle Controller firmware to the latest version.

STOR057.Description: The instrumentation for the specified RAID controller is not in state where the requested operation can be performed because system inventory collection (the CSIOR feature) has not been executed.
STOR057.Resolution: Enable the CSIOR (Collect System Inventory On Restart) feature and restart the server to cause CSIOR execution. Make sure the Remote Services status is Ready and retry the operation. To get the Remote Services status, invoke the GetRSStatus method. For more information about this method, see Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Guide.
STOR057.Message: The specified RAID controller is not currently available for configuration.

RAC952.Description: The allocated size for the Lifecycle Log entries has reached its maximum limit, and no further work notes can be added to the Lifecycle Log.
RAC952.Message: There is no free space to add new work notes to the Lifecycle Log.

PWR8518.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned on.
PWR8518.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned on.

LC042.Description: Configure Console name while Virtual Address Management is in FlexAddr mode.
LC042.Resolution: Configure the Virtual Address Management to Console mode, and then configure the name of a console.
LC042.Message: Configure Console name in FlexAddr mode

SYS035.Description: The component configuration operation was completed, however some of the configuration values were not successfully applied.
SYS035.Resolution: Retrieve and view configuration operation results in the Lifecycle Log. For more information to retrieve the configuration results see the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services User's Guide. Identify the unsuccessful configuration operations. Modify the input data as appropriate for the component and retry the configuration operation.
SYS035.Message: Some configuration values were not applied to: %1

CTL52.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation.

CTL51.Description: The text for this message is generated by the controller during runtime and can vary depending on the situation.
CTL51.Resolution: Make sure the SAS cables attached to the enclosure/backplane are attached securely. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables. Contact technical support if the issue persists.

SWC8605.Description: Information about the server identified in the message is not recognized.
SWC8605.Resolution: Restart the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and retry the operation. The CMC can be restarted by using the Web UI interface and selecting Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components and then select the Reset/Failover CMC button. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8605.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Server %1 generation information is not recognized.

OSD52.Resolution: Enable the vFlash from the iDRAC GUI or RACADM, and then proceed.

RAC0262.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the Preferred IPv6 DNS Server address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0262.Resolution: Enter a valid Preferred IPv6 DNS server address.
RAC0262.Message: The Preferred IPv6 DNS Server Address is invalid.

AMP0307.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0307.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is less than the lower critical threshold.

SWC0228.Description: Invalid values passed to the function.
SWC0228.Message: Partition label must be an alphanumeric character string.

DIS108.Description: The server could not be successfully configured, because Lifecycle Controller is either not installed or not enabled.
DIS108.Resolution: Verify that the Lifecycle Controller firmware on the server being configured is installed and enabled, then restart the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for 15 seconds. For more information about Lifecycle Controller, see the Lifecycle Controller Users Guide available at dell.com/support/manuals.
DIS108.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig import operation, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

BAR032.Description: The system profile backup file validation did not complete successfully.
BAR032.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) An incorrect passphrase may have been entered, correct the input and retry the operation. 2) Download a valid backup image of the host system and retry. 3) Reboot the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) and retry. 4) Download a new firmware image for the iDRAC and retry.

TMP0203.Resolution: Check system operating environment, fans, and heatsinks.
TMP0203.Message: CPU %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PCI3018.Description: New PCI card(s) have been detected in the system that may require additional airflow. Fan speeds may have changed to add additional cooling to the cards.
PCI3018.Resolution: Changing default fan response to PCIe cards should be done with appropriate understanding of the PCIe cooling needs of the cards present in the system. If the automatic cooling response is insufficient, additional cooling can be added by one of the following methods. 1) From iDRAC Web GUI, click Hardware -> Fans -> Setup, then from the fan speed offset drop-down list appropriately select the cooling level needed or set the minimum fan speed to a custom value. 2) From F2 System Setup, select iDRAC Settings -> Thermal, and set a higher fan speed from the fan speed offset or minimum fan speed. 3) For RACADM commands run "racadm help system.thermalsettings". If a lower fan speed is required, contact your service provider for the appropriate IPMI commands to reduce the default fan speed response for new PCIe cards.
PCI3018.Message: New PCI card(s) have been detected in the system. Fan speeds may have changed to add additional cooling to the cards.

VRM0019.Description: The Remote Image is now configured and ready to use.

OSD76.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is invalid.
