OSD76.Resolution: Check the value provided for input parameter "ResetType" and retry the operation.
OSD76.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is invalid.

DIS107.Description: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because an invalid AutoConfig time-to-wait value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS107.Resolution: In the DHCP scope option field where VendorID=iDRAC, enter a time-to-wait (-t) value more than 300 seconds and less than 3600 seconds and then retry the operation.
DIS107.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because an invalid AutoConfig time-to-wait value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

UEFI0060.Description: Power required by the system exceeds the power supplied by the PSUs. Continuing to restart the system may automatically turn off the system without any notification.
UEFI0060.Resolution: Check the PSU and system configuration, and then upgrade the PSU, if necessary.
UEFI0060.Message: Power required by the system exceeds the power supplied by the Power Supply Units (PSUs).

PST0134.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the interrupt controller during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 86)
PST0134.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

RAC954.Description: Up to 128 characters are allowed for a comment.
RAC954.Resolution: Do not exceed 128 characters for the comment, and retry the operation.
RAC954.Message: The number of characters entered for the comment exceeds the supported limit.

CTL87.Description: One or more settings on the controller identified in the message do not match the settings of its peer controller. This can cause issues in a fault tolerant setup.
CTL87.Resolution: Make sure that each controller is using the same setting by reconfiguring the settings of the identified controller.
CTL87.Message: %1 settings do not match the settings of its peer.

VF047.Description: This is not a Dell-licensed VFlash.
VF047.Resolution: This feature requires a Dell SD card.

OSD64.Description: The ConfigurableBootToNetworkISO method cannot be run by specifying the ResetType parameter as 'warm reboot' because the server is in turned-off state.
OSD64.Resolution: Make sure that the server is turned on and retry the operation.
OSD64.Message: Unable to invoke the ConfigurableBootToNetworkISO method by specifying the ResetType parameter as 'warm reboot' because the server is in turned-off state.

SWC0111.Description: The serveraction subcommand requires an option to be specified.
SWC0111.Resolution: Refer the help for serveraction subcommand, and enter a valid option.
SWC0111.Message: A server action command must be specified.

HWC0012.Description: The USB drive is write protected.
HWC0012.Resolution: Remove write protection on the USB drive before retrying the operation.
HWC0012.Message: Unable to write to the USB drive.

SUP0102.Description: The TFTP IP Address specified is invalid.
SUP0102.Resolution: Specify a valid TFTP IP Address.

LC037.Description: Lifecycle Controller is locked by another instance of Lifecycle Controller Log Export operation. Wait for that operation to complete before attempting to run another command.
LC037.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Wait approximately 2 minutes and retry the operation. 2) Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
LC037.Message: An instance of Lifecycle Controller Log Export is already running.

BAR011.Description: Hardware Inventory data collection and export did not complete successfully.
BAR011.Resolution: Enter system services to enter Unified Server Configurator (USC), and select exit and reboot option in USC to instantiate the database, if Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) is not enabled. If the hardware inventory database is present, restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC)and retry.
BAR011.Message: Unable to collect Hardware Inventory information.

PST0143.Description: TXT boot failed. This could be related to memory errors or an error with the system TXT configuration. A socketed TPM module may have been removed. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.
PST0143.Resolution: Check TPM presence. Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PST0143.Message: Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) fatal error.

RDU8514.Description: A failover operation has been requested, but a failover operation cannot be completed while CMC firmware update is in progress.
RDU8514.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover, firmware update is in progress.

PR16.Description: The device could not apply some of the configuration settings. This may indicate configuration changes since the last system inventory or mutually exclusive settings.
PR16.Resolution: Check the current system configuration and ensure all settings are correct. If not, retry the operation.
PR16.Message: Some of the configuration values could not be applied to device: %1

VDR55.Description: The controller cannot communicate with attached devices. A disk may be removed or contain errors. Cables may also be loose or defective.
VDR55.Resolution: Verify the health of attached devices. Review the Alert Log for significant events. Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables.

SUP0530.Description: The catalog repository path entered is not accessible.
SUP0530.Resolution: Retry the operation with the correct catalog repository path.

SYS003.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the operation are missing.
SYS003.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation and retry the operation with the required parameters.

BIOS005.Description: The number of AttributeName and AttributeValue parameters do not match.
BIOS005.Resolution: Enter the same number of parameters for AttributeName and AttributeValue. Refer to documentation for method input parameter details.
BIOS005.Message: Mismatch in AttributeName and AttributeValue count

RAC0714.Description: Server failed to power up due to noncontinuous power action.
RAC0714.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller web interface to check available power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, allocate power necessary and retry the operation.
RAC0714.Message: Server failed to power up due to noncontinuous power action.

SWC0261.Description: The option requested is not available on the interface being used.
SWC0261.Resolution: Refer to the help to get the list of commands/options valid for the interface.
SWC0261.Message: The specified option is not supported with the interface being used.

VLT0228.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0228.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0228.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is outside of range.

UEFI0267.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the IPv4 initiator gateway address is invalid.
UEFI0267.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the Initiator Gateway field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0267.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the IPv4 initiator gateway address is invalid.

STOR022.Description: The operation cannot be completed because controller is not secuirty capable.
STOR022.Message: The controller is not security capable.

HWC0005.Description: Internal error while retrieving firmware version for the currently installed components. For more information about the failure, see Lifecycle Log.
HWC0005.Resolution: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
HWC0005.Message: Internal error while retrieving update information.

CMC8507.Description: The Extended Storage feature synchronizes data from the primary CMC removable flash media SD Card is synchronized with the secondary CMC removable flash media SD Card.
CMC8507.Message: Extended Storage for primary CMC and secondary CMC synchronization is complete.

PST0138.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the SIO. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST code exception code 8A)
PST0138.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

BAR037.Description: Adjustments to Lifecycle and Integrated Remote Access Controller environments are complete.
BAR037.Message: System Reset or Lifecycle Controller Actions Canceled, System Profile Failure Recovery completed.

PDR57.Description: The bad block table is the table used for remapping bad disk blocks. This table fills as bad disk blocks are remapped. When the table is full, bad disk blocks are no longer remapped, which means that disk errors are no longer corrected. At this point, data loss can occur.
PDR57.Resolution: Replace the disk generating this message and restore from a backup copy. You may have lost data.
PDR57.Message: Bad block table on %1 is full. Unable to log block %2.

SYS158.Description: Unable to erase hardware caches during the System Erase operation.
SYS158.Resolution: Retry the System Erase operation with only the hardware cache erase option selected.

SUP0513.Description: The specified filename path to the Update Package is incorrect.
SUP0513.Resolution: Enter the correct file path where the Update Package is located and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system and retry the operation.
SUP0513.Message: Unable to access the Update Package.

SWC5003.Description: The System Controller (SC) has either stopped functioning or is updating a firmware version.
SWC5003.Resolution: Make sure that the System Controller is functioning.
SWC5003.Message: System Controller (SC) has either stopped functioning or is updating a firmware version.

SWC0142.Message: Certificate successfully uploaded to the RAC.

STOR084.Description: The requested job cannot be run because another job is currently running. Two options for running jobs on multiple storage controllers are: 1) Run the jobs on each controller individually. Wait for each job to complete before starting the configuration and job creation on the next controller. 2) Schedule multiple jobs to run at a later time using the scheduling options.
STOR084.Resolution: Make sure that the currently running job is completed, and then retry the operation. If necessary, recreate the configuration and the job. For information about running jobs on multiple storage controllers, see the iDRAC Online Help or iDRAC Users Guide.
STOR084.Message: Unable to create the job because another job is currently running

PDR105.Description: The physical disk drive identified in the message is assigned as a dedicated hot-spare.
PDR105.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is assigned as a dedicated hot-spare.

IOID003.Description: The Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Auxiliary powered devices is changed to the restart type identified in the message.
IOID003.Message: The Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Auxiliary powered devices is changed to %1.

SWC0057.Description: Unable to copy the file to the network share because it does not have the specified folder, the specified folder name has space between the characters, does not have enough free space, or is read-only.
SWC0057.Resolution: Make sure that the network share has the specified folder, the specified folder name has no space between the characters, has enough free space, or is not read-only. If the problem persists, perform an AC power cycle and retry the operation.
SWC0057.Message: Unable to export the file to the network share.

PDR1020.Message: Consistency check for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 completed.

BIOS022.Description: The BIOS password is disabled in the hardware using a jumper and can not be set. See the system owners manual for jumper location.
BIOS022.Resolution: Change the jumper setting on the system board to enable changing the BIOS password.
BIOS022.Message: Cannot set the BIOS password. Password is disabled due to a jumper setting on the motherboard.

SWC8543.Description: The Boot Identity operation cannot be performed because server in the slot identified in the message does not have a Service Tag.
SWC8543.Resolution: Set the Service Tag value using the F2 System Setup boot utility. Follow the Server BIOS menu instructions for setting an absent Service Tag or contact your service provider.
SWC8543.Message: Unable to perform the Boot Identity profile operation because the server in slot %1 does not have a Service Tag.

VF0060.Description: The SD card was not detected. Therefore, the requested operation cannot be completed.
VF0060.Resolution: Verify whether the SD card is inserted and enabled, then re-try.
VF0060.Message: Unable to perform the requested operation. Make sure the SD card is inserted and enabled.

SWC0240.Description: The requested object is auto-assigned if DNS Server DHCP is enabled, and hence cannot be configured.
SWC0240.Resolution: Disable DNS Server DHCP and re-try the command.
SWC0240.Message: The IPv6 DNS Server IP address is not allowed to be configured if IPv6 DNS Server DHCP (cfgIPv6DNSServersFromDHCP6) is enabled

SYS041.Description: The configuration update is complete, however all of the values were not correctly applied.
SYS041.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log for the values that were not set. Resolve the issues in the XML configuration input file and retry the operation. Alternatively, configure each of the attributes using the component service methods. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
SYS041.Message: Unable to apply some component configuration values.

SWC8503.Description: The Profile identified in the message has been renamed.

LIC016.Description: The license includes features that are dependent upon additional licensed features not included in this license. These licensed features are not activated until license(s) with the dependent licensed features are imported to the system.
LIC016.Resolution: Import the license(s) that meet the license features dependencies.
LIC016.Message: The feature dependencies of the license are not met.

BAR065.Description: Collecting the Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration and copying it into the server profile backup file.
BAR065.Message: Collecting Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration.

TMP0104.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0104.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0104.Message: The system board %1 temperature is outside of range.

RAC034.Resolution: Wait for existing jobs to run to completion or delete some jobs from the job queue.
RAC034.Message: Unable to create a job because the job queue is full.

STOR011.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the stripe size entered is not supported by the controller.
STOR011.Resolution: Enter a valid stripe size and retry the operation.
STOR011.Message: Stripe size not supported on controller.

SWC0036.Description: Unable to launch hardware diagnostics because the Enterprise UEFI Diagnostics application is corrupt or iDRAC is not responding.
SWC0036.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the Enterprise UEFI Diagnostics using one of the following methods: 1) Use the Firmware Update feature in Lifecycle Controller. 2) Use the Server Update Utility. 3) Run the Update Package from the operating system. If the problem continues to persist, reset the iDRAC. For more information, contact your service provider.

SWC0320.Description: Racadm tool failed to get the total number of records.
SWC0320.Message: Unable to get the number of records available.

BAR062.Description: Collecting the Lifecycle Controller configuration database and copying it into the server profile backup file.

RAC0401.Description: Critical error from iDRAC service recovery program.

PCI5003.Description: A PCIe card carrier is removed from the PCIe slot identified in the message.
PCI5003.Message: A PCIe card carrier is removed from the PCIe slot%1 .

SYS192.Description: The provided System Configuration Profile XML file is being previewed on the system. No configuration changes will be applied.
SYS192.Resolution: No response action is required. Use the GetConfigResults() method to get the preview job results or export the Lifecycle Log to review the preview job results.
SYS192.Message: The System Configuration Profile XML file preview operation is started.

LNK0002.Description: The DNS query did not complete successfully. This may be because the connection timed out due to an incorrect host name or a DNS server configuration issue.
LNK0002.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Verify host name entered is valid and retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, verify the DNS server settings are configured properly to resolve the host name.

SYS034.Description: The configuration operation for the specified device is in progress.

SWC0222.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0222.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0222.Message: Invalid syntax. The -d option is not valid with -c.

RAC021.Description: The static values for IPAddress Net mask or Gateway cannot be set because DHCP is enabled.
RAC021.Resolution: Disable DHCP to set static values for IPAddress Net mask or Gateway.
RAC021.Message: Unable to set static values for IPAddress Net mask or Gateway because DHCP is Enabled.

PST0140.Description: System BIOS failed to initialize the system management interrupt. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code 8C)
PST0140.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

UEFI0071.Description: One or more UEFI network interfaces is not available. The corresponding UEFI network devices are disabled.
UEFI0071.Resolution: Connect the missing network interface card to the system and enable the UEFI network interface in System Setup.
UEFI0071.Message: One or more UEFI network interfaces is not available. The corresponding UEFI network devices are disabled.

PDR83.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC013.Description: The method cannot be run because an invalid FQDD is entered.
RAC013.Resolution: Enter a valid FQDD and retry the operation.
RAC013.Message: Unable to run the method because an invalid FQDD is entered.

PDR1021.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is no longer in the critical array.

TMP0108.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0108.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0108.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

SUP0114.Message: The firmware update operation could not be completed successfully.

PST0192.Description: System BIOS shutdown test failed during POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code C0).
PST0192.Resolution: Check system event log for CMOS battery exceptions. Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

LOG303.Description: Unable to rename current Chassis Log file during archive operation. Some log entries may be lost.
LOG303.Message: Unable to archive the Chassis Log file.

PDR35.Description: The only physical disk available to be assigned as a hot spare is using SATA technology. The physical disks in the virtual disk are using SAS technology. Because of this difference in technology, the hot spare cannot rebuild data if one of the physical disks in the virtual disk fails.
PDR35.Resolution: Add a SAS disk that is large enough to be used as the hot spare and assign the new disk as a hot spare.
PDR35.Message: The only hot spare available is a SATA disk %1.

SWC0287.Description: The value of a parameter in the config file is invalid.

UEFI0134.Description: Unable to allocate Memory Mapped Input Output (MMIO) resources for one or more PCIe devices because of insufficient MMIO memory.
UEFI0134.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove unused PCIe card(s) to free up MMIO space. 2) Go to System Setup and enable the 'Memory Mapped I/O above 4GB' option.
UEFI0134.Message: Unable to allocate Memory Mapped Input Output (MMIO) resources for one or more PCIe devices because of insufficient MMIO memory.

RAC1181.Description: USB Management Port state cannot be changed because of an unknown hardware or firmware issue.
RAC1181.Resolution: To change the Management Port mode settings do the following: If a device is present, remove and reinsert the USB device from the front panel USB Management port and retry the operation. If the issue persists restart the iDRAC and retry the operation.
RAC1181.Message: Unable to change USB Management Port mode.

HWC0007.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to retrieve vFlash SD card information from iDRAC.
HWC0007.Resolution: Reinsert the vFlash SD card and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
HWC0007.Message: Unable to load vFlash SD card settings.

ENC17.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
ENC17.Message: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has been discovered on %1.

RAC0746.Description: Unable to perform virtual disk(VD) operations, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0746.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. To enable Lifecycle Controller, restart the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes.
RAC0746.Message: Unable to perform virtual disk (VD) operations, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

JCP017.Description: The current job count has reached the maximum value supported. No more jobs are created until the number of jobs on the system is reduced. Completed jobs are automatically deleted if they are older than the DeleteOnCompletionTimeout setting.
JCP017.Resolution: Do one of the following to reduce the job count: 1) Delete one or more jobs and retry the operation. 2) Wait until existing jobs have an elapsed time since completion that is greater than the delete on completion timeout setting and are automatically deleted. 3) change the DeleteOnCompletionTimeout setting using the WSMAN API to a smaller value so that completed jobs are automatically deleted sooner.
JCP017.Message: Job creation request unsuccessful. Maximum number of jobs reached.

CMC8503.Description: CMC is unable to access the IPv4 information for the specified server. Unable to display the specified server's Launch iDRAC link on the CMC Web interface.
CMC8503.Resolution: Enable IPv4 on the specified slot's iDRAC via the CMC command line or Web GUI interface, for the iDRAC's launch point to show up on the CMC web GUI. For the command line options or navigation for Web interface, see the Troubleshooting section in the CMC User's Guide.
CMC8503.Message: Unable to access the IPv4 information of the server.

PWR1006.Resolution: Review system configuration, upgrade power supplies or reduce system power consumption.
PWR1006.Message: The system halted because system power exceeds capacity.

USR8508.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.
USR8508.Resolution: Maximum sessions already in use, so close any of existing session and retry the operation.
USR8508.Message: %1 login was not successful (username=%2, ip=%3, reason=%4)

OSD25.Description: Detaching the USB device (that contains drivers for the operating system installation) from the host has failed. The device may be detached, or iDRAC may not be operating normally.
OSD25.Resolution: Reset iDRAC to detach this device automatically.
OSD25.Message: Unable to detach USB device containing operating system drivers.

SWC8516.Description: Unable to modify privileges of the User identified in the message.
SWC8516.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8516.Message: Unable to modify privileges of User %1: %2-%3

LIC002.Description: The error may occur when License Manager: 1) Is unable to allocate system resources.2) Determines one or more files is incompatible with the current firmware version. This occurs when an older firmware version has been uploaded to a system that was previously running a newer firmware version. If this occurs, the current internal License Manager files are deleted and new ones are created, which align with the firmware version. A license reimport may be required. NOTE: All import, delete, export, view license commands are blocked until this issue is resolved.
LIC002.Resolution: If the firmware has been rolled back to a previous version, this error may occur. All previously installed licenses must be re-imported. If this is not the case, contact technical support.
LIC002.Message: License Manager is unable to allocate the required resources at startup.

UEFI0096.Description: The Advanced ECC memory operating mode cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or system configuration does not support Advanced ECC mode.
UEFI0096.Resolution: Check DIMM population and system configuration to make sure Advanced ECC memory operating mode can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0096.Message: Unable to enable the Advanced ECC memory operating mode because the current DIMM population or system configuration does not support Advanced ECC mode.

CMC8513.Description: The Extended Storage feature activation on the secondary CMC timed out. If the media on Standby CMC doesn't respond within 90 seconds of confirming activation the feature returns to single CMC mode.
CMC8513.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration, and verify if the SD card on secondary CMC displays errors. 2) If errors are displayed, execute the following racadm command: "racadm cmcchangeover". 3) Repair the removable flash media SD Card by selecting the Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration > Repair Active Controller Media in the CMC Web interface. Repairing is only allowed on the SD card of the primary CMC. If the problem persists, replace the card.
CMC8513.Message: The Extended Storage feature activation on the secondary CMC timed out. The feature is being returned to single CMC mode.

PDR85.Description: Errors were detected with security related operations on the disk. The data on the disk might not be retrieved or stored successfully. In addition, the security of the stored data might be at risk.
PDR85.Resolution: Verify the disk is a Secure Encrypted Disk and is not locked. If it is not, replace the disk with a Secure Encrypted Disk. See the storage hardware documentation for more information.

SWU8662.Description: The IOA firmware cannot be updated because of an issue in the network communication session between CMC and IOA.
SWU8662.Resolution: Power-cycle the IOA and if the firmware version is unchanged, retry the firmware update operation.
SWU8662.Message: Unable to update the I/O Aggregator (IOA) firmware because of an issue in the network communication session between CMC and IOA in slot %1.

RAC1002.Description: The Active Directory SSO cannot be enabled, because the object SmartCardLogonEnable is enabled.
RAC1002.Resolution: Disable the object SmartCardLogonEnable using "racadm set iDRAC.SmartCard.LogonEnable <0 | Disabled>", and retry the operation.
RAC1002.Message: Active Directory Single Sign On (SSO) cannot be enabled.

OSD32.Description: Cannot continue with DetachISOImage because the system does not have an attached ISO image.
OSD32.Resolution: The call to DetachISOImage is unnecessary since the ISO image is not currently attached.
OSD32.Message: Unable to detach ISO image from the system.

HWC2005.Description: The cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC2005.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC2005.Message: The system board %1 cable or interconnect is not connected, or is improperly connected.

PWR2251.Description: The server did not turn on because the chassis cover is open.
PWR2251.Resolution: Close the chassis cover and retry the operation.
PWR2251.Message: Unable to turn on the server because the chassis cover is open.

NIC005.Description: The number of AttributeName and AttributeValue parameters do not match.
NIC005.Resolution: Pass the same number of parameters for AttributeName and AttributeValue. Refer to documentation for method input parameter details.
NIC005.Message: Mismatch in AttributeName and AttributeValue count

SYS069.Description: The settings specified in the system configuration XML file match the current configuration for all components.
SYS069.Message: No changes were applied since the current component configuration matched the requested configuration.

NIC508.Message: NIC teaming info is not currently available.

RAC996.Description: Unable to set the specified object value because the object DNS RAC Name is not configured.
RAC996.Resolution: Configure DNS Rac Name using "racadm set iDRAC.NIC.DNSRacName <Name>" command, and retry the operation.
RAC996.Message: Unable to set the object value because the DNS RAC Name object is not configured.

STOR083.Description: The Physical Disk(s) specified are too small to create a Virtual Disk of the requested size.
STOR083.Resolution: Specify Physical Disk FQDD IDs of physical disk drive(s) that have a larger disk space, and retry the operation.
STOR083.Message: The Physical Disk(s) specified are too small to create a Virtual Disk of the requested size.

SWC0152.Message: RAC configuration from file completed successfully

RDU8501.Description: The Active CMC has detected a problem or a low memory condition. It is waiting for the Standby CMC to reset the Active CMC.
RDU8501.Message: CMC%1: waiting to be reset by other CMC

PDR96.Description: Security on a secure encrypted disk was disabled.

PSU1010.Description: The power supply unit is switched off. Either you have switched off the power supply unit or it is defective.
PSU1010.Resolution: Check to see whether the power switch is turned off or on. If it is turned off, turn it on. If the problem is not corrected, verify that the power cord is attached and functional. If the problem continues or if the power switch is already turned on, then replace the power supply unit.
PSU1010.Message: The DC power supply is switched off.

RAC067.Description: iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation was not successful. This may be due to IPMI communications issues.
RAC067.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, remove AC input power from the server and re-apply AC power to the server and retry the operation. 3) If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
RAC067.Message: iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation was not successful.

RAC0282.Description: This is the number of login failures attempted from an IP address before further login attempts are rejected from that address. The default value is 10.
RAC0282.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Blocking Fail Count. Expected range: 2-16.
RAC0282.Message: IP Blocking Fail Count is invalid. Expected range: 2-16.

PST0082.Description: System is at the BIOS Setup Menu.

RAC0235.Description: When uploading an image to the vFlash partition, the operation is unresponsive, and has timed out.
RAC0235.Resolution: Try uploading the vFlash image again.

UEFI0274.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI login operation did not complete successfully.
UEFI0274.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, make sure the target name is correct. 2) On the iSCSI target system, make sure the initiator name is added into the target identifiers. 3) Compare the authentication settings in the iSCSI initiator setup page to that of the iSCSI target system and make sure the settings match. 4) Retry the operation.
UEFI0274.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI login operation did not complete successfully.

SUP1908.Resolution: Reacquire the image from the original source and retry the operation.

CTL45.Description: The Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) is beginning to malfunction.
CTL45.Resolution: Replace the Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) to avoid data loss or data corruption. The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM.

CBL0002.Description: A backplane power cable was detected, but the accompanying signal cable was not present.
CBL0002.Resolution: Reconnect or replace the signal cable for the backplane identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

HWC0011.Description: The USB drive does not have sufficient free space to copy the file.
HWC0011.Resolution: Make sure the USB drive has sufficient free space before retrying the operation.
HWC0011.Message: Insufficient space to copy the file to the USB drive.

SWC0275.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0275.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0275.Message: Invalid syntax. The -c option is only valid with -f or -g.

SWC0011.Description: The front panel security settings were successfully configured.
SWC0011.Message: Successfully applied front panel security settings.

UEFI0153.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology 2.0 (DPAT 2.0) Enterprise license. Related DPAT 2.0 BIOS settings will be lost if the license is not found in three consecutive reboots.
UEFI0153.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0153.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license. Related DPAT BIOS settings will be lost if the license is not found in three consecutive reboots.

CTL33.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL33.Message: The %1 debug log file has been exported.

SWC0310.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0310.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0310.Message: Invalid syntax. The -f is not valid with the option specified.

OSD68.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareName' is missing.
OSD68.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ShareName" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD68.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareName' is missing.

CTL86.Description: The controller is operating in conjunction with another controller to service the same set of virtual and physical disks, providing better redundancy.
CTL86.Message: %1 is operating in Fault Tolerant Mode.

PWR8598.Description: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) identified in the message is turned off because it is not compatible with the other PSUs in the Chassis.
PWR8598.Resolution: Replace the PSU with an appropriate unit, and then retry the operation. For a list of PSUs that are compatible, consult the system Owner's Manual or contact your service provider.
PWR8598.Message: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) %1 is turned off because it is not compatible with the other PSUs used in the Chassis.

USR8513.Description: Successful login from IP address identified in the message by username identified in the message.

PWR8593.Description: The chassis power operation cannot be performed when a chassis infrastructure firmware update is in progress.
PWR8593.Resolution: Retry the operation after the chassis infrastructure component firmware update is complete.
PWR8593.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on or turn off the chassis because the chassis infrastructure component firmware update is in progress.

RAC0617.Description: An error occurred while generating new iDRAC SSL Certificate or signing it with new custom signing certificate.
RAC0617.Resolution: Make sure to upload an PKCS#12 file that contains a valid custom signing certificate and private key, then retry the operation.
RAC0617.Message: An error was encountered while generating new SSL Certificate.

USR8500.Description: Multiple login attempts were unsuccessful from the identified IP address. After detecting this error condition, this IP address will be blocked from login for the duration specified in the message.
USR8500.Resolution: Make sure the username and password credentials used are correct, wait for the duration specified in the message and then retry the login.
USR8500.Message: Excessive login failures from %1; blocked for %2 seconds.

MEM0006.Message: Memory device at location %1 is present.

RAC0514.Description: Virtual disk(s) cannot be created because of one or more reasons identified in the Recommended Response Action.
RAC0514.Resolution: Check the following: 1) If no physical disk drives are available for virtual disk (VD) creation, install additional physical disk drives. 2) If the maximum number of VDs that can be created on the controller has been reached, a new VD cannot be created until an existing VD is deleted. 3) If the maximum number of VDs supported by drive group has been created, a new VD cannot be created until an existing VD is deleted from the selected drive group. 4) If the physical disk drive(s) are in non-RAID mode, convert them to RAID mode by pressing Ctrl+R while restarting the server, and then select the required controller. Press F2 and select the Convert to RAID capable option, and then complete the operation. 5) If a job is currently running or scheduled on the selected controller, the job must be completed or deleted before attempting a new operation. Status of the scheduled job can be viewed and managed on the Job Queue page on iDRAC. Click Job Queue link to view the status of the scheduled jobs.
RAC0514.Message: Unable to create virtual disk(s) on the selected controller.

PWR8673.Description: Displays voltage change with power configuration change.

VDR49.Description: A redundant virtual disk has lost redundancy. This may occur when the virtual disk suffers the failure of more than one physical disk. In this case, both the source physical disk and the target disk with redundant data have failed. A rebuild is not possible because there is no longer redundancy.
VDR49.Resolution: Replace the failed disks and restore from backup.

SWC0122.Description: The syntax of the sslcertupload command is invalid.
SWC0122.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertupload subcommand.
SWC0122.Message: Invalid syntax. SSL key type (-t) must be specified.

CTL37.Description: A patrol read operation was initiated by the controller or the user.
CTL37.Message: A Patrol Read operation started for %1.

BIOS024.Description: The operation cannot run as the attribute value cannot be modified.
BIOS024.Resolution: For more information on the attribute, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
BIOS024.Message: The set operation did not complete successfully as the attribute is read-only.

LIC904.Description: The network share is not accessible from the iDRAC.
LIC904.Resolution: Verify the network share connection and retry the operation.
LIC904.Message: Could not connect to network share.

RAC1168.Description: The RACADM "getconfig" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.
RAC1168.Resolution: Run the RACADM "racadm get" command to retrieve the iDRAC configuration parameters. For more information on the get command, run the RACADM command "racadm help get".
RAC1168.Message: The RACADM "getconfig" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.

SEL1402.Message: The platform generated a LAN alert.

RAC1058.Description: The requested firmware Rollback operation did not complete successfully because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.
RAC1058.Resolution: Run the RACADM command "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1" to enable Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.
RAC1058.Message: Rollback operation did not complete successfully because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.

RAC0666.Description: A RAID Controller Log is created.
RAC0666.Resolution: To export the Log report, click OK. To delete the report, click Cancel.
RAC0666.Message: A RAID Controller Log is created.

HWC6002.Description: Information and status from the controller is unavailable.
HWC6002.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
HWC6002.Message: The %1 controller is stuck in boot mode.

CTL83.Description: The management controller is not communicating with the storage controller identified in the message. This may be because of any one of the following: a) PCIe subsystem is has stopped functioning b) An issue in the storage controller c) An issue in the management controller.
CTL83.Resolution: Restart the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

JCP030.Description: Unable to schedule jobs for execution while an iDRAC firmware update job is running.
JCP030.Resolution: Wait for the running job to complete, and then retry the operation.
JCP030.Message: Unable to schedule jobs while an iDRAC firmware update or configuration job is running.

CMC8525.Description: The FRU on the sleeve specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8525.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8525.Message: The FRU on the sleeve %1 is not functioning.

PCI3012.Description: System performance may be degraded. The bus is not operating at maximum speed or width.
PCI3012.Resolution: Reset the system, if the problem persists reinstall processors.

RAC0728.Description: The Quick Sync communication or the connection to the iDRAC is no longer functioning.
RAC0728.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove and reseat the bezel. 2) Turn the bezel on by pressing the activation button. 3) Try the Quick Sync feature again. If the issue persists, contact your technical support provider.
RAC0728.Message: The Quick Sync communication is no longer functioning.

VLT0105.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is within range.

RAC011.Description: A Job has already been scheduled to apply pending iDRAC attribute values. Additional configuration operations are not allowed while there is a configuration Job pending execution.
RAC011.Resolution: Wait for the scheduled Job to complete before setting more attributes.
RAC011.Message: A configuration Job already exists, cannot process more set operations.

RAC1047.Description: Successfully cleared the Automatic Update(autoupdate) feature settings.
RAC1047.Message: Successfully cleared the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings.

RAC0656.Description: The iDRAC Service Module (iSM) service cannot be started by just enabling in iDRAC web interface because the service has to also be manually restarted on the server operating system.
RAC0656.Resolution: To re-enable the iDRAC Service Module (iSM), do the following: 1) Enable the iSM in the iDRAC web interface, 2) Start the iSM service on the server operating system.
RAC0656.Message: Are you sure you want to disable the iDRAC Service Module on the server operating system?

VDR23.Description: This message is generated after initialization completes on a virtual disk.

OSD062.Description: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is started and is in progress.
OSD062.Message: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is started and is in progress.

SWU8513.Description: The firmware update operation of IOM infrastructure is successful.
SWU8513.Message: Successfully updated the IOM infrastructure firmware of slot %1.

RAC0506.Description: This error occurs when the user tries to access a program or function that is beyond user granted privileges.
RAC0506.Resolution: Contact the system administrator to perform the operation or grant the required privileges.
RAC0506.Message: You do not have privileges to perform this operation.

OSD24.Description: Unable to continue with DetachDrivers - UnPackAndAttach is in progress.
OSD24.Resolution: Wait until UnpackAndAttach finishes and then run DetachDrivers. This can take more than 5 minutes.
OSD24.Message: Unable to continue with DetachDrivers - UnPackAndAttach is in progress.

SWC0239.Description: The requested object is auto-assigned if IPv6 AutoConfig is enabled, and hence cannot be configured.
SWC0239.Resolution: Disable IPv6 AutoConfig and re-try the command.
SWC0239.Message: The requested object is not allowed to be configured if IPv6 AutoConfig is enabled.

RDU8523.Description: The CMC identified in the message was reset by other CMC. This occurs during failover and CMC firmware update to the standby CMC.

POW002.Description: Host failed to power up because unsupported components installed in Fabric1/fabric2.This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2252
POW002.Resolution: Check for unsupported components installed in Fabric1/Fabric2.
POW002.Message: Power on permission error, unknown component installed in Fabric1/Fabric2.

UEFI0073.Description: When the Secure Boot feature is enabled, the system BIOS authenticates each boot option against the Secure Boot policy. If a boot option does not meet the policy criteria, the system BIOS does not boot to the boot option and displays this message. The Secure Boot policy consists of authorized and unauthorized X.509 certificates; signed boot images must chain to an authorized certificate. The policy may also authorize hash values of individual boot images. Users can configure the Secure Boot feature and the Secure Boot policy in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page.
UEFI0073.Resolution: If the Secure Boot feature is not desired, disable it in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. Otherwise, do the following: 1) review the Secure Boot Policy Summary in F2 System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. The boot option must be authorized by a public key or hash value in the Authorized Signature Database. 2) If the boot option is not authorized but it can be trusted, enter System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page, set Secure Boot Policy to Custom, and add a entry for the boot option in the Authorized Signature Database (System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings > Custom Policy Settings > Authorized Signature Database > Import Database Entry).
UEFI0073.Message: Unable to boot %1 because of the Secure Boot policy.

BAR090.Description: A request to create a System Profile Backup file has been made by the user of the Unified Server Configurator interface.

RAC0628.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested recurrent Automatic Update job is already scheduled.
RAC0628.Resolution: Delete the current scheduled job, and then retry to create a new Automatic Update job with a new schedule.
RAC0628.Message: Unable to schedule, because the requested recurrent Automatic Update job is already scheduled.

RDU8511.Description: For failover, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same firmware version as the primary CMC and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC does not meet this criteria
RDU8511.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8511.Message: Unable to failover, CMC%1 in unknown state.

PDR70.Description: A copyback operation began to copy data from one physical disk to another physical disk. This may be due to a user initiated operation or a predictive failure.

UEFI0170.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because of an attempt to simultaneously configure incompatible A7 mode and Target Address Decode (TAD) 3-way interleave during memory initialization.
UEFI0170.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0170.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

BAR084.Description: System profile backup file validation failed because the host system service tag information does not match the value stored in the file.
BAR084.Resolution: Obtain a valid host system backup image and try the operation again. Reboot the remote access controller and try the operation again. If the error continues, download a new remote access controller firmware image and try the operation again.
BAR084.Message: Host System Service Tag does not match the Backup file Service Tag.

FAN902.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode cannot be set because required power is not available.
FAN902.Resolution: Add PSUs with higher power capability or remove Chassis components such as I/O Modules or servers until the power requirements have been lowered enough to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode, and then retry the operation.
FAN902.Message: Cannot enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode because sufficient power is not available.

PDR17.Description: A user has have assigned a physical disk as a global hot spare. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

UEFI0161.Description: An unsupported DIMM population has been detected on memory slots identified by this message.
UEFI0161.Resolution: Remove all unsupported DIMM modules from the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0161.Message: An unsupported DIMM population has been detected on memory slots: %1.

DIS009.Description: iDRAC IP address sent to Provisioning Server.
DIS009.Message: Notification of iDRAC IP address changed to %1 sent to Provisioning Server.

TMP0102.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0102.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0102.Message: The system board %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

RAC004.Description: The parameter value for the given parameter is invalid.
RAC004.Resolution: Provide a valid parameter value for specified parameter.

ISM0015.Description: The iDRAC Service Module detected a change in the host name of the server OS.
ISM0015.Message: The iDRAC Service Module detected a change in the host name of the server operating system (OS).

BAR092.Description: The attempt to disconnect from the specified NFS location was not successful.
BAR092.Resolution: If this happens on a backup request, restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller and try the operation again. If this is a restore request the Integrated Remote Access will be restarted during the execution of the request. Only restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller if it does not restart on its own.

STOR004.Description: Provided parameter value is not valid.
STOR004.Resolution: Refer to the RAID profile to determine the valid parameters values.

JCP026.Description: Update packages are being downloaded for other jobs initiated on this system. This job resumes when the downloads complete.
JCP026.Message: Update packages are being downloaded. This job resumes when the downloads are completed.

VF042.Description: The remote file could not be found.

PDR114.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message is between 90% and 100% of reaching read-only mode.

PSU0801.Description: The Power Supply had a CRC error detected
PSU0801.Resolution: Acquire the power supply firmware image and update the power supply indicated in the message.

SWC5001.Resolution: Reboot the system and attempt the upgrade again.

RAC1050.Description: One or more required options to configure the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature are missing.
RAC1050.Resolution: For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help systemconfig backup".
RAC1050.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings. The required options are either invalid or not provided.

AMP0300.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0300.Message: The system board %1 current is less than the lower warning threshold.

SWC0007.Description: The export current hardware inventory operation did not complete because the destination: 1) does not have the specified folder, 2) does not have enough free space, or 3) is read-only.
SWC0007.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, verify the following and retry the operation: 1) Destination has the specified folder. 2) Destination has enough free space. 3) Destination is not write-protected.
SWC0007.Message: Unable to write the current hardware inventory to the specified destination.

SUP003.Description: One of the uniform resource input (URI) string, target or reboot flag parameters is missing or exceeds the prescribed length.
SUP003.Resolution: Verify that the URI, target or reboot flag parameter values are correct and retry the action
SUP003.Message: Invalid URI, target or reboot flag.

CTL89.Description: The peer controller is no longer active in this fault tolerant pair. This can be a temporary situation.
CTL89.Resolution: Check the chassis log for issues with the peer controller. If the peer controller does not resume normal operations after 5 minutes contact your service provider.
CTL89.Message: %1 is no longer fault tolerant because the peer controller is not available.

SWC8524.Description: A Chassis Group member already exists with the same hostname or IP address information as the target identified in the message.
SWC8524.Message: Unable to add %1 to Chassis Group because a member already exists with the same addressing information.

RAC1040.Description: The requested RAID storage operation was successfully accepted and now must be applied by creating a RAID storage configuration job.
RAC1040.Resolution: To apply the configuration operation, create a configuration job, and then restart the server. To create the required commit and reboot jobs, run the jobqueue command. For more information about the jobqueue command, enter the RACADM command "racadm help jobqueue".
RAC1040.Message: Successfully accepted the RAID storage configuration operation. The change is in pending state.

SWU8501.Description: This message is displayed when:1. A reboot job is unable to provide a valid reboot ID.2. The WSMAN command to set up a job queue on Lifecycle Controller was not successful.
SWU8501.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the error persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8501.Message: The reinstall/rollback request to Lifecycle Controller on server %1 was not successful.

PST0131.Description: Memory errors occurred copying BIOS image into system memory. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception Code 83)
PST0131.Resolution: Remove input power. Reduce system memory to minimum configuration and apply input power.

RAC1120.Description: The command could not be successfully run, because an incorrect Proxy type value was entered for the -pt option.
RAC1120.Resolution: Make sure that you entered either "http" or "https" as the proxy type. Enter the correct type, and then retry the operation.
RAC1120.Message: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Proxy type is entered.

TST105.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.
TST105.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

LC012.Description: Lifecycle Controller is in use by another process. Wait for other process to complete before attempting to run another command.
LC012.Resolution: Try one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes. 2) Make sure that Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator or an Update Package is not currently running on the server 3) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
LC012.Message: Another process is using Lifecycle Controller.

RED080.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because the required parameters identified in the message is not present in the method invocation.
RED080.Resolution: Verify that all required parameters for the method are present and retry the operation.
RED080.Message: The required parameter %1 is not present.

RAC0646.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'day of the week' while scheduling a job.
RAC0646.Resolution: Enter a correct value, and then retry the operation.
RAC0646.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid value is entered for the day of the week.

ISM0020.Description: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the iDRAC emulated USB device with the OS Collector application was not found.
ISM0020.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
ISM0020.Message: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the iDRAC emulated USB device with the OS Collector application was not found.

PFM0002.Description: The utilization value of the sensor identified in the message is higher than the upper warning threshold.
PFM0002.Resolution: Check the work load of the server and reduce the workload if necessary to bring the system performance into required ranges. For more information about the specified values, see the relevant product documentation available at the support site.
PFM0002.Message: The value of %1 is greater than the upper warning threshold.

BAR072.Description: The vFlash backup partition format operation was not successful.
BAR072.Resolution: Enable and initialize the vFlash media and retry the export. If the issue persists, try a new vFlash media or use the network share option(s).
BAR072.Message: Format of vFlash Backup partition unsuccessful.

SWC0323.Description: The number of records specified to be displayed should be lesser than number of records available.
SWC0323.Resolution: Get the number of records available, and then run the command.
SWC0323.Message: Number of records specified exceeds number of records available.

BAR043.Description: A timeout occurred waiting for the Unified Server Configurator (USC) to exit.
BAR043.Message: Timeout waiting for Unified Server Configurator to exit.

PWR206.Description: The Server Based Power Management (SBPM) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.
PWR206.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR206.Message: The Server Based Power Management (SBPM) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance mode is enabled.

OSD8.Description: The BIOS boot order set to PXE using a standard IPMI command has failed.
OSD8.Resolution: 1) Check BIOS PXE settings. 2) Rerun the command. 3) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD8.Message: Setting Boot to PXE through IPMI failed.

PCI1322.Description: System performance may be degraded. The bus is not operating at maximum speed or width.
PCI1322.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1322.Message: Bus performance degraded for a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

BAR068.Description: The system profile export destination is not supported.
BAR068.Resolution: Insert, enable and initialize supported vFlash media and retry the operation.

STOR007.Description: The operation could not be completed because of insufficient memory space on the management controller (either the iDRAC or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC)) managing the storage.
STOR007.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

RAC986.Description: The "vmkey" sub-command is deprecated, and the functionality is available using "vflashsd" sub-command.
RAC986.Resolution: Use "vflashsd" sub-command instead of "vmkey". For more information about the sub-command, use "racadm help vflashsd" command.

RAC0141.Description: Firmware update verification process failed; the firmware update status is unknown.
RAC0141.Resolution: Verify if the firmware has been updated by checking the new firmware version number. If it has not been updated try the firmware update again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, try uploading the firmware through another interface such as Web GUI, RACADM, or DUPs.
RAC0141.Message: Firmware update verification failed: The update status is unknown.

HWC1103.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message is removed from the unsupported slot identified in the message.
HWC1103.Message: The %1 installed in an unsupported slot %2 is removed.

SWC8509.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required. The Lifecycle log in the server identified in the message may have additional information about the inability of the iDRAC to apply Profile settings.
SWC8509.Message: Unable to apply %1 Profile to server in slot %2

VLT0208.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0208.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0208.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

RAC1006.Description: The update was not applied because of one of the following reasons: 1) The Update Package is invalid. 2) Lifecycle Controller is corrupted. 3) Another update is in progress.
RAC1006.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Download the correct Update Package from your service provider. 2) Use the Lifecycle Controller repair package to repair Lifecycle Controller. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide. 3) Wait until the current update operation is complete.
RAC1006.Message: Unable to process the %1, and the update was not applied.

BOOT011.Description: The provided vFlash partition could not be set for one time boot.
BOOT011.Resolution: Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
BOOT011.Message: Failed to set vFlash partition for one time boot

PWR220.Description: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because the slot identified in the message is empty.
PWR220.Resolution: Insert an appropriate PSU in the slot identified in the message and retry the operation.
PWR220.Message: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because slot %1 is empty.

SYS142.Description: The OS driver pack is deleted because of a System Erase operation.
SYS142.Message: The OS driver pack is deleted.

VDR24.Description: The re-configuration operation on the virtual disk completed.

MEM1013.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in a full state.

VFL0715.Resolution: Contact the administrator for the required permissions and try again.
VFL0715.Message: Error occurred while initializing the SD Card due to insufficient permission.

RAC973.Description: The configuration XML file which was specified for import, had the same configuration as the current system configuration.
RAC973.Resolution: Make any desired system configuration changes to the configuration XML file and retry the operation.
RAC973.Message: The imported configuration XML file matches the current system configuration.

FAN0010.Description: The fan may be required for optimal performance.

TMP0111.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is within range.

JCP032.Description: The configuration job cannot be created because the -r and --realtime options cannot be used at the same time.
JCP032.Resolution: Make sure that only one of either -r or --realtime option is entered. For example, to run a job immediately, enter the --realtime option. To schedule a job that will be run after restarting a server, use the -r option. For more information about options, see the RACADM Command Line Reference Guide available at the support site. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
JCP032.Message: Unable to create a job because conflicting options are entered.

UEFI0268.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI target name is invalid.
UEFI0268.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, make sure the iSCSI Target Name in the iSCSI setup page is correct, and retry the operation.
UEFI0268.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI target name is invalid.

SUP1909.Resolution: Check that the image is available and retry the operation.

HWC0004.Description: The vFlash SD card is incorrectly inserted, the vFlash SD card is faulty, or there is an iDRAC communication failure.
HWC0004.Resolution: Reinsert or replace the vFlash SD card, or reset iDRAC, and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
HWC0004.Message: Unable to initialize vFlash SD card.

SYS075.Description: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file does not exist on the remote share.
SYS075.Resolution: Make sure the import configuration file exists on the remote share before retrying the operation.
SYS075.Message: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file does not exist on the remote share.

PWR2250.Description: The server did not turn on because the chassis infrastructure is not ready. The chassis infrastructure includes: PCIe subsystem, storage components, and the chassis management controller.
PWR2250.Resolution: Check the status of the chassis infrastructure in the CMC Web or RACADM interface. Wait until the chassis infrastructure components are fully turned on.
PWR2250.Message: Unable to turn on the server because the chassis infrastructure not ready.

LOG204.Description: The archive operation did not complete. 10% of the events from the cache will be dropped to make space for new events.
LOG204.Message: Lifecycle Log archive operation did not complete.

VFL1008.Description: An error is reported during a SD card read or write.
VFL1008.Resolution: Re-install the flash media, if the issue persists replace the media.
VFL1008.Message: Failure detected on Removable Flash Media %1.

PDR6.Description: A physical disk in the virtual disk is offline. This may have been user initiated.
PDR6.Resolution: Force the physical disk online or assign a hot spare to the virtual disk.

SYS068.Description: Some configuration changes that require system reboot were not applied because the values specified in the input XML file are incorrect.
SYS068.Resolution: Use the GetConfigResults() method to get the configuration job results or export the Lifecycle Log and review the configuration job results to identify the errors. Make changes to the input XML to correct the errors. Retry the import operation.
SYS068.Message: Configuration changes that require system reboot were not applied.

SWC0701.Description: Power capping is enabled and sets user-defined power capping limits for the system.

SEL0008.Description: When the event log is full, additional events are not written to the log; or older events will be overwritten and lost. This message may also appear if the user disabled event logging. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 04h)

MEM0008.Message: Memory device at location %1 is spare memory.

RED057.Description: An internal error occurred because of insufficient memory available on iDRAC.
RED057.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
RED057.Message: An internal error occurred. Unable to complete the specified operation.

LIC902.Description: Unable to allocate the resource because of lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC.
LIC902.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.

RDU8513.Description: The firmware version of Active CMC and Standby CMC are the same.

RAC0209.Description: Certificate upload failed because iDRAC unable to upload at this time.
RAC0209.Resolution: Try the operation again in a few minutes.
RAC0209.Message: Certificate upload failed: iDRAC unable to upload at this time.

PST0086.Description: System BIOS has launched the Lifecycle Controller user interface.

PDR76.Description: Copyback not possible as SAS or SATA mixing is not supported in the same virtual disk. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR76.Message: Copyback not possible as SAS or SATA mixing is not supported.

RDU0002.Description: One of more fans have failed or have been removed or a configuration change occurred which requires additional fans.
RDU0002.Resolution: Remove and re-install failed fans or install additional fans.

VRM0014.Description: Racadm tool was unable to get the status of the USB interface.
VRM0014.Message: Unable to determine current state of Virtual Media USB interface.

RAC1155.Description: The operation was not completed because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.
RAC1155.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. To enable Lifecycle Controller, run the command 'racadm set LifeCycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1'.
RAC1155.Message: Unable to complete the operation because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.

VME0004.Description: Virtual Media session fails to start.
VME0004.Resolution: Retry the Virtual Media session initiation.
VME0004.Message: Virtual Media session fails to start.

BAT1024.Description: The battery or the battery charger is not functioning properly. The battery may have an inadequate charge.

SWC0124.Description: The syntax of the sslcsrgen command is invalid.
SWC0124.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcsrgen subcommand.
SWC0124.Message: The -u option requires -f to be specified.

SWC0141.Message: Certificate successfully downloaded from the RAC

SYS187.Description: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.
SYS187.Resolution: Retry the operation after the server has finished starting and POST has completed.
SYS187.Message: Unable to start the collection of TTY log data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.

PWR2404.Description: Power supply capacity alert disabled due to user configuration.

SWC0278.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0278.Resolution: Enter the values for the group name and object name correctly.

RAC0242.Description: The vFlash partition does not exist. This may be due to another user deleting that partition.
RAC0242.Resolution: Refresh the Web GUI page to see the available partitions.
RAC0242.Message: The selected partition does not exist.

PDR1121.Message: Drive %1 is no longer in the critical array.

SWC8541.Description: The Profile identified in the message is imported.

CBL8500.Description: SAS cables are not connected to the expander correctly.
CBL8500.Resolution: Check whether or not the SAS cables are connected to the expander. Reconnect the cables and retry the operation.
CBL8500.Message: SAS cable %1 to expander %2 is not connected.

PR6.Description: The configuration values stored for the previous device were applied to the current device.
PR6.Message: Configuration changes successfully applied to device: %1

UEFI0115.Description: The BIOS has recovered the Management Engine after it became unresponsive via the HECI interface. There is no performance degradation and the Management Engine is functioning normally now.
UEFI0115.Resolution: The Management Engine is functioning normally now. No response action is required.
UEFI0115.Message: The Management Engine firmware has recovered from one or more correctable errors.

OSE0004.Description: A separate exception or status condition shutdown the operating system. (IPMI sensor type 20h - offset 04h).
OSE0004.Resolution: Review system event log for platform events capable of shutting the system down.
OSE0004.Message: A soft shut-down initiated by platform event filter.

HWC0014.Description: The import operation failed because the vFlash SD card is missing or disabled.
HWC0014.Resolution: Make sure the vFlash SD card is inserted and enabled before retrying the operation.
HWC0014.Message: Unable to detect vFlash SD card.

STOR038.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because one or more input parameters identified in the message are not valid.
STOR038.Resolution: Specify a valid value for identified parameter.

SYS132.Description: An issue occurred while loading the OS Collector IPMI library. This may be because the OS collector binary images are not valid and need to be re-installed.
SYS132.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS132.Message: OS Collector: Unable to communicate with OS Collector IPMI library.

RAC0213.Description: Login page is missing a username.

SWC8613.Description: The selected profile does not contain setting information for the boot list identified in the message in a usable format.
SWC8613.Resolution: Recreate the profile or use a different profile.
SWC8613.Message: Unable to fully extract %1 boot list settings from the profile.

RAC0743.Description: Unable to perform storage configuration operations because no storage controllers are detected on the server
RAC0743.Message: Unable to perform storage configuration operations because no storage controllers are detected on the server.

JCP005.Description: System services was cancelled by selecting CTRL+E on boot up and cancelling it through the iDRAC configuration utility. This prevents jobs from executing further.
JCP005.Resolution: Enable system services through the CTRL+E on boot up on the target system through the iDRAC configuration utility.

CTL43.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The text for this alert is generated by the utility that ran the diagnostics and can vary depending on the situation.

NIC002.Description: Unable to allocate required memory to perform the operation
NIC002.Resolution: Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.

JCP011.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid and must be corrected for the invoked method to complete successfully.
JCP011.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation. Retry the operation requested with corrected value.

VDR53.Description: The consistency check can no longer report errors in the parity data.
VDR53.Resolution: See the storage hardware documentation for more information on consistency check operation. Contact technical support.
VDR53.Message: The consistency check logging of inconsistent parity data is disabled for %1.

VLT0221.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0221.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0221.Message: The %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SYS159.Description: The vFlash SD Card erase operation was unsuccessful. This may be because the SD card is not enable, not licensed or not initialized.
SYS159.Resolution: Make sure the vFlash SD Card is enabled, licensed and initialized, and then retry the System Erase operation with only the vFlash option selected.

HWC5010.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

PSU8517.Description: The operation to change the PSU redundancy policy is complete.

SWU8552.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC was not successful.
SWU8552.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8552.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Active CMC.

RDU8517.Description: No failover or other action can occur while a CMC firmware update is in progress.

USR101.Description: Unable to allocate the resource because of the lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC firmware.

RAC940.Description: If an existing system profile import or export job is running, then a system configuration profile backup or restore operation cannot be started.
