CPU0801.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0801.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

CMC8517.Description: A double height server is detected in slot specified in the message, however the server is not detected in the bottom slot. This occurs if the server is not correctly inserted into the chassis.
CMC8517.Resolution: Remove the server from the chassis, check for any broken or bent pins at the rear of the server. If there is no damage, reinsert the server into the chassis.

RAC1003.Description: The smart card certificate revocation list (CRL) cannot be enabled, because the object SmartCardLogonEnable is disabled.
RAC1003.Resolution: Enable the object SmartCardLogonEnable using "racadm set iDRAC.SmartCard.SmartCardLogonEnable <1 | Enabled>", and retry the operation.
RAC1003.Message: The smart card certificate revocation list (CRL) cannot be enabled.

USR0032.Description: The session for the username, IP address, and interface identified in the message is logged off.
USR0032.Message: The session for %1 from %2 using %3 is logged off.

SWC8554.Description: The Virtual MAC Address Pool identified in the message is not valid. This can occur because the XML syntax is not correct or because of invalid configuration values.
SWC8554.Resolution: Edit the Virtual MAC Address Pool and correct any XML schema or configuration errors present, and then retry the operation.

PWR8569.Description: The requested power cycle operation cannot be performed when the server is not turned on. The server should be already turned on for the power cycle operation to be successful.

SWC0075.Description: Unable to perform RAID operations because the selected controller is in HBA mode.

SWC0276.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.

VDR92.Description: This message occurs if there are medium errors in the physical drives.

LOG504.Description: The Chassis Log was successfully exported to the destination specified.

SWC0219.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.

FAN0013.Description: The cooling device is not performing optimally. The cooling device may be installed improperly.

UEFI0219.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Read Timing Centering 2D Training phase.
UEFI0219.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.

LC049.Description: The value provided to set the attribute identified in the message is invalid.
LC049.Resolution: For more information on the valid values, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation. Retry the operation with a valid value for the VirtualAddressManagement attribute.

OSD27.Description: Copying drivers for selected operating system failed. The Driver Pack may be unusable.

JCP022.Description: An invalid Job ID was provided as input for a scheduling or deletion operation. The Job ID indicated in the message does not match an existing Job on the target system.

UEFI0111.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during memory test.

UEFI0111.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

VLT0213.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.

RAC929.Description: The category or subcategory specified is incorrect. The recurrence interval is applicable only to the TMPS subcategory and system category.

OSD17.Description: Unable to expose the ISO image as an internal CD device to the host system because the ISO file is no longer present, network errors are preventing access to the ISO file, or iDRAC may not be responsive.

SYS199.Description: The state of Lifecycle Controller is successfully changed to "disabled", but other attributes are not set. When the LifecycleControllerState attribute is set to disabled in the SCP xml file, other attributes settings in the SCP xml file are not applied.
SYS199.Resolution: The Lifecycle Controller state must be "enabled" before performing the import SCP operation and the LifecycleControllerState attribute should not be set to disabled in the SCP xml file while attempting to configure other attribtue settings. To set LifecycleControllerState attribute to enabled using the RACADM command line utility, type "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState Enabled".
SYS199.Message: The state of Lifecycle Controller is successfully changed to "disabled", but other attributes specified in the System Configuration Profile (SCP) xml file are not changed.

CTL88.Description: The firmware running on the controller identified in the message does not match the firmware version of its peer controller. This can cause issues in a fault tolerant setup.
CTL88.Resolution: Make sure each controller is using the same firmware by updating the firmware of the identified controller.
CTL88.Message: %1 firmware does not match the firmware of its peer controller.

FCD8505.Description: Features cannot be deactivated when the chassis is turned on.
FCD8505.Resolution: Turn off the chassis via the Web interface or RACADM command line interface before deactivating the feature. To turn off the chassis using Racadm type "racadm chassisaction -m chassis powerdown". To deactivate the feature using RACADM, type "racadm <feature> -d" where <feature> is the name of the feature to be deactivated.
FCD8505.Message: The features cannot be deactivated when the chassis is turned on.

RAC0225.Description: Sending the test mail failed. This will prevent alert messages from being sent to this email address.
RAC0225.Resolution: Confirm that:1. A valid SMTP server address is configured in the iDRAC. 2. The remote email server is configured properly to send and receive emails.

IOV119.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has disabled PCIe ride-through mode. PCIe adapters that are turned on and in "ride-through" mode are immediately turned off.

RAC0150.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about system intrusion.
RAC0150.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0150.Message: Unable to retrieve the intrusion sensor information. The system is powered off.

RAC957.Description: Another import or export operation cannot be started until the current operation is complete.
RAC957.Resolution: Wait until the current import or export operation is complete before starting another operation. Use the racadm jobqueue view command to check the status of the current import or export operation.
RAC957.Message: An import or export operation is currently in progress.

SYS063.Description: The input file for the import configuration operation does not contain a closed root element.
SYS063.Resolution: Open the input file in any Web browser to check for invalid content before the expected root element. Correct the invalid content and make sure that the XML file is compliant to the system configuration schema before retrying the operation.
SYS063.Message: Input file for import configuration operation is invalid. The expected root element was not closed.

RAC1131.Description: The iDRAC was reset and is successfully restarted.

PDR54.Description: This message is generated after a disk media error is corrected on a physical disk.
PDR54.Message: A disk media error on %1 was corrected during recovery.

NIC500.Description: The values of IP Address is not allowed to change if DHCP is enabled.
NIC500.Resolution: Disable DHCP and then modify the value.
NIC500.Message: The requested object is not allowed to be configured if DHCP is enabled.

PWR8566.Description: Unable to turn off the Server before the Power Off timer has expired. This happens if the Server did not show "power off" status change within 30 seconds after the operation was initiated. This situation may also occur when iDRAC is rebooting.
PWR8566.Resolution: The Server may need more time to turn off. Wait for ten seconds and check the power status. If the Server was not turned off, retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the Server, wait for the iDRAC to complete startup, and retry the operation.
PWR8566.Message: Unable to turn off the Server %1 before the Power Off timer expired.

DIS003.Description: Auto Discovery process will try to connect to a Provisioning Server over the next 24 hours.

SWC8609.Description: The CMC was unable to perform the operation described in the message because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller of the server is disabled.
SWC8609.Resolution: Make sure that iDRAC on the server identified in the message is operating and that Lifecycle Controller is enabled, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform a virtual reseat of the server and retry the operation. To perform a virtual reseat of the server, on CMC Web interface, select Chassis Overview -> Troubleshooting -> Reset Components. On the Reset Components page, select Virtual Reseat from the drop-down menu for the server identified in the message.
SWC8609.Message: Server Profiles: unknown response received from server: %1 for operation [%2] because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller of the server is disabled.

SWC1921.Description: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is disabled.
SWC1921.Message: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is disabled.

PDR23.Description: A disk is degraded and has received a SMART alert (predictive failure). The disk is likely to fail in the near future.
PDR23.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk will cause the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.

STOR055.Description: The BIOS on the server is not Dell Key Management capable.
STOR055.Resolution: For more information about key management capabilities, see Dell Key Manager or Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Guide available at dell.com/support/manuals.
STOR055.Message: BIOS does not support Dell Key Manager capabilities.

RAC976.Description: The configuration XML file export operation was initiated.
RAC976.Resolution: Use the racadm jobqueue view i <Job ID> command to view the status of the operation.
RAC976.Message: Export configuration XML file operation initiated.

VDR96.Description: This message occurs if the virtual disk has bad blocks.
VDR96.Resolution: Replace the disk in the Virtual disk, generating this message.
VDR96.Message: Bad block table on %1 is 80 percent full.

RAC042.Description: The number of input parameters provided is not valid to perform the operation.
RAC042.Resolution: Verify that all required parameters are provided. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

HWC4010.Message: Hardware successfully updated for mezzanine card %1.

SEL9901.Description: The current software version cannot decode this event. The source of the event may come from a source that is not compatible with this software or the event may have been added after the release of this software. You may need to review this event using a tool which displays raw data such as Ipmitool with the -vvv option or Racadm with the -E option.
SEL9901.Resolution: See product documentation for additional information

SWC0018.Description: The BIOS boot mode settings could not be applied due to an internal error.
SWC0018.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit the Lifecycle Controller and perform an AC power cycle.
SWC0018.Message: Unable to apply the boot mode settings for BIOS.

USR0005.Description: Login failed from UserID: IP Address
USR0005.Resolution: Contact the iDRAC administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct.

ISM0012.Description: The IDRAC Service Module is successfully ended on the server OS.
ISM0012.Message: The IDRAC Service Module is successfully ended on the server operating system (OS).

SWC0037.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to export the file to the network share because the destination folder is not present or inaccessible.
SWC0037.Resolution: Make sure that the destination folder is present and accessible, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, check network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0037.Message: Unable to export the file to the network share.

UEFI0093.Description: The DIMM installed on the memory slot identified in the message does not meet the minimum supported frequency.
UEFI0093.Resolution: Remove all unsupported DIMM modules from the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0093.Message: The DIMM installed on the memory slot: %1 does not meet the minimum supported frequency.

RAC072.Description: The iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation cannot be completed because a firmware upgrade operation is in progress.
RAC072.Resolution: Wait for the current update process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC072.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation because the firmware upgrade is in progress.

TMP0122.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0122.Message: The system inlet temperature is outside of range.

SEC0033.Description: The chassis is open while the power is off. System security may have been comprised.
SEC0033.Resolution: Close the chassis and verify hardware inventory. Check system logs.
SEC0033.Message: The chassis is open while the power is off.

LC073.Description: An SSL Certificate cannot be generated because one or more mandatory security attributes are invalid.
LC073.Resolution: Make sure that the security attributes are valid and retry the operation.
LC073.Message: Unable to generate an SSL Certificate because one or more mandatory security attributes are invalid.

SWC0088.Description: The DHCP IP address of iDRAC cannot be retrieved because a network cable is not connected or a DHCP server is not functioning.
SWC0088.Resolution: Make sure that the network cable is connected, DHCP server is turned on, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform the following steps: 1) Turn off the server and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the server, and then retry the operation.
SWC0088.Message: Unable to retrieve the iDRAC DHCP IP address.

PDR14.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC1069.Description: The minimum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.
RAC1069.Resolution: Check the maximum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the maximum critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1069.Message: Unable to set minimum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.

MEM9010.Description: BIOS logged the major and minor code of a QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) Reference Code warning. This information can be reviewed by using a tool which displays raw IPMI SEL log data such as IPMItool with the -vvv option or RACADM with the -E option.
MEM9010.Message: A QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) Reference Code warning message code is logged.

RAC0289.Description: When creating a user account, the same value must be entered for New Password and Confirm New Password.
RAC0289.Resolution: Enter the same values for both New Password and Confirm New Password.
RAC0289.Message: Values in New Password and Confirm New Password fields do not match.

CMC8523.Description: The Mezz card 3 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8523.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8523.Message: The Mezz card 3 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.

VDR29.Description: A mirrored virtual disk is un-mirrored. When a virtual disk is mirrored, its data is copied to another virtual disk to maintain redundancy. After being un-mirrored, the disk formerly used as the mirror returns to being a physical disk and becomes available for inclusion in another virtual disk.
VDR29.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR29.Message: A mirrored virtual disk has been un-mirrored.

RAC038.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in the iDRAC.
RAC038.Resolution: Retry the action. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
RAC038.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

BAR108.Description: The license required for Server Profile Import and Export operations to function is not present.
BAR108.Resolution: Obtain the license for Server Profile Export and Import, install the license and retry the operation.
BAR108.Message: License to Export and Import Server Profile not present.

RAC0901.Description: The syntax of the specified command is invalid. In this case, the usage of the -t option is invalid.
RAC0901.Resolution: See the help text/documentation for the valid syntax of the subcommand.
RAC0901.Message: Invalid syntax. The -t option value must set to 1.

PDR49.Description: The dedicated hot spare is not large enough to protect all virtual disks that reside on the disk group.
PDR49.Resolution: Assign a larger disk as the dedicated hot spare.
PDR49.Message: The dedicated hot spare %1 is too small.

RAC1004.Description: The smart card login cannot be enabled, because the Active Directory Single Sign On is enabled.
RAC1004.Resolution: Disable Active Directory Single Sign On (SSO) using "racadm set iDRAC.ActiveDirectory.SSOEnable <0 | Disabled>", and retry the operation.
RAC1004.Message: The smart card login cannot be enabled.

RAC0744.Description: Unable to perform storage configuration operations because neither Storage controllers nor PCIe Extenders detected on the system.
RAC0744.Message: Unable to perform storage configuration operations because neither Storage controllers nor PCIe Extenders detected on the system.

OSD5.Description: A Driver Pack was not found on the Lifecycle Controller.
OSD5.Resolution: Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and then run the command again.
OSD5.Message: Lifecycle Controller Driver Pack not found.

RAC0501.Description: Physical disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off or the physical disks are removed. This may result in communication loss while retrieving controller data.
RAC0501.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Check if the physical disks are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane. 3. There are no out-of-band capable controllers detected.
RAC0501.Message: There are no physical disks to be displayed.

VF043.Description: The file size is too large to be used.

PDR1017.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is operating normally.

SUP014.Description: An unknown error was encountered while trying to delete the job.
SUP014.Resolution: Retry the action. If this fails, reboot the iDRAC.

PST0209.Description: System BIOS has halted and is unable to continue. System BIOS has detected a Non-Maskable Interrupt (NMI) which may have been caused by a hardware change.
PST0209.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) If new hardware has been added, remove the new hardware and restart the server, 2) Turn server off and back on using the power button, or 3) Remove and reapply server input power. If the problem persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PST0209.Message: System BIOS has halted due to Non-Maskable Interrupt (NMI).

VF022.Description: The size specified is lower than the minimum allowed for a partition.

RAC924.Description: The inlet temperature history was successfully exported to the specified file.

SWU8536.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8536.Resolution: Make sure that the iKVM firmware image file is available at the specified location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8536.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because the Image file could not be accessed. ErrorCode=0x%1.

PWR8527.Description: Server slot power priorities were changed. Power to servers is being reallocated.
PWR8527.Message: Server slot power priorities changed - reallocating power.

HWC2010.Message: The riser board cable or interconnect is connected.

SWC1929.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout value is set to the value identified in the message.
SWC1929.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout value is set to %1.

PDR9.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SYS012.Description: The user credentials provided do not have appropriate privileges to perform the operation requested.
SYS012.Resolution: Retry operation using user credentials that have appropriate privileges to perform the operation.
SYS012.Message: User privileges are not sufficient to perform operation.

LNK8500.Description: The server identified in the message could not be successfully connected to the external network, because the network connection is not functional.
LNK8500.Resolution: Do one of the following, and then retry the operation: 1) Check whether or not the external network cable is functioning. 2) Reinstall or replace network cable of the IOM and port identified in the message.
LNK8500.Message: Unable to connect the server in slot %1 to the IOM in slot %2 port %3, because the IOM port is down.

BAR087.Description: The system profile import of Lifecycle Controller firmware images has failed.
BAR087.Resolution: Apply the Dell Update Package for this system. If the error continues, use the field service repair software to repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download all Dell Update Packages for USC, Diagnostics Driver Packs, and device firmware for all host system devices, install all packages and retry the operation.
BAR087.Message: Unable to Restore the Lifecycle Controller Firmware images.

CTL26.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL26.Message: Copyback and Abort CC on Error has changed for %1.

BAR052.Description: The required device firmware was not found, and the update cannot continue. The device firmware is either not present on the firmware storage partition or does not match the version stored in the configuration information database. No response action is required, however obtaining and installing the update package for the device indicated will update the firmware storage partition. A backup of the server profile is recommended after updating.
BAR052.Message: Firmware update cannot be performed for Device: %1

OSD31.Description: Copying drivers for the selected operating system to network share failed. The share may be read-only or the Driver Pack present in Lifecycle Controller may be unusable.
OSD31.Resolution: 1) Make sure that the network share has write permission. 2) Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and then rerun the command.
OSD31.Message: Copying operating system drivers to network share failed

VDR11.Description: This message is generated after initialization of a virtual disk starts.

SWC0089.Description: One or more iDRAC configurations cannot be saved by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.
SWC0089.Resolution: Make sure that the network cable is connected, DHCP server is turned on, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform the following steps: 1) Turn off the server and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the server, and then retry the operation.
SWC0089.Message: Unable to save one or more iDRAC configurations by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.

USR103.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the operation are missing.
USR103.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation and provide the required parameters.

RAC1033.Description: The server component software inventory cannot be retrieved because of an internal error.
RAC1033.Resolution: Make sure to enable Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature, reboot the server, and retry the operation. If CSIOR is already enabled, restart iDRAC using "racadm racreset" command, and retry the operation.
RAC1033.Message: Unable to retrieve the server component software inventory.

DKM1006.Resolution: Review server error logs for additional information.

UEFI0189.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Transmit DQS DCC phase.
UEFI0189.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0189.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

SWC0291.Description: Another object of the same value exists. Typically in the case of username.
SWC0291.Resolution: Change the specified value and re-try.
SWC0291.Message: Another object exists with the specified value. Duplicate values are not allowed for the requested object.

PWR8532.Description: Server Based Power Management Mode is disabled.
PWR8532.Message: Server Based Power Management Mode is disabled.

CMC8528.Description: CMC is unable to obtain the link tuning or flex address information for the newly installed hardware (server, Input Output Module, or Mezzanine card), or is unable to send the link tuning or flex address information to iDRAC.
CMC8528.Resolution: Make sure that the currently installed CMC firmware is the latest. Otherwise, update the CMC with the latest CMC firmware and retry the operation.
CMC8528.Message: Unable to obtain or send link tuning or flex address data to server-%1.

RAC0260.Description: The specified IPv6 address prefix length is invalid.
RAC0260.Resolution: Enter a valid IPv6 prefix length. Expected range: 0-128.
RAC0260.Message: Invalid IPv6 prefix length. Expected range: 0-128.

RAC0124.Description: All characters in the label must be alphanumeric.
RAC0124.Message: Invalid label: Label must be exclusively alphanumeric characters.

BAR017.Description: A system profile backup file validation has been requested.

RFL2004.Description: The SD card module is installed but improperly configured or failed to initialize.
RFL2004.Resolution: Reinstall the SD module and remove and reinstall SD cards.
RFL2004.Message: Failure detected on Internal Dual SD Module %1.

SUP0118.Message: iDRAC reset failed. Please reset the iDRAC manually to complete the firmware rollback operation.

RED032.Description: The rollback firmware images previously stored were deleted to provide space for storing the firmware images for the requested operation. All the rollback firmware images are deleted.
RED032.Message: Reached maximum size limit allowed for storing firmware images. Deleted all rollback firmware images.

PSU501.Description: The server was already up, when the user gave a power on request.

SYS182.Description: Collecting OS and Application Data cannot be completed because Lifecycle Controller is used by another operation.
SYS182.Resolution: Make sure all other Lifecycle Controller operations are finished and retry the operation. Using the iDRAC Web UI, select Server > Job Queue, check the job queue for unfinished jobs and wait for the jobs to finish before retrying the operation. Also, check whether there are update packages being executed in the server OS and wait for these operations to finish before retrying the operation. For remote web services API access, make sure that the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status, and then retry the operation.
SYS182.Message: Unable to collect OS and Application Data because another Lifecycle Controller operation is currently in progress.

RAC1026.Description: A custom signing certificate must be present in the system to delete or download the certificate.
RAC1026.Message: A custom signing certificate does not exist.

PFM0003.Description: The utilization value of the sensor identified in the message is lower than the lower warning threshold value.
PFM0003.Resolution: The workload on server is almost zero. Consider assigning additional workloads to the server.
PFM0003.Message: The value of %1 is less than the lower warning threshold.

BAT1033.Description: The controller cannot communicate with the battery. Either the battery was removed, or the contact point between the controller and the battery is degraded.
BAT1033.Resolution: Make sure that the battery is present and properly connected. If the battery is present, wait for a few minutes and re-check if the battery is detected. If the contact point between the battery and the controller is degraded, you must replace the battery, the controller, or both. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on how to safely access, or remove. Contact technical support if the issue persists.

DH004.Resolution: Boot the OS. If the error persists, contact technical support.
DH004.Message: iDRAC does not have sufficient free resources to generate keys

SWC0115.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0115.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0115.Message: The -s option cannot be used with any other options.

VFL0703.Message: The SD card initialization was successful.

SWU8557.Description: Invalid firmware: The uploaded firmware image does not contain a verification signature.
SWU8557.Resolution: Use a valid firmware image and retry the operation.
SWU8557.Message: Invalid firmware: The uploaded firmware image does not contain a verification signature.

RAC0903.Description: The syntax of the specified command is invalid. In this case, the usage of the -d option is invalid.
RAC0903.Resolution: See the help text/documentation for valid syntax of the subcommand.
RAC0903.Message: The -d option cannot be used with any other options.

RAC1183.Description: The IP addresses 169.254.0.3 and 169.254.0.4 cannot be assigned to the device identified in the message because the IP addresses entered are reserved for the iDRAC Direct feature.
RAC1183.Resolution: Enter another appropriate IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC1183.Message: Unable to assign IP addresses 169.254.0.3 and 169.254.0.4 to the device OSBMC USBNIC because the IP addresses entered are reserved for the iDRAC Direct feature.

BAR117.Description: The firmware version for the iDRAC contained in the hardware Server Profile image is not compatible with this system hardware. Continue to use the installed firmware version or update to later versions if necessary.
BAR117.Message: The iDRAC firmware cannot be restored due to hardware compatibility restraints.

RAC1005.Description: The hardware inventory was successfully exported.

CTL10.Description: The controller alarm test has run successfully. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC917.Description: The syntax of the specified command is incorrect.
RAC917.Resolution: See the command help text. To see the help text, run "racadm help <subcommand>".
RAC917.Message: The syntax of the specified command is not correct.

UEFI0082.Description: The system was reset due to a timeout from the watchdog timer.
UEFI0082.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) or crash dumps from Operating System to identify the source that caused the watchdog timer reset. Update the firmware or driver for the identified device.
UEFI0082.Message: The system was reset due to a timeout from the watchdog timer.

PDR50.Description: The global hot spare is not large enough to protect all virtual disks that reside on the controller.
PDR50.Resolution: Assign a larger disk as the global hot spare.
PDR50.Message: Insufficient space on the global hot spare %1.

SWC1918.Description: HTTP to HTTPS redirection is enabled. Any iDRAC connection made over the HTTP port (default port number 80) will be redirected to the secure HTTPS port (default port number 443).

UEFI0052.Description: The rebranding process cannot be completed because of the reasons identified on the computer screen.
UEFI0052.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Update the iDRAC firmware. 2) Update the system BIOS. 3) Update the OEM ID module.
UEFI0052.Message: Unable to complete the rebranding operation because of the issue(s) displayed earlier.

STOR12.Description: One or more RAID controllers is disabled. This prevents Fault Tolerant mode from operating.
STOR12.Message: Chassis is operating with a disabled RAID controller.

BIOS003.Description: An invalid number of arguments was passed to the method.
BIOS003.Resolution: Enter all the required command parameters. Check documentation and try again.
BIOS003.Message: Missing required parameter. Refer to the inserted comment.

RAC1039.Description: The subcommand entered is not supported on the specified server.
RAC1039.Message: The subcommand entered is not supported on the specified server.

UEFI0026.Description: iDrac is not responding to BIOS commands. The BIOS will reset the system to retry the initialization process.
UEFI0026.Resolution: Wait for the BIOS to reset the system and reinitialize the iDRAC. If the issue persists, remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.

PST0009.Description: System BIOS has started PCI bus enumeration and video initialization.

PWR8535.Description: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to disable.
PWR8535.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8535.Message: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to disable.

IOID006.Description: The Storage Target Persistence Policy setting is changed to the restart type identified in the message.
IOID006.Message: Storage Target Persistence Policy setting is changed to %1.

NIC022.Description: The current BIOS password jumper setting prevents the BIOS password from being changed.
NIC022.Resolution: Change the jumper setting to enable setting the BIOS password.
NIC022.Message: Unable to set the BIOS password because of a jumper setting on the motherboard.

UEFI0185.Description: A Load-Reduced DIMM (LR-DIMM) buffer initialization failure was detected during memory initialization.
UEFI0185.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0185.Message: Load Reduced DIMM (LR-DIMM) training errors have occurred on memory riser %1.

BAT1023.Description: The battery health has returned to normal.
BAT1023.Message: The charge level for the battery on %1 is within normal limits.

LC032.Description: This method is not supported in the current version of iDRAC firmware.
LC032.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware to a version that supports this method.
LC032.Message: The Hardware Inventory Export method not supported.

SWC4006.Description: FlexAddress is not implemented in one of the versions of firmware. Please update the firmware.
SWC4006.Resolution: Check firmware versions of BIOS and CMC. Update to latest version.
SWC4006.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility detected between system BIOS in slot %1 and CMC.

ENC29.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PDR1005.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is in the critical array.

PSU0077.Description: Power supplies should be of the same input type and power rating.
PSU0077.Resolution: Install matched power supplies and review product documentation for proper configuration.
PSU0077.Message: Power supply %1 vendor type mismatch detected.

RAC0217.Description: Client did not receive a response for the login request.
RAC0217.Resolution: Try pinging the iDRAC and then try again.

HWC7010.Description: Server <number> health changed to a critical state from a non-recoverable state.
HWC7010.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7010.Message: Server %1 health changed to a critical state from a non-recoverable state.

RAC1156.Description: The server network interface information cannot be received because the iDRAC Service Module is not installed or not running on the server operating system (OS) or collection of the OS data is disabled.
RAC1156.Resolution: Run the command 'racadm get iDRAC.ServiceModule' to check if iDRAC Service Module is installed and running on the server operation system, and the collection of the OS data is enabled.
RAC1156.Message: Unable to display the information about the server network interfaces.

RED094.Description: The firmware for the component identified in the message is being updated to the firmware version identified in the message.
RED094.Message: Updating firmware for %1 from version %2 to version %3.

STOR009.Description: Physical disk did not identify valid physical disk for the operation.
STOR009.Resolution: Provide compatible physical disk with the operation.
STOR009.Message: Physical disk FQDD did not identify a valid physical disk for the operation.

RAC1109.Description: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Share type was entered.
RAC1109.Resolution: Enter an appropriate Share location of the following types: FTP, NFS, or CIFS. For more information, run the "racadm help update" command.
RAC1109.Message: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Share type is entered.

LC023.Description: Credentials or network share identity information provided did not result in a network connection being established.
LC023.Resolution: Check network share access credentials (IP address, user name, password, share type, and so on). Refer to Lifecycle Controller Profile documentation for more details.

IOV102.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected the removal of an adapter card from the slot identified in the message.
IOV102.Message: A PCIe adapter %1 is removed from %2 %3.

PWR219.Description: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because PSU in the slot identified in the message is not a 3000 W PSU.
PWR219.Resolution: In order to use the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature, replace the PSU identified in the message with a 3000 W PSU.
PWR219.Message: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature cannot be enabled because the PSU in slot %1 is not a 3000 W PSU.

PST0128.Description: System BIOS was unable to detect memory in the system . This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video (BIOS Post Exception 80).

PDR68.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes
PDR68.Message: Dedicated spare %1 imported as global due to missing disk groups.

PDR63.Description: A write operation cannot complete because the disk contains bad disk blocks that could not be reassigned. Data loss may have occurred. Data redundancy may be lost.
PDR63.Message: A bad disk block on %1 cannot be reassigned during a write operation.

RAC015.Description: The input attribute value is not valid for the attribute identified in the message.
RAC015.Resolution: Provide valid attribute value for the attribute identified in the message and retry the operation.
RAC015.Message: Unable to run the method because the input value is not one of the possible values for AttributeName %1.

LC026.Description: This method is not supported in this version of the iDRAC firmware.
LC026.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware to a version that supports the log export.
LC026.Message: Lifecycle Controller Log Export method is not supported.

RDU0014.Description: The current power supply configuration does not meet the platform requirements to enable redundancy. If a power supply fails the system may shut down.
RDU0014.Resolution: If unintended, review system configuration and power consumption and install power supplies accordingly. Check power supply status for failures.
RDU0014.Message: The power supplies are not redundant.

RAC0740.Description: The Prepare to Remove operation will stop any activity on the PCIe SSD device so that it can be removed safely. The device is safe to remove when the disk shows the safe to remove LED pattern.
RAC0740.Message: The Prepare to Remove operation will stop any activity on the PCIe SSD device so that it can be removed safely. The device is safe to remove when the disk shows the safe to remove LED pattern.

VDR60.Description: There are two modes of virtual disk initialization, full and fast. This initialization type identified in the message is running on the virtual disk identified in the message.

RSI0004.Description: The Remote Service database is unavailable.

RAC955.Description: The specified record does not exist in the Lifecycle Log.
RAC955.Resolution: Run the racadm lclog view -i command to get the sequence number of the records logged in the Lifecycle Log, and retry the command with a valid sequence number.
RAC955.Message: Unable to retrieve the information related to the specified record in the Lifecycle Log.

SWC0285.Description: The value given for the object is not valid.
SWC0285.Resolution: Enter a valid value for the corresponding object.

PWR8595.Description: The turn-on request for the server identified in the message did not succeed because of insufficient power to the chassis component identified in the message.
PWR8595.Resolution: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) will retry turning on the server and the corresponding components associated to the server after a predefined interval. If the issue persists, refer to the Managing and Monitoring Power section in the CMC User Guide for more information on configuring power management settings.
PWR8595.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server %1 due to insufficient power for the %2.

RAC0291.Description: The user name value does not accept these characters.
RAC0291.Resolution: Do not enter /, \, @, ., or " (quotation mark) for user name.
RAC0291.Message: The user name cannot contain: /, \, @, ., or " (quotation mark).

HWC4016.Description: The system has detected a mezzanine card that is not supported on this system.
HWC4016.Resolution: 1) Review system documentation for supported mezzanine cards. 2) Replace mezzanine card with a supported mezzanine card.
HWC4016.Message: Hardware incompatibility detected with mezzanine card %1.

RAC1021.Description: NIC objects are not available if NIC devices are not installed in the system, or if some iDRAC services are busy.
RAC1021.Resolution: Make sure the NIC devices are correctly installed in the system and retry the operation after the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature has updated the system inventory. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC1021.Message: NIC objects are not available in the current system configuration.

SEL1302.Description: The disk in the drive is not formatted correctly or does not contain the necessary operating system files(IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 01h)

LIC024.Description: The License can not be installed, deleted or replaced when the device is on.
LIC024.Resolution: Turn off the respective device and retry the License operation.
LIC024.Message: License operation did not complete successfully because the device is turned on.

VF002.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an internal issue with the firmware.
VF002.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.

RFM1034.Description: The SD card is not detected or not installed.
RFM1034.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
RFM1034.Message: Media not present for Removable Flash Media.

RAC0256.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the Preferred DNS IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0256.Resolution: Enter a valid Preferred DNS Server Address. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0256.Message: The Preferred DNS Server Address is invalid. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].

JCP035.Description: New jobs cannot be created because a backup job is currently running.
JCP035.Resolution: Wait for the running job to complete, and then retry the operation. To view a list of the jobs currently running, use the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view" or using the WSMAN API, enumerate DCIM_LifeCycleJob to view the list of jobs that are currently scheduled.
JCP035.Message: Unable to create new jobs because a backup job is currently running.

SWC0700.Description: iDRAC7 is not ready or is busy and is not responding to iDRAC7 Settings IPMI requests.
SWC0700.Resolution: Turn off the system, Remove AC. Wait for 5 seconds. Connect AC. Turn it on.
SWC0700.Message: iDRAC is not ready. The configuration values cannot be accessed. Please retry after a few minutes.

SWC0001.Description: The network cable may not be connected or an internal error occurred. For more information about the failure, see Lifecycle Log.
SWC0001.Resolution: Verify the network cable is connected and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0001.Message: Unable to save the network settings.

RAC0679.Description: Unable to process the request because a job operation is already running.
RAC0679.Resolution: Wait until the running job is completed or delete the scheduled job and retry the operation.
RAC0679.Message: A job operation is already running. Retry the operation after the existing job is completed.

PDR1004.Message: Consistency check is in progress for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

UEFI0239.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - Calculation phase.
UEFI0239.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0239.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

FAN908.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already disabled.
FAN908.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is already disabled.

CTL16.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL16.Message: None of the %1 properties are set.

SWC0300.Description: There is no coredump available to display.
SWC0300.Message: There is no coredump currently available.

SWC0015.Description: The operating system driver pack is missing or not accessible.
SWC0015.Resolution: Update the system with the latest Lifecycle Controller OS Driver Pack. Obtain the OS Driver Pack from the service provider.
SWC0015.Message: Unable to retrieve the list of supported operating systems.

UEFI0006.Description: A CPU double fault exception (type 0x08) occurred.
UEFI0006.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

PCI1346.Resolution: Reboot the system and update the component drivers.
PCI1346.Message: A software error was detected on a component at slot %1.

PR21.Description: The specified job did not complete successfully.
PR21.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log for more details associated with this failure then retry the operation.

VLT0206.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0206.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0206.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

VDR39.Description: The virtual disk check consistency has identified issues and made corrections. For example, the check consistency may have encountered a bad disk block and remapped the disk block to restore data consistency. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR39.Resolution: No response action is required. As a precaution, monitor the Log for other errors related to this virtual disk. If problems persist, contact technical support.
VDR39.Message: The check consistency has made corrections and completed for %1.

MEM1208.Description: The assigned spare is no longer available.
MEM1208.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>
MEM1208.Message: Memory spare redundancy is lost. Check memory device at location %1.

BAT1012.Description: Diagnostic event for service to determine if there is an ambient temperature problem.
BAT1012.Message: The %1 battery temperature is above normal.

CMC8553.Description: An internal I2C hardware occurred and CMC initiated a failover to clear the hardware error. If the issue persists, contact your service provider..
CMC8553.Message: An internal error occurred and a failover condition is detected.

BAR058.Description: The system profile import or export network destination is being tested for access.

PDR43.Description: This message is generated after a clear operation completes on a physical disk.
PDR43.Message: The clear operation on %1 has completed.

PCI1308.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1308.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1308.Message: A PCI parity error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

BAR047.Description: The System Profile operation was canceled as part of a clean up operation performed during a restart of the Integrated Remote Access Controller.
BAR047.Message: System Profile operation canceled by user.

HWC8506.Description: During a Chassis Management Controller (CMC) firmware update, the control panel firmware synchronization failed. The control panel may be inoperable.
HWC8506.Resolution: Remove and reapply chassis input power. If problem persists, contact your service provider.
HWC8506.Message: Unable to synchronize control panel firmware due to internal error.

RAC0512.Description: Virtual disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, no virtual disks were created, or incorrect filters are applied.
RAC0512.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is ON. 2. Check if virtual disks are created. 3. Check if correct filters are applied. 4. Check if the Storage Enclosure is ON. 5. Verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0512.Message: There are no virtual disks to be displayed.

BAT0007.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may have failed because of thermal exceptions.
BAT0007.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation. 2) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.

RAC0612.Description: Cancelling the firmware update operation will cancel all firmware updates selected and delete all uploaded firmware files.
RAC0612.Resolution: Select Yes to cancel the firmware update operation and delete all uploaded firmware files. Select No to dismiss the message and continue the firmware update operation.
RAC0612.Message: Cancelling the firmware update operation will delete all the uploaded firmware files. Do you want to continue?

UEFI0118.Description: Card identification signature is not present on Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card 2.
UEFI0118.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Check the IDSDM or the SD card media. 2) Try reseat or replace the SD card media. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0118.Message: Card identification signature is not present on Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card 2.

VRM0013.Description: Simultaneously connecting Virtual Media and USB interface is not possible.
VRM0013.Resolution: Detach the USB interface and re-try.
VRM0013.Message: Virtual Media services is currently attached to the USB interface. It must be detached before the image server can be connected.

RDU8520.Description: The standby CMC is recovered from unhealthy state by the monitoring daemon.

RAC062.Description: The WatchdogResetTime can not be set if the IPMI Watchdog state is disabled.
RAC062.Resolution: Enable the IPMI Watchdog state and retry the operation.
RAC062.Message: Unable to set the WatchdogResetTime because the IPMI Watchdog state is disabled.

RAC0725.Description: Unable to update the Quick Sync Firmware.
RAC0725.Message: Unable to update the Quick Sync Firmware.

TMP0119.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0119.Message: The system inlet temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

PST0133.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the DMA controller during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 85)

VF011.Description: The specified password was not correct.

PR3.Description: The current component firmware version is higher than the replaced component firmware version.
PR3.Message: Newer version of firmware found on device: %1

RFL2002.Description: The SD card module is installed but may be improperly installed or configured incorrectly.
RFL2002.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is offline.

CTL20.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL20.Message: Copyback and Load Balance has changed for %1.

OSE1010.Description: The system has successfully booted to ROM.

RAC0267.Resolution: Enter a valid VLAN Priority. Expected range: 0-7.

SWC0160.Message: PK SSH Authentication Key file successfully uploaded to the RAC.

SWC0250.Resolution: Enter the subcommand without any options.
SWC0250.Message: Invalid syntax. The specified subcommand does not require any options.

STOR082.Description: The operation cannot be stopped or canceled because the operation is not currently running.
STOR082.Resolution: Make sure the operation is running before attempting to cancel or stop the operation.
STOR082.Message: The operation cannot be stopped or cancelled because the operation is not currently running.

FAN0000.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.
FAN0000.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan at the next scheduled service window. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0000.Message: Fan %1 RPM is less than the lower warning threshold.

RAC1038.Description: Unable to clear pending values for the specified component. This may be because there is an existing configuration job for the component.
RAC1038.Resolution: Make sure that a config job is not scheduled for this component. For more information, view the help command by running the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue help delete".
RAC1038.Message: Unable to clear pending values for the specified component.

VFL0011.Description: The vFlash media is not disabled.
VFL0011.Resolution: Disable the vFlash media by running the command 'racadm set idrac.vFlashSD.Enable 0'.

RAC0240.Description: vFlash needs to be enabled before attempting this operation.
RAC0240.Resolution: Enable vFlash before trying the operation.

ISM0022.Description: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the application encountered an error.
ISM0022.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the OS Collector on the iDRAC to the most recent version available, and then retry the operation.
ISM0022.Message: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the application encountered an error.

HWC3000.Description: The removed device may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC3000.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-install or reconnect

FAN0014.Description: The cooling device is not performing optimally. The cooling device may be installed improperly.
FAN0014.Resolution: Remove and re-install the cooling device. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0014.Message: %1 RPM is greater than the upper warning threshold.

RAC1029.Description: The certificate cannot be deleted if the certificate type specified is not "3".
RAC1029.Resolution: Make sure to specify "3" for the certificate type (-t) option, and retry the operation.
RAC1029.Message: Unable to delete the specified certificate type.

RED005.Description: The uniform resource identifier (URI) specified for the share location is invalid.
RED005.Resolution: Provide a valid uniform resource identifier (URI) for the share location

STOR040.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because an invalid AttributeName value is specified.
STOR040.Resolution: Specify a valid AttributeName value for the attribute identified in the message and retry the operation.

PDR1003.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is the hot-spare drive.

LC006.Description: The Auto-Discovery action selected is invalid.
LC006.Resolution: Verify that the selected Auto-Discovery action is supported. The supported commands are documented in the Lifecycle Controller User Guide.

VDR52.Description: The data on physical disk members of the virtual disk does not match. Redundancy may be lost.
VDR52.Resolution: Rerun the consistency check task. If you receive this message again, verify the health of the physical disks included in the virtual disk. See the storage hardware documentation for more information. Review messages for significant messages related to the physical disks. If a physical disk has a problem, replace it and restore from a backup copy. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
VDR52.Message: The consistency check found inconsistent parity data on %1.

STOR048.Description: Either the controller or the firmware on the controller does not support the Dell Key Management feature.
STOR048.Message: Controller is not Dell Key Management capable.

RAC0273.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0273.Resolution: Enable remote access to access iDRAC remotely.
RAC0273.Message: iDRAC access will be limited to running the Racadm utility on the local server or using the serial interface.

UEFI0162.Description: An incompatibility has been detected between an installed memory buffer and the downstream DDR channel design.
UEFI0162.Message: A 3 DIMM Per Channel (DPC) configuration has been detected on a 2 DPC memory buffer.

HWC2001.Description: The cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC2001.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC2001.Message: The %1 cable or interconnect is not connected or is improperly connected.

PWR8581.Description: A chassis power operation is currently in progress and the server identified in the message could not be turned on.
PWR8581.Resolution: Wait until the current chassis power operation is complete and the chassis is On and then retry the operation.
PWR8581.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because another chassis power operation is in progress.

RAC939.Description: The request to perform a system profile export or import operation cannot be started because a firmware update operation is already in progress.
RAC939.Resolution: Wait until the update operation is completed or cancel the update operation, and retry.
RAC939.Message: Unable to start the system configuration profile export or import operation.

LC007.Description: One of the parameters specified in the method is invalid.
LC007.Resolution: Verify that the parameters specified are correct. For a list of parameters for this method refer to the Lifecycle Controller User Guide.

JCP038.Description: The job (installation or configuration job) identified in the message cannot be run. For more information, see the Job Queue.
JCP038.Resolution: See the Job Queue by using racadm jobqueue view -i <job ID> or navigating to the Jobs page in the iDRAC GUI.
JCP038.Message: Unable to run the (installation or configuration) job %1 because %2.

RAC1056.Description: The requested firmware Rollback operation was initiated successfully.

SWU8518.Description: The server was pulled out from the chassis during the iDRAC firmware update operation.
SWU8518.Resolution: Reinsert the server and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8518.Message: The firmware update operation on the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is stopped.

PSU0041.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0041.Message: An output over voltage fault detected on power supply %1.

RAC1184.Description: The getuscvresion RACADM subcommand will be deprecated in a future release.
RAC1184.Resolution: Instead of getuscversion, run the getversion -f lc subcommand.
RAC1184.Message: The getuscvresion RACADM subcommand will be deprecated in a future release.

RAC1025.Description: Some objects have dependencies on other objects that are required to perform a task. However, some of the objects are read-only because of the current system configuration and the values of the dependent objects.
RAC1025.Resolution: Verify the object dependency using "racadm help <device class>.<groupname>.<objectname>", and retry the operation.
RAC1025.Message: The specified object is read-only and cannot be modified due to an object dependency.

SYS128.Description: Unable to generate a zip archive of the OS and Application Data report.
SYS128.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS128.Message: OS Collector: Unable to generate a zip archive of the OS and Application Data report.

FC006.Description: A configuration job already exists for the specified target. No further configuration operations are allowed until the existing job is competed or the job is cancelled.
FC006.Resolution: Wait until the existing configuration job for the targeted component is complete or cancel the existing job before retrying the operation.
FC006.Message: Configuration job already created, cannot set attribute on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled.

SWC0027.Description: The backup Server Profile operation successfully completed.
SWC0027.Message: Successfully backed up a Server Profile by using the Lifecycle Controller GUI.

RAC1035.Description: The command is unable to clear the pending state for attributes of the specified component because there are no pending values.
RAC1035.Resolution: Make sure that there is at least one attribute on the specified device has a pending value, and retry the operation.
RAC1035.Message: There are no pending values to be cleared.

CTL38.Message: The Patrol Read operation completed for %1.

TMP6.Description: You have changed the value for the minimum temperature probe warning threshold. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
TMP6.Message: The temperature probe minimum warning value was changed on %1.

SWC1930.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync feature is set to automatically disable after a specified inactivity time.
SWC1930.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout feature is enabled.

SWC1917.Description: HTTP to HTTPS redirection is disabled. Any iDRAC connection made over the HTTP port (default port number 80) will no longer be redirected to the secure HTTPS port (default port number 443). This will make the connections insecure as the data transmitted over the port is no longer encrypted.

HWC7000.Message: Server %1 health changed to a normal state.

RAC1008.Description: The Active Directory object DCLookupByUserDomain cannot be disabled, because the Active Directory object DCLookupDomainName is not configured.
RAC1008.Resolution: Configure the Active Directory object DCLookupDomainName using "racadm set iDRAC.ActiveDirectory.DCLookupDomainName <Name>", and retry the operation.
RAC1008.Message: The Active Directory object DCLookupByUserDomain cannot be disabled.

SWC0290.Description: Failed to configure the object specified in the error message.
SWC0290.Message: Failed to configure object. Group: %1, Object : %2

PWR8682.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the storage sled controller identified in the message. The Chassis storage sled controller is unable to turn on due to a configuration or hardware issue.
PWR8682.Resolution: Remove the storage sled identified in the message, re-insert it and observe whether the issue is resolved. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8682.Message: Unable to turn on the storage sled controller %1 in slot %2 because the %3 module is not functioning.

RED0101.Description: The firmware was rolled back to the previous version.

RAC1052.Description: The Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature is not enabled.
RAC1052.Resolution: To enable, run the RACADM command "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.lcattributes.autobackup 1".
RAC1052.Message: The Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature is not enabled.

RRDU0006.Description: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild initiated.
RRDU0006.Message: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild initiated.

SEC0613.Description: The default username and password is changed.
SEC0613.Message: The default username and password is changed.

SWC0281.Description: The value being modified is READ only.
SWC0281.Message: The specified object is READ ONLY and cannot be modified.

ENC32.Description: The SEP has been rebooted as part of the firmware download operation and will be unavailable until the operation completes.
ENC32.Message: Storage Enclosure Processor (SEP) for %1 has been rebooted.

STOR058.Description: The operation is not supported on the target device.
STOR058.Resolution: For more information, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
STOR058.Message: This operation is not supported on this device.

SWC0120.Description: The syntax of the sslcertview command is invalid.
SWC0120.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertview subcommand.
SWC0120.Message: Invalid syntax. Certificate type (-t) must be specified.

STOR3.Description: Storage Management has lost communication with a controller. This may occur if the connectivity between the controller and iDRAC is disrupted or any underlying hardware problems are encountered.
STOR3.Resolution: Reboot the system or iDRAC. If the problem is not resolved, contact technical support.
STOR3.Message: CEM Storage Management has lost communication with the %1.

LNK0001.Description: The entered network share name is not valid.
LNK0001.Resolution: Enter a valid network share name and retry the operation. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.

SWC8604.Description: The target server identified in the message does not support server configuration using profiles.
SWC8604.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Server %1 does not support configuration using profiles.

SWU8534.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation is not successful.
SWU8534.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8534.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware.

BOOT012.Description: A job was created to configure a OneTime boot to the specified vFlash SD card partition. If this partition was not attached to the system, the job attaches it as well.
BOOT012.Message: Job started to attach and set vFlash SD card partition for OneTime boot.

PSU1004.Description: The enclosure detected that AC power supply was restored to the power supply unit.
PSU1004.Message: Power supply cable has been inserted into %1.

RRDU0007.Description: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild completed successfully.
RRDU0007.Message: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild completed successfully.

RAC0723.Description: The Chassis Management Controller firmware version identified in the message is earlier than the version required to support the server.
RAC0723.Resolution: Update the Chassis Management Controller firmware to the required version identified in the message.
RAC0723.Message: The firmware version %1 of the Chassis Management Controller is earlier than the required version %1.

CTL21.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL21.Message: Abort CC on Error and Load Balance has changed for %1.

HWC1002.Resolution: If device disabled unexpectedly, re-enable device.

STOR079.Description: The requested operation cannot be performed because it is either not supported by the device or the device was not in the right state to perform the operation.
STOR079.Resolution: Make sure the device supports the requested operation. If the operation is supported, then make sure the server is turned on and retry the operation.
STOR079.Message: The device does not support this operation or is in a state that does not allow this operation.

BAR061.Description: Collecting system information and copying it into the backup file. The operation collects system information that includes System Model and Service Tag.

RRDU0003.Description: Either one of the SD card or both the SD cards are not functioning properly.
RRDU0003.Message: Internal Dual SD Module redundancy is degraded.

CTL22.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

UEFI0100.Description: The Memory Mirroring feature cannot be enabled because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.
UEFI0100.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0100.Message: Unable to enable the Memory Mirroring feature because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.

CMC8563.Description: The KVM is mapped to the server slot number specified in the message.
CMC8563.Message: The KVM is mapped to the server slot %1.

JCP033.Description: This job is newly created. This is the default message in a job when it has just been created..

BOOT008.Description: More source arguments were provided than are available for the impacted Boot Configuration.
BOOT008.Resolution: Verify that all of the Boot Source instance IDs being entered are as they appear in the DCIM_BootSourceSetting enumeration.
BOOT008.Message: Source argument contains more devices than are present on the system

CMC8514.Description: This error may occur due to any of the following conditions: 1) Invalid I/O Module and mezzanine card configuration, where a newly installed I/O Modules fabric type and the resident mezzanine cards fabric types do not match or are incompatible. 2) Invalid I/O Module and I/O Module configuration, where a newly installed I/O Module has a different or incompatible fabric type from an I/O Module already installed in the fabric.
CMC8514.Resolution: Refer to Chassis Management Controller User's Guide for additional information.
CMC8514.Message: Fabric mismatch is detected in the I/O Module %1.

LIC006.Description: The license end date has been reached.
LIC006.Resolution: Obtain a replacement license and import it.

VFL0704.Resolution: Insert the SD card and try again.
VFL0704.Message: SD card is not present and could not be initialized.

JCP037.Description: The job (installation or configuration job) identified in the message is successfully completed on iDRAC.
JCP037.Message: The (installation or configuration) job %1 is successfully completed.

SWC1913.Description: Network Time Protocol configuration is enabled.
SWC1913.Message: Network Time Protocol configuration is enabled.

CTL85.Description: The controller identified in the message experienced a PCIe training error and is operating at less than full bandwidth. Until this issue is resolved, a reduction in the storage performance is expected.
CTL85.Resolution: Perform a Powercycle operation on the Chassis. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CTL85.Message: %1 is operating at less than optimal bandwidth.

SUP0516.Description: Do not turn off the system while firmware update is in progress.

SWC0085.Description: Integrated Data Center Mode is disabled because of one of the following reasons: 1) The feature was disabled 2) The server is not supported for the Integrated Data Center solution 3) The default user credentials on the iDRAC were changed 4) Supression of the default credentials warning was selected.
SWC0085.Message: The Integrated Data Center mode is disabled.

SWC0314.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0314.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0314.Message: Invalid syntax. The -o option requires -g to be specified also.

RAC0709.Resolution: Acquire the latest Chassis Management Controller (CMC) firmware that supports the server indicated and update the CMC to at least that version.

IOV108.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected a power fault in an adapter after the adapter was powered on. A power fault may be caused by a damaged adapter or the adapter power requirements exceed the maximum power limits of the slot.
IOV108.Resolution: Make sure a supported PCIe device is used and that it is properly inserted in the PCIe slot. For a list of supported devices, contact your service provider.
IOV108.Message: Power fault detected on PCIE adapter %1 in %2 %3.

SWC0292.Description: The queried object does not exist at the specified index.
SWC0292.Resolution: Check for the objects available at the specified index and re-try.
SWC0292.Message: The specified object at index %1 does not exist.

PDR25.Description: Portions of the physical disk that were formerly inaccessible have been recovered. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

STOR066.Description: The requested operation did not succeed because the selected RAID controller is not T10 Protection Information capable.
STOR066.Resolution: Verify that the RAID controller selected for the operation is T10 Protection Information capable, and then retry the operation.
STOR066.Message: Controller is not T10 Protection Information capable.

BIOS011.Description: Configuration job already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job is completed.
BIOS011.Resolution: Cancel the configuration job or wait for the job to complete. Refer to documentation on job cancellation.
BIOS011.Message: Configuration job already created, pending data cannot be deleted

UEFI0240.Description: An error occurred during Memory Voltage Regulator initialization during the VR0 SVID Ramp phase.
UEFI0240.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0240.Message: An error occurred during Voltage Regulator (VR) initialization on memory riser %1.

USR0019.Description: The specified username exceeds the prescribed limit (255)
USR0019.Message: Specified user name is too long.

SWC0090.Description: iDRAC is successfully configured by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.
SWC0090.Message: iDRAC is successfully configured by using the Initial Setup feature of Lifecycle Controller.

SYS039.Description: The requested configuration changes have not passed the component specific verification checks, and therefore the changes will not be applied.
SYS039.Resolution: Check the scripts or related documentation and retry the operation.
SYS039.Message: Verification of requested configuration changes failed.

PR26.Description: The configuration data associated with the specified job could not be located.
PR26.Resolution: Retry the operation. If this issue persists, contact technical support.

MEM9008.Description: A non-recoverable issue was detected in the propagation of signals on the Intel DDR memory interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9008.Resolution: Reseat all DIMMs on the memory riser, reseat the memory riser, and restart the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9008.Message: Intel DDR Memory interconnect %1 has a non-recoverable issue.

RAC0756.Description: Fan information cannot be displayed. This situation may occur if the server is powered off.
RAC0756.Resolution: Power on the server. If the server is already powered on, wait for a few minutes and refresh the page. If the problem persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0756.Message: Unable to retrieve the fan information.

NIC507.Description: For the requested operation, enable the NIC to get the NIC details.
NIC507.Resolution: Check if the NIC is disabled. If disabled, enable the NIC.
NIC507.Message: Unable to determine current NIC state.

SYS036.Description: The configuration settings could not be applied to the component. This may indicate configuration changes since the last system inventory collection was completed.
SYS036.Resolution: Retry the operation or try the attribute set operation for the component.
SYS036.Message: Unable to apply the configuration to the component.

PCI1344.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1344.Message: An I/O channel check error was detected.

PWR2006.Message: The OS run-time software initiated a warm reset.

VDR46.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC0054.Description: There was an internal error while saving the settings.
SWC0054.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system or update the Lifecycle Controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.

LIC022.Description: License Manager database is locked while a backup and restore operation is in progress. License import/export/delete operations are not allowed but a user can view license information.
LIC022.Resolution: Wait until the backup or restore operation completes and try again.
LIC022.Message: License Manager database locked due to ongoing backup and restore operation.

SWC8607.Description: The Quick Deploy of Profile process has started for the server identified in the message.
