SWC8607.Message: Quick Deploy Profile: Starting to apply profile %1 to server %2.

SYS029.Description: The parameter name is not supported.
SYS029.Resolution: Remove the unsupported parameter and retry the operation.

SUP0131.Message: FTP firmware update has been initiated. This update process may take several minutes to complete.

CTL66.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL66.Message: Attempted to import Unsupported Virtual Disk type RAID%1 on %2.

RAC950.Description: The work note cannot be added to the Lifecycle Log if iDRAC is archiving the older records in the Lifecycle Log.
RAC950.Resolution: Wait for several minutes while iDRAC archives the older records, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC950.Message: Unable to add the work note to the Lifecycle Log.

SWC0273.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0273.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0273.Message: Invalid syntax. The -g option requires -o to also be specified.

PWR8506.Description: Resetting the power computation reading causes the log to report time at which it is reset.
PWR8506.Message: Cumulative power computation (KWH) time is reset on %1.

SEC0608.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0608.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

BAR064.Description: Collecting the Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware and copying it in the server profile backup file.
BAR064.Message: Collecting Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

PDR87.Description: The physical device was reset. This is a normal part of operations and is not a cause for concern.

SWC8500.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required.
SWC8500.Message: Unable to generate Profile with [ %1 ] settings.

RAC0699.Description: The value for Minimum Fan Speed must be within the range identified in the Recommended Response Action.
RAC0699.Message: Invalid value for Minimum Fan Speed.

RED061.Description: The job is successfully scheduled. The job will automatically start at the specified start time.

UEFI0022.Description: The Management Engine firmware cannot be initialized because the Management Engine is not responding.
UEFI0022.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0022.Message: Unable to initialize Management Engine because the Management Engine is not responding.

VLT0231.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0231.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the mezzanine card.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0231.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

RAC041.Description: The event filters set operation did not complete successfully due to invalid input parameters.
RAC041.Resolution: Verify the specified input parameters and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC041.Message: The set operation on the event filters failed.

USR0183.Description: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature is detected.
USR0183.Message: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature is detected.

UEFI0187.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Clock Detection phase.
UEFI0187.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0187.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RAC0505.Description: Devices are not displayed. This error may occur because these components are removed or disconnected.
RAC0505.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is ON. 2. Check if the Storage Enclosure is ON. 3. Verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0505.Message: There are no devices to be displayed.

RAC0245.Description: The vFlash partition is in-use by another process. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0245.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes or with another partition. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.
RAC0245.Message: The partition is in-use by another process.

RDU0019.Message: The storage voltage is not redundant.

SWU001.Description: The expander or storage enclosure processor firmware is successfully updated.
SWU001.Message: The expander or storage enclosure processor firmware is successfully updated.

UEFI0095.Description: A DIMM with unsupported voltage is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0095.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module and replace it with a DIMM with a supported voltage. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0095.Message: A DIMM with unsupported voltage is installed on memory slot %1.

CPU0819.Message: The power input for CPU %1 voltage regulator module has been restored.

RED091.Description: Unable to install Lifecycle Controller firmware.
RED091.Resolution: Reinstall the iDRAC7 firmware (DUP) to repair Lifecycle Controller. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
RED091.Message: Unable to install Lifecycle Controller firmware.

BAT0004.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0004.Resolution: Check the system board battery to confirm presence.
BAT0004.Message: The system board battery is absent.

UEFI0232.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Configuration Write phase.
UEFI0232.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0232.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

VDR13.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

CTL6.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL6.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.

STOR0106.Description: No fan data to display. The system is powered off, no fan enclosures are present in the system, or the fans are not connected to the enclosures.
STOR0106.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosure fan is available, and fan is connected to the enclosure.
STOR0106.Message: Fans are not connected to enclosures or data about fans is unavailable.

LC074.Description: The Certificate export operation did not complete successfully.
LC074.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation.
LC074.Message: The Certificate export operation did not complete successfully.

RED065.Description: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were applied. A system restart was not required.
RED065.Message: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were applied. A system restart was not required.

BAT1022.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SEL1308.Description: The system has failed to boot to an operating system and needs the user to select a boot source. (IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 04h)
SEL1308.Resolution: Select boot source within the time allowed.
SEL1308.Message: A time-out occurred while waiting for user to select a boot source.

PDR4.Description: A physical drive that was previously in an error state has returned to a ready state.

RAC0132.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while formatting the vFlash partition.
RAC0132.Message: An error has occurred while formatting a partition.

BAT1030.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1030.Message: The %1 battery charge level is normal.

BIOS025.Description: The status of the password is Locked in BIOS and must be set to Unlocked for the operation to succeed.
BIOS025.Resolution: Change BIOS password status in the BIOS setup from Locked to Unlocked and retry the operation.
BIOS025.Message: Unable set the BIOS password as the BIOS password status is locked.

NIC007.Description: A configuration job already exists for the specified target. No further configuration operation is allowed until the existing job completes or the job is cancelled.
NIC007.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Wait for the existing configuration job to complete and retry the operation, 2) To continue with a configuration change, cancel the existing job and retry the operation.
NIC007.Message: A configuration job already exists, Cannot create another configuration job on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled

BAR050.Description: The firmware update for the specified device in progress.

RAC1153.Description: The time stamp was not recorded for the previous techsupreport collect operation.
RAC1153.Resolution: Run the RACADM techsupreport collect command. After the techsupreport collect operation completes, run the RACADM getupdatetime command.
RAC1153.Message: The time stamp is not available to display.

RDU0004.Description: One of more fans have failed or have been removed or a configuration change occurred which requires additional fans.
RDU0004.Resolution: Remove and re-install failed fans or install additional fans.

CPU0003.Resolution: 1) Turn off the server and disconnect input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Reduce system configuration to minimum memory and remove all PCI devices. If system completes POST, update system BIOS. Re-install memory and PCI one component at a time to meet the original configuration. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

RED024.Description: Lifecycle Controller is in use or currently processing another job. The specified job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.
RED024.Resolution: Wait for current Lifecycle Controller task to complete.
RED024.Message: The specified job starts when Lifecycle Controller is available.

SUP020.Description: The specified job was successfully deleted from the job queue.

SEL1400.Message: The platform generated a page alert.

RRDU0008.Description: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild failed because read/write to one of the SD cards failed.
RRDU0008.Resolution: Replace the failed SD card and retry rebuild.
RRDU0008.Message: Internal Dual SD Module rebuild did not complete successfully.

RAC0226.Description: Sending the test mail failed. This will prevent alert messages from being sent to this email address.
RAC0226.Resolution: Confirm that:1. A valid SMTP server address is configured in the iDRAC. 2. The remote email server is configured properly to send and receive emails.

CMC8508.Description: The Extended Storage feature is not activated if the removable flash media SD Card on the secondary CMC is not functioning properly.
CMC8508.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration, and verify if the SD card on secondary CMC displays errors. 2) If errors are displayed, execute the following racadm command: "racadm cmcchangeover". 3) Repair the removable flash media SD Card by selecting the Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration > Repair Active Controller Media in the CMC Web interface. Repairing is only allowed on the SD card of the primary CMC. If the problem persists, replace the card.
CMC8508.Message: Unable to synchronize the primary and secondary CMC removable flash media and the Extended Storage feature is not available.

MEM0702.Description: The memory may not be operational. This an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0702.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM0702.Message: Correctable memory error rate exceeded for %1.

RAC0904.Description: The iDRAC cannot access the remote file location. The credentials or path to the remote file location is incorrect or iDRAC cannot connect to the network address.
RAC0904.Resolution: Confirm that the path and credentials to remote file are correct, and check that the iDRAC can connect to the network address.
RAC0904.Message: The remote file location is not accessible or reachable.

SWC8618.Description: The request for the WS-Man method identified in the message for server in slot identified slot is unsuccessful.
SWC8618.Resolution: Make sure that iDRAC is ready and system is functioning correctly. run the RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure that the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required.
SWC8618.Message: Server Profiles: request %1 for server in slot %2 was unsuccessful. Message ID %3. Returned fault: %4.

RAC0603.Description: The Job Queue is updated with the selected update jobs. The status of the update jobs can be viewed and managed within the Job Queue page.
RAC0603.Resolution: Click Job Queue button to view the status of the update jobs.
RAC0603.Message: Updating Job Queue. Status of the update jobs can be viewed and managed within the Job Queue page.

CTL32.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL32.Message: Abort CC on Error is modified for %1.

UEFI0105.Description: The Cluster on Die (COD) feature cannot be enabled because of an unsupported memory configuration.
UEFI0105.Resolution: Make sure to populate all memory channels in the system with a minimum of one DIMM per channel. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0105.Message: Unable to enable the Cluster on Die (COD) feature because of an unsupported memory configuration.

VDR26.Description: You paused the Check Consistency operation on a virtual disk.
VDR26.Resolution: To resume the Check Consistency operation, right-click the virtual disk in the Storage Management tree view and select Resume Check Consistency.
VDR26.Message: The check consistency on a %1 has been paused (suspended).

SWC0114.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0114.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0114.Message: The -o option cannot be used with any other options.

SUP0125.Message: Current firmware update status is unknown

UEFI0033.Description: The NVRAM_CLR jumper is installed to clear the BIOS configuration. After clearing the BIOS configuration, remove the NVRAM_CLR jumper so that the system can function normally and any non-default BIOS system setting changes can be persistently saved.
UEFI0033.Resolution: To change the system BIOS settings and persistently save the settings, remove the NVRAM_CLR jumper and then go to the System Setup to configure system settings.
UEFI0033.Message: Default system BIOS settings are in use because NVRAM_CLR jumper is installed on the system board.

NIC015.Description: A set attribute operation was attempted on a read only attribute.
NIC015.Message: AttributeValue cannot be changed to read only AttributeName %1.

TMP8500.Description: The temperature of the I/O Module identified in the message has increased beyond the operational range. Thermal protection shut down the I/O Module. Factors external to the I/O Module may have caused this situation.
TMP8500.Resolution: Check the chassis event log for fan issues and fix any issues present. If no fan issues are detected, check chassis ambient temperature and make sure the temperature is within operating range. Utilize the RACADM command "racadm getsensorinfo" to check the chassis ambient temperature.
TMP8500.Message: I/O Module %1 temperature exceeded operating range.

PFM0001.Description: The utilization value of the sensor identified in the message is higher than the upper critical threshold.
PFM0001.Resolution: Check the work load of the server and reduce the workload if necessary to bring the system performance into required ranges. For more information about the specified values, see the relevant product documentation available at the support site.
PFM0001.Message: The value of %1 is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SWC0084.Description: The iDRAC has successfully joined Integrated Data Center network. This iDRAC will now be managed by the Integrated Data Center solution.
SWC0084.Message: The iDRAC successfully joined Integrated Data Center network.

RDU0005.Description: One of more fans have failed or have been removed or a configuration change occurred which requires additional fans.
RDU0005.Resolution: Remove and re-install failed fans or install additional fans.
RDU0005.Message: The fans are not redundant. Insufficient resources to maintain normal operations.

SWC0064.Description: The details provided to access the network share are incorrect.
SWC0064.Resolution: Enter the correct network share details, and retry the operation.
SWC0064.Message: Unable to mount the network share.

RAC990.Description: If Lifecycle Controller is disabled, the firmware update operation cannot continue.
RAC990.Resolution: Enable Lifecycle Controller using the "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.lcattributes.lifecyclecontrollerstate 1" command, and retry the operation.

RAC0250.Description: The vFlash partitions are read-only. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0250.Resolution: Make sure the partitions are writable before attempting to change their contents.
RAC0250.Message: One or more partitions are read-only.

CMC8522.Description: The Mezz card 2 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8522.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8522.Message: The Mezz card 2 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.

PDR15.Description: This message is generated after a rebuild completes on a physical disk.

USR0030.Description: Successful login for the username, IP address, and interface identified in the message.
USR0030.Message: Successfully logged in using %1, from %2 and %3.

SYS136.Description: An issue was encountered while communicating with iDRAC Service Module (iSM) present on the operating system.
SYS136.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Restart the iDRAC Module Service on the OS and retry the operation. 2) Stop iDRAC Service Module Service on the OS and try manually executing the OS Collector application .
SYS136.Message: An issue was encountered while communicating with iDRAC Service Module (iSM) present on the operating system.

PSU8501.Description: Unable to retrieve input voltage information for the PSU specified in the message.
PSU8501.Resolution: Remove the PSU from the chassis, wait for two minutes, and reinsert it. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8501.Message: Unable to retrieve PSU %1 input voltage information.

BAR051.Description: The configuration import for the specified device is in progress.
BAR051.Message: Performing Component Configuration Restore for Device : %1

RAC0712.Description: Server failed to power up due to zero power allocated.
RAC0712.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller web interface to check available power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, allocate power necessary and retry the operation.
RAC0712.Message: Server failed to power up due to zero power allocated.

ENC15.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
ENC15.Message: An enclosure blink operation has initiated on %1.

BAR109.Description: The OEMDRV partition is mounted for performing operating system deployment use. This situation prevents the Export and Import Server Profile operation from continuing.
BAR109.Resolution: Dismount the OEMDRV partition by selecting F10 during boot and retry the operation.

RAC1112.Description: Unable to clear the pending state from the attributes for a RAID object. A job is currently running and iDRAC internal storage is in use.
RAC1112.Resolution: Retry the operation after any currently running jobs have completed. Jobs can be monitored by running the racadm command "racadm jobqueue view".
RAC1112.Message: Unable to delete the pending values for the specified device because the iDRAC internal storage is in use by a currently running job.

RED087.Description: Unable to update the Chassis firmware because the Allow CMC Updates Through OS and Lifecycle Controller setting is set to Disabled.
RED087.Resolution: Make sure that the Allow CHC Updates Through OS and Lifecycle Controller setting is set to Enabled, and then retry the operation. Using the iDRAC Web UI, select iDRAC > Update, click on the Settings tab, select Enabled for the setting and then click Apply button.
RED087.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware, Allow CMC Updates Through OS and Lifecycle Controller is set to Disabled.

LC019.Description: The PKCS12 string could not be decoded from the Base64 encoding into a PKCS12 binary file.
LC019.Resolution: Validate that the contents of the PKCS12 parameter is base64 encoded. Openssl can be used to validate the encoding.
LC019.Message: Base64 decode of PKCS12 content was not successful.

PSU0004.Description: The operating requirements for the power supply may be found in product documentation or on the power supply itself.
PSU0004.Resolution: Verify the input source is attached to the power supply. Verify the input power is within the operating requirements for the power supply.
PSU0004.Message: The power input for power supply %1 is outside of range.

SUP027.Description: The required parameter identified in the message is missing.
SUP027.Resolution: Verify the required parameter value for the method is specified and retry the operation.

BAR002.Description: The system profile Backup partition detection operation is in progress.

RAC0151.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about removable flash media.
RAC0151.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0151.Message: Unable to retrieve the removable flash media information. The system is powered off.

CMC8511.Description: The data on the Extended Storage removable flash media SD cards is not synchronized when the CMC is unable to determine which card has the latest data.
CMC8511.Resolution: Disable and then enable the Extended Storage feature. Using racadm, execute the following commands: "racadm feature -d -c Extended Storage" to disable and then "racadm -a -c Extended Storage" to enable the feature. NOTE: All the data on the removable flash media SD card is erased when the feature is disabled.
CMC8511.Message: Unable to synchronize the data in the Extended Storage removable flash media in the primary and secondary CMCs.

VF021.Description: The size specified is greater than the maximum allowed for a partition.
VF021.Resolution: Try a partition size that is smaller than 4GB and the available space on the card.

RED068.Description: Unable to successfully complete the job identified in the message.
RED068.Resolution: For more information about the job, view the job queue.

IOV101.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected the insertion of an adapter in the slot identified in the message.
IOV101.Resolution: If the adapter in slot identified in the message is mapped to a server, the server must be turned off then back on before server can access adapter. If the adapter in slot is a shared adapter and any server is on then the entire chassis must be turned off and turned on for the server(s) to gain access to the installed shared adapter.
IOV101.Message: A PCIe adapter %1 is inserted in %2 %3.

PSU0076.Description: Power supplies should be of the same input type and power rating.
PSU0076.Resolution: Install matched power supplies and review product documentation for proper configuration.
PSU0076.Message: A power supply wattage mismatch is detected; power supply %1 is rated for %2 watts.

UEFI0212.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Early Command Training phase.
UEFI0212.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0212.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

USR0022.Description: The username specified already exists and cannot be assigned.
USR0022.Message: The specified user already exists. Duplicate user names are not allowed.

RAC1043.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the option identified in the message.
RAC1043.Resolution: Retry with a correct value for the option identified in the message. For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help autoupdatescheduler".
RAC1043.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings. The option %1 is either invalid or not provided.

RAC0638.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid proxy host name or IP address is entered.
RAC0638.Resolution: Enter a valid proxy host name or IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC0638.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid proxy host name or IP address is entered.

RAC1061.Description: The requested SystemErase operation was initiated successfully.
RAC1061.Resolution: Check the job status by running the RACADM command: "racadm jobqueue view -i <JobID>".

IOV003.Description: A PCIe device error was detected that does not allow the assignment, unassignment, or the turning off of the device. The errors can be caused by incorrect PCIe device installation or installation of an unsupported PCIe adapter card. For a list of supported PCIe adapter cards contact your service provider.
IOV003.Resolution: Make sure that supported adapters are used and installed correctly in the PCIe slots.
IOV003.Message: Unable to manage the device located in the PCIe slot specified in the operation.

RAC0508.Description: The server encountered an unexpected condition. This may be due to invalid JavaScript Object Notation.
RAC0508.Resolution: Wait for few minutes and refresh the page. If the problem persists, contact service provider.

STOR032.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to gain access to internal storage because it is in use by another application or operation.
STOR032.Resolution: Wait for current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Configuration utility 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
STOR032.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

PWR213.Description: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) is enabled.
PWR213.Resolution: Disable the Max Power Conservation Mode and retry the operation.
PWR213.Message: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) is enabled.

DIS113.Description: The AutoConfig configuration import operation could not be started, because no options were specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS113.Resolution: Make sure that the following are correctly entered in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC, and then retry the operation: 1) Filename -f <filename>). 2) The IP address of the network share folder (-i <ip-address>). 3) Network share name (-n <share-name>). 4) The share type (-s <0 or 2>) where 0 = NFS, 2 = CIFS. 5) The username and password (-u <username> & -p <password>) 6) Shutdown type (-d <0 or 1>) where 0 = Graceful shutdown and 1 = Forced shutdown. 7) Time to wait (-t <value>) where value is more than 300 seconds and less than 3600 seconds.
DIS113.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because no options were specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

PST0193.Description: System BIOS POST memory test failed. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code C1)
PST0193.Resolution: Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce system configuration to minimum memory configuration.

SEL0012.Description: if the system event log failed to initialize platform status and failure events are not captured. Some management software will not report platform exceptions.
SEL0012.Resolution: Reboot the management controller or iDRAC. Cycle system input power. If problem persists call support.
SEL0012.Message: Could not create or initialize the system event log.

SWC4009.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between CMC 1 and CMC 2.

VDR32.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk has started. This is an automated process that writes the parity or mirror data on newly created virtual disks.

RAC1146.Description: The SNMPv3 username cannot be set because SNMPv3 is not enabled for the specified user on iDRAC.
RAC1146.Resolution: Enable SNMPv3 for the specified user by running the command "racadm set iDRAC.Users.<user index>.SNMPv3Enable 1", and then retry the operation.
RAC1146.Message: Unable to set the SNMPv3 username because SNMPv3 is not enabled for the specified user on iDRAC.

DIS102.Description: The AutoConfig configuration import operation could not be started, because the AutoConfig .xml file is not available in the sharename or location specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS102.Resolution: Update the sharename or location in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC, make sure the AutoConfig import file is available, and then retry the operation.
DIS102.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig import operation, because the AutoConfig import file is not available.

SWC0237.Description: The key text in the public key specified is corrupt.
SWC0237.Resolution: Request for a valid public key from the system and re-try the command.
SWC0237.Message: Key text appears to be corrupted.

SYS016.Description: All the operations in the Job were attempted, but some did not complete successfully.
SYS016.Resolution: Review the Job content and verify the values are correct. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation.

SWU8524.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful. This may be due to a problem encountered by the firmware, or because a server was removed during the firmware update operation.
SWU8524.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source folder, and then retry the operation.
SWU8524.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 firmware: ErrorCode=0x%2.

ISM0029.Description: Unable to complete the iDRAC Hard Reset operation because BIOS on the server does not support this feature.
ISM0029.Resolution: Install the required BIOS version and retry the operation. To know about the recommended BIOS version, see the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
ISM0029.Message: Unable to complete the iDRAC Hard Reset operation because BIOS on the server does not support this feature.

RAC0216.Description: Login failed because of an unknown reason.
RAC0216.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.

UEFI0029.Description: iDRAC could not be initialized because of some critical issues. Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as remote out of band access, active power management, thermal management, inventory collection, LCD, or system error reporting.
UEFI0029.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. 3) Continue to boot. Note: This may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as remote out of band access, active power management, thermal management, inventory collection, LCD, or system error reporting.
UEFI0029.Message: Unable to initialize iDRAC because of some critical issues.

SYS057.Description: The current system configuration is being collected and the System Configuration Profile XML file is being generated.
SYS057.Message: Exporting System Configuration Profile XML file.

HWC0003.Description: vFlash SD card was successfully initialized.

DIS002.Description: Use the Lifecycle Controller or other service to enable Auto Discovery and restart.
DIS002.Resolution: If you want AutoDiscovery to locate a Provising Server enable this feature

SWC0019.Description: The Test Network Connection ping test timed-out. The network cable is disconnected or the network is not configured correctly.
SWC0019.Resolution: Check the network cable connection and network configuration settings, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, reconfigure the network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0019.Message: The Test Network Connection operation completed with errors.

CTL71.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL71.Message: Attempted to import an incompatible Physical Disk on %1.

RAC060.Description: The attribute identified in the message could not be set, because certain features cannot be enabled when OMSA is installed on the server.
RAC060.Resolution: Uninstall OMSA, and then retry the operation.
RAC060.Message: Unable to set the attribute because OpenManage Server Administrator (OMSA) is installed on the server %1

SWC0318.Description: The value for -s must be greater than zero.
SWC0318.Resolution: Enter a value greater than zero, for the option -s.
SWC0318.Message: The starting record must be greater than zero.

PST0129.Description: System BIOS detected memory, but was unable to configure the memory for system operation. Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce the system to minimum memory configuration if acceptable. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.(BIOS POST Exception Code 81).
PST0129.Resolution: Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations.
PST0129.Message: Memory is detected, but is not configurable.

BAT1021.Description: The controller battery cannot maintain sufficient charge level to function properly or the battery is discharging.
BAT1021.Resolution: Check for other events related to the state of the battery. These may help determine the cause of this event.
BAT1021.Message: The charge level for the battery on %1 is below the normal threshold.

LOG505.Description: The network share access cannot be accessed.
LOG505.Resolution: Make sure that correct network share access credentials are entered (such as IP address, username, password, and share type). For more information, see the Chassis Record Log Profile.
LOG505.Message: Unable to access the network share.

STOR031.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G systems: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
STOR031.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G systems: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

SUP0111.Message: Timeout waiting for firmware update process to complete.

USR8505.Description: The operation to invalidate the Session identified in the message was successful.

AMP0317.Message: System level current is within range.

RAC1023.Description: Configuration jobs are created only if at least one object on the device or component (for example, NIC.Slot.1 or BIOS) has a pending value to be applied.
RAC1023.Resolution: Make sure that there is at least one object on the specified device or component that has a pending value, and retry the operation.
RAC1023.Message: Unable to create the configuration job.

UEFI0246.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. Link option mismatch detected.
UEFI0246.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0246.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

PSU8504.Description: Selecting the Allow 110 VAC Operation involves potential risk that an overload can occur. The overload risk was not acknowledged in the CMC Web interface when the selection was made.
PSU8504.Resolution: Select the Allow 110 VAC Operation and accept the subsequent dialog that acknowledges the overload risk.
PSU8504.Message: The Allow 110 VAC Operation overload risk is not acknowledged.

SYS191.Description: The provided System Configuration Profile XML file is being applied to the system. The host may reboot to apply all changes.
SYS191.Resolution: No response action is required. Use the GetConfigResults() method to get the configuration job results or export the Lifecycle Log to review the configuration job results.
SYS191.Message: The System Configuration Profile XML file import operation is started.

RAC051.Description: The parameter name is not supported.
RAC051.Resolution: Remove the unsupported parameter and retry the operation.

SWC8562.Description: All of the specified MAC addresses are deactivated from the Virtual MAC Address Pool.
SWC8562.Message: All of the specified MAC addresses are deactivated from the Virtual MAC Address Pool of Boot Identity profile operations.

MEM0009.Resolution: If unexpected, review system logs for power or thermal exceptions.
MEM0009.Message: Memory device at location %1 is throttled.

RAC1037.Description: Unable to clear pending attribute(s). This may be because the FQDD entered is incorrect.
RAC1037.Resolution: Check that the FQDD entered is correct. View the Help information by running the RACADM command "racadm help clearpending".

UEFI0102.Description: The Memory Sparing feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.
UEFI0102.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure Memory Sparing feature can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0102.Message: Unable to enable the Memory Sparing feature because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.

PWR8549.Description: The requested chassis shutdown operation did not complete successfully.
PWR8549.Message: Chassis shutdown did not complete successfully.

PDR94.Description: The attempt to update the physical disk has timed out. This may be due to too much activity on the bus, a bad update package, or a bad disk.
PDR94.Resolution: Retry the update. The update utility may have already performed the retry operation.
PDR94.Message: Microcode update on %1 has timed out.

RAC0253.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0253.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Address. Expected range: [1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0253.Message: The IP Address is invalid. Expected range: [1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].

VFL0001.Description: The requested operation for the vFlash SD Card completed successfully.
VFL0001.Message: The vFlash SD Card operation is successful.

LIC008.Description: All bound perpetual licenses contain the unique identifier of a specific device. The unique identifier binds a license to the device. For example, iDRAC's unique identifier is the service tag.
LIC008.Resolution: Obtain a new license file with the correct unique identifier for the device. To use this license, import to the device with the correct unique identifier.
LIC008.Message: The license binding ID does not match the device unique identifier.

PDR1104.Message: Consistency check is in progress for drive %1.

RED074.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because the required parameters were not present in the method invocation.
RED074.Resolution: Verify that all required parameters for the method are present and retry the operation.
RED074.Message: A required parameter is not present.

RDU0031.Description: The system has redundant voltage lines. One of voltage line is no longer available.
RDU0031.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

UEFI0068.Description: The mezzanine card configuration used is not supported on this Chassis. Server modules used in different Chassis may require cards with different configuration properties. For more information, contact your service provider.
UEFI0068.Resolution: Make sure that a supported mezzanine card is used and retry the operation. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual of the Chassis available at the support site.
UEFI0068.Message: The mezzanine card configuration used is not supported on this Chassis.

VDR58.Description: Virtual disk bad blocks are due to presence of unrecoverable bad blocks on one or more member physical disks.
VDR58.Resolution: Recovering a physical disk bad block depends on the RAID level and state of the virtual disk. If a virtual disk is redundant, the controller can recover a bad block on a physical disk. If a virtual disk is not redundant, then the physical disk bad block results in a virtual disk bad block.
VDR58.Message: Bad block medium error is detected at block %1 on %2.

RAC0710.Resolution: Ensure that the IO Module (IOM) and Mezzanine (Mezz) cards are appropriately matched. Check the M1000e Hardware Manual for correct component compatibility.

AMP0309.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0309.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0309.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PST0002.Description: System BIOS has started loading the processor microcode.

UEFI0138.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware is unable to complete a requested task or function.
UEFI0138.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0138.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was unable to complete a requested task or function.

SWC4004.Description: FlexAddress is not implemented in one of the versions of firmware. Please update the firmware.
SWC4004.Resolution: Check firmware versions of iDRAC and CMC. Update to latest version.
SWC4004.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility detected between iDRAC in slot %1 and CMC.

BAR074.Description: The collection and export of firmware inventory data did not complete successfully.
BAR074.Resolution: Apply the Dell Update Package for Unified Server Configurator (USC). If collect system inventory on reboot (CSIOR) is not enabled, enter and exit System Services in USC to update the database, reboot the system and try the operation again. If the error continues, use the field service repair software to repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download all Dell Update Packages for USC, Diagnostics Driver Packs, and device firmware for all host system devices, install all packages and retry the operation.
BAR074.Message: Unable to collect Firmware Inventory information.

PR1.Description: The specified device has been replaced.
PR1.Message: A replacement part was detected for device: %1

SYS071.Description: The export of system configuration XML did not complete because the operation took too long.
SYS071.Resolution: Make sure the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) Lifecycle Controller setting is enabled and reboot the system. Retry the operation after CSIOR has completed. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds and retry the operation after iDRAC has fully restarted.
SYS071.Message: System configuration XML export operation timed-out.

BAR024.Description: The restoration environment is being initialized.

RAC0637.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid proxy user name is entered.
RAC0637.Resolution: Enter a valid proxy user name, and then retry the operation.
RAC0637.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid proxy user name is entered.

SYS198.Description: An internal iDRAC memory component is unresponsive.
SYS198.Resolution: The iDRAC requires an AC power cycle. Do the following: 1) Determine a time that the AC power can be removed and then reapplied to the server. 2) Save data and perform an AC power cycle.
SYS198.Message: Unable to communicate with internal iDRAC memory.

SYS177.Description: There was an issue retrieving Hardware data from the iDRAC internal storage. This may be because Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled and has never executed or the iDRAC Remote Services API status may not be in the Ready state.
SYS177.Resolution: Make sure the Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) is enabled and has run at least once before retrying this operation. For remote web services API access, make sure the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status before trying this operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
SYS177.Message: There was an issue retrieving Hardware data.

OSD74.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is invalid.
OSD74.Resolution: Check the value provided for input parameter "ShareType" and retry the operation.
OSD74.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is invalid.

SEL1306.Description: The disk in the drive is not formatted correctly or does not contain the necessary operating system files (IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 03h)

SWC0233.Description: Indexed groups in the configuration file is more than the indexed groups in iDRAC.
SWC0233.Resolution: Verify if the number of indexed groups available in iDRAC match the indexed groups in the configuration file. If it does not match, either reset the unnecessary indexes on iDRAC or remove the extra groups from the configuration file.
SWC0233.Message: No indexes are available to configure additional groups.

SYS127.Description: OS log data was not collected. An issue occurred while collecting OS log data because of an unknown exception.
SYS127.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS127.Message: OS Collector: Unable to collect OS log data

AMP0303.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0303.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0303.Message: The system board %1 current is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SWC0107.Description: The command takes in only one option which is the Session ID.
SWC0107.Resolution: Enter the command only with one option i.e. the Session ID
SWC0107.Message: More than one option is not allowed with this command.

RAC0562.Description: iDRAC automatically restored connection with CMC proxy component. Agent free Monitoring will now be supported for Chassis PCIe slots.
RAC0562.Message: iDRAC-CMC communication restored for agent free monitoring of chassis PCIe slots.

RAC052.Description: Unable to create a configuration job because an existing configuration job is already in progress. Only one configuration job for a component can run or can be processed at any time.
RAC052.Resolution: Retry the operation after the existing configuration job is complete, or cancel the existing configuration job and retry the operation.
RAC052.Message: Unable to create a configuration job because an existing configuration job is already in progress.

CTL63.Description: The controller is unable to retrieve storage configuration saved during last shut down. This can generally happen if some configured physical disks are removed from the system when the system was shutdown.
CTL63.Resolution: Shut down the system. Re-insert the removed physical disks and re-start the system.
CTL63.Message: Previous configuration was found completely missing during boot time on %1.

RED033.Description: The request to shut down the operating system did not complete successfully. The iDRAC was unable to complete the system reboot. Any operation that depends on the system reboot will not complete until reboot is complete.
RED033.Resolution: Identify and resolve any operating system issues that prevented the shutdown. After resolving the issues preventing the operating system shutdown, retry the operation or reboot the system using other methods or interfaces.

PWR2254.Description: The use of 110V is unacknowledged for the chassis and the chassis cannot grant power on permission to the server.
PWR2254.Resolution: Check for unacknowledged use of 110V and change to acknowledged. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Chassis Overview>Power>Configuration and then check the 110V Acknowledge field. Retry the operation to turn on the server.
PWR2254.Message: The use of 110V is unacknowledged and the chassis cannot grant power on permission to the server.

IOV113.Description: Chassis Infrastructure firmware re-installation is successful.
IOV113.Message: Chassis Infrastructure firmware re-installation is successful.

ENC28.Description: The firmware on the EMM modules is not the same version. Both modules must have the same firmware version. This message is caused when you attempt to insert an EMM module that has a different firmware version than an existing module.
ENC28.Resolution: Upgrade to the same version of the firmware on both EMM modules and then powercycle the system and attached enclosures.
ENC28.Message: Enclosure Management Module (EMM) firmware version mismatch detected in %1.%2 %3.

UEFI0079.Description: One or more Uncorrectable Memory errors occurred in the previous boot.
UEFI0079.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the non-functional DIMM, and then replace the DIMM.
UEFI0079.Message: One or more Uncorrectable Memory errors occurred in the previous boot.

PDR115.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message is in read-only mode.
PDR115.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.

OSD7.Description: Unable to connect to Lifecycle Controller because of an existing open connection or an internal error.
OSD7.Resolution: Reset iDRAC, and rerun the command to correct the problem.
OSD7.Message: Unable to retrieve Lifecycle Controller handle.

FAN900.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully enabled.
FAN900.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully enabled.

VF032.Description: The specified partition type is not a valid type.
VF032.Resolution: Try a partition type that is supported.

SWC0224.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0224.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0224.Message: Invalid syntax. The -d option is not valid with -u.

SWC0026.Description: Status of backup Server Profile operation could not be retrieved because an unrecoverable error occurred while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0026.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0026.Message: Unable to retrieve status of backup Server Profile operation.

SWC0226.Description: The Remote/Firmware racadm did not find any AD/LDAP certificate at specified path.
SWC0226.Message: No valid directory service certificate exists

OSE1001.Resolution: review system boot configuration and boot media. Verify the media in a: is bootable. See system video for additional information.

UEFI0023.Description: The End of POST message could not be sent to the Management Engine because the Management Engine is not responding.
UEFI0023.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0023.Message: BIOS is unable to send the End of POST message to Management Engine because the Management Engine is not responding.

SEC0032.Message: The chassis is closed while the power is on.

RAC0103.Description: Smart Card login is only supported in newer versions of Internet Explorer.
RAC0103.Resolution: See the iDRAC help text or documentation for a list of supported browsers.
RAC0103.Message: This browser does not support Smart Card logon on iDRAC. Use Internet Explorer version 7.0 or later to use this feature.

VLT0304.Description: Voltages outside the allowable range may damage electrical components or may cause the system to shutdown.
VLT0304.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0304.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is outside of range.

PDR61.Description: It is not possible to rebuild data that resides on a defective disk.
PDR61.Resolution: Replace the source disk and restore data from backup.
PDR61.Message: The rebuild of %1 failed due to errors on the source physical disk.

IOID117.Description: The iDRAC has applied I/O Identity settings on NIC and FC HBA devices. All the device configuration related to virtual addresses, initiator and target settings have been configured successfully according to the current persistence policy settings.
IOID117.Message: The operation to apply I/O Identity settings based on current persistence policy settings has completed successfully.

DH001.Resolution: Try again. If the error persists, use RACADM command racreset to clear the issue.
DH001.Message: Resource needed to perform the operation is unavailable.

SWC1931.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout configuration is disabled. The iDRAC Quick Sync feature will remain available after pressing the activate button.
SWC1931.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync inactivity timeout configuration is disabled.

OSD4.Description: Driver Pack partition in Lifecycle Controller is not accessible. The Lifecycle Controller or the iDRAC might be unresponsive.
OSD4.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and rerun the command. If the command fails again, check if the iDRAC is functional and accessible on the system.
OSD4.Message: Cannot access Lifecycle Controller Driver Pack partition.

SWC0049.Description: The Import operation cannot continue because backup image file is not present on the vFlash SD card, the image is invalid, or the entered passphrase is incorrect.
SWC0049.Resolution: Make sure that the backup image file is present on the vFlash SD card, the image is valid, and the entered passphrase is correct.
SWC0049.Message: Unable to continue the Import operation.

PDR62.Description: It is not possible to rebuild data that resides on a defective disk.
PDR62.Resolution: Replace the target disk. If a rebuild does not automatically start after replacing the disk, then initiate the Rebuild task. You may need to assign the new disk as a hot spare to initiate the rebuild.
PDR62.Message: The rebuild failed due to errors on the target %1.

UEFI0255.Description: Network Daughter Card 1 and Network Daughter Card 2 in the system do not match.
UEFI0255.Resolution: Check the Network Daughter Cards and make sure they are the same type.
UEFI0255.Message: Network Daughter Card 1 and Network Daughter Card 2 in the system do not match.

RAC073.Description: The iDRAC reset operation cannot be completed because a vFlash partition creation operation is in progress.
RAC073.Resolution: Wait for the vFlash partition creation process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC073.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset operation because a vFlash partition creation operation is in progress.

BAR071.Description: Access to the CIFS export/import destination is not possible or has been denied.
BAR071.Resolution: Verify that the input parameters are correct, connectivity exists to the destination end point, and retry the operation.

SWC0255.Description: Unable to open the specified file.

PDR77.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR77.Message: %1 state changed from READY to Non-RAID.

UEFI0196.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Error Training phase.
UEFI0196.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0196.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RAC1154.Description: The requested techsupreport collect or export operation is initiated.
RAC1154.Resolution: Run the RACADM jobqueue sub-command, using the job id to check the status of the requested operation.

UEFI0014.Description: A CPU alignment check exception (type 0x11) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0014.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

UEFI0191.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the VCK Reference Clock phase.
UEFI0191.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0191.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

MEM1212.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed.
MEM1212.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>

PCI1348.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1348.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1348.Message: A PCI parity error was detected on a component at slot %1.

RAC1042.Description: One or more required options to configure the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature are missing.
RAC1042.Resolution: For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help autoupdatescheduler".
RAC1042.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings. The required options are either invalid or not provided.

SEL0006.Description: This message appears when all event logging has been disabled by the user. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 03h)

LNK2700.Resolution: Check network cable and network connections.

RAC938.Description: The configuration XML file export operation was successfully initiated after it was invoked by the user specified in the message.
RAC938.Message: Successfully initiated configuration XML file export operation invoked by the %1.

TMP7.Description: A device has been failed and the system is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

RAC008.Description: The attribute boolean value is not valid for the specified attribute.
RAC008.Resolution: Provide valid boolean value for the specified attribute.

UEFI0214.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Basic Receive Enable Training phase.
UEFI0214.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0214.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

VF007.Description: A partition with an image was created.

SWC0066.Description: Unable to connect to the Network Share due to one of the following: 1) Login credentials entered are incorrect. 2) Network is inaccessible. 3) System IP address conflicts with another system on the network.
SWC0066.Resolution: Verify the login credentials. Make sure the Network Share is accessible and the system IP address does not conflict with any other system on the network. If the problem persists, perform an AC power cycle and retry.
SWC0066.Message: Unable to connect to the Network Share.

SYS155.Description: Initiating clear operation on non-secure erase-capable drives for the controller identified in the message.
SYS155.Message: Initiating clear operation on non-secure erase-capable drives for controller: %1.

PDR31.Description: The controller cannot to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a global hot spare. The disk either failed or was removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.
PDR31.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and installed. Check the cables. Refer to the product documentation and see the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the global hot spare.
PDR31.Message: A global hot spare has been removed.%1

UEFI0172.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.
UEFI0172.Resolution: Quad Rank DIMM modules must be installed before Single Rank DIMM modules on the channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0172.Message: A Quad Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Single Rank DIMM module.

RAC921.Description: The file type specified (with the t parameter) is invalid. The temperature history can be exported in XML or CSV.
RAC921.Resolution: Change the requested export file type to either XML or CSV. To do this, change the argument given to the t parameter. The argument given to the parameter is case-insensitive.
RAC921.Message: The temperature history can be exported in XML or CSV format only.

USR0171.Description: The device identified in the message is connected to the Front Panel USB port and detached from the iDRAC.
USR0171.Message: The Front Panel USB port is detached from the iDRAC Disk.USBFront.%1. Device Details: Device Class %2, Vendor ID %3, Product ID %4.

STOR0512.Description: Unable to apply the encryption key due to an internal error.
STOR0512.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
STOR0512.Message: Unable to apply the encryption key.

RAC049.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC.
RAC049.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.

SWC0212.Message: Perform POST Virtual Console disable from local system

OSE1013.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. See system video for additional information

SWC5006.Description: System Controller (SC) reported a successful Firmware Update

SWC8559.Description: A new Virtual MAC Address Pool is created with the number of addresses identified in the message starting from the MAC address identified in the message.
SWC8559.Message: A new Virtual MAC Address Pool is created with %1 addresses from %2 for Boot Identity profile operations.

RED078.Description: Unable to delete the Automatic Update schedule information because the schedule is not configured.
RED078.Message: Unable to delete the Automatic Update schedule.

RAC012.Description: The user credentials supplied do not have sufficient privileges to perform the operation.
RAC012.Resolution: Retry the operation with user credentials authorized for the requested operation.
RAC012.Message: Unable to perform the operation because of insufficient user privileges.

FCD8504.Description: The card was installed and activated on another chassis. To use this card, it must be deactivated (uninstalled) on the other chassis.
FCD8504.Resolution: Remove the card and install it on the chassis where the feature is activated.
FCD8504.Message: The feature was previously activated on another chassis.

RAC1161.Description: Unable to initiate the techsupreport collect operation because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running.
RAC1161.Resolution: Run the command 'racadm get iDRAC.ServiceModule to make sure that iDRAC Service Module is installed and running on the server operation system (OS) and also to verify that the collection of the server OS data is enabled.
RAC1161.Message: Unable to initiate the techsupreport collect operation for the Tech Support Report (TSR) because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running.

RAC0645.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'recurrence frequency' while scheduling a job.
RAC0645.Resolution: Enter a correct value, and then retry the operation.
RAC0645.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid value is entered for the recurrence frequency.

SWC8501.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required.

PWR2253.Description: The server did not turn on because a PCIe card or Mezzanine card is not installed.
PWR2253.Resolution: Install a PCI or Mezzanine card in the appropriate slot and retry the operation.
PWR2253.Message: Unable to turn on the server because a PCIe card or Mezzanine card is not installed.

TMP8502.Description: The system has recovered from being unable to read planar board or control panel temperature sensors.
TMP8502.Message: Able to read planar board temperature sensors. Cooling set for normal chassis operation.

RED026.Description: An internal error occurred while processing the current update. The update did not complete successfully.
RED026.Message: An internal error occurred while processing updates.

RFL2006.Description: The module is write-protected. Changes may not be written to the media.
RFL2006.Resolution: if unintended, remove the media and disable write protection.
RFL2006.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is write protected.

PCI3014.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next scheduled service time.
PCI3014.Message: A non-fatal PCIe error detected on a component at slot %1.

RAC009.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the length of the input string exceeds maximum length allowed.
RAC009.Resolution: Verify the string length and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC009.Message: Input string length exceeds maximum length.

RAC1138.Description: Unable to export the remote diagnostics results because the remote diagnostics results have not been generated.
RAC1138.Resolution: Using the RACADM command line interface, run the "racadm diagnostics run" command to make sure that the diagnostics results are available, and then retry the operation.
RAC1138.Message: Unable to export the diagnostics results because the results do not exist.

RAC0212.Description: This is a generic error message used on all the login pages.
RAC0212.Message: Login failed. Verify that username and password is correct.

VF033.Description: The specified format type is not a valid type.
VF033.Resolution: Try a format type that is supported.

RED098.Description: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is not compatible with the target system.
RED098.Resolution: Identify and download the firmware version that corresponds to the system model being updated, and retry the operation. For a list of supported firmware versions, refer to the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
RED098.Message: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is not compatible with the target system model.

STOR301.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because there is an operation pending to change the controller mode. This operation is exclusive because it requires a server reboot for changes to apply..
STOR301.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending controller mode change request operation, allow the job to complete, restart the server, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR301.Message: Unable to perform the operation because the controller mode change request is pending.

PDR22.Description: A disk has reached an unacceptable temperature and received a SMART alert (predictive failure). The disk is likely to fail in the near future.
PDR22.Resolution: Do the following:1) Determine why the physical disk reached an unacceptable temperature. For example, a fan failure, incorrect thermostat settings, or the room temperature may be too hot or cold. 2) Verify that the fans in the server or enclosure are working. 3) If the physical disk is in an enclosure, check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source. Verify the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information. 4) If you cannot identify why the disk has reached an unacceptable temperature, then replace the disk. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk causes the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.

STOR0102.Description: No battery data to display. The system is powered off, batteries are not present on the system, batteries are not connected to the RAID controller, or the batteries are depleted.
STOR0102.Resolution: Check if the server has power, batteries are available, and batteries are connected to the RAID controller.

SYS040.Description: An operation to update the firmware of a component did not complete successfully.
SYS040.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log for more details about the unsuccessful operation. Resolve the issue and retry the operation.
SYS040.Message: The firmware update operation did not complete successfully.

PSU8515.Description: Unable to set the Enable Dynamic Power Supply Engagement attribute.
PSU8515.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, review the tracelog for more details. To retrieve the tracelog, in the CMC Web interface, go to Troubleshooting > Diagnostics page and enter the "gettracelog" command, or use RACADM "gettracelog" command. If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider and provide the tracelog.
PSU8515.Message: Unable to set the Enable Dynamic Power Supply Engagement attribute.

AMP0323.Message: Chassis power level current is within range.

SWC0259.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0259.Resolution: Refer the list of groups and enter a valid option.

USR0172.Description: The Front Panel USB Management Port Mode setting is changed as identified in the message.
USR0172.Message: The Front Panel USB Management Port Mode setting is changed from %1 to %2.

RED077.Description: Unable to get the Automatic Update schedule information because the schedule is not configured.
RED077.Message: Unable to get the Automatic Update schedule information.

MEM9002.Description: A correctable error was detected in propagation of signals between processors through the Intel QPI interconnect interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9002.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the server and check whether the issue persists. 2) If the issue is not resolved by the preceding action, reseat the processors and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9002.Message: Intel QPI interconnect %1 has a correctable error.

SWC0218.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0218.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0218.Message: The -c option requires -p to also be specified.

RAC1189.Description: The idrac.serviceModule.watchdogtmer object can not be enabled if the OS watch dog timer is already enabled.
RAC1189.Resolution: Disable the object using "racadm set bIOS.integratedDevices.osWatchdogTimer Disabled " Then retry the operation.
RAC1189.Message: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC Service Module.

ISM0010.Description: The iDRAC Service Module received a request from a source identified in the message to stop the Service Module services. For example, a requesting source can be an OS or iDRAC.
ISM0010.Resolution: If the requesting source is iDRAC, enable the iDRAC Service Module on the iDRAC before starting this service on the server OS. To enable the Service Module by using iDRAC GUI: Click Network, click OS to iDRAC Pass-through, and then click the USB NIC option. In the OS IP Address box , type an IP address, and then click Apply. To enable the module by using RACADM command, run the following command at the command line interface: racadm set idrac.servicemodule.ServiceModuleEnable enabled
ISM0010.Message: The iDRAC Service Module received a request from the %1 to stop the services of Service Module.

CTL74.Description: The controller has preserved data in the cache from a virtual disk, which it can no longer locate. No data loss has occurred as the controller is saving these operations in its cache.
CTL74.Resolution: Check for the existence of a foreign configuration and import if any. Check that enclosures are cabled correctly.

SWC8519.Description: The user name identified in the message was successfully modified.
SWC8519.Message: Successfully modified user name from %1 to %2.

PWR8576.Description: The virtual reseat initiated on the Sleeve or Sled identified in the message successfully turned off the component. However, the Sleeve or Sled did not turn on successfully. A virtual reseat is the same as removing and inserting a Sleeve or Sled.
PWR8576.Resolution: Retry the virtual reseat operation on the Sleeve or Sled identified in the message. If the issue persists, manually remove and reinsert the Sleeve or Sled in the chassis.
PWR8576.Message: Unable to turn on the Sleeve or Sled %1 after a virtual reseat operation.

HWC7006.Description: Server <number> health changed to a non-recoverable state from a less severe state.
HWC7006.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7006.Message: Server %1 health changed to a non-recoverable state from a less severe state.

UEFI0007.Description: A CPU coprocessor segment overrun exception (type 0x09) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0007.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0007.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x09: Coprocessor Segment Overrun (Software).

VDR47.Description: A disk media error was detected while the controller was completing a background task. A bad disk block was identified. The disk block was remapped.
VDR47.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle log for information related to members of this virtual disk.
VDR47.Message: A disk media error was corrected on %1.

PR13.Description: The Part Replacement feature detected a firmware difference and cannot apply the configuration changes. After the device firmware is updated, configuration changes can be applied.
PR13.Message: Firmware mismatch detected. Configuration changes not applied.

PST0091.Description: A problem was detected in Memory Reference Code (MRC). The next logged message contains more specific details for the detected issue.
PST0091.Resolution: Review the next logged message for the recommended response action to resolve the problem.
PST0091.Message: A problem was detected in Memory Reference Code (MRC).

RAC1110.Description: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Proxy port number was entered. The Proxy port value must be a positive integer.
RAC1110.Resolution: Enter only numbers for a Proxy port value.
RAC1110.Message: Unable to run the command, because an incorrect Proxy port number was entered.

RAC0215.Description: Login failed because the user does not have 'Login to iDRAC' privilege.
RAC0215.Resolution: Login to iDRAC' privilege is needed.
RAC0215.Message: Login failed: User does not have 'Login to iDRAC' privilege.

RAC0274.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0274.Resolution: See iDRAC user documentation for more information on using racadm.
RAC0274.Message: See the iDRAC user documentation for more information on using the Racadm utility or the serial interface.

LC0100.Description: A persistent error has occurred while carrying out a Lifecycle Controller operation. This situation causes Lifecycle Controller to enter Recovery mode. Any remote jobs pending execution were cancelled.
LC0100.Resolution: To verify or change Recovery mode, use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings. Updating Lifecycle Controller clears the Recovery mode.
