LC0100.Message: Lifecycle Controller has entered Recovery mode.

PSU0023.Message: Power supply %1 operating at 110 volts has been acknowledged by user.

MEM1017.Message: Memory device at location %1 is installed correctly.

SWC1927.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-only mode.
SWC1927.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-only mode.

RSI0003.Description: The Remote Service database is being updated.
RSI0003.Message: The remote service is reloading data

VDR91.Description: This message occurs if there are medium errors in the physical drives.
VDR91.Message: Consistency check for %1 has detected multiple uncorrectable medium errors.

BAR059.Description: The system profile import or export network destination is being tested for access.

UEFI0083.Description: One or more PCI System errors (SERR) have occurred.
UEFI0083.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCI device that caused the SERR. Update the identified device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0083.Message: One or more PCI System errors (SERR) have occurred.

SWC8553.Description: The profile identified in the message is not valid.
SWC8553.Resolution: Edit the profile and make sure no XML schema or configuration errors are present and then retry the operation.

RAC032.Description: The DNS RAC name specified is not valid.
RAC032.Resolution: Retry operation with valid DNS RAC name.
RAC032.Message: Invalid value specified for DNS RAC name.

RAC1180.Description: A USB Device inserted in the front panel USB Management port and is in use by the server operating system. The device needs to not be in use in order to change the port mode settings.
RAC1180.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the USB device and retry the operation.
RAC1180.Message: A USB device is inserted in the front panel USB Management port and is in use by the server operating system.

UEFI0220.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write Voltage Training phase.
UEFI0220.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0220.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

CTL94.Description: The controller identified in the message has been changed to operate as a single controller and not as part of a fault tolerant pair.
CTL94.Message: %1 has been successfully changed to operate in single controller mode.

IPA0100.Description: The iDRAC IP Address changed from the earlier IP Address identified in the message to the new IP Address identified in the message. This notification will be generated when the iDRAC network card selection is changed, if the DHCP lease expires and the DHCP server assigns another address, or if iDRAC IP address is manually changed.
IPA0100.Resolution: Remote management consoles that have cached or stored the iDRAC IP address may have to be updated with the new IP address either through a re-discovery or manual reconfiguration. A response action may not be required if the console receives this SNMP notification and updates the iDRAC IP address accordingly.
IPA0100.Message: The iDRAC IP Address changed from %1 to %2.

RAC0908.Description: The System ID LED was successfully set to off.

UEFI0167.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because the number of allowable Rank Interleave Register (RIR) rules exceeded during memory initialization.
UEFI0167.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0167.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

CMC8604.Description: The FRU on the storage sled specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8604.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reinsert the specified storage sled or virtual reseat the sled 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes for the CMC to finish restarting. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8604.Message: The FRU on storage sled %1 is not functioning.

BAR006.Description: The system profile backup file is being finalized and closed.

OSD3.Description: Lifecycle Controller is currently locked by another process. Make sure that the process completes before attempting to run another command.
OSD3.Resolution: 1) After two minutes, rerun the command. 2) Make sure that USC or DUP is not currently running on the server. 3) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD3.Message: Lifecycle Controller is being used by another process.

BAR115.Description: The number of Automatic Server Profile backup files has reached the specified limit. Restarting the numbering from 1 which will overwrite the oldest backup file.
BAR115.Message: The number of Automatic Server Profile backup files has reached the specified limit. Restarting the numbering from 1.

UEFI0205.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Command Clock Training - Group 0 phase.
UEFI0205.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0205.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

PWR8534.Description: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to enable.
PWR8534.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8534.Message: Unable to set Server Based Power Management Mode to enable.

RAC928.Description: Racadm unable to set the recurrence value. This occurs if the underlying instrumentation do not set the value.
RAC928.Resolution: Wait for a few minutes and retry the command. If the problem persists, contact the service provider.
RAC928.Message: Unable to modify the recurrence value.

RAC069.Description: Unable to complete the operation because the string length is less than the minimum supported length.
RAC069.Resolution: Enter a string value that is greater than the minimum supported length and retry the operation.
RAC069.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the string length is less than the minimum supported length.

IOV109.Description: An error condition associated with the PCIe slot is cleared.
IOV109.Message: An error condition associated with the PCIe slot is cleared.

NIC504.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC504.Message: The IPv6 DNS Server IP address is not allowed to be configured if IPv6 DNS Server DHCP (cfgIPv6DNSServersFromDHCP6) is enabled

UEFI0124.Description: The size and speed of the primary SD card do not match those of the secondary SD card. The secondary SD card needs to have equal or greater capacity and speed than the primary SD card.
UEFI0124.Resolution: Replace the secondary SD card with one that has equal or greater capacity and speed than the primary SD card.
UEFI0124.Message: The size and speed of the secondary SD card do not match those of the primary SD card.

LC021.Description: The contents of the PKCS12 parameter was not valid because: 1) not a valid PKCS12 file 2) not a valid pfx file 3) did not contain a valid key.
LC021.Resolution: Validate that the PKCS12 file was Base64 encoded. OpenSSL can be used to create or validate a PKCS12 file.
LC021.Message: PKCS12 decrypt of private key could not complete.

RED020.Description: The feature invoked is not supported by the current version of the Unified Server Configurator.
RED020.Resolution: Upgrade Unified Server Configurator to the latest available version before using this feature.
RED020.Message: Feature not supported on current version of USC.

USR0153.Description: The VNC client is logged off from the IP address identified in the message.
USR0153.Resolution: To re-establish the remote VNC session, log in again using the VNC client.
USR0153.Message: Logging off the remote VNC session from the IP address %1, because the session timed out.

SUP0531.Description: The repository location is invalid or the repository does not contain the Update Packages.
SUP0531.Resolution: Enter another repository location that contains the desired Update Packages and retry the operation.
SUP0531.Message: Unable to install the Update Packages.

RED053.Description: Processing of update packages has completed.
RED053.Message: Processing of update packages has completed.

PSU8503.Description: The input voltage of the PSU specified in the message does not match the input voltage of the PSUs already present in the chassis.
PSU8503.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check if the input voltage of all the PSUs are the same. 2) If the input voltage of the PSU specified in the message is not the same, then remove the unmatched PSU.
PSU8503.Message: The PSU in slot %1 detected 220 VAC input voltage and does not match chassis configuration.

VLT0100.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0100.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0100.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

RED000.Resolution: Check the uniform resource identifier (URI) target path and make sure the repository server is available.

RAC988.Description: A new firmware update job cannot be initiated while an existing firmware update job is still in one of these states: "New", "Downloading", or "Running".
RAC988.Resolution: Wait until the existing firmware update jobs are completed or scheduled before retrying the operation. To monitor the status of the existing jobs, use the "racadm jobqueue view" command.
RAC988.Message: Unable to initiate the %1 firmware update.

CMC8555.Description: An internal memory error occurred affecting the configuration database and CMC has initiated a failover . If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8555.Message: An internal memory error has occurred and a failover condition is detected.

RAC0600.Description: Temperature information cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the server is powered off.
RAC0600.Resolution: Power on the server. If the server is already powered on, wait for a few minutes and refresh the page. If the problem persists, contact service provider.
RAC0600.Message: Unable to retrieve the temperature information.

SEL1512.Description: The Chassis Controller is not responding or is not inserted properly.
SEL1512.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reinsert Chassis Controller, if removed. 2) If Chassis Controller is present but is not responding, reset the Chassis Controller. To reset the Chassis Controller using the graphical user interface (GUI), click Chassis Overview > Power > Control > Reset CMC. To reset by running the RACADM command at the command line interface (CLI), enter: "racadm racreset".
SEL1512.Message: The Chassis Controller is not responding or is not inserted properly. The status of Chassis Controller is critical.

UEFI0165.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because the number of allowable System Address Decode (SAD) rules exceeded during memory initialization.
UEFI0165.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0165.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

PDR53.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR53.Message: A redundant path has been restored for %1.

RAC0137.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while changing the read-write state of the vFlash partition.
RAC0137.Message: An error has occurred while changing the read-write state for the partition.

ASR0104.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was powered cycled. (IPMI sensor 23h offset - 03h event 3:0 - 4h)
ASR0104.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0104.Message: The OS watchdog timer powered cycle the system.

HWC2006.Description: The device may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC2006.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

UEFI0036.Description: The iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) interface cannot be initialized. The BIOS will use the Keyboard Controller Style (KCS) interface.
UEFI0036.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0036.Message: Unable to initialize the iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) interface.

VF006.Description: Creating a partition without image failed.
VF006.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.

SWC8511.Description: The user name identified in the message was added successfully.

IOID001.Description: After the I/O Identity optimization feature is enabled, the time during boot to configure I/O Identity attributes using the Server Configuration Profile (Configuration XML) import feature will be significantly reduced.
IOID001.Message: The Input/Output Identity (I/O Identity) optimization feature is enabled.

BAT1020.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1020.Message: The %1 battery is executing a learn cycle.

SWC0031.Description: iDRAC is unable to initiate the backup Server Profile operation because an unrecoverable error occurred.
SWC0031.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0031.Message: Unable to initiate the backup Server Profile backup operation.

RAC0659.Description: The storage configuration operation(s) cannot be performed on the adapter identified in the message because a job is currently pending or is running on the adapter.
RAC0659.Resolution: Wait for the job to completely run, or delete the job, and then retry the operation. To view the status of the scheduled jobs, go to the Job Queue page of iDRAC.
RAC0659.Message: Unable to perform the storage configuration operation(s) on %1 because a job is currently pending or is running on the adapter.

MEM1016.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.
MEM1016.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM1016.Message: Memory device at location %1 is not installed correctly.

SWC0207.Message: Display the version info of RACADM

UEFI0216.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Late Command Training phase.
UEFI0216.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0216.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC068.Description: Both SHA256Password and Plain Password cannot be attempted to set together on Configuration import per user.
RAC068.Resolution: One of either SHA256Password or Plain password can be attempted to be imported for an user.
RAC068.Message: SHA256Password and Plain Password cannot be imported together.

VDR12.Description: This message is generated after reconfiguration of a virtual disk starts.

RRDU0004.Resolution: Install additional SD card and configure for redundancy if redundancy is desired.
RRDU0004.Message: Internal Dual SD Module is not redundant.

PWR8571.Description: Another power action is in progress. The requested power action cannot be carried out until the power action in progress completes
PWR8571.Resolution: Wait for the power action in progress to complete and retry the operation. It may take a few minutes for the current power action to complete.
PWR8571.Message: Unable to perform the power action requested for the server %1because another power action is in progress.

PR14.Description: The device identified in the message could not apply the configuration settings. This may indicate configuration changes since the last system inventory.
PR14.Resolution: Check the current system configuration and retry the operation.
PR14.Message: The configuration could not be applied to device: %1

AMP0321.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0321.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes
AMP0321.Message: Chassis power level current is greater than the upper critical threshold.

RAC0155.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about system temperature.
RAC0155.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0155.Message: Unable to retrieve the temperature information. The system is powered off.

SYS021.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of incorrect parameters or internal firmware issues.
SYS021.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following: 1) verify the value being set is correct, 2) reset the iDRAC.
SYS021.Message: Unable to set the value for %1

PDR27.Description: A user assigned a physical disk as a dedicated hot spare to a virtual disk. See Protecting Your Virtual Disk with a Hot Spare for more information. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SYS011.Description: A configuration job is scheduled to apply pending set attribute operations. Set operations are not allowed if there is an existing configuration job for a component.
SYS011.Resolution: Wait for the scheduled job to complete or delete the configuration jobs before attempting more set attribute operations.
SYS011.Message: Pending configuration values are already committed, unable to perform another set operation.

PST0013.Description: System extended memory test in progress.

LIC204.Description: This error occurs when the Lifecycle Controller restore operation is interrupted before it completes. This can occur due to a power outage or when the iDRAC is reset while the restore operation is in progress.
LIC204.Resolution: Repeat the Lifecycle Controller restore operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC204.Message: The License Manager database restore operation failed.

BOOT013.Description: The boot list is currently not active. Changes cannot be made to boot list that is not active.
BOOT013.Resolution: Alter boot mode to set the boot list active and retry the operation.
BOOT013.Message: Cannot make changes to non-active boot list.

SWC0723.Description: iDRAC is not responding to the current Reset status query.
SWC0723.Message: Error occurred while Resetting to defaults. The Reset status is not available.

CTL81.Description: The security key assigned to the controller identified in the message is modified.
CTL81.Message: Security key assigned to %1 is modified.

FAN0004.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.
FAN0004.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0004.Message: Fan %1 RPM is outside of range.

IOV1004.Description: The parameters for the method identified in the message are not passed correctly.
IOV1004.Resolution: Refer to the DCIM Chassis PCI Management Profile document and provide the required parameters.
IOV1004.Message: Too many slots provided as parameters to Assign and UnAssign Servers methods.

RED049.Description: When an Automatic Backup or Automatic Update recurring operation is disabled or the license for this feature is expired, the next job in the sequence had not started yet and was deleted.
RED049.Message: The job %1 is deleted because the recurring operation %2 is currently not enabled.

RAC1185.Description: The static IPv6 address is not configured because an invalid IPv6 address or IPv6 Gateway is entered.
RAC1185.Resolution: Enter a valid IPv6 address and IPv6 Gateway, and retry the operation.
RAC1185.Message: Unable to configure static IPv6 address because an invalid IPv6 address or IPv6 Gateway is entered.

SWC0221.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0221.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0221.Message: The -l option requires -c to also be specified.

RAC1020.Description: Some objects have dependencies on other objects that are required to perform a task. The specified group does not contain any objects, because the dependent objects are not part of the current system configuration.
RAC1020.Resolution: Verify the dependencies of the objects under the specified group using "racadm help <device class>.<groupname>", and retry the operation. For example, "racadm help NIC.IscsiSecondTgtParams".
RAC1020.Message: No objects are available under the specified group for the current system configuration.

UEFI0065.Description: One or more attributes are successfully configured. The system is automatically turned off in 5 seconds.
UEFI0065.Message: One or more attributes are successfully configured. The system will be automatically turned off in 5 seconds.

SWC0126.Description: Racadm tool was unable to download the generated CSR file.

RAC946.Description: The "Auto Dedicated NIC" mode cannot be set for a NIC if the NIC selection mode is set to "Dedicated NIC".
RAC946.Resolution: To set the NIC to Auto Dedicated NIC mode, set NIC selection mode to "Shared NIC", and retry the operation.
RAC946.Message: Unable to set the NIC to Auto Dedicated NIC mode.

SWC0286.Description: Objects in the cfgUserAdmin group corresponding to index 1 cannot be modified.
SWC0286.Message: Modifying the user configuration at index 1 is not allowed.

PWR8568.Description: The server identified in the message did not gracefully shutdown before the CMC shutdown timer expired. This happens if the server did not show power off status change within 60 seconds after the operation was initiated, or if the OS in the server has not successfully shutdown.
PWR8568.Resolution: Check if the OS in the server identified in the message has successfully shutdown, if not, manually complete the shutdown or wait for the shutdown to complete normally. If the issue persists, perform a forced power down of the server identified in the message.
PWR8568.Message: Server %1 did not gracefully shutdown before the timer expired.

SYS008.Description: The input value for the specified attribute is not a valid boolean value for the attribute.
SYS008.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and provide a valid boolean value for the specified attribute.
SYS008.Message: Invalid boolean in value for attribute: %1.

ENC1.Description: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has failed is inserted into the enclosure.

SYS151.Description: A System Erase job with the job ID identified in the message is completed.

TMP0110.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0110.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0110.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is outside of range.

VLT0214.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0214.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0214.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

VFL0719.Description: The SD card is in use by another process. Initialization requires exclusive access to the SD card to complete the initialization.
VFL0719.Resolution: The SD card is in use by another process. Retry after a few minutes.
VFL0719.Message: One or more partitions are in use; the SD card could not be initialized.

ISM0027.Description: An unprivileged user identified in the message tried to perform an iDRAC Hard Reset operation from the operating system (OS).
ISM0027.Message: An unprivileged user %1 tried to perform an iDRAC Hard Reset operation from the operating system (OS).

SWC0294.Description: The group name specified is incorrect.
SWC0294.Resolution: Refer to the list of groups available and choose the correct one.

RED058.Description: A repository update job with the job ID identified in the message was created.
RED058.Message: A repository update job %1 was created.

RAC1041.Description: Successfully configured the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings.
RAC1041.Message: Successfully configured the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings.

RFM1022.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.

RAC0693.Description: Pending operations are created for the selected operations on the selected physical disk drives.
RAC0693.Resolution: To view the pending operations, click the Pending Operations button.
RAC0693.Message: Pending operations are created for the selected operations on the selected physical disk drives.

LC004.Description: The Provisioning Server parameter information is not formatted correctly.
LC004.Resolution: Verify the string format. Enter a valid IP address or hostname for the Provisioning Server such as: 1) hostname 2) hostname.domain.com 3) 1.1.1.1 4) hostname:8080 5) hostname.dell.com:8080 6) hostname1:80,hostname2:8080
LC004.Message: Provisioning Server information is not formatted correctly.

OSD19.Description: Failed to execute fork() system call to perform the task in a child process. iDRAC may be unresponsive.
OSD19.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD19.Message: The fork() command for a child process to perform the task failed.

RAC1187.Description: The remote diagnostics operation could not be initiated because the Start Time entered is invalid. It is earlier than the current iDRAC time.
RAC1187.Resolution: Enter a Start Time that is later than the current iDRAC time and retry the operation. Run the "racadm getractime" command to obtain the current iDRAC time.
RAC1187.Message: Invalid Start Time Entered. Unable to start the Remote Diagnostics operation because the Start Time entered is earlier than the current iDRAC time.

UEFI0144.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error happens during the identification of memory module type or memory size.
UEFI0144.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0144.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

RAC0758.Description: The Tech Support Report generation will take the time identified in the message to complete.
RAC0758.Resolution: To cancel the reports collection click Cancel.
RAC0758.Message: Tech Support Report (TSR) data is being collected. This operation will take less than %1 minutes.

SWC8611.Description: CMC cannot perform the server profile application because the selected profile version and the server identified in the message are not compatible.
SWC8611.Resolution: Make sure to select the correct version of the profile and/or server, and then retry the operation.
SWC8611.Message: Profile "%1" and Server (Service Tag: %2 in Slot %3) are not compatible.

SUP0130.Message: TFTP firmware update has been initiated. This update process may take several minutes to complete.

UEFI0276.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the initiator information from DHCPv6 server cannot be obtained.
UEFI0276.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Check the configuration of DHCPv6 server. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable DHCP and configure the initiator information manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0276.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the initiator information from DHCPv6 server cannot be obtained.

RAC017.Description: The requested job has been created.
RAC017.Message: Job created to apply the attribute value.

SEL1206.Message: An entry was added to auxiliary log.

PDR1007.Message: Rebuild is in progress for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

SWU8527.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation is successful.
SWU8527.Message: Successfully completed the iKVM firmware update.

SWC8610.Description: All settings of the selected profile were sent to the server identified in the message and the operation is captured in the job identified in the message.
SWC8610.Message: Job ID: %1. CMC sent all settings of profile %2 to Server (Service Tag: %3) in Slot %4.

RFM1020.Message: Removable Flash Media is IPMI-function ready.

SYS125.Description: The OS Collector application is unable to communicate with the WMI service. This may be because the user context the application is running in does not have appropriate access privileges or firewall/security settings are preventing retrieving registry and software data from WMI.
SYS125.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure the user context the OS Collector application is running in has the appropriate privileges to access WMI. Make sure that firewall or security settings are set to allow access and retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, restart the WMI service and retry the operation. 3) If the issue continues to persists, restart the server OS and retry the operation.
SYS125.Message: OS Collector: Unable to communicate with WMI services.

SWC0234.Description: The remote host specified for the ftp update is not reachable.
SWC0234.Resolution: Check the connectivity between iDRAC and the remote host used for the ftp update.
SWC0234.Message: Remote host is not reachable or connection is interrupted.

SWC0223.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0223.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0223.Message: Invalid syntax. The -d option is not valid with -p.

RAC071.Description: The iDRAC reset operation cannot be completed because a firmware upgrade operation is in progress.
RAC071.Resolution: Wait for the current update process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC071.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset operation because the firmware upgrade operation is in progress.

USR8502.Description: The operation to close a user session using the session ID identified in the message was successful.

LC078.Description: The Message Registry was successfully exported to the specified destination file folder.
LC078.Message: The Export Message Registry operation was successfully completed.

PSU0092.Description: The rating of the power supply unit identified in the message does not exceed system power distribution limits.
PSU0092.Message: Power supply unit %1 rating is appropriate for the system power distribution limits.

ISM0002.Description: The OS to iDRAC Pass-through mode is disabled. The iDRAC Service Module is currently enabling the OS to iDRAC Pass-through mode in the USB NIC mode. This operation is done only for the first run of iDRAC Service Module. If OS to iDRAC Pass-through is disabled after this point of time, iDRAC Service Module will not be able to connect to iDRAC until user enables the OS-iDRAC Pass-through in the USB mode.
ISM0002.Message: The OS to iDRAC Pass-through is disabled. The iDRAC Service Module is currently enabling the OS to iDRAC Pass-through in the USB NIC mode.

LC067.Description: The Export Certification operation successfully exported the SSL Certificate.

UEFI0139.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This situation is caused by LC partition attach issues.
UEFI0139.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0139.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

PFM0004.Description: The value of the sensor identified in the message is within specified limits.
PFM0004.Message: The value of %1 is within specified limits.

MEM9014.Description: The memory device identified in the message has encountered a correctable memory error. This may be an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM9014.Resolution: This is a correctable error. Review log information and if multiple correctable errors have occurred on the DIMM identified in the message, re-install the memory device. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9014.Message: A correctable memory error has occurred in Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) device %1.

BAR114.Description: The Automatic Backup job identified in the message is created per the Server Profile automatic export schedule previously configured.
BAR114.Message: An Automatic Backup job %1 is created.

SWC0268.Description: The ASR screen is already cleared.
SWC0268.Message: There is no ASR screen currently available to clear

RAC920.Description: From firmware racadm, the inlet temperature history can be exported only to a remote file share.
RAC920.Resolution: Create a remote file share to export the inlet temperature history. Else, use remote/local racadm to export to the file system accessible by the racadm executable.
RAC920.Message: This interface does not support the specified option.

RED052.Description: Processing of update packages is starting. Attempting a manual update will not be possible until current update package processing is completed.
RED052.Message: Processing of update packages is starting.

RAC0905.Description: Unable to obtain the USC version details.
RAC0905.Message: Failed to get the USC version details.

LIC001.Description: The command or command parameters passed to License Manager is invalid. This is an internal error indicative of memory corruption. Under normal circumstances this error should not occur.
LIC001.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC001.Message: The License Manager command parameter used is invalid.

SWC8550.Description: An insufficient number of unused MAC addresses are available in the Virtual MAC Address database to capture the requested number of profiles.
SWC8550.Resolution: Add more MAC addresses to the Virtual MAC Address Pool and retry the capture Boot Identity profile operation. Using the CMC GUI, navigate to the Boot Identity page. More MAC addresses are added using "Add MAC Address" option provided in "Manage Virtual MAC Address Pool" section.
SWC8550.Message: Unable to capture the server profile because an insufficient number of unused Media Access Control (MAC) addresses in the Virtual MAC Address Pool.

HWC0016.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to communicate with iDRAC.
HWC0016.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.

CTL69.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL69.Message: Attempted to import virtual disk with outdated physical disk information on %1.

CMC8579.Description: The security certificate cannot be uploaded because of an Unexpected Event issue in the Remote Access Controller.
CMC8579.Resolution: Upload the certificate again and retry operation.
CMC8579.Message: Unable to upload the security certificate because of an Unexpected Event issue in the Remote Access Controller (RAC).

SWC8555.Description: The Boot Identity operation cannot be started because a Boot Identity operation is already in progress.
SWC8555.Resolution: Wait for the current operation to complete, and then retry. Only one Boot Identity operation can be performed at a time.
SWC8555.Message: Unable to start the Boot Identity profile operation because a Boot Identity operation is already in progress.

MEM1201.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM1201.Message: Memory RAID redundancy is lost. Check memory device at location(s) %1.

RAC0747.Description: Unable to perform reset configuration on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0747.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes.
RAC0747.Message: Unable to perform reset configuration on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

MEM0601.Message: Memory device is removed from location %1.

RAC0611.Description: The IP address cannot be blank for import or export of system configuration profile operation.
RAC0611.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Address for network location.

RAC1000.Description: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 Address1 and IPv6 Gateway, because the object IPv6 Autoconfig is enabled.
RAC1000.Resolution: Disable the object IPv6 AutoConfig using "racadm set iDRAC.IPv6.AutoConfig <0 | Disabled >", and retry the operation.
RAC1000.Message: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 address or gateway.

UEFI0163.Description: Unsupported DIMM module with technology less than 2Gb is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0163.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0163.Message: Unsupported DIMM module with less than 2Gb technology is installed on memory slot: %1.

UEFI0236.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - FIFO Reset phase.
UEFI0236.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0236.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC063.Description: The string length of the entered value for the attribute identified in the message may be less than the minimum length or greater than the maximum length allowed.
RAC063.Resolution: Make sure that the string length is correct and retry the operation.
RAC063.Message: The string length of the provided value for %1 is inappropriate.

SWC0159.Message: Kerberos Keytab successfully uploaded to the RAC.

DKM1004.Resolution: Check for network connectivity. Review network, server, and client configuration.
DKM1004.Message: The key management server received a bad request.

UEFI0247.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. The requested Memory Mapped IO (MMIOH) size is not supported. MMIOH allocation was forced instead.
UEFI0247.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0247.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

BAT1031.Description: The room temperature may be too hot. In addition, the system fan may be degraded or failed.
BAT1031.Resolution: Verify that the room temperature is normal and that fans are functioning properly. See the storage hardware documentation for acceptable operating temperatures.
BAT1031.Message: The battery temperature on %1 is above normal.

MEM9005.Description: A link degradation was detected in propagation of signals between processor and memory through the Intel SMI 2 memory interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9005.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9005.Message: Intel SMI 2 Memory interconnect %1 has degraded.

RDU8524.Description: CMC failover action is not allowed in the current configuration.

RED022.Description: The version compatibility check of the firmware update package was not successful for the device specified.
RED022.Resolution: The version compatibility check was not successful for the device specified. Verify that the firmware version pre-requisites specified in the release notes are satisfied.
RED022.Message: Version compatibility check was not successful.

RAC1063.Description: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.
RAC1063.Resolution: Run the RACADM command "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1" to enable Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.
RAC1063.Message: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation because Lifecycle Controller is disabled.

OSD72.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ImageName' is missing.
OSD72.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ImageName" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD72.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ImageName' is missing.

HWC3006.Description: There are not enough IPv4 addresses reserved for the servers in this chassis. Therefore the newly inserted server could not be configured with the QuickDeploy feature.
HWC3006.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the number of reserved IPv4 addresses for QuickDeploy. 2) Modify it such that the newly inserted blade will obtain an IP address for QuickDeploy. 3) Reseat the server to retry the QuickDeploy operation or manually configure the network parameters for the server. (Note that some chassis models may require a response at the LCD panel)
HWC3006.Message: Unable to QuickDeploy server in slot %1.

PWR2207.Message: The system is in a mechanical off state.

BAR013.Description: The request to shut the Host system down did not complete successfully.
BAR013.Resolution: Restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) and retry the operation.

SWC0227.Description: Invalid values passed to the function.
SWC0227.Resolution: Enter a shorter path to the firmware image file.
SWC0227.Message: Partition label exceeds maximum limit of 6 alphanumeric characters.

UEFI0094.Description: Unsupported Non-ECC memory module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0094.Resolution: Remove all Non-ECC DIMMs and replace them with ECC DIMMs. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0094.Message: Unsupported Non-ECC memory module is installed on memory slot: %1.

OSD60.Description: Connecting ISO using Remote File Share (RFS) was unsuccessful.
OSD60.Resolution: Verify ISO is connected using Remote File Share (RFS) and retry the operation.
OSD60.Message: Unable to connect to ISO using Remote File Share (RFS).

IOV012.Description: By default, the non-licensed system assigns virtual adapters (VA) 1-4 to servers 1-4 respectively.
IOV012.Resolution: Import a license which enables the assignment of a PERC virtual adapter (VA) to any server. For more information about licenses, contact your service provider.
IOV012.Message: Unable to assign a virtual adapter (VA) to a non-default server because a license is required.

LC011.Description: There was a general failure in the certificate import process.
LC011.Resolution: Try one of the following: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and run the command.

LC033.Description: The Hardware Inventory XML file representing the system configuration as shipped from the factory was successful.
LC033.Message: As-Shipped Hardware Inventory export was successful.

FSD002.Description: A RACADM Debug command failed. If the RACADM Debug command was executed under the direction of Dell tech support then further assistance from tech support should be requested. Otherwise this command is not intended for customer use.
FSD002.Resolution: Verify all of the following 1) ensure that the unblock, grant, and invoke/start/stop/resume commands are all executed against the same iDRAC. 2) ensure dat.ini file has not been changed in any way. 3) ensure that current date falls between the start and end times. Note that Dell can further restrict both the set of debugCaps that is authorized and the start and stop times. If an authorized person did not enter a RACADM debug command then an attacker may have entered the command.
FSD002.Message: Debug authorization failed; for debugCaps: %1, authorized by iDRAC user: %2, and Dell employee: %3, at %4 for the period: %5 to %6.

SWC0230.Description: vFlash is not enabled. This may be because the user does not have enough privileges.

UEFI0143.Resolution: Replace the processor(s) with supported ones. For more information about supported processors, contact your service provider.

RAC0504.Description: Enclosures cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, there is no enclosure connected to the controller, or there is a bad or disconnected adapter cable for the enclosure.
RAC0504.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is ON. 2. Check if the Storage Enclosure is ON. 3. Verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0504.Message: There are no enclosures to be displayed.

MEM1011.Message: Memory device at location %1 is on-duty.

SUP025.Description: Generic message to show that last command was successful.

SUP0540.Description: The update packages cannot be installed because of insufficient space in the iDRAC even after deleing firmware installation files stored in the Rollback feature.
SUP0540.Resolution: Delete Lifecycle Controller related data by using the Repurpose or Retire System features, and then retry the operation.
SUP0540.Message: Unable to install update packages because of insufficient space in the iDRAC.

SWC0110.Description: The build information is not available for racdump.
SWC0110.Message: No build information is currently available.

AMP0310.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0310.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0310.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is outside of range.

OSD39.Description: Unable to get VFlash information from internal instrumentation.
OSD39.Resolution: 1) Make sure the Dell VFlash is seated correctly. 2) Make sure a Dell licensed VFlash card is inserted 3) Make sure the Dell VFlash doesn't have any hardware issues by accessing it through the iDRAC GUI.

RFM1035.Message: Media is present for Removable Flash Media.

CPU0000.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.
CPU0000.Resolution: Review System Event Log and Operating System Logs. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SYS005.Description: The AttributeName input array and AttributeValue input array do not have the same number of elements.
SYS005.Resolution: Verify AttributeName and AttributeValue pairs match and are valid. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation.
SYS005.Message: AttributeName array and AttributeValue array element count mismatch.

PWR8590.Description: The PCIe Mezzanine card in the slot C1 is absent. Without PCIe Mezzanine cards, the chassis PCIe cards will not be available for servers.
PWR8590.Resolution: Insert a PCIe Mezzanine card in slot C1.
PWR8590.Message: The server-%1 does not have PCIe Mezzanine card in slot C1.

VF051.Description: The copying partition operation did not complete successfully.
VF051.Message: Export partition operation did not complete successfully.

CPU0700.Description: System BIOS was unable to boot the processor.
CPU0700.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SUP0511.Description: The Diagnostic application (Embedded Preboot System Assessment - Enterprise UEFI Diagnostics) is not installed or is corrupt.
SUP0511.Resolution: Update the Diagnostics application using the Firmware Update feature in Lifecycle Controller. For the latest Update Packages, contact your service provider.

CTL65.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL65.Message: Attempted to import Unsupported Virtual Disk type RAID%1 on %2.

VDR34.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk failed.
VDR34.Resolution: Run a consistency check on the virtual disk. If that fails, check the health of the member drives of the virtual disk and then recreate.

CMC8564.Description: The KVM is not mapped to any of the server slots.
CMC8564.Message: The KVM mapping feature is disabled.

HWC2013.Message: Fabric mismatch corrected on fabric %1 with server in slot %2.

BAR042.Description: Lifecycle Controller/System services are not available. There is another operation using the resources at this time.
BAR042.Resolution: Wait for the other operation to release the resources, as indicated by the System Services option presence and retry the operation.

ENC18.Description: The controller has lost communication with an Enclosure Management Module (EMM). The cables may be loose or defective.
ENC18.Resolution: Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables. Reboot the system.

PR29.Description: The device that the job was intended for has no previous information recorded. The request has failed as this information is required to initiate the operation. This has been deprecated.
PR29.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory on Restart attribute of the Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. Alternatively, use the Unified Server Configurator utility.
PR29.Message: Unable to locate device in previous configuration.

CTL79.Description: This controller does not support features required for this chassis. This controller will not be powered on to prevent data loss.
CTL79.Resolution: Replace the controller with a supported controller.
CTL79.Message: Controller in %1 is not supported and will not be powered on.

USR8501.Description: The operation to close a user session using the process ID identified in the message was successful.
USR8501.Message: Successfully closed Session process: pid=%1 sid=%2

RAC0131.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while deleting the vFlash partition.
RAC0131.Message: An error has occurred while deleting a partition.

RAC1117.Description: The operation specified in the command could not be successfully completed.
RAC1117.Resolution: Retry the operation after 2 minutes. If the problem persists, contact your service provider.

PWR8676.Description: The chassis power property identified in the message cannot be set.
PWR8676.Message: Unable to set the chassis power property %1.

STOR069.Description: The method name identified in the message could not be successfully completed, because the number of elements entered for VDPropNameArry and VDPropValueArray is not equal.
STOR069.Resolution: Enter equal number of elements (pair value), and then retry the operation.
STOR069.Message: Unable to run the %1 method, because the number of elements entered for VDPropNameArry and VDPropValueArray is unequal.

SWC8510.Description: Unable to communicate with the iDRAC of the requested Server.
SWC8510.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required. The Lifecycle log in the server may have additional information about the inability of the iDRAC to apply Profile settings.
SWC8510.Message: Unable to apply %1 Profile to requested Server(s)

UEFI0025.Description: The Management Engine firmware cannot be initialized. The BIOS will reset the system to retry the initialization process.
UEFI0025.Resolution: Wait for the BIOS to reset the system and reinitialize the Management Engine. If the issue persists, turn off the input power to the system and turn on again.
UEFI0025.Message: Unable to initialize Management Engine firmware.

RED047.Description: An Automatic Server Profile Backup or Automatic Update operation is already configured.
RED047.Resolution: Clear the existing configuration settings for the operation identified in the message and retry the operation.
RED047.Message: A recurring operation %1 was not created because the operation is already configured.

RAC066.Description: iDRAC was successfully reset to factory-default properties.
RAC066.Message: iDRAC is successfully reset to factory-default properties.

RAC0697.Description: Choose to create a job from the existing successful pending operations.
RAC0697.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Click Pending Operations button to view pending operations. 2) Click Create Job button to create a configuration job. 3) Click Cancel button to quit job creation.
RAC0697.Message: Choose to create a job from the existing successful pending operations.

RDU8502.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.
RDU8502.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8502.Message: CMC%1 cannot go standby since the other CMC is not present or healthy.

SWC0257.Description: Invalid number of arguments were passed to the command.
SWC0257.Resolution: Refer the help text for the command.
SWC0257.Message: Invalid syntax. Too many options specified.

RAC1024.Description: The pending value is applied during the next reboot of system.
RAC1024.Resolution: Verify the job status using "racadm jobqueue view -i JID_xxxxx" command.

SUP0541.Description: The maximum disk space (storage capacity) for storing firmware image files is reached. The rollback firmware image file identified in the message was deleted to create free disk space.
SUP0541.Message: The maximum disk space (storage capacity) for storing firmware image files is reached. The rollback firmware image file of %1 was deleted to create free disk space.

RAC045.Description: The combination of input parameters provided did not match any event filters.
RAC045.Resolution: Verify the combination of input parameters and retry the operation.
RAC045.Message: Event filter does not exist for input parameter combination.

OSE1003.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. Verify the media in C: is bootable. See system video for additional information.

UEFI0019.Description: The system boot process did not complete repeatedly due to problems encountered while performing a Lifecycle Controller task for function. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0019.Resolution: Repair Lifecycle Controller firmware using the Lifecycle Controller Dell Update Package (DUP) or Lifecycle Controller Repair Package via iDRAC. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
UEFI0019.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) is unable to complete a requested task or function and prevented the boot process from completing on multiple attempts. LC is in Recovery Mode.

PSU0007.Description: A power supply that is designed to operate at 220V, but is connected to a 110V power source requires additional current for operation. The additional current may trip circuit-breakers or cause other electrical issues with the input source.
PSU0007.Resolution: Check input power source and cabling. Use recommended input power. Review the product documentation. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0007.Message: Power supply %1 is operating at 110 volts, and could cause a circuit breaker fault.

SEC0018.Message: The I/O card area is closed.

MEM1015.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in a power active state.

TST104.Description: The SNMP trap being tested is not properly configured.
TST104.Resolution: Configure the SNMP trap and retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC.

SWC0008.Description: The export As Shipped hardware inventory operation did not complete because the destination: 1) does not have the specified folder, 2) does not have enough free space, or 3) is read-only.
SWC0008.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, verify the following and retry the operation: 1) Destination has the specified folder. 2) Destination has enough free space. 3) Destination is not write-protected.
SWC0008.Message: Unable to write the As Shipped hardware inventory to the specified destination.

SWU8533.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation is not successful, because the target is not ready.
SWU8533.Resolution: Wait for the target to become ready. This may take a few minutes. After the target is ready, then retry the operation.
SWU8533.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because the target is not ready. ErrorCode=0x%1.

OSD9.Description: Resetting the targeted server using the standard IPMI command has failed.
OSD9.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD9.Message: Failed to reboot the system using an IPMI command.

SYS183.Description: The memory cannot be allocated because of insufficient storage space in iDRAC.
SYS183.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and then retry the operation.
SYS183.Message: Unable to allocate memory because of insufficient storage space in iDRAC.

DIS006.Description: Auto Discovery operation was successful in establishing connection and getting certificate. Auto Discovery feature is no longer needed and has been disabled.
DIS006.Message: Auto Discovery operation successful. Disabling Auto Discovery feature.

BAT1026.Description: The controller has retrieved cached data.
BAT1026.Message: The %1 has recovered cached data from the Battery Backup Unit (BBU).

STOR094.Description: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.
STOR094.Resolution: To apply the configuration operation immediately, create a configuration job using the --realTime option. To apply the configuration after restarting the server, create a configuration job using the -r option. To create the necessary real-time and restart jobs, run the jobqueue command. For more information about jobqueue command, run the racadm help jobqueue command.
STOR094.Message: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.

UEFI0125.Description: Unable to finish The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) image rebuild process because of issues.
UEFI0125.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat or replace the SD card media. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0125.Message: Unable to finish The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) image rebuild process because of issues.

PR34.Description: The job was attempted but failed unexpectedly. An AC Power loss, system crash, or other interruption during the job processing can cause this failure.
PR34.Message: %1 failed after exceeding retry attempt limit.

PST0136.Description: System BIOS detected an failure with the programmable interval timer during POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.(BIOS POST Exception code 88)
PST0136.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

CTL28.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL28.Message: The Background Initialization (BGI) rate has changed for %1.

PWR8683.Description: A Virtual Reseat for the peripheral sled identified in the message is initiated. A Virtual Reseat is the same as removing and inserting a peripheral sled.
PWR8683.Message: Initiated the Virtual Reseat of peripheral %1.

LIC020.Description: Importing an upgrade license without a base license is not allowed, as it may be a violation of the license EULA agreement. If the base license was deleted, the system allows the user to override the warning by invoking the import override option.
LIC020.Resolution: If the base license was deleted, override the warning by invoking the import override option.
LIC020.Message: Import failed: End User License Agreement (EULA) import upgrade warning.

VDR27.Description: The check consistency on a virtual disk has resumed processing after a pause.
VDR27.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR27.Message: The consistency check on a %1 has been resumed.

SYS167.Description: The TTY Log data export did not complete within the allocated time. Currently the maximum allocated time is 20 minutes.
SYS167.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
SYS167.Message: TTY Log data export did not complete within the allocated time.

RAC0912.Description: The management system could not connect to the iDRAC.
RAC0912.Resolution: Verify whether the IP address of the remote iDRAC is correct. Verify whether connectivity exists between the management system and the iDRAC.
RAC0912.Message: Unable to connect to RAC at specified IP address.

PDR52.Description: The controller has two connectors that are connected to the same enclosure. The communication path on one connector has lost connection with the enclosure. The communication path on the other connector is reporting this loss.
PDR52.Resolution: Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. Make sure both Enclosure Management Modules (EMMs) are healthy.

PWR8667.Description: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is resetting iKVM to its default settings.
PWR8667.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is resetting iKVM to its default settings.

PSU0078.Description: This power supply revision is not supported for this system.
PSU0078.Resolution: Review product documentation, change power supply with correct revision.

SWC0220.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0220.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0220.Message: The -u option requires -c to also be specified.

SEC0700.Description: If the property name is configured without changing the default password, iDRAC may be accessible on the Internet. This causes a severe security risk for iDRAC.
SEC0700.Resolution: To change the password, run the following racadm command: racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.Password <new password string>.Alternatively, to avoid this warning message, run the following racadm command: racadm set iDRAC.Tuning.DefaultCredentialWarning Disable.
SEC0700.Message: Warning: Default username and password are currently in use. It is strongly recommended to change the default password before configuring the property. Else, it causes a severe security risk for iDRAC.

MEM9007.Description: A non-recoverable link issue was detected in propagation of signals between processor and memory through the Intel SMI 2 memory interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9007.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9007.Message: Intel SMI 2 Memory interconnect %1 has a non-recoverable issue.

SEC0100.Description: The Storage disk tray identified in the message is open. The tray should be closed as soon as any service action is completed. Leaving the tray open for an extended period may result in drives over heating.
SEC0100.Resolution: Close the Storage disk tray identified in the message.

RDU8512.Description: The firmware versions of the Active CMC and the Standby CMC are different.
RDU8512.Resolution: Update the firmware so that the Active and Standby CMC firmware versions are the same.

SUP029.Description: The catalog in the repository specified in the operation has the same firmware versions as currently present on the server. Firmware updates in the specified repository are not applicable to the server.
SUP029.Message: Firmware versions on server match catalog, applicable updates are not present in the repository.

USR0014.Description: The user session which is currently in use is invalid.
USR0014.Message: The current user session is invalid.

VF052.Description: The device is not ready to access media information.

SYS015.Description: The requested job has been created.

UEFI0091.Description: A Quad-Rank (QR) DIMM is installed on the memory slot identified in the message. QR DIMMs should be installed on the first DIMM slot in a channel if there is only one QR DIMM in the channel. QR DIMMs cannot be installed on the third slot of the channel.
UEFI0091.Resolution: Install the QR DIMM in the correct channel. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0091.Message: A Quad-Rank (QR) DIMM is installed on memory slot: %1. QR DIMMs should be installed on the first DIMM slot in a channel if there is only one QR DIMM in the channel. QR DIMMs cannot be installed on the third slot of the channel.

DIS014.Description: Auto Discovery client is using the customer provided Certificate Authority certificate to authenticate the Provisioning Server for the SSL connection.
DIS014.Message: Auto Discovery client using customer provided CA certificate to authenticate Provisioning Server.

BAR095.Description: The request to restore a System Profile from a Backup file did not complete successfully because there is already a request in progress.
BAR095.Resolution: If possible monitor the in progress job for completion and then retry the request. If that is not possible try clearing all jobs and try the request again. If the issue persists, restart the Integrated Remote Access controller and try the request again.
BAR095.Message: Another Restore operation already in progress.

UEFI0256.Description: Unable to allocate legacy I/O resources for one of more PCIe devices because the legacy I/O space limit was reached. The legacy I/O space limit is 64K.
UEFI0256.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Remove unused PCIe cards to free up legacy I/O space. 2) Go to System Setup and disable unused PCIe cards to free up legacy I/O space.
UEFI0256.Message: Unable to allocate legacy I/O resources for one of more PCIe devices because the legacy I/O space limit was reached.

PDR113.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message has either reached or exceeded the warranted wear-out limit.
PDR113.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.
PDR113.Message: The %1 has reached or exceeded its warranted wear-out limit.

TMP0121.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm.
TMP0121.Message: The system inlet temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

RAC1032.Description: The job specified in the message were cancelled.
RAC1032.Message: %1 jobs was cancelled by the user.

VLT0202.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0202.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0202.Message: The system board %1 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

MEM0001.Description: The memory has encountered a uncorrectable error. System performance may be degraded. The operating system and/or applications may fail as a result.
MEM0001.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0001.Message: Multi-bit memory errors detected on a memory device at location(s) %1.

RAC919.Description: Racadm could not export the inlet temperature history file to the specified remote share. This is because the specified share may be write- protected.
RAC919.Resolution: To export the file, change the permissions on the remote share. Else, create another share with write permissions.
RAC919.Message: Copy to remote share unsuccessful. Remote share might be write protected.

BAT1004.Description: The controller battery must be fully charged before the learn cycle can begin. The battery may be unable to maintain a full charge causing the learn cycle to timeout. In addition, the battery must be able to maintain cached data for a specified period of time in the event of a power loss. For example, some batteries maintain cached data for 24 hours. If the battery is unable to maintain cached data for the required period of time, then the Learn cycle will timeout.
BAT1004.Resolution: Replace the battery pack. The battery is unable to maintain a full charge.
BAT1004.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has timed out.

VDR20.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk has failed or is corrupt. You may also have cancelled the rebuild.
VDR20.Resolution: Replace the failed or corrupt disk. You can identify a disk that has failed by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. Restart the virtual disk rebuild.

RDU0018.Description: The storage system has multiple redundant power lines. One or more of these power lines is no longer available.
RDU0018.Resolution: Turn system off and remove AC input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. If the issue still persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
RDU0018.Message: The storage power redundancy is degraded.

SYS013.Description: The attribute name provided for the requested operation does not exist on the target system or is invalid.
SYS013.Resolution: For more information, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

UEFI0051.Description: Brand information is successfully collected. The system is being restarted. The rebranding process is completed.
UEFI0051.Message: Brand information is successfully collected. The system is being restarted.

OSD48.Description: ISO Images of more than 4GB are not supported and cannot be copied to VFlash.
OSD48.Resolution: Use an ISO that is smaller than 4GB.
OSD48.Message: ISO Images of more than 4GB not supported.

CMC8519.Description: FRU of the LOM riser specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8519.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8519.Message: The LOM riser FRU for slot %1 FRU ID %2 is not functioning.

STOR013.Description: One or more storage device(s) are in a state that prevents the operation from completing.
STOR013.Resolution: Make sure the specified storage devices are in a state appropriate for the requested operation and retry the operation.
STOR013.Message: One or more storage device(s) are not in a state where the operation can be completed.

LC068.Description: The import or export system configuration operation cannot be performed because there are pending attribute changes or a configuration job is in progress.
LC068.Resolution: Apply or cancel any pending attribute changes. Changes can be applied by creating a targeted configuration job, or the changes can be cancelled by invoking the DeletePendingConfiguration method. If a configuration job is in progress, wait until it is completed before retrying the import or export system configuration operation.
LC068.Message: Unable to perform the import or export operation because there are pending attribute changes or a configuration job is in progress.

UEFI0145.Description: The Trusted Platform Module (TPM) installed on this system is not supported.
UEFI0145.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the BIOS firmware. 2) Replace the TPM with a supported one. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0145.Message: The Trusted Platform Module (TPM) installed on this system is not supported.

VLT0234.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0234.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions. 2) Reseat the mezzanine card. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0234.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is outside of range.

PWR8520.Description: The chassis reset operation was initiated.

PWR8533.Message: Power cap changed from %1 W AC to %1 W AC.

SUP0507.Description: The FTP server setting details are incorrect.
SUP0507.Resolution: Enter the correct FTP server settings details, and retry the operation.
SUP0507.Message: Unable to download the Update Packages from the FTP server.

SUP0503.Description: Unable to retrieve the system ID from BIOS.
SUP0503.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do one of the following: 1) Reboot the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the BIOS firmware to the latest version and retry the operation. If the problem continues to persist contact the service provider.
SUP0503.Message: Unable to retrieve the system ID.

UEFI0197.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Read Level Coarse Training phase.
UEFI0197.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0197.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

STOR306.Description: Controller mode cannot be changed as the controller currently has the security key assigned.
STOR306.Resolution: Delete the security key and retry the operation.
STOR306.Message: Unable to change controller mode while security key is assigned to the controller.

UEFI0021.Description: The Lifecycle Controller feature is disabled. The feature was disabled because of one of the following conditions: 1) The feature was disabled manually using the F2 System Setup utility or through an iDRAC interface, 2) BIOS encountered an issue starting the feature and automatically disabled it.
UEFI0021.Resolution: To enable the Lifecycle Controller (LC) feature using F2 System Setup, select the iDRAC Settings > Lifecycle Controller and then select Enabled. If LC becomes disabled automatically, update the Lifecycle Controller firmware or apply the Lifecycle Controller Repair Package.
UEFI0021.Message: The Lifecycle Controller feature is disabled.

BAT1027.Description: The battery successfully completed a charge cycle.
BAT1027.Message: The battery on %1 completed a charge cycle.

RAC1142.Description: The Remote diagnostic operation cannot be performed because the difference between "Start Time" and "Expiration Time" is less than 5 minutes.
RAC1142.Resolution: Make sure that the Expiration Time is greater than five minutes, and then retry the operation.
RAC1142.Message: Unable to start the Remote Diagnostics operation because the Expiration Time entered (difference between Start Time and Expiration Time) is less than five minutes.

CMC005.Description: The operation cannot be completed because of a mismatch between AttributeName and AttributeValue count.
CMC005.Resolution: Enter a valid AttributeName and AttributeValue count, and then retry the operation.
CMC005.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of a mismatch between AttributeName and AttributeValue count.

RAC963.Description: iDRAC is unable to read Lifecycle Controller status. Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to run the operation.
RAC963.Resolution: Run the racadm get LifeCycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState command to get the status of the Lifecycle Controller. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC963.Message: Unable to retrieve the status of Lifecycle Controller.

CTL7.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL7.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.

RDU8515.Description: A CMC failover was initiated by the CMC health monitoring process. There should be a reason listed in the chassis log.
RDU8515.Message: CMC%1: failover was initiated by internal health monitoring process.

VF015.Description: Disabling vFlash was not successful because the vFlash feature is not enabled.
VF015.Resolution: The vFlash is disabled and an attempts to disable it will not be successful.

VDR33.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk was cancelled. This may be due to user action. This operation may automatically restart.

ASR0101.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. System was reset. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset 01 - event 3:0 - 3h if booting 4h if running)
ASR0101.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0101.Message: The OS watchdog timer reset the system.

VDR2.Description: The virtual disk has returned to a healthy state and is working properly.

PSU8513.Description: Unable to update the PSU firmware due to PMBus communication errors.
