PSU8513.Resolution: Retry the firmware update operation. If the problem persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8513.Message: Unable to complete the PSU slot %1 firmware update. Error=0x%2.

VFL1013.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 has finished booting.

PWR8573.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is not able to communicate with the iDRAC on the server identified in the message. Therefore the server could not be turned off. This situation may occur when iDRAC is restarting.
PWR8573.Resolution: Wait for three minutes, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the server and wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting before retying the operation.
PWR8573.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate to the iDRAC, when trying to turn off the server %1.

RAC003.Description: One or more required parameters for the method are missing.
RAC003.Resolution: Refer to the profile document and provide the required parameters.

SEL1503.Message: The chassis management controller (CMC) is not redundant.

CMC8520.Description: FRU on the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8520.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8520.Message: The FRU on server %1 is not functioning.

PWR2208.Message: The system is in a sleep state.

RFM1031.Message: Removable Flash Media has finished booting.

SWU8544.Description: The firmware update operation of the Standby CMC was not successful. The Standby CMC could not be prepared for firmware update.
SWU8544.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware because the Standby CMC could not be prepared for firmware update.

RED083.Description: The Chassis firmware is not updated because the firmware version currently on the Chassis is same as the requested version.
RED083.Message: The Chassis firmware is not updated because the version currently on the Chassis is same as the requested version.

CTL77.Description: This alert message occurs if controller firmware is flashed successfully.
CTL77.Message: Flash of new firmware image(s) completed on %1

PSUA0016.Description: The supply has been removed or has failed.
PSUA0016.Resolution: Install the power supply if needed.

UEFI0211.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Transmit Buffer Vref Training phase.
UEFI0211.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0211.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC0121.Description: SD card not readable. The card must be initialized.
RAC0121.Resolution: Initialize the SD card before it can be used.

PWR8543.Description: Invalid power inventory reported by the iDRAC of the server identified in the message to the CMC.
PWR8543.Resolution: Turn on the server identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8543.Message: Server %1 power inventory is not valid. Power inventory reading is Max Power=%2 AC Watt, Min Power=%3 AC Watt, Allocated Power=%4 AC Watt

RAC945.Description: The dedicated NIC or shared NIC scan time value is not between 5 and 255 seconds.
RAC945.Resolution: Make sure to set the scan time value between 5 and 255 seconds, and retry the operation. For more information, see RACADM help.

RAC0685.Description: A pending operation has been created for this operation identified in the message.
RAC0685.Resolution: To view the pending operations click the Pending Operations button.
RAC0685.Message: A pending operation has been created for this %1 operation.

UEFI0228.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Receive Enable Training - Configuration Write phase.
UEFI0228.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0228.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

BAR099.Description: License data is being collected and copied into the backup Server Profile.

IOID116.Description: The iDRAC has started to apply I/O Identity settings on NIC and FC HBA devices based on the current persistence policy settings.
IOID116.Message: Applying I/O Identity settings based on current persistence policy settings.

PDR2.Description: This message is generated if a physical disk does not have enough space to do a copyback operation.
PDR2.Resolution: Replace the physical disk with a larger physical disk, and then restart the copyback operation.
PDR2.Message: Insufficient space available on %1 to perform a copyback operation.

RAC0715.Description: Image file does not exist in the given remote share path.
RAC0715.Resolution: Ensure that the image file is available on the share path provided. Retry the operation.
RAC0715.Message: Image file does not exist in the given remote share path.

UEFI0173.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.
UEFI0173.Resolution: Quad Rank DIMM modules must be installed before Dual Rank DIMM modules on the channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0173.Message: A Quad Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after a Dual Rank DIMM module.

SEC0000.Description: The chassis is open. System performance may be degraded, and security may be compromised.
SEC0000.Resolution: Close the chassis. Check system logs.

JCP016.Description: The UntilTime input parameter for the job or job queue creation must be at least 5 minutes after the value specified in the StartTime parameter.
JCP016.Resolution: Set the UntilTime at least 5 minutes after StartTime and retry the operation.
JCP016.Message: Invalid UntilTime value. A minimum of 5 minutes is required.

UEFI0209.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Transmit Buffer Per Bit Deskew Training phase.
UEFI0209.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0209.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

LC047.Description: The DownloadClientCerts operation is in progress. The operation may take a few minutes to compete before the operation can be attempted again.
LC047.Resolution: Wait a few minutes before retrying retry the operation.
LC047.Message: An instance of DownloadClientCerts is already running.

RAC1016.Description: iDRAC does not allow duplicate user names for each of the 16 users.
RAC1016.Resolution: Make sure that each of the 16 user names are unique.
RAC1016.Message: The specified user already exists. Duplicate user names are not allowed.

SWC8602.Description: The system is busy with other operations. The feature was unable to get mutex.
SWC8602.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, make sure any other operations have completed and then retry the operation.
SWC8602.Message: Quick Deploy Profile for server %1 was not successful.

STOR13.Description: The operation mode of the newly inserted storage sled in the slot identified in the message cannot be set because the storage sled has only one PERC controller. The operation mode will only be Join after part replacement.
STOR13.Resolution: Make sure that the newly inserted storage sled has the same number of PERC controllers as the pervious storage sled so that the new sled will have the same operation mode after part replacement.
STOR13.Message: Unable to set the operation mode of the newly inserted storage sled in slot %1 to Split Single or Split Dural Host, because the storage sled has only one PERC controller.

HWC5034.Description: Link tuning table not supported for this IO modular.
HWC5034.Resolution: Update the CMC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC5034.Message: A link tuning failure detected on IO module %1.

SEC0703.Description: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is disabled.
SEC0703.Message: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is disabled.

PDR32.Description: The controller cannot to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a global hot spare. The disk either failed or was removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.
PDR32.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and installed. Check the cables. Refer to the product documentation and see the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the global hot spare.

RAC1011.Description: The OS to iDRAC pass-through cannot be enabled, because the NIC is in Dedicated mode.
RAC1011.Resolution: Change the iDRAC NIC mode to shared mode using "racadm set idrac.nic.selection <value>", and retry the operation.
RAC1011.Message: The OS to iDRAC pass-through cannot be enabled.

LC017.Description: A parameter value provided when the method was invoked is not valid.
LC017.Resolution: Verify that parameter values provided to the method are typed as they appear in the enumeration and that the parameter data type matches the Lifecycle Controller Profile documentation.

PSU0045.Message: Power supply %1 status information successfully obtained.

SWC0246.Description: The specified value is outside of the valid range.
SWC0246.Resolution: Verify that a valid value is specified. See the help text or documentation for valid values.
SWC0246.Message: Value specified is invalid: Valid range is %1.

BAR081.Description: Importing the Lifecycle Controller firmware image data is from the system profile backup file.

SWC0724.Description: Resetting to defaults did not complete within the maximum process allotted time.
SWC0724.Message: Error occurred while Resetting to defaults due to a timeout.

JCP008.Description: Multiple attributes were set in the operation but some set attribute actions were not successful. For example, setting an attribute that is not valid for the component being configured,
JCP008.Resolution: Examine the results of the configuration job in the Lifecycle Log for the source of the errors. Modify the settings as necessary and resubmit the job.

SWC8557.Description: The profile identified in the message cannot be deleted because it is currently in use.
SWC8557.Message: Unable to delete the profile %1 because the profile is in use.

PDR81.Description: The physical disk firmware update operation has started.

RAC1009.Description: The Active Directory objects DCLookupEnable or GCLookupEnable cannot be enabled, because IPv4.DNS1, IPv4.DNS2, IPv6.DNS1, or IPv6.DNS2 is not configured.
RAC1009.Resolution: Configure IPv4.DNS1, IPv4.DNS2, IPv6.DNS1, or IPv6.DNS2 using racadm set command, and retry the operation. For example, "racadm set iDRAC.IPv4.DNS1 <address>".
RAC1009.Message: The Active Directory objects DCLookupEnable or GCLookupEnable cannot be enabled.

SYS133.Description: An issue was encountered while creating an IPMI session.
SYS133.Resolution: Restart the WMI service and retry the operation.

VLT0229.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is within range.

SWC0109.Description: There is no RAC diagnostic information available.
SWC0109.Message: No process information is currently available.

RAC0227.Description: The SD card is not present, or communication with the SD card is lost. This could result in reduced functionality and capabilities.
RAC0227.Resolution: This error may occur because: 1. Make sure the SD card is seated correctly. 2. The SD card is invalid. Insert a valid SD card of size greater than 256MB and try again.
RAC0227.Message: SD card is not detected: Insert an SD Card of size greater than 256MB.

RED048.Description: The next job in the recurring operation sequence identified in the message was not started and was deleted, because an Automatic Server Profile Backup or Automatic Update operation was cleared.
RED048.Message: The job %1 was deleted because the recurring operation %2 was cleared.

DH006.Resolution: Validate that the certificate parameter matches the certificate contents; the certificate can be validated using OpenSSL tools.
DH006.Message: Not the right passphrase for the private key (need to re-write).

BAT0006.Message: The storage battery is operating normally.

UEFI0225.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the DDR4 LR-DIMM Receive Buffer Training phase.
UEFI0225.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0225.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

BAR101.Description: Importing license data from the backup Server Profile.

BAT1011.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1011.Message: Battery on %1 is in warn only mode and requires reconditioning.

TMP0113.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0113.Message: The %1 temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

TMP8501.Description: System was unable to read planar board or control panel temperature sensors. The fan speed was increased to protect system hardware.
TMP8501.Resolution: Remove AC power from the system and reapply AC power. Check to see if the issue is resolved. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
TMP8501.Message: Unable to read planar board temperature sensors. The cooling has been increased to safeguard the system.

RAC1111.Description: Unable to clear pending values or operations from the specified storage device because there are no pending operations for the specified device.
RAC1111.Message: Unable to delete the pending values or operations of the specified device.

BAR104.Description: Unable to collect system branding data to copy to backup Server Profile.
BAR104.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
BAR104.Message: Unable to collect system branding data.

PDR34.Description: The hot spare is no longer required because the virtual disk it was assigned to has been deleted.
PDR34.Message: A dedicated hot spare has been automatically unassigned.%1

STOR097.Description: A virtual disk cannot be created because the memory size of the physical disk drive is less than available or entered virtual disk size.
STOR097.Resolution: Enter the FQDD of a physical disk drive that has a larger disk space, and then retry the operation. To view a list of physical disk drives and associated disk space, run the RACADM command "racadm storage get pdisks -o -p size". To view a list of virtual disks and associated size, run the RACADM command "racadm storage get vdisks -o -p size".
STOR097.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the memory size of the physical disk drive is less than the available or entered virtual disk size.

OSD20.Description: Unable to get the size or label for selected operating system from the Driver Pack present in Lifecycle Controller. The driver pack may be corrupt.
OSD20.Resolution: Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and rerun the command.
OSD20.Message: Unable to get size or label from Driver Pack for selected operating system.

ASR0000.Description: The operating system or potentially an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC) within the timeout period.
ASR0000.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.

BOOT015.Description: The boot partition configuration request was successful. An unattached vFlash partition was configured for one-time boot using the ChangeBootOrderByInstanceID method. The method creates a job (to attach the vFlash partition and set the partition for one-time boot.
BOOT015.Message: Set operation successful for the boot partition.

PCI3006.Description: Either the BIOS or BMC/iDRAC firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3006.Resolution: Update BIOS, and BMC/iDRAC firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3006.Message: Failed to get Link Tuning or FlexAddress data from iDRAC.

SWU8540.Description: The PSU firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8540.Resolution: Make sure that the PSU firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8540.Message: Unable to update the PSU firmware, because the transfer of Image file is not successful. ErrorCode=0x%1.

SWC0269.Description: Local Configuration using RACADM may be disabled.
SWC0269.Resolution: Check if the Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled and enable it through GUI.
SWC0269.Message: Unable to clear the RAC log. Possible reason may be that Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled.

MEM7002.Resolution: Review product documentation for proper memory riser installation and configuration
MEM7002.Message: A hardware mismatch detected for memory riser.

ENC19.Description: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has failed. The failure may be caused by a loss of power to the EMM. The EMM self-test may also have identified a failure. There may also be a firmware problem or a multi-bit error.
ENC19.Resolution: Reset the Enclosure Management Module (EMM). See the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the EMM. Replace the EMM. Contact technical support if the issue persists.

RAC975.Description: The share type specified using the l parameter is invalid. Only CIFS or NFS share types are supported for this operation.
RAC975.Resolution: See the subcommand help text for supported share types.

RAC0615.Description: The contents of the PKCS12 file was not valid because one of the following: 1) Not a valid PKCS#12 file, 2) Not a valid pfx file or 3) Did not contain a valid key.
RAC0615.Resolution: Make sure to upload the file in PKCS#12 format. OpenSSL can be used to validate a PKCS#12 file.

SEL0013.Message: The system event log was created or initialized successfully.

OSD44.Description: The ISO on VFlash is not currently attached, so the DetachISOFromVFlash command could not be executed.
OSD44.Resolution: Since the ISO image is not attached, the detachISOFromVflash command does not have to be run.
OSD44.Message: Unable to detach ISO image on VFlash.

TMP0201.Message: CPU %1 temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

BAR015.Description: The Backup file information was not properly processed and the operation cannot continue. This can be due to resource constraints within the processing environment. If the network share is read only, this error will be thrown also.
BAR015.Resolution: If this is backup to network share, check to make sure network share is read/write accessible. Restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) and retry the operation.

BIOS002.Description: Unable to allocate required memory to perform the requested operation; see the inserted comment.
BIOS002.Resolution: Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.

SWC0025.Description: The operation completed successfully, however the system is unable to automatically shut down.
SWC0025.Resolution: Manually shut down the system. For more information about the failure, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0025.Message: The operation completed successfully, however the system is unable to automatically shut down.

HWC1200.Description: The sled identified in the message is inserted in the slot identified in the message.
HWC1200.Message: The sled %1 is inserted in slot %2.

ASR0105.Description: The operating system or an application failed to failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was powered off. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset - 02h event 3:0 - 4h)
ASR0105.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0105.Message: The OS watchdog timer powered off the system.

UEFI0013.Description: A CPU floating point error (type 0x10) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0013.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0013.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x10: Floating Point Error (Software).

SWU8548.Description: The firmware update operation of Standby CMC was not successful. The firmware image could not be accessed.
SWU8548.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8548.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware. The Image was not accessible.

PWR2201.Message: The system is sleeping with system hardware and processor context maintained.

RAC0102.Description: The software to communicate with the Smart Card is not loaded in this browser. Smart Card can be used for log in only if the appropriate Smart Card software is installed in the browser.
RAC0102.Resolution: Install the plug-in prompted by the iDRAC Web GUI to log in using Smart Card.
RAC0102.Message: The Smart Card Logon plug-in is not installed. Install the plug-in from the iDRAC Web GUI to log in using Smart Card.

SYS082.Description: The request to preview the system configuration XML file import operation completed. Some changes specified in the configuration XML file will not be successfully applied in an import configuration XML file operation.
SYS082.Resolution: Identify the configuration changes that cannot be completed successfully by 1) Export the Lifecycle Log review the configuration results in the entries for the preview job or 2) Retrieve the preview operation configuration results using the GetConfigResults() method. Retry those changes that did not complete in a separate import operation.
SYS082.Message: Completed the preview of system configuration XML file import operation. Some changes specified in the configuration XML will not be successfully applied in an import operation.

RAC0302.Description: This error message is displayed when iDRAC does not have a valid Enterprise license.
RAC0302.Resolution: Upgrade to iDRAC Enterprise for supporting this feature.
RAC0302.Message: iDRAC Express does not support this feature.

MEM0004.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.
MEM0004.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. Review product documentation for supported memory configurations. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM0004.Message: Memory device at location %1 is disabled.

RAC0208.Description: Upload failed possibly due to invalid key data.
RAC0208.Resolution: Upload a certificate with a valid key.
RAC0208.Message: Upload failed: May be due to invalid key data.

CTL82.Description: The controller identified in the message is functioning normally.

BAR110.Description: All the existing jobs are canceled during the Import Server Profile operation or if the Import operation fails.
BAR110.Resolution: Resubmit any jobs that were cancelled by the Import operation after the Import Server Profile operation completes.
BAR110.Message: All existing jobs cancelled because of Import Server Profile request processing.

PWR8505.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature was not successfully enabled.
PWR8505.Resolution: Restart the Chassis Management Controller and retry the operation. To restart the Chassis Management Controller, using the WEB UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Control, select the Reset CMC option, and then click Apply.
PWR8505.Message: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature was not successfully enabled.

JCP015.Description: The job is currently executing and cannot be deleted. The job needs to finish running, whether successful or not, before it can be deleted.
JCP015.Resolution: Wait for the job to have a completed job status. Retry the operation.
JCP015.Message: A running job cannot be deleted.

PWR8654.Description: CMC could not successfully send the power allocation information to the component identified in the message, because either iDRAC is stopped after the power allocation was sent by CMC or the communication between CMC and iDRAC has ended.
PWR8654.Resolution: Perform a Virtual Reseat operation of the component, and then retry the operation. To virtually reseat a component, log in to the CMC Web interface, select Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components > select the option corresponding to the component, and then click Virtual Reseat.
PWR8654.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to send power allocation information to the component %1-%2.

PR35.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference for the power supply and will start the firmware update process upon system reboot.
PR35.Message: Power Supply slot %1 firmware update will be performed during next system reboot.

DH002.Resolution: Try again. If the error persists, use RACADM command racreset to clear the issue.

PCI3015.Message: The component at slot %1 recovered from a non-fatal PCIe error.

VDR18.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk has failed or was removed.
VDR18.Resolution: If a physical disk has failed, replace the physical disk. Restart the virtual disk initialization.

UEFI0080.Description: The PCIe link speed is not optimal for the identified PCIe device.
UEFI0080.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Turn off the input power to the system and turn on again. 2) Update the PCIe device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0080.Message: PCIe link speed is not optimal for %1. Expected link speed: Gen %2 and actual link speed: Gen %2.

PDR84.Description: The Security key on a secure encrypted disk was activated.

CMC8558.Description: The system health has recovered from a failover condition.

PR30.Description: Operation validation was unsuccessful. The command, target and operation data are all validated before proceeding. If any of them are missing or incorrect the request is failed.
PR30.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory on Restart attribute of the Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. After the system has restarted, retry the operation.

SWC1916.Description: Network Time Protocol server configuration has changed.
SWC1916.Message: Network Time Protocol server configuration has changed.

CMC8570.Description: The server slot specified in the message is disabled for DVD drive mapping. The DVD drive cannot be mapped to this server slot.
CMC8570.Message: The server slot %1 is disabled for DVD drive mapping.

CMC8568.Description: The DVD drive is disabled and is not mapped to any of the server slots.
CMC8568.Message: The DVD drive mapping feature is disabled.

UEFI0077.Description: One or more PCIe device errors occurred in the previous boot.
UEFI0077.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCIe device with errors, and then update its firmware.
UEFI0077.Message: One or more PCIe device errors occurred in the previous boot.

SWU8521.Description: The firmware update operation of iDRAC identified in the message was stopped. The selected Image file is not compatible with the server hardware.
SWU8521.Resolution: Make sure that the Image file is compatible with the server hardware, and then retry the operation.
SWU8521.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 was stopped. The selected Image file is not compatible with the server hardware.

SUP0124.Message: Firmware update is not currently in progress

RAC998.Description: IPv6 cannot be enabled if iDRAC NIC is disabled.
RAC998.Resolution: Enable iDRAC NIC using "racadm set iDRAC.NIC.Enable < 1 | Enabled >" command and retry the operation.

STOR6.Description: A comparison of storage inventory collected before and after the host re-boot/re-set. reports differences. There could have been some storage components added or removed when the host was powered down.
STOR6.Message: CEM Storage Management detected inventory change(s) after host re-boot.

HWC0015.Description: iDRAC has encountered a hardware error.
HWC0015.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.

OSD40.Description: This is not a Dell-licensed VFlash.
OSD40.Resolution: Insert a Dell VFlash and then retry this command.

POW004.Description: Host failed to power up because of unacknowledged use of 110V. This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2254
POW004.Message: Power on permission error, unacknowledged use of 110V.

CBL0004.Description: The cable identified in the message is incorrectly connected to the backplane connector.
CBL0004.Resolution: Make sure the cable identified in the message is cabled correctly. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0004.Message: The %1 cable is incorrectly connected to backplane %2 connector %3.

CTL11.Description: A user operation to reset the controller configuration was performed.

BAR040.Description: Access to the vFlash media is not possible, or has been denied.
BAR040.Resolution: Make sure the vFlash SD media is enabled, not write protected, and initialized. Retry the operation.

VRM0011.Description: The Virtual Media server is already disconnected.
VRM0011.Message: The Virtual Media image server is not currently connected.

BIOS0001.Description: BIOS logged a Trusted Compute Module (TPM) Physical Presence Operation.
BIOS0001.Message: Trusted Compute Module (TPM) Physical Presence Operation %1 logged.

SWC0048.Description: The backup server profile operation did not complete because:1) The backup server configuration profile image file present on the vFlash SD card is invalid for this system.2) The passphrase entered does not match the passphrase used to secure the backup server configuration profile image file.
SWC0048.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation:1) Reinsert the vFlash SD card with correct backup image file.2) Enter the passphrase that was used to secure the backup server configuration profile image file.
SWC0048.Message: Unable to validate the backup server configuration Profile image file for this system.

SWU8542.Description: The firmware update operation for the CMC was not successful. The Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8542.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware Image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8542.Message: Unable to update the Active CMC firmware. The Image file transfer process was not successful.

UEFI0237.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - Memory Test phase.
UEFI0237.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0237.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

VFL0005.Description: There are no vFlash partitions available currently for the display.

HWC0010.Description: Operation failed because the folder name entered is incorrect or the USB drive is disconnected.
HWC0010.Resolution: Enter a valid folder name or attach the USB drive and retry the operation.
HWC0010.Message: Invalid folder name or USB drive not found.

RAC0269.Resolution: Enter a valid NIC MTU. Expected range: 576-1500 or 0x240-0x5DC.
RAC0269.Message: The NIC MTU is invalid. Expected range: 576-1500 or 0x240-0x5DC.

OSD70.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'Username' is missing.
OSD70.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "Username" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD70.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'Username' is missing.

NIC018.Description: The input BIOS password used in the operation is invalid.
NIC018.Resolution: Use a valid BIOS password and retry.

UEFI0179.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Read Receive Enable error was detected.
UEFI0179.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0179.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

DH007.Resolution: Check that the private key parameter is correct. The passphrase can be validated against the private key, passphrase, and certificate can be validated using OpenSSL tools.
DH007.Message: The password unlocked the private key but it was the wrong private key.

PWR8563.Description: The Server identified in the message did not turn on due to a fabric mismatch between the I/O Module and the Mezzanine card on the Server.
PWR8563.Resolution: Make sure that the hardware compatibility between the I/O Module (IOM) and the Mezzanine (Mezz) card is correct. Check the M1000e Hardware Manual for correct component compatibility.
PWR8563.Message: Unable to turn on Server %1 due to I/O fabric inconsistency.

VDR37.Description: Disk space that was formerly "dead" or inaccessible to a redundant virtual disk has been restored. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR37.Message: Dead disk segments are restored on %1.

STOR065.Description: Unable to create the requested virtual disk because one or more specified physical disk(s) is not T10 Protection Information capable.
STOR065.Resolution: Verify that the physical disks selected for creating a virtual disk are T10 Protection Information capable, and then retry the operation.
STOR065.Message: One or more physical disks specified for creating a virtual disk are not T10 Protection Information capable.

BAR060.Description: Collecting firmware inventory and copying it into the system profile backup file.

ASR0100.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the system board within the timeout period. The system was reset per the configured setting. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset 01h event 3:0 - 2h)
ASR0100.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0100.Message: The BIOS watchdog timer reset the system.

UEFI0097.Description: The Advanced ECC memory operating mode cannot be enabled because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.
UEFI0097.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0097.Message: Unable to enable the Advanced ECC memory operating mode because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.

PDR64.Description: The rebuild or recovery operation encountered an unrecoverable disk media error.
PDR64.Message: An unrecoverable disk media error occurred on %1.

FCD8501.Description: The FlexAddress, FlexAddress+ or extended storage feature is deactivated. Turn chassis off and remove the feature card.
FCD8501.Resolution: Turn chassis off and remove the feature card.

MEM9004.Description: A link degradation was detected in propagation of signals between processors through the Intel QPI interconnect interconnect identified in the message. The system will continue to operate at reduced performance.
MEM9004.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the server and check whether the issue persists. 2) If the issue is not resolved by the preceding action, reseat the processors and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

USR0002.Description: Details the Username that logged in and the IP Address they are coming from.

RRDU0005.Description: The current operating configuration cannot maintain redundancy. The unit may operate in a degraded state.
RRDU0005.Resolution: Review product documentation and SD card configuration.
RRDU0005.Message: Internal Dual SD Module is not redundant. Insufficient resources to maintain normal operations.

CMC8539.Description: CMC cannot log new events to Hardware Log if Hardware Log is full. Therefore, new events are not written to the log unless older events are cleared. This issue also occurs if event logging is disabled.
CMC8539.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Save the Hardware Log if required. 2) Clear the Hardware Log.
CMC8539.Message: The CMC %1 is unable to log %2 event to the Hardware Log.

PCI1356.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1356.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1356.Message: A bus uncorrectable error was detected on a component at slot %1.

RED090.Description: A Chassis firmware update operation is no longer in progress. This is not an indication of success or failure.
RED090.Message: A Chassis firmware update operation is no longer in progress.

PWR2256.Description: The chassis infrastructure components are being initialized and are not ready to grant power on permission to the servers.
PWR2256.Resolution: Wait until the chassis infrastructure has been initialized and then retry the operation. To check that the infrastructure is initialized, using the RACADM command line utility run the command "racadm getmodinfo" and check that the "pwrstate" field is on for the chassis component.
PWR2256.Message: Unable to allocate power for servers to turn on because the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is initializing chassis infrastructure components.

HWC0006.Description: If a vFlash SD card is not present in the system or if the card is locked, Lifecycle Controller cannot save the settings.
HWC0006.Resolution: Insert the vFlash SD card or unlock the vFlash SD card and retry the operation.
HWC0006.Message: Unable to save vFlash SD card settings.

UEFI0070.Description: One or more correctable PCIe errors have occurred. Data about the errors are logged into SEL during the POST operation.
UEFI0070.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCIe device, and then update its firmware.
UEFI0070.Message: One or more correctable PCIe errors have occurred.

PWR8515.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is not turned on.
PWR8515.Resolution: Turn the chassis on and retry the operation.
PWR8515.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is not turned on.

PWR8585.Description: Chassis Management Controller granted the power required to turn on the server identified in the message.
PWR8585.Message: Chassis Management Controller granted the power required to turn on server-%1.

CTL9.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL9.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL9.Message: Bad block extended medium error on %1.

CTL27.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC962.Description: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to run the operation.
RAC962.Resolution: Enable the Lifecycle controller using the racadm set LifeCycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1 command, and retry the operation.
RAC962.Message: Unable to continue with the operation because Lifecycle Controller is in recovery state,

VDR98.Description: The virtual disk identified in the message has changed active paths. This can be because of an attempt to optimize the throughput of the system or it could be because of a controller failover.
VDR98.Message: %1 has switched active controllers. Its active path is now through %2.

PDR1016.Description: The controller detected that the drive was removed.
PDR1016.Resolution: Verify drive installation. Remove and reseat the failed drive. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PDR1016.Message: Drive %1 is removed from disk drive bay %2.

STOR15.Description: The storage sled identified in the message was inserted in a location which does not support split dual host operation mode. The storage sled can functionally work in the current location with only primary PERC controller enabled.
STOR15.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Change the operating mode of the storage sled identified in the message. 2) Insert the storage sled to a different slot.
STOR15.Message: The storage sled %1 is improperly configured.

STOR0513.Description: Unable to encrypt unsecure virtual disks due to an internal error.
STOR0513.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.

SWC8552.Description: The server in slot identified in the message does not have a profile associated with it.
SWC8552.Message: The server in slot %1 does not have a profile associated with it.

SYS098.Description: A Remote Diagnostic (ePSA) job already exists and only one job of this type can exist at a time.
SYS098.Resolution: A response action is not required if the scheduled start time of the existing Remote Diagnostic (ePSA) job is ok. Else, delete the existing Diagnostics (ePSA) job and recreate another with an appropriate start time.
SYS098.Message: A Remote Diagnostic (ePSA) job already exists.

JCP025.Description: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller can be enabled in the F2 Setup application or through a remote operation.
JCP025.Resolution: If Lifecycle Controller is in Recovery mode a firmware update of Lifecycle Controller may be required. To change the Lifecycle Controller mode, do the following: 1) Restart the system and press F2 to launch the System Setup application 2) Select iDRAC Configuration 3) Select Lifecycle Controller Settings to enable Lifecycle Controller.

DIS013.Description: Default client certificate is being used. Auto Discovery client is using this certificate for the SSL connection with the Provisioning Server.
DIS013.Message: Auto Discovery client using default client certificate.

DH010.Description: The iDRAC must be reset to apply a new certificate. Until the iDRAC has reset, the old certificate will be active.
DH010.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC. The iDRAC can be reset by pressing the Identify button for 15 seconds. Using the RACADM command line utility, run "racadm racreset"
DH010.Message: Reset iDRAC to apply new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset, the old certificate will be active.

RAC1136.Description: The remote unattended diagnostic execution operation is initiated.
RAC1136.Resolution: Using the RACADM command line interface, run the "racadm jobqueue view -i <job id>" command to view the status of the operation.
RAC1136.Message: Remote unattended diagnostic execution operation initiated.

PCI5001.Description: A PCIe card carrier containing a PCIe card is present in the slot identified in the message. This PCIe card will be enabled when the associated server is turned on or power cycled.
PCI5001.Resolution: Turn on or power cycle the associated server to enable the PCIe card.
PCI5001.Message: A PCIe card carrier containing a PCIe card is inserted in PCIe slot%1 .

ASR0102.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was shutdown. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset - 02h event 3:0 - 4h)
ASR0102.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0102.Message: The OS watchdog timer shutdown the system.

TMP0101.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0101.Message: The system board %1 temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

SYS124.Description: The OS and Application data collection by the OS Collector application is unable to execute on the OS installed on the server because the OS is not supported.
SYS124.Message: OS Collector: The OS Collector application does not support execution in the OS installed on the server.

RAC0635.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid domain name is entered.
RAC0635.Resolution: Enter a valid domain name, and then retry the operation.
RAC0635.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid domain name is entered.

JCP014.Description: The number of jobs specified in the SetupJobQueue request combined with the existing job count contains more jobs IDs than the maximum number of jobs supported by the system (256). Completed jobs are automatically deleted if they are older than the delete on completion timeout setting.
JCP014.Resolution: Reduce the number of jobs specified in the operation or reduce the existing job count before retrying the operation. Perform one of the following to reduce the job count: 1) Delete one or more jobs and retry the operation. 2) Wait until existing jobs have an elapsed time since completion that is greater than the delete on completion timeout setting and are automatically deleted. 3) Change the delete on completion timeout setting to a smaller value so that completed jobs are automatically deleted sooner.

DIS001.Description: Auto Discovery starts automatically, but was unable to find a valid license. Once you have obtained a valid license and installed it, restart.
DIS001.Resolution: Follow service providers instructions to enable the license.

FSD001.Description: Dell has authorized the specified debug capabilities. Each debug capability represents a certain action Dell engineers can perform to debug iDRAC.
FSD001.Message: Debug authorized by Dell; debugcaps: %1, at %2, was authorized by Dell employee: %3, for the time period %4 to %5

TMPS0100.Description: <font face="Calibri">Inlet temperature has been above the warning threshold for duration of 8% or more for the operational time during the last one year.</font>
TMPS0100.Resolution: This condition will occur if the ambient temperature is high. Make sure the ambient temperature of the environment is in normal range.
TMPS0100.Message: Inlet temperature is above warning level for extended duration.

PDR1102.Description: The controller received a SMART error from the drive. The drive is operational but needs replacement.
PDR1102.Resolution: The drive will need replacement at the next service window.
PDR1102.Message: A predictive failure detected on drive %1.

SUP018.Description: The specified until time is invalid.
SUP018.Resolution: Until Time should be in the form YYYYMMDDHHMMSS. Verify the specified until time and retry the action.

STOR4.Description: There was a software problem in initializing the CEM storage management components. Storage inventory and monitoring will be affected.
STOR4.Resolution: Reboot the system or iDRAC. If the problem is not resolved, contact technical support.
STOR4.Message: CEM Storage Management encountered internal error.

SUP0514.Description: An internal error occurred while performing firmware rollback operation.
SUP0514.Resolution: Exit the Firmware Rollback wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system and retry the operation.

HWC5001.Resolution: If unexpected, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

RAC1044.Description: The Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature is not enabled
RAC1044.Resolution: To enable, run the RACADM command "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.lcattributes.autoupdate 1".
RAC1044.Message: The Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature is not enabled.

RAC0662.Description: Clear foreign configuration will delete the foreign virtual disk information from the controller's associated physical disk drives. Clearing will remove metadata associated with the virtual disks, making the physical disk drives available for creating new virtual disks. To remove foreign data, perform an initialization operation.
RAC0662.Message: The Clear Foreign Configuration operation will delete the foreign virtual disk information from the controller's associated physical disk drives. Clearing will remove metadata associated with the virtual disks, making the physical disk drives available for creating new virtual disks. To remove foreign data, perform an initialization operation.

RAC1134.Description: Unable to export the Lifecycle log data, because the export file size larger than 25MB and cannot be processed locally.
RAC1134.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log to a network file share. Using the RACADM command line utility, run the lclog export command with --complete option and related network file share parameters, and then retry the operation. For more information about the --complete option, run the "racadm help lclog export" command at the command line interface.
RAC1134.Message: Unable to export the Lifecycle log data, because the export file size larger than 25MB and cannot be processed locally.

USR8507.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.
USR8507.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct. Retry the operation with valid credentials.
USR8507.Message: %1 login was not successful (username=%2, ip=%3, error=0x%4)

RAC0696.Description: The iDRAC is unable to retrieve hardware overview related information while the server is turned off.
RAC0696.Resolution: Turn the server on to view the hardware overview information.
RAC0696.Message: Unable to retrieve the hardware overview information because the server is turned off.

VF035.Description: The image file is not valid.

RAC1165.Description: Unable to configure the port number that is entered for either http or https ports of the iDRAC Web server, because the port number is already in use.
RAC1165.Resolution: Enter a port number that is not already in use and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC1165.Message: Unable to configure the port number that is entered for either http or https ports of the iDRAC Web server, because the port number is already in use.

SWC8502.Description: A Profile is successfully generated with the number of settings identified in the message.
SWC8502.Message: A Profile is successfully generated with [ %1 ] settings.

UEFI0178.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Read DQ/DQS error was detected.
UEFI0178.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0178.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

RAC0239.Description: The contents of a write protected SD Card cannot be modified.
RAC0239.Resolution: Make sure the SD Card is not write-protected before attempting to change its contents.

RAC1119.Description: The command could not be successfully run because of one or more of the following reasons:1. The command does not have "--verifycatalog" in it.2. The updates available on the repository are not applicable for the operation that is requested.
RAC1119.Resolution: To generate a comparison report, type "--verifycatalog" in the racadm command, and then retry the operation.
RAC1119.Message: Unable to generate a comparison report for the specified repository.

RAC0513.Description: There are no virtual disks to be displayed. There may be no virtual disks created, the controller(s) may not be in RAID mode, or there may be pending creation or deletion jobs that have not completed.
RAC0513.Resolution: Check the following: 1) Check if the server is turned off. If the server is turned off, turn it on and wait until POST completes. 2) If no virtual disks are created, to start the virtual disk creation process, click #{create_virtualdisk_link}. 3) If create virtual disk operation(s) are in a pending state, complete the creation process. To complete the virtual disk(s) creation, go to the Pending Operations page and create a configuration job on the appropriate controller. 4) If delete virtual disk operation(s) are in pending state, then cancel the operation. To cancel delete virtual disk pending operation(s), go to the Pending Operations page and delete all pending operation(s) on the appropriate controller. 5) If the Controller(s) are in HBA mode, switch the controller(s) to RAID mode. To switch controller(s) to RAID mode using the F2 System Setup utility, go to Device Settings > RAID Controller > Controller Management > Advanced Controller Management > Switch to RAID mode.
RAC0513.Message: There are no virtual disks to be displayed.

PWR2258.Description: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) hotspare thresholds were modified to the Wake Threshold and Sleep Threshold identified in the message.
PWR2258.Message: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) hotspare thresholds were modified. Wake Threshold: %1 %, Sleep Threshold: %2 %.

SWC0325.Message: The specified object is WRITE-ONLY and cannot be displayed.

RAC947.Description: The value used for the object set operation is invalid.
RAC947.Resolution: Make sure to specify the value depending on the type of object. For more information, see RACADM help.

SWC0256.Description: Unable to read the specified file.

AMP0305.Message: The system board %1 current is within range.

VF018.Description: The specified partition index is not valid for the command.

PDR1119.Message: Drive %1 is no longer the hot-spare drive.

NIC505.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC505.Message: The DNS domain name is not allowed to be configured if domain name DHCP (cfgDNSDomainNameFromDHCP) is enabled.

ISM0018.Description: The OS Collector application is started on the server Operating System.
ISM0018.Message: The OS Collector application is successfully started on the server operating system (OS).

RAC0671.Description: Going out of this page will not save the operations or configuration settings that were selected.
RAC0671.Resolution: Press OK to continue. Press Cancel to continue working on the page.
RAC0671.Message: Going out of this page will not save the operations or configuration settings that were selected.

SYS002.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in iDRAC.
SYS002.Resolution: Retry the action. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC.
SYS002.Message: Unable to perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

UEFI0009.Description: A CPU segment not present exception (type 0x0B) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0009.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0009.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x0B: Segment Not Present (Software).

PWR8677.Description: Dynamic Power Supply Engagement configuration is changed.
PWR8677.Message: Dynamic Power Supply Engagement configuration is changed.

VDR35.Description: Background initialization of a virtual disk completed.

PST0130.Description: During memory configuration system BIOS encountered device failures or speed configurations that resulted in unused memory. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 82)
PST0130.Resolution: Remove input power. Reseat memory devices or reduce system to minimum supported memory configuration.
PST0130.Message: Memory is configured, but not usable.

PWR8531.Description: Server Based Power Management Mode is enabled.
PWR8531.Message: Server Based Power Management Mode is enabled.

DIS007.Description: Unable to connect to Provisioning Server to notify about new iDRAC IP .
DIS007.Resolution: Check Provisioning Server connectivity and retry..
DIS007.Message: Unable to notify Provisioning Server of iDRAC IP address change.

AMP0314.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0314.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0314.Message: System level current is greater than the upper warning threshold.

PWR8567.Description: Unable to turn off the Server on a power cycle operation. This happens if the Server did not show a "power off" status change within the expected time.
PWR8567.Resolution: The Server could have taken more time to turn off than expected. If the Server is turned off, turn on to complete the power cycle. If the Server has not completed a power cycle, retry the operation.
PWR8567.Message: Unable to turn off Server %1 on a power cycle action.

UEFI0008.Description: A CPU invalid task segment state (TSS) exception (type 0x0A) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0008.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0008.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x0A: Invalid Task Segment State Segment (TSS) (Software).

SYS173.Description: The TTY Log cannot be retrieved because another operation is in progress on the RAID controller.
SYS173.Resolution: Do the following: 1) View the job queue and make sure all jobs are in a completed state. 2) Retry the operation.
SYS173.Message: Unable to retrieve the TTY Log because another operation is in progress on the RAID controller.

IOID002.Description: After the I/O Identity optimization feature is disabled, the time during boot to configure I/O Identity attributes using the Server Configuration Profile (Configuration XML) import feature will increase.
IOID002.Message: The Input/Output Identity (I/O Identity) optimization feature is disabled.

UEFI0018.Description: An internal error occurred. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0018.Resolution: Repair Lifecycle Controller firmware using the Lifecycle Controller Dell Update Package (DUP) or Lifecycle Controller Repair Package via iDRAC. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
UEFI0018.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) is unable to complete a requested task or function and therefore is in Recovery Mode.

DIS012.Description: Factory signed client certificate is being used. Auto Discovery client is using this certificate for the SSL connection with the Provisioning Server.
DIS012.Message: Auto Discovery client using factory signed client certificate.

VLT0233.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0233.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the mezzanine card.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0233.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

LC053.Description: Lifecycle Controller Remote Service is either not ready or currently reloading server information.
LC053.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, refer to Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation for more information.
LC053.Message: Lifecycle Controller Remote Services is currently unavailable.

LC082.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) attribute setting is disabled on the system.
LC082.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) attribute setting and then retry the operation. To enable the CSIOR setting using the RACADM command line utility, type "racadm set lifecyclecontroller.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart Enabled".
LC082.Message: Unable to complete the requested operation because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) attribute setting is disabled on the system.

SWC0069.Description: The new boot mode settings for BIOS were successfully applied.
SWC0069.Message: Successfully applied the new boot mode settings for BIOS.

RAC0180.Description: Certificate upload failed. Unable to get local issuer certificate. The local issuer certificate is the certificate for the Certificate Authority (CA) that has signed the certificate for the Active Directory (AD) server, unless it is self signed. The iDRAC needs to verify that the CA is legitimate.
RAC0180.Resolution: Certificate has expired. Try creating a new CSR and then upload the certificate.
RAC0180.Message: Certificate upload failed: Unable to get local issuer certificate from the Certification Authority (CA) for confirming the CA is legitimate.

PDR36.Description: The only physical disk available to be assigned as a hot spare is using SAS technology. The physical disks in the virtual disk are using SATA technology. Because of this difference in technology, the hot spare cannot rebuild data if one of the physical disks in the virtual disk fails.
PDR36.Resolution: Add a SATA disk that is large enough to be used as the hot spare and assign the new disk as a hot spare.
PDR36.Message: The only hot spare available is a SAS disk %1.

SWC0123.Description: The syntax of the sslcsrgen command is invalid.
SWC0123.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcsrgen subcommand.
SWC0123.Message: The -s option is not valid with any other options.

RAC0270.Description: This is a warning message that continuing this operation does not allow subsequent GUI interactions to this NIC.
RAC0270.Resolution: Enable IPv4 or IPv6 before continuing the operation.

LIC203.Description: Signature verification failed due to an error in the saved license file.
LIC203.Resolution: Delete and re-import the license file.
LIC203.Message: The license %1 has encountered an error.

LIC502.Description: The attempted features are not available in the system.
LIC502.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

RAC997.Description: The DHCP for Domain Name cannot be enabled if IPv4 and IPv4 DHCP or IPv6 and IPv6 AutoConfig is disabled.
RAC997.Resolution: Make sure that IPv4 and IPv4 DHCP are enabled, or IPv6 and IPv6 AutoConfig are enabled.
RAC997.Message: The object DNSDomainFromDHCP cannot be enabled.

STOR071.Description: The configuration operation could not be performed because the specified span count is not valid.
STOR071.Resolution: Enter a valid span count, and then retry the operation.
STOR071.Message: The Span Count is not valid for creating a RAID 10. Valid Span counts are %1.

RAC0902.Description: The syntax of the specified command is invalid. In this case, the usage of the -f option is invalid.
RAC0902.Resolution: See the help text/documentation for the valid syntax of the subcommand.
RAC0902.Message: The -f option requires -d to also be specified.

PWR8685.Description: The firmware identified in the message supports the storage sled.
PWR8685.Message: The %1 firmware in the server slot %2 supports the storage sled.

STOR078.Description: The requested operation cannot be performed because it involves server reboot type which is different than the reboot type of pending operations. Combining operations with different reboot types for the same RAID controller is not supported by iDRAC.
STOR078.Resolution: Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller and then retry the operation.
STOR078.Message: The requested operation requires a reboot type that does not match the reboot type required for pending operations.

UEFI0037.Description: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI). Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as active power management, thermal management.
UEFI0037.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0037.Message: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of an issue in the iDRAC Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI).

RAC0618.Description: The data entered caused an error while processing the request.
RAC0618.Resolution: Make sure to enter the correct data and retry the operation.

RAC918.Description: Racadm unable to obtain the inlet temperature data. This happens if there is no data populated in the temperature tables or if the underlying instrumentation does not return valid values.
RAC918.Resolution: Wait for the underlying instrumentation to populate the thermal tables. Retry the operation.
RAC918.Message: Unable to get the inlet temperature data.

RAC1186.Description: Only possible configurations for the DRAC NIC are 10Mbps and 100 Mbps. For documentation with respect to this setting, refer to the racadm User Guide under cfgNetTuning group.
RAC1186.Message: 1000Mbps speed setting is Read Only and cannot be configured for the iDRAC NIC.

SWC8527.Description: Chassis Management Controller unable to update the IDRAC root user username as root. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or if the username supplied is not valid.
SWC8527.Resolution: Make sure the user name is valid. If communication with iDRAC is not successful, reset the iDRAC. Retry the operation after a few minutes.
SWC8527.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to update the iDRAC user name to "root".

PWR8680.Description: The firmware identified in the message does not support the storage sled.
PWR8680.Resolution: Update the firmware identified in the message to the supported latest available version. See the latest iDRAC User Guide for information on the versions that support the storage sled.
PWR8680.Message: The %1 firmware in the server slot %2 does not support the storage sled.

RAC0674.Description: Export Report will create a zip file of XML and text-based logs intended for Dell Technical Support assistance with troubleshooting system issues. Choose Advanced Export Options to specify optional report settings and actions.
RAC0674.Message: Export Report will create a zip file of XML and text-based logs intended for Dell Technical Support assistance with troubleshooting system issues. Choose Advanced Export Options to specify optional report settings and actions.

PWR8670.Description: The server identified in the message cannot be turned on if the Connector Limit for the subsystems identified in the message is exceeded .
PWR8670.Resolution: Make sure the system operates within the subsystem Connector Limit for the components specified. To review power budget information select Chassis Overview -> Power -> Budget Status. Turn off unused components within the subsystem to make power available for the server to turn on or turn off low priority servers and try the operation again.
PWR8670.Message: Unable to turn on server%1 because the required power %2 AC Watts exceeds the subsystem Connector Limit %3 AC Watts for IO modules, Blowers and Servers.

PST0127.Description: System BIOS gave control to the operating system.

IOV103.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected the replacement of an adapter in the slot identified in the message.
IOV103.Message: A PCIe adapter %1 in %2%3 is replaced by PCIe adapter %1.

RFM1026.Description: An error is reported during a SD card read or write.
RFM1026.Resolution: Re-install the flash media, if the issue persists replace the media.
RFM1026.Message: Failure detected on Removable Flash Media.

RAC1049.Description: Successfully configured the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.
RAC1049.Message: Successfully configured the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.

IOID004.Description: The Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Non-Auxiliary powered devices is changed to the restart type identified in the message.
IOID004.Message: Virtual Address Persistence Policy setting for Non-Auxiliary powered devices is changed to %1.

SYS038.Description: Unable to locate the configuration data associated with the job.
SYS038.Resolution: Retry the operation. If this issue persists, contact your service provider.

CPU0804.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0804.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0804.Message: The power input for CPU %1 voltage regulator module is outside of range.

USR8506.Description: The operation to invalidate the Session identified in the message was successful.

RAC1147.Description: The SNMPv3 user cannot be set because the user with the entered username for the SNMPv3 group is not present or enabled on iDRAC.
RAC1147.Resolution: Make sure the specified username is present on iDRAC and enabled, and retry the operation.
RAC1147.Message: Unable to set the SNMPv3 username entered in the command because the username is not present or enabled on iDRAC.

CTL112.Description: The Loadbalance Mode of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL112.Message: The Loadbalance Mode of %1 is set to %2.

PSU0914.Description: Status from the power supply indicates a power supply exception occurred. The power supply will try to operate. System Performance and power redundancy may be degraded or lost.
PSU0914.Resolution: Remove input power and re-install supply at the next service window.
PSU0914.Message: A predictive failure detected on power unit %1.

RAC1162.Description: The requested techsupreport collect operation cannot be initiated because another techsupreport collect operation for the Tech Support Report (TSR) is in progress.
RAC1162.Resolution: Wait for the current collect operation to complete before initiating another collect operation. To view the status of the techsupreport collect operation, run the command 'racadm jobqueue view'.
RAC1162.Message: Unable to initiate the techsupreport collect operation for the Tech Support Report (TSR) because another collect operation is in progress.

HWC7014.Description: An invalid cable related hardware configuration detected on the system.
HWC7014.Resolution: Make sure the hardware and related cables are installed correctly. For information about configuration and installation procedures, see the system's Owners Manual available at the support site.
HWC7014.Message: An invalid cable or incorrect cable configuration is detected.

RAC1070.Description: The maximum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is greater than or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.
RAC1070.Resolution: Check the maximum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the maximum critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1070.Message: Unable to set the maximum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum critical threshold value.

RAC923.Description: The specified file path (specified with the f parameter) is too long. This path should be less than 64 characters in length.
RAC923.Resolution: Try the same command with a shorter file path (specified with the f parameter) which is less than 64 characters in length.
RAC923.Message: The file path is too long.

RAC1031.Description: The custom signing certificate on iDRAC cannot be deleted because of an internal error.
RAC1031.Resolution: Verify if iDRAC has a custom signing certificate. If it has the certificate, retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC1031.Message: Unable to delete the custom signing certificate.

SYS140.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running in the server OS.
SYS140.Resolution: Enable and start the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) from within the server OS and then retry the operation.
SYS140.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) is not running in the server OS.

FAN901.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully disabled.
FAN901.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode is successfully disabled.

VFL0705.Description: An error has occurred while initializing the SD card. The SD card is not present or vFlash is not enabled, or the SD card is write-protected.
VFL0705.Resolution: Re-insert the SD card, enable the SD card, or disable write-protection on the SD card. Then try to initialize the SD card again.
VFL0705.Message: Error occurred and SD card could not be initialized.

PWR8597.Description: The identified Power Supply Unit (PSU) is turned off because it is not supported by the Chassis.
PWR8597.Resolution: Replace the PSU identified in the message with an appropriate unit, and then retry the operation. For a list of PSUs that are compatible, consult the system Owner's Manual or contact your service provider.
PWR8597.Message: The Power Supply Unit (PSU) %1 is turned off because it is not supported by the Chassis.

RAC0231.Description: This message is displayed when a confirmation is required to format the vFlash SD Card partition.
RAC0231.Resolution: Press OK to initialize this partition of the SD Card. This action will erase all the data in this partition. If undesired press Cancel.
RAC0231.Message: This operation erases all data in the partition. Do you want to continue?

RAC0237.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while uploading the vFlash image.
RAC0237.Resolution: Try uploading the vFlash image again.
RAC0237.Message: An error occurred while uploading the vFlash image.

STOR045.Description: The specified physical disks have fragmented disk space, therefore StartingLBA and Size parameters are required to be specified in order to create a virtual disk.
STOR045.Resolution: Specify StartingLBA and Size parameters and retry the operation.
STOR045.Message: StartingLBA and Size parameters are required to create a virtual disk.

RAC1190.Description: unable to configure the provisioning server
RAC1190.Message: Unable to configure the Provisioning Server feature settings. The required options are either invalid or not provided.

VFL1009.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is operating normally.

UEFI0072.Description: When the Secure Boot feature is enabled, the system BIOS authenticates each UEFI driver against the Secure Boot policy. If a UEFI driver does not meet the policy criteria, the system BIOS does not load or execute the UEFI driver and displays this message at the end of POST. The Secure Boot policy consists of authorized and unauthorized X.509 certificates; signed drivers must chain to an authorized certificate. The policy may also authorize hash values of individual UEFI driver images. Users can configure the Secure Boot feature and the Secure Boot policy in F2 System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page.
UEFI0072.Resolution: If the Secure Boot feature is not desired, disable it in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. Otherwise, do the following: 1) Make sure the firmware on the failing device is up-to-date. 2) If subsequent failures occur, review the Secure Boot Policy Summary in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. The device firmware must be authorized by a public key or hash value in the Authorized Signature Database. The public key or hash value must not be present in the Forbidden Signature Database.
UEFI0072.Message: Unable to load the firmware from %1 because of the Secure Boot policy.

VDR44.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PSU8511.Description: The firmware for the PSU identified in the message was successfully updated.
PSU8511.Message: Successfully updated the firmware for the PSU in slot %1.

PSU0031.Description: The power supply may operate, however power supply monitoring will be degraded. System performance may be degraded.
PSU0031.Resolution: Remove and re-install the power supply. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SWC5005.Description: The System Controller (SC) firmware cannot be updated. For information about the causes, see SEL Event Data Byte 2.
SWC5005.Resolution: Retry the SC firmware update operation. If the issue persists, try updating by using a different firmware update file.
SWC5005.Message: Unable to update the System Controller (SC) firmware

STOR305.Description: Controller mode cannot be changed as controller has a preserved cache.
STOR305.Resolution: Delete the preserved cache and retry the operation.
STOR305.Message: Unable to change controller mode while there is preserved cache present on the controller.

ISM0021.Description: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the OS Collector executable was not found.
ISM0021.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the OS Collector on the iDRAC to the most recent version available, and then retry the operation.
ISM0021.Message: The OS Collector application did not start successfully on the server operating system (OS) because the OS Collector executable was not found.

RAC1113.Description: The configuration XML preview operation cannot be executed because the -b, -s, and -w options must not be used with the --preview option.
RAC1113.Resolution: Remove the -b, -w, and -s options when using the --preview option and retry the operation.
RAC1113.Message: Unable to perform the preview operation because the options -b, -c, -w, and -s must not be used with the --preview option.

BIOS014.Description: AttributeValue may be invalid because of the following causes: 1) Length of new AttributeValue is not within required minimum length and maximum length 2) Value of new AttributeValue is not within required LowerBound and UpperBound 3) Value of new Attributevalue is not one of the possible values.
BIOS014.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on valid Attribute values.

TMP0301.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is disabled.
TMP0301.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is disabled.

BIOS007.Description: A configuration job is already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job succeeds or the job is cancelled.
BIOS007.Resolution: Wait for the job to complete. To continue with more set operations on the specified target, cancel the job and proceed.
