BIOS007.Message: Configuration job already created, cannot create another configuration job on specified target until existing job is completed or is cancelled

SWC8623.Description: The current configuration details of IOA in the slot identified in the message could not be saved to its startup configuration.
SWC8623.Resolution: Power-cycle the IOA and retry the operation.
SWC8623.Message: Unable to save the I/O Aggregator configuration in %1.

RAC1121.Description: The command could not be successfully run, because one or more values about the proxy server was not entered.
RAC1121.Resolution: Make sure that you enter the following data, and then retry the operation:- proxy server address- proxy user name- proxy password
RAC1121.Message: Unable to run the command, because the data entered for connecting to the Proxy server is insufficient.

RED072.Description: Unable to delete the Automatic Backup schedule information because the schedule is not configured.
RED072.Message: Unable to delete the Automatic Backup schedule.

UEFI0254.Description: Unable to enable NUMA Fault Resilient Memory operating mode because of channel configuration mismatches.
UEFI0254.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0254.Message: Unable to enable NUMA Fault Resilient Memory operating mode because of channel configuration mismatches.

SWC0030.Description: iDRAC is unable to complete the backup Server Profile operation.
SWC0030.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0030.Message: Unable to complete the backup Server Profile backup operation.

PDR44.Description: A Clear task was being performed on a physical disk but the task was interrupted and did not complete successfully. The controller may have lost communication with the disk, the disk was removed, or the cables may be loose or defective.
PDR44.Resolution: Verify that the disk is present and not in a Failed state. Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables. Restart the Clear task.

UEFI0159.Description: Unsupported 4Gb technology DIMM module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0159.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0159.Message: Unsupported Unregistered Dual In-line Memory Module (UDIMM) memory is installed on memory slot: %1

SYS135.Description: The user context the OS Collector is being run in does not have the necessary privileges for running the application successfully.
SYS135.Resolution: Run the OS Collector application as administrator or as a user added to admin group or domain administrator or Local administrator.
SYS135.Message: OS Collector: The user context the OS Collector is being run in does not have the necessary privileges for running the application successfully.

PSU1006.Description: The enclosure detected that a power supply unit was inserted.

BAR063.Description: Collecting the Lifecycle Controller firmware images and copying them in the server profile backup file.

VF023.Description: Partition with this label exists. Duplicate labels are not supported.

ENC21.Description: A device has been removed and the system is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

UEFI0038.Description: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because an expected interrupt(s) from the iDRAC SMA (Shared Memory Architecture) interface did not happen. Continuing to boot may result in unexpected power loss because of unknown power inventory and unavailability of features such as active power management, thermal management.
UEFI0038.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware on the system.
UEFI0038.Message: Unable to communicate with iDRAC because of missing interrupts on the Shared Memory Architecture (SMA) interface.

TST101.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC firmware.
TST101.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.

RAC007.Description: The attribute value is outside the acceptable range.
RAC007.Resolution: Enter a value within the range and retry the operation. For more information about the acceptable range, refer to the Dell Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide and DCIM Profile Documents available at the support site.
RAC007.Message: The attribute value is outside the acceptable range.

CTL53.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL53.Message: A controller hot plug has been detected.

PST0085.Description: System is performing CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart).

SYS196.Description: The OEM ID module installation process tried to apply all settings and branding information, but had issues during installation.
SYS196.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Log report to analyze the issue. Review settings and branding information that the ID module configured, resolve the issue, and then retry the installation process.
SYS196.Message: The OEM ID module is installed but with some errors. %1

BAR008.Resolution: Verify the request parameters and retry. Check passphrase for rule validity. NOTE: A valid passphrase contains 8 to 32 characters. It must include a combination of uppercase and lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols without spaces.

TMP0120.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm.
TMP0120.Message: The system inlet temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

IOV1003.Description: One or more parameters identified in the message required for the method are missing.
IOV1003.Resolution: Refer to the DCIM Chassis PCI Management Profile document and provide the required parameter.

HWC8501.Description: The operation could not successfully completed because of an issue with the I/O panel cable.
HWC8501.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Connect the I/O panel cable properly 2) Replace the I/O panel cable.
HWC8501.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of an issue with the I/O panel cable.

PST0135.Description: System BIOS detected a timer refresh failure during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code 87).
PST0135.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

HWC7008.Description: Server <number> health changed to a warning state from more severe state.
HWC7008.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7008.Message: Server %1 health changed to a warning state from more severe state.

RAC1143.Description: The job identified in the message is not a configuration job, a configuration XML import or preview type job that generates configuration results.
RAC1143.Message: Configuration results are not applicable for the job type for Job: %1.

SWC0073.Description: The Repurpose or Retire system operation cannot be successfully started because the current version of iDRAC firmware does not support the operation.
SWC0073.Resolution: Update iDRAC firmware to the latest version and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC0073.Message: Unable to start operation with the current iDRAC version.

BAR005.Description: The Lifecycle Controller data is being collected and copied into the backup file.

OSD063.Description: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is successfully completed.
OSD063.Message: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is successfully completed.

AMP0304.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0304.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0304.Message: The system board %1 current is outside of range.

USR102.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.
USR102.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

UEFI0032.Description: The TPM chip cannot be initialized because the TPM chip is not functioning.
UEFI0032.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0032.Message: Unable to initialize the TPM chip because the TPM chip is not functioning.

RAC0623.Description: A firmware update is not required for the components on the server, because current firmware versions are the latest available in the repository.
RAC0623.Message: The firmware versions on all the components of this server are up-to-date.

RAC0134.Description: The SD card is not a valid vFlash SD card. The use of non-Dell media prevents the use of some extended capabilities and functions.
RAC0134.Resolution: Insert a valid vFlash SD card.
RAC0134.Message: This operation is unavailable for non-vFlash SD cards.

RAC033.Description: The specified attribute cannot be enabled since it depends on IPv4 to be enabled.
RAC033.Resolution: Enable IPv4 and retry the operation.
RAC033.Message: Unable to enable attribute because IPv4 is Disabled.

LC056.Description: The name value pairs in the input parameter arrays do not match in the input.
LC056.Resolution: Retry the operation with a valid (AttributeName, AttributeValue) pair.

RAC0755.Description: The selected value is not supported on this server.
RAC0755.Resolution: Retry the operation with another value.
RAC0755.Message: The selected value is not supported on this server.

VLT0104.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0104.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Remove the processor module. Inspect processor socket for bent pins. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0104.Message: Processor module %1 voltage is outside of range.

ISM0008.Description: iDRAC Service Module detected that OpenManage Server Administrator is running on the OS of this server. Therefore, one or more features of iDRAC Service Module will be disabled.
ISM0008.Resolution: End the OpenManage Server Administrator session. The features will be automatically started by iDRAC Service Module.
ISM0008.Message: Some features of iDRAC Service Module will be disabled on this server, because OpenManage Server Administrator is running on the operating system (OS) of this server.

CTL58.Description: The text for this alert is generated by the firmware and can vary depending on the situation. The reference to SMP in this text refers to SAS Management Protocol.
CTL58.Resolution: There may be a SAS topology error. See the hardware documentation for information on correct SAS topology configurations. There may be problems with the cables such as a loose connection or an invalid cabling configuration. See the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. See the hardware documentation for information on correct cabling configurations. Verify that the firmware version is supported.

TMP0126.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0126.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0126.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

SUP026.Description: The value entered for the parameter identified in the message is invalid.
SUP026.Resolution: Correct the specified input value and retry the operation.
SUP026.Message: The input value entered for the parameter %1 is invalid.

IOV1006.Description: The PCI slot or Server slot FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) values entered for the operation are not valid.
IOV1006.Resolution: Perform the Enumerate operation on the DCIM_ChassisPCISlot class and DCIM_BladeServerView class to get the correct FQDD values for the PCIe slot and Server slot. Retry the operation with the correct FQDD values.
IOV1006.Message: Invalid PCI slot or Server slot.

VLT0225.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0225.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0225.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

BAR070.Description: Access to the NFS export/import destination is not possible or has been denied.
BAR070.Resolution: Verify that the input parameters are correct, connectivity exists to the destination end point, and retry the operation.

SEC0044.Description: TXT initialization cannot be completed because system configuration may have changed.
SEC0044.Resolution: Check system hardware inventory for TPM presence, clear and reconfigure TPM and TXT in BIOS setup menu.
SEC0044.Message: SINIT Authenticated Code Module detected an Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) problem at boot.

UEFI0030.Description: A keyboard device is not connected to the system.
UEFI0030.Resolution: Connect a keyboard device to the system.
UEFI0030.Message: A keyboard device is not connected to the system.

SWC8565.Description: The Boot Identity profile identified in the message is created with number of templates as identified in the message.
SWC8565.Message: The Boot Identity profile %1 is created with %2 templates.

UEFI0224.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Transmit Buffer Per Bit Deskew Training phase.
UEFI0224.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0224.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SYS054.Description: The current configuration for components that require staged configuration already match the configuration specified by the input file. A system restart to apply staged configuration is not required.
SYS054.Message: No configuration changes requiring a system restart need to be applied.

FAN8500.Description: Enabling Enhanced Cooling Mode will provide increased airflow capability to the blades by increasing the maximum allowable blower speed at the cost of increased power consumption.

PST0089.Description: A problem was detected during Power-On Self-Test (POST). The next logged message contains more specific details for the detected issue.
PST0089.Resolution: Review the next logged message for the recommended response action to resolve the problem.
PST0089.Message: A problem was detected during Power-On Self-Test (POST).

JCP021.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of an unknown error in the iDRAC.
JCP021.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
JCP021.Message: The operation failed due to an internal iDRAC error.

SWC1909.Description: The privilege level of the iDRAC User ID indicated in the message has been changed.
SWC1909.Message: User ID %1 RAC Privilege has been changed.

DIS114.Description: The AutoConfig feature timed out while waiting for Remote Services to be ready.

DIS114.Message: The AutoConfig feature timed out while waiting for Remote Services to be ready.

SWC0271.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0271.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0271.Message: Invalid syntax. The -f option is only valid with -p and -c.

OSD55.Description: Cannot attach the ISO image since it is already attached to the host.
OSD55.Resolution: ISO Image is already attached to the host server. Detach the ISO and then rerun the command
OSD55.Message: ISO Image is attached to host

RAC985.Description: The object "cfgServerBootOnce" cannot be configured if the object "cfgServerFirstBootDevice" is set to F10, F11, or BIOS value.

RAC985.Message: Unable to configure the cfgServerBootOnce object.

STOR0702.Description: The value entered for the option name identified in the message is invalid.
STOR0702.Resolution: For more information, run the RACADM command "racadm raid help createvd".
STOR0702.Message: The value entered for the %1 option is invalid

PST0144.Description: System BIOS is unable to load the required BIOS files.
PST0144.Resolution: Remove and reapply power to server. If the problem persists, contact your server provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PST0144.Message: Unable to load required BIOS files.

SWC0053.Description: The file extension of the Update Package is not supported or the Update Package is invalid.
SWC0053.Resolution: Use a valid Windows-based Update Package with an .exe extension.
SWC0053.Message: File extension is not supported or the Update Package is invalid.

BAR030.Description: The import system profile is complete. iDRAC restarts to complete restore.

LC029.Description: An invalid File Path was specified in the export operation.

PCI1358.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.

PCI1358.Message: A fatal error was detected on a component at slot %1.

RAC1163.Description: The peak utilization value of out-of-band performance monitoring sensor identified in the message is successfully reset.
RAC1163.Message: The peak utilization value of out-of-band performance monitoring sensor %1 is successfully reset.

BAR091.Description: A System Profile Backup request made by the user of the Unified Server Configurator interface has completed.

SWC0282.Description: The value being modified is READ only.
SWC0282.Message: The specified object is READ ONLY for this index and cannot be modified.

SWC0297.Description: After the Groups are downloaded to a file, the passwords are to be deleted.

PDR103.Description: Cryptographic Erase operation is successfully completed on the physical disk drive identified in the message.

RAC0700.Description: An email page was successfully sent.

OSD6.Description: Unable to dynamically allocate memory to perform the task.

SWC0028.Description: iDRAC is unable to complete the backup Server Profile operation because an unrecoverable error occurred.
SWC0028.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.

RAC0632.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid hostname or IP address is entered.

RAC0632.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid network file share hostname or IP address is entered.

SYS147.Description: Starting non-secure erase-capable drives erase operations because of a System Erase operation request.

MEM1202.Message: Memory RAID redundancy is degraded. Check memory device at location(s) %1.

RAC035.Description: There are no pending values for the any of the iDRAC attributes.
RAC035.Resolution: Make sure there are pending values for the attributes that are targeted for configuration.

UEFI0188.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Host Impedance phase.
UEFI0188.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0188.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

OSD16.Description: Unable to mount the network share using the parameters specified in the command because either the IP address or share name is incorrect.
OSD16.Resolution: Rerun the command with the correct IP address and share name.
OSD16.Message: Mount network share failed - incorrect IP address or share name.

SWC0024.Description: The Test Network Connection ping test timed-out. The network cable is disconnected or the network is not configured correctly.
SWC0024.Resolution: Check the network cable connection and network configuration settings, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, reconfigure the network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0024.Message: The Test Network Connection ping test timed-out.

SYS037.Description: Operation validation is unsuccessful. The command, target and operation data are all validated before an update is performed. If any of them are missing or incorrect the operation does not complete successfully.
SYS037.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory on Restart attribute using Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. Retry the operation after the system restarts.

USR0177.Description: Configuring the Front Panel USB Port Mode to Automatic because the iDRAC is unable to retrieve the Front Panel USB Port Mode.
USR0177.Message: Configuring the Front Panel USB Port Mode to Automatic because the iDRAC is unable to retrieve the Front Panel USB Port Mode.

CTL35.Description: The operation to import foreign configuration (virtual disks, host spares, and so on) completed successfully.
CTL35.Resolution: Verify the foreign configuration was successfully imported by viewing the virtual disks and hot spares. See the hardware documentation for more information.
CTL35.Message: A foreign configuration was imported on %1.

ENC26.Description: The enclosure or an enclosure component is in a Failed or Degraded state. It is not responding to storage management commands or there is a connectivity problem between the controller and enclosure.
ENC26.Resolution: Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. See the hardware documentation to for more information. Contact technical support.

PSU500.Description: Racadm tool cannot obtain the power status possible reason is that the IPMI call failed.
PSU500.Message: Unable to get the current server power status.

SYS100.Description: A FQDD equivalent for the token name identified in the message cannot be found.
SYS100.Resolution: Make sure that only valid FQDDs are entered as input to the Target parameter, and then retry the operation.
SYS100.Message: Unable to find an FQDD equivalent for the token %1

RAC0681.Description: Shared component updates through the Server OS or Lifecycle controller cannot be applied because the CMC setting for Chassis Management at Server Mode is not set to 'Manage and Monitor'.
RAC0681.Resolution: To enable this feature do the following: 1) Launch CMC Web UI. 2) Navigate to Chassis Overview -> Setup -> General, and select 'Manage and Monitor' option for the Chassis Management at Server Mode. 3) Click Apply to save changes in CMC. 4) Retry the operation in iDRAC. For more information, refer to the CMC User Guide.
RAC0681.Message: Shared component updates through the Server OS or Lifecycle controller cannot be applied because the CMC setting for Chassis Management at Server Mode is not set to 'Manage and Monitor'.

FC004.Description: The value for the specified parameter is invalid.
FC004.Resolution: Make sure that the input parameter values that are provided to the method match the parameter data type and possible values defined in the FC HBA Profile specification.

SWU8517.Description: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware. The firmware Image file is not accessible.
SWU8517.Resolution: Make sure the iDRAC firmware Image file is available in the given path and retry the operation.
SWU8517.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware on the server in slot %1. The Image file is not accessible. ErrorCode=0x%2.

SYS022.Description: The operation could not complete because of an internal resource allocation issue with the firmware.
SYS022.Resolution: Reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.

ENC9.Description: You have changed the enclosure asset tag. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

UEFI0204.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Clock Training FIFO Reset phase.
UEFI0204.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0204.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

MEM1005.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to power off.

SWC0296.Description: Either the password field or the username field is empty.
SWC0296.Resolution: Enter the command with the username and password.
SWC0296.Message: The specified value is not allowed to be configured if the user name \nor password is blank.

VFL1003.Description: The removable flash media is installed but improperly configured or failed to initialize.
VFL1003.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media and module.
VFL1003.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is not IPMI-function ready.

OSD13.Description: iDRAC was unable to mount the drivers as a USB device for the OS installation to proceed.
OSD13.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD13.Message: Cannot mount the USB device needed to copy drivers for the selected operating system.

SUP0535.Description: Component firmware update is in progress.
SUP0535.Resolution: No response action is required. Do not turn off the system while the update is in progress.

RAC0280.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0280.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Range Address. Expected range: 0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255.
RAC0280.Message: The IP Range Address is invalid. Expected range: 0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255.

PWR200.Description: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature will disable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature. MPCM forces servers in to a low-power and limited-performance mode, and then disables the ability to turn on additional servers.
PWR200.Message: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature will disable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature.

PDR56.Description: The bad block table is the table used for remapping bad disk blocks. This table fills as bad disk blocks are remapped. When the table is full, bad disk blocks are no longer remapped, which means that disk errors are no longer corrected. At this point, data loss can occur. The bad block table is now 80 percent full.
PDR56.Resolution: Replace the disk generating this message.
PDR56.Message: Bad block table on %1 is 80% full.

UEFI0201.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Write Training phase.
UEFI0201.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0201.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

UEFI0241.Description: An error occurred during Memory Voltage Regulator initialization during the VR1 SVID Ramp phase.
UEFI0241.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0241.Message: An error occurred during Voltage Regulator (VR) initialization on memory riser %1.

UEFI0005.Description: A CPU math coprocessor not available (type 0x07) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0005.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0005.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x07: Math Coprocessor Not Available (Hardware).

USR0180.Description: The Quick Sync feature is enabled because the activate button on the bezel was pressed.
USR0180.Message: The Quick Sync feature is enabled because the activate button on the bezel was pressed.

CMC8501.Description: Multi Chassis Management feature on CMC allows for pushing the lead chassis configuration data to it's members. This message appears in the member's log when the configuration data is successfully synchronized with the Chassis group leader's configuration data.
CMC8501.Message: Chassis Group Leader has synchronized this member's configuration.

USR0170.Description: The device identified in the message is connected to the Front Panel USB port and attached to the iDRAC.
USR0170.Message: The Front Panel USB port is attached to iDRAC Disk.USBFront.%1. Device details: Device class %2, Vendor ID %3, Manufacturer Name %4, Product ID %5, Product Name %6, Serial Number %7.

PDR24.Description: A disk has received a SMART alert (predictive failure) due to test conditions.
PDR24.Message: Failure prediction threshold exceeded on %1 due to test. No action needed.

CBL8501.Description: The SAS cable identified in the message is not connected to the correct expander.
CBL8501.Resolution: Reconnect the SAS cable to the correct expander and retry the operation.
CBL8501.Message: SAS cable %1 is connected to the incorrect expander.

RAC1001.Description: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 DNS1 or DNS2, because the object DNSFromDHCP6 is enabled.
RAC1001.Resolution: Disable the object DNSFromDHCP6 using "racadm set iDRAC.IPv6.DNSFromDHCP6 <0 | Disabled>", and retry the operation.
RAC1001.Message: Unable to set the object value for iDRAC IPv6 DNS1 or DNS2.

DH008.Description: Unable to save the provided client certificate to internal persistent storage.
DH008.Resolution: Try again. If the error persists, use RACADM command racresetcfg to clear the issue.
DH008.Message: There was a problem saving the certificate to persistent storage.

BAR098.Description: The Service Tag installed on the system is invalid. The Backup and Restore feature will not operate without a valid Service Tag.

RAC1030.Description: The custom signing certificate present on iDRAC was deleted.
RAC1030.Message: The custom signing certificate was deleted.

SWC0128.Description: The Common Name field is necessary for generating a CSR. It is not generated if Common Name is empty.
SWC0128.Resolution: Configure the Common Name field by using config command.
SWC0128.Message: The Common Name (CN) field of the CSR Security group must be configured before a CSR can be generated.

BAT0009.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may report absent due to disconnect or thermal exceptions.
BAT0009.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation.2) If installed, reseat or reconnect the battery and cables. 3) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.

BIOS030.Description: The BIOS password cannot be configured because an Import Server Profile operation is already running.
BIOS030.Resolution: Wait until the current import operation is completed, and then retry the operation.
BIOS030.Message: Unable to change the BIOS password because an Import Server Profile operation is already running.

MEM1006.Message: Memory device at location %1 is online.

RAC0120.Description: Requested partition size exceeds the available space.
RAC0120.Resolution: Enter a partition size smaller than the unused space on the vFlash SD card.
RAC0120.Message: The selected partition size exceeds the available space.

PWR8596.Description: The Chassis Management Controller cannot turn on the server identified in the message, because PSU redundancy is lost or PSUs are removed. Sufficient power is not available for the operation.
PWR8596.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Go to, the Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field, view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis. When enough power is available, retry the operation.
PWR8596.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because PSU redundancy is lost and the available power is insufficient.

ISM0024.Description: The NVMe Device identified in the message is successfully prepared for removal from the PCIe slot identified in the message.
ISM0024.Resolution: No further response action is required before removing the NVMe Device identified in the message. To enable the NVMe Device for use, remove and re-insert the device or restart the system with the device inserted.
ISM0024.Message: The NVMe Device %1 is successfully prepared for removal from PCIe slot %2.

LC050.Description: The value provided to set the attribute identified in the message is invalid.
LC050.Resolution: For more information on the valid values, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation. Retry the operation with a valid value for the SystemServicesState attribute.

UEFI0227.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Receive Enable Training - Configuration Read phase.
UEFI0227.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0227.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

UEFI0164.Description: The Advanced ECC memory operating mode cannot be enabled because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations.
UEFI0164.Resolution: Make sure identical memory modules in corresponding slots of channel pairs are populated. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0164.Message: Unable to enable the Advanced ECC memory operating mode because of mismatches in the DIMM channel configurations on memory slots: %1.

RED025.Description: The firmware for the indicated device updated successfully to the identified firmware version.

PSU8521.Description: The power supply unit (PSU) identified in the message was turned off because the temperature exceeded the high temperature threshold in the unit.
PSU8521.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the PSU or remove AC power and reapply power to the PSU to get it functional again.
PSU8521.Message: PSU %1 exceeded upper temperature threshold and has been turned off.

UEFI0075.Description: The Network Daughter Card 1 is not detected.
UEFI0075.Resolution: Install a Network Daughter Card in the system.
UEFI0075.Message: Network Daughter Card 1 is not detected.

SWU8519.Description: The iDRAC firmware update operation was stopped, because the Image file is corrupted.
SWU8519.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the original source, and then retry the operation.
SWU8519.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is stopped. The Image file is corrupted.

LOG202.Description: Unable to access part of Lifecycle Controller Log comments file during iDRAC boot. The file was truncated at the point of corruption.
LOG202.Message: Recovered from Lifecycle Controller Log comments file corruption.

IPA0003.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.

RED035.Description: The firmware for the component identified in the message was updated successfully by the firmware rollback operation. The component firmware was updated from the earlier version to the current version identified in the message.
RED035.Message: %1 Rollback successful. Earlier version:%2, Current version:%2.

STOR0508.Description: Unable to configure RAID as the supported RAID controller is not present.
STOR0508.Resolution: Install a supported RAID controller and the required number of physical disks for the RAID configuration, and retry the operation.
STOR0508.Message: No supported controllers present for RAID configuration.

ISM0003.Description: The iDRAC Service Module could not successfully discover iDRAC from the server OS. However, the iDRAC Service Module will continue the discovery operation. Make sure that the IPMI drivers are enabled on the server operating system.
ISM0003.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is unable to discover iDRAC from the operating system of the server.

LIC004.Description: This error condition is reported when one of the following conditions occur: 1) Operating system detected a file error (for example, bad CRC, bad sector) when reading/writing a license manager file. The error could indicate bad or corrupt FLASH device. 2) License Manager detected an internal memory data corruption.3) The command or command parameters passed to License Manager is invalid. This is an internal error showing memory corruption. Under normal circumstances this error should not occur.4) When exporting a license file, License Manager was unable to allocate the temporary space required for the transfer of the file.
LIC004.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC004.Message: An internal system error has occurred.

SWU8561.Description: The firmware version selected for rollback does not support the current chassis hardware configuration.
SWU8561.Resolution: Make sure that firmware version selected for rollback is supported for the current hardware configuration, such as I/O modules, PSU modules, and servers. For example, a newer generation PSU may not work with an earlier iDRAC or CMC firmware. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual or CMC or iDRAC Release Notes for details.
SWU8561.Message: Unable to downgrade the firmware version because the current hardware configuration does not support rollback to the earlier firmware version.

RED050.Description: The download of the update package was not successful because the user name or password provided to access the network share or the proxy server settings were not correct.
RED050.Resolution: Check the network connection and access to the update package from the iDRAC. Verify that the user access credentials and proxy server settings are correct.
RED050.Message: The specified user credentials necessary for downloading an update package were not correct.

PR32.Description: The configuration changes requested, for the indicated job, have not passed the device specific verification check and will not be applied.
PR32.Resolution: Check the scripts or company documentation and try again

CTL114.Description: The encryption key for the controller identified in the message matches with its peer.
CTL114.Message: The encryption key of %1 matches with its peer controller.

RED096.Description: The maximum iDRAC storage space allocated for storing firmware image files is reached. The firmware image of the earlier version that was stored for a rollback operation is now deleted.
RED096.Message: The maximum iDRAC storage space allocated for storing firmware image files is reached. The firmware image of the earlier version that was stored for a rollback operation is now deleted.

SYS052.Description: Configuration changes that do not require a system restart are currently being applied.
SYS052.Message: Analyzing iDRAC, System, or Lifecycle Controller configuration for changes to be applied.

MEM1007.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to transition to online.

OSD57.Description: Remote File Share (RFS) is currently configured to be in auto-attach mode. For Web services to attach an ISO, RFS should be changed to attach mode.
OSD57.Resolution: Change the Remote File Share (RFS) mode to Attach using iDRAC GUI or Remote Services API and retry.
OSD57.Message: Remote File Share (RFS) is in Auto-Attach mode.

CMC8532.Description: The user account does not have sufficient privileges to perform the requested operation. Server Administrator privilege is required to perform the requested action.
CMC8532.Resolution: Use a different user account that has Server Administrator privilege, and retry the operation. For more information, contact your system administrator or service provider.
CMC8532.Message: Unable to perform the requested action on the peripheral sled %1, because of insufficient privileges.

VF010.Description: Formatting the specified partition did not complete successfully.
VF010.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
VF010.Message: Partition formatting did not complete successfully.

SWU8528.Description: The process of iKVM firmware update is not successful due to a checksum error of the firmware image.
SWU8528.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source folder, and then retry the operation.
SWU8528.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware, because of a checksum error.

CMC8524.Description: The Mezz card 4 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8524.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8524.Message: The Mezz card 4 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.

USR0034.Description: The account identified in the message is temporarily disabled because of consecutive unsuccessful Login attempts to iDRAC from the IP address identified in the message.
USR0034.Resolution: Contact the iDRAC administrator and make sure the username and password credentials used are correct. Check the Lifecycle Controller Log (LC Log) to see if more unauthorized iDRAC access attempts are occurring than would be expected due to forgotten account names or passwords.
USR0034.Message: Login attempt alert for %1 from %2 using %3, IP will be blocked for %4 seconds.

UEFI0127.Description: The secondary SD card is write-protected mode.
UEFI0127.Resolution: No response action is required if this is intentional.
UEFI0127.Message: The secondary SD card is in write-protected mode.

RED067.Description: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were staged. The system will now restart to apply the staged updates.
RED067.Message: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates were staged. The system will now restart to apply the staged updates.

SWC8533.Description: The delete all keys for service accounts for all slots operation did not complete successfully due to problems encountered while saving the key file.
SWC8533.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8533.Message: Unable to complete delete all keys operation for service accounts for all slots due to problem saving key file.

HWC1015.Description: The mezzanine card may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC1015.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

FAN0019.Description: An incompatibility between operating mode and fan type was corrected for the fan identified in the message.
FAN0019.Message: An incompatibility between operating mode and fan type was corrected for fan %1.

PST0254.Description: System BIOS detected a functional or configuration issue during system POST. Check the system video screen for more information. The system event log may contain additional details. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code FE).
PST0254.Resolution: Check system video and review event log for additional information.

RFM1023.Description: The media is being prepared or is under maintenance. If the problem persists, reinstall the card.
RFM1023.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
RFM1023.Message: Removable Flash Media is not ready.

SYS1002.Description: System is performing a power cycle.
SYS1002.Message: System is performing a power cycle.

PWR8672.Description: The server identified in the message does not have a card in the Mezzanine slot as identified in the message. A mezzanine card position is identified with the following numbers: For quarter-width server, the position number is 1. For half-width server mezzanine C & B maps to position numbers 1 & 2 respectively. For full-width server, mezzanine C & B on the upper- or left part of the server maps to position numbers 1 & 2 respectively. Mezzanine C & B on the lower- or right part of the server maps to position numbers 3 & 4 respectively.
PWR8672.Resolution: Insert a mezzanine card in the slot identified in the message.
PWR8672.Message: The server in slot %1 does not have a %2 mezzanine card in slot %3.

PWR8511.Description: Unable to set the CHASSIS_POWER_button_disable chassis power property.
PWR8511.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8511.Message: Unable to set the CHASSIS_POWER_button_disable chassis power property.

OSD11.Description: Lifecycle Controller does not have any drivers for the selected operating system. The operating system installation uses the native drivers present on the operating system media.
OSD11.Message: Driver Pack does not have drivers for the selected operating system.

ENC10.Description: You have changed the enclosure asset name. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

OSD50.Description: Lifecycle Controller is in field service mode and needs to be updated before proceeding further.
OSD50.Resolution: Install the Lifecycle Controller field services package using the iDRAC GUI.
OSD50.Message: Lifecycle Controller is in field service mode.

DH003.Resolution: Try again. If the error persists, use RACADM command racreset to clear the issue.
DH003.Message: Service tag could not be read

SWC0322.Description: The starting record value has to be lesser than the number of records available.
SWC0322.Resolution: Get the number of records available, and then run the command. If the command is gettracelog, try executing the command again.
SWC0322.Message: Starting record specified exceeds number of records available.

VLT0219.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0219.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0219.Message: The %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

IOV011.Description: All servers that PCIe slots or virtual adapter (VA) will be assigned-to and unassigned-from must be turned off before an assign or unassign operation can be performed.
IOV011.Resolution: Turn off all servers that the PCIe slots or virtual adapter (VA) will be assigned-to and unassigned-from, and then retry the operation.
IOV011.Message: Unable to assign or unassign PCIe slot(s) or virtual adapter (VA) because all affected servers must be turned off.

PDR51.Description: The controller firmware attempted to do SMART polling on the hot spare but could not complete the SMART polling. The controller may have lost communication with the hot spare.
PDR51.Resolution: Verify the health of the disk assigned as a hot spare. Replace the disk and reassign the hot spare. Make sure the cables are attached securely. See the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cables.
PDR51.Message: Hot spare %1 SMART polling has failed.%2

ENC16.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
ENC16.Message: An enclosure blink has ceased on %1.

CTL98.Description: The security key provided as input has been assigned to the controller identified in the message.

RAC0686.Description: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.
RAC0686.Resolution: View successful pending operations by clicking the Pending Operations button.
RAC0686.Message: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.

RED063.Description: The iDRAC firmware updated successfully to the firmware version identified in the message.
RED063.Message: The iDRAC firmware updated successfully. Previous version: %1, Current version: %2

LIC021.Description: All the features in the evaluation license are currently licensed in the system. The license is not imported as it would duplicate existing and active licensed features.
LIC021.Resolution: Remove the license(s) that contain the license set from the evaluation license.
LIC021.Message: Import failed: The features contained in the evaluation license are already licensed.

STOR059.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because there are no virtual disks (VD) available on the specified controller.
STOR059.Resolution: Create a virtual disk and retry the operation.
STOR059.Message: The requested operation is not currently valid because there are no virtual disks on the controller.

SWC0121.Description: The syntax of the sslcertview command is invalid.
SWC0121.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertview subcommand.
SWC0121.Message: Invalid syntax. User index (-i) must be specified.

UEFI0155.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.
UEFI0155.Resolution: If the absence of license is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0155.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Number of Cores per Processor BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.

RAC0133.Description: A non-specific error has been detected when downloading the partition.
RAC0133.Resolution: Try downloading the partition again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC before trying the operation again.
RAC0133.Message: An error has occurred while downloading a partition.

JCP009.Description: Scheduled jobs were deleted as a result of a cancel job request. The job cancellation request is manually or programmatically initiated. Lifecycle Controller enters Recovery mode when unrecoverable and persistent errors occur.
JCP009.Resolution: If the job was not cancelled manually, then Lifecycle Controller may be in Recovery mode. To verify or change Recovery mode, use F2 Setup to select iDRAC Configuration then Lifecycle Controller Settings.

CTL73.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL73.Message: Foreign configuration is imported only partially. Some configurations failed to import on %1.

VF020.Description: The number of partitions exceeded the maximum number allowed on a SD card.
VF020.Resolution: This SD card has reached the partition limit. Delete any partitions that are not necessary and try again.

DIS104.Description: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access the network share folder, because an invalid filename is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS104.Resolution: Specify a valid file name in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC using the (-f <filename>).
DIS104.Message: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access the network share folder, because an invalid filename is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

RAC0760.Description: Unable to perform storage configuration operations on physical disk drive(s) as there are no disk drive(s) available with Ready/RAID/NON-RAID state or the selected controller is in HBA mode.
RAC0760.Resolution: Check the following: 1) If there are no physical disk drive(s) in either Ready state or in RAID/NON-RAID state, insert additional disk drive(s). 2) If the Controller(s) are in HBA mode, switch the controller(s) to RAID mode. To switch controller(s) to RAID mode using the F2 System Setup utility, go to Device Settings > RAID Controller > Controller Management > Advanced Controller Management > Switch to RAID mode.
RAC0760.Message: Unable to perform physical disk(s) storage configuration operations for the selected controller.

SWU8505.Description: The specified Lifecycle Controller operation is successfully submitted and the operation will be executed on the basis of scheduling criteria.
SWU8505.Message: Successfully scheduled the reinstall/rollback operation on the server %1.

RAC1158.Description: The requested number of Lifecycle log entries exceed the limit and cannot be displayed. The remote RACADM operation may time out before retrieving all the log entries.
RAC1158.Resolution: Retrieve a smaller number of log entries using remote RACADM or use firmware or local RACADM to view all the log entries. To retrieve a limited number of log entries, use the -n option. For example, to view the last 10 log entries, run the command 'racadm lclog view -n 10'.
RAC1158.Message: The requested number of log entries exceeds the limit.

MEM9011.Description: BIOS logged location information of a QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) warning. This information can be reviewed by using a tool which displays raw IPMI SEL data such as IPMItool with the -vvv option or RACADM with the -E option.
MEM9011.Message: QuickPath Interconnect (QPI) Reference Code warning location information is logged.

STOR307.Description: Unable to perform the configuration operation because the export log operation is currently in progress.
STOR307.Resolution: Wait until the current export operation is complete, and then try the configuration operation again.
STOR307.Message: Unable to perform the configuration operation because the export log operation is currently in progress.

SWC0005.Description: The view current hardware inventory operation encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0005.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0005.Message: Unable to display the current hardware inventory.

FAN0017.Description: The RPM of the fan identified in the message is functioning correctly.
FAN0017.Message: %1 RPM is within normal operating range.

BAT1017.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1017.Message: The %1 battery learn mode has changed to Warn.

PWR8560.Description: Unable to turn on the I/O Module identified in the message due to insufficient chassis power.
PWR8560.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface to check available power and I/O Module power requirements. If sufficient power is available, restart the CMC and retry the operation. If sufficient power is not available due to an insufficient number of PSUs, add additional PSU(s) and reinsert the I/O Module.
PWR8560.Message: Unable to turn on I/O Module %1 due to insufficient chassis power.

SUP1907.Resolution: Reacquire the image from the original source and retry the operation.

JCP031.Description: The job ID specified as input to the operation has configuration data that is currently being processed by the iDRAC. The job can be deleted after the processing is done.
JCP031.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for 15 seconds, wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting, and then retry the operation.
JCP031.Message: Unable to delete the job because the configuration is still being committed.

CMC8504.Description: The NIC is disabled on the server identified in the message, and the CMC is unable to display the link to launch the iDRAC web interface.
CMC8504.Resolution: Enable the NIC on the server identified in the message using the CMC command line or CMC Web interface, so that the link to launch iDRAC is displayed on the CMC Web interface. To enable the NIC for DHCP using RACADM, enter "racadm setniccfg -m server-<slot number> -d" where <slot number> is the server identified in the message. To enable the NIC using the Web interface, click Server Overview > select the identified server, go to Setup > select the Enable LAN check box.
CMC8504.Message: Unable to access server: %1, because the NIC is disabled on the identified server.

VFL0714.Message: SD card is not ready and could not be initialized.

UEFI0263.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the network cable is not connected.
UEFI0263.Resolution: Check the network cable connection of the system and retry the operation.
UEFI0263.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the network cable is not connected.

HWC1006.Resolution: If adapter disabled unexpectedly, re-enable the storage adapter.

RAC1160.Description: Unable to set USB group objects because the user account identified in the message does not have the System Control privilege, which is required for this operation.
RAC1160.Resolution: Contact the iDRAC system administrator and get the System Control privilege added to the account identified in the message or use account credentials that have System Control privilege and retry the operation.
RAC1160.Message: Unable to set USB group objects because of insufficient privilege for user account %1.

PWR2400.Description: The power management firmware cannot reduce power consumption to meet configuration or user defined settings,
PWR2400.Resolution: "1) Review system power policy.2) Check system event logs for thermal or power related exceptions."
PWR2400.Message: Power management firmware unable to maintain power limit

SWC8529.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to enable the iDRAC root user. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or iDRAC is rebooting
SWC8529.Resolution: If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8529.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to enable the iDRAC root user.

UEFI0122.Description: The secondary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.
UEFI0122.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Install a SD card media in the secondary SD card slot. 2) Reseat or replace the SD card media. 3) If the secondary SD card is intentionally not installed or write-protected mode is expected, then no response action is required.
UEFI0122.Message: The secondary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.

SWC8548.Description: The Media Access Control (MAC) addresses cannot be deleted from the pool because they are not present in the MAC address pool.
SWC8548.Message: Unable to delete some of the Media Access Control (MAC) addresses because the MAC addresses are not present in the MAC address pool or used by Boot Identity profile.

LIC014.Description: An attempt to lock the License Manager database for Lifecycle Controller backup or restore occurred when the License Manager database was already locked. This may occur when two or more users attempt to do a backup or restore operation simultaneously.
LIC014.Resolution: Repeat the Lifecycle Controller backup or restore operation.
LIC014.Message: Multiple backup or restore operations have been simultaneously attempted on the License Manager database.

SUP005.Description: Reboot value specified is not supported.
SUP005.Resolution: Verify the reboot value and retry the action. Current options available are 1)Power Cycle 2) Graceful shutdown without forced shutdown 3) Graceful shutdown with forced shutdown (~10 minutes wait time).

CTL84.Description: The firmware on the controller identified in the message is not supported by this version of the CMC. This may result in degraded functionality.
CTL84.Resolution: Update the CMC Firmware to the latest version available or revert the controller firmware to a previous version.
CTL84.Message: %1 is running an unsupported firmware version.

ISM0000.Description: The iDRAC Service Module is started on the OS of server.
ISM0000.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is started on the operating system (OS) of server.

OSD49.Description: VFlash cannot be accessed because RIPS mode is enabled.
OSD49.Resolution: Disable the RIPS mode from BIOS or from the iDRAC GUI, and then continue executing the method.
OSD49.Message: Disable RIPS mode to access VFlash.

RDU8518.Description: The active CMC requests the Standby CMC to go active. If the user did not initiate this request, review the chassis log for the reason.
RDU8518.Message: CMC%1: active CMC%1 requests Standby CMC to go active state.

CTL90.Description: The peer controller is not compatible with the controller identified in the message because of a hardware mismatch.
CTL90.Resolution: Replace the peer controller with the same model controller as the controller identified in the message.
CTL90.Message: %1 is not operating in Fault Tolerant Mode because of an incompatible peer controller.

UEFI0113.Description: The Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.
UEFI0113.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure the Memory Mirroring feature can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0113.Message: Unable to enable the Fault Resilient Memory (FRM) feature because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.

BAR073.Description: The operation to delete the vFlash backup partition did not complete successfully.
BAR073.Resolution: Enable and initialize the vFlash media and retry the export. If the error continues, try a new vFlash media or use the network share option(s).
BAR073.Message: Delete of vFlash Backup partition unsuccessful.

SUP0113.Description: The cfgRhostsFwUpdateTftpEnable object must be set.
SUP0113.Resolution: Set the cfgRhostsFwUpdateTftpEnable object in cfgRemoteHosts group using config subcommand.
SUP0113.Message: TFTP firmware update is currently disabled.

SWC0216.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0216.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0216.Message: The -c option requires -l to also be specified.

SWC0131.Description: The destination Ip address must be configured for the Trap.
SWC0131.Resolution: Set cfgIpmiPetAlertDestIpAddr in cfgIpmiPet group using config subcommand for the corresponding index.
SWC0131.Message: Trap destination address must be configured.

VLT0235.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is within range.

CPU0704.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.
CPU0704.Resolution: 1) Check system and operating system logs for exceptions. If no exceptions are found continue. 2) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 3) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 4) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

BAR097.Description: The current Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator software installed on the system does not have Backup and Restore feature support.
BAR097.Resolution: Obtain the Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator update package with Backup and Restore support, update the software and try the operation again.
BAR097.Message: Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator incompatibility detected.

SWC0263.Description: The length of path to the firmware image is longer than the specified value.
SWC0263.Resolution: Enter a shorter path to the firmware image file.

VFL1014.Description: The card is write-protected by the physical latch on the SD card. IDSDM cannot use a write-protected card.
VFL1014.Resolution: if unintended, remove the media and disable write protection.
VFL1014.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is write protected.

RAC0107.Description: Communication with the Smart Card reader is established and a Smart Card is inserted, but there are problems accessing the Smart Card. The appropriate Cryptographic Service Provider (CSP) drivers are not installed.
RAC0107.Resolution: There may be an issue with the Smart Card Cryptographic Service Provider (CSP) drivers. Use the client OS to install CSP driver. If the OS has problem with Smart Card, then there will have problem using the Smart Card. So make sure Smart Card can login with Windows OS.
RAC0107.Message: The inserted Smart Card cannot be recognized. Ensure that the correct Smart Card CSP drivers are installed.

OSD30.Description: The value specified for ExposeDuration is out of range. It must be between 60 and 65535 seconds
OSD30.Resolution: Rerun the command with a ExposeDuration value between 60 and 65535 seconds.
OSD30.Message: Invalid value for ExposeDuration - must be 60 - 65535 seconds

STOR310.Description: The virtual disk cannot be initialized because the RAID controller selected does not support the initialization mode.
STOR310.Resolution: Make sure that the RAID controller selected for the operation supports the initialization mode, and they retry the operation. For more information about supported RAID controllers, see the specific documentation of RAID controller. Also, refer to the Dell Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide available at the support site.
STOR310.Message: Unable to initialize the virtual disk because the RAID controller selected does not support the initialization mode.

ENC4.Description: The firmware on the EMM modules is not the same version. It is required that both modules have the same version of the firmware. This alert may be caused when you attempt to insert an EMM module that has a different firmware version than an existing module.
ENC4.Resolution: Download the same version of the firmware to both EMM modules.

NIC503.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC503.Message: The DNS server IP address is not allowed to be configured if DNS server DHCP (cfgDNSServersFromDHCP) is enabled.

VRM0018.Message: Virtual Media image server operation successful

CTL8.Description: A portion of a physical disk is damaged. See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL8.Resolution: See Receive a "Bad Block" Alert with "Replacement," "Sense," or "Medium" Error for more information.
CTL8.Message: Bad block extended sense error on %1.

PDR29.Description: See A Rebuild Completes with Errors for more information.
PDR29.Resolution: See A Rebuild Completes with Errors for more information.

BAT1010.Description: Battery is in warn only mode and requires reconditioning.
BAT1010.Resolution: Start a learn cycle on the battery.
BAT1010.Message: Battery on %1 requires reconditioning. Initiate a learn cycle.

SWC0279.Description: The group is not indexed and does not require an index to be specified.
SWC0279.Resolution: Enter the command without the index.
SWC0279.Message: The specified group is not indexed and does not support -i.

HWC4003.Message: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and other hardware.

FAN906.Description: Changes are not made to the current settings.
FAN906.Resolution: Make sure that changes are made to the settings and retry the operation.
FAN906.Message: Changes are not made to the current settings.

ASR0009.Description: The system is communicating to the baseboard management controller (BMC).
ASR0009.Message: The system returned from a watchdog timer event.

SWC8518.Description: Unable to modify the password of the User identified in the message.
SWC8518.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name and password given are valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8518.Message: Unable to modify password of User %1: %2-%3

DIS010.Description: The Auto Discovery process has encountered a problem. One of the following messages will be displayed on the LCD display and entered in the LC log: 1) No credentials returned, 2) Blocked Because Admin Account Enabled, 3) Blocked Because IPv6 Enabled, 4) No IP on NIC, 5) No provisioning server found, 6) Provisioning server is unreachable/invalid address, 7) SSL connection failed no service at IP/port, 8) SSL connection refused, 9) SSL connection failed (Server authentication), 10) SSL connection failed (client authentication), 11) SSL connection failed other, 12) SOAP failure, 13) Failed to create account, 14) Blocked Because Active Directory Enabled, 15) No Service Tag, and 16) Unknown.
DIS010.Resolution: Refer to Lifecycle Controller Remote Services User's Guide for additional information for LCD messages.

RAC936.Description: iDRAC cannot enable or disable the hot spare property, because the system has a non-PMBus PSU.
RAC936.Message: Unable to change the hot spare property for the PSU.

SWC8523.Description: Unable to complete a configuration sync with the member identified in the message.
SWC8523.Resolution: Check the communications between the Chassis Group Leader and the member. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping <DNS or IP address> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, resolve the communications issue. If the communications are functional, remove the member from the group and re-add the member. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8523.Message: Unable to complete Chassis Group Leader update of member %1.

MEM9006.Description: A non-recoverable link issue was detected in propagation of signals between processors through the Intel QPI interconnect interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9006.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the server and check whether the issue persists. 2) If the issue is not resolved by the preceding action, reseat the processors and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9006.Message: Intel QPI interconnect %1 has a non-recoverable issue.

VDR10.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SYS130.Description: Unable to create the final zip archive name because the Service Tag and time stamp could not be retrieved from OS interfaces.
SYS130.Resolution: Do the following: 1) On Windows, restart the WMI service and retry the operation, 2) Restart the OS and retry the operation.
SYS130.Message: OS Collector: Unable to create filename for zip archive.

PDR79.Description: A user aborted an ongoing copyback operation. The operation did not complete.
PDR79.Message: A user terminated Copyback from %1 to %1.

CTL111.Description: The CopyBack Mode the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL111.Message: The CopyBack Mode of %1 is set to %2.

AMP0308.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0308.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0308.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is greater than the upper warning threshold.

FC015.Description: A set attribute operation was not successful because the attribute is read-only.

BIOS004.Description: The value for the specified parameter is invalid.
BIOS004.Resolution: Verify that parameter values passed to the method are entered as they appear in the enumeration and parameter data type matches the documentation.

PDR69.Description: Physical disk inserted is of the incorrect protocol. SAS or SATA mixing is not supported in the same virtual disk.
PDR69.Resolution: Remove drive, insert correct protocol type, and force a rebuild as imposed for controller and system.

RAC1067.Description: The minimum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is lesser than, or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.
RAC1067.Resolution: Check the minimum critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the minimum threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1067.Message: Unable to set the minimum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is lesser than, or equal to the minimum critical threshold value.

VDR48.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes. The virtual disk has inconsistent data. This may be caused when a power loss or system shutdown occurs while data is being written to the virtual disk.

PDR48.Description: This message is generated after rebuild resumes on a physical disk.

PDR73.Description: The physical disk participating in the copyback operation failed.
PDR73.Resolution: Replace the disk and retry the operation.

CTL30.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL30.Message: The Check Consistency rate has changed for %1.

IOV122.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter (VA) identified in the message has been assigned to the extension of the server slot identified in the message.
IOV122.Message: %1 %2 is mapped/assigned to extension of server slot %3.

TMP0135.Message: The control panel temperature is within range.

PDR55.Description: The physical disk inserted is too small for the rebuild to occur.
PDR55.Resolution: Replace the physical disk with one of correct protocol (SAS, SATA) with at least the required size. Force rebuild if it does not start automatically.
PDR55.Message: Insufficient space available on the %1 to perform a rebuild.

SYS152.Description: Some of the requested storage component erase tasks were not successful. Retrying the System Erase operation may be required. The vFlash SD Card must be initialized and licensed to be erased successfully.
SYS152.Resolution: Retry the System Erase operation. To retry the System Erase operation using the Lifecycle Controller utility, restart the server and when the company logo is displayed, press <F10>. Select Hardware Configuration > Retire or Repurpose System, check appropriate storage options, and then retry the operation.
SYS152.Message: Erase operations for some System Erase tasks did not complete successfully.

STOR0103.Description: No physical disk data to display. The system is powered off, physical disks are not present on the system, or physical disks are not connected to the enclosure or backplane
STOR0103.Resolution: Check if the server has power, physical disks are available, and physical disks are connected to the enclosure or backplane.

UEFI0250.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. The Legacy VGA range processor target is not populated. Decode was forced to the Legacy CPU socket.
UEFI0250.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0250.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

RAC0750.Description: The USB NIC IP address cannot be accessed by using the PING process.
RAC0750.Resolution: Enter another appropriate IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC0750.Message: Unable to access the USB NIC IP address by using PING process.

RAC956.Description: The allocated size for the Lifecycle Log entries has reached its maximum limit, and no further comments can be added to the Lifecycle Log.
RAC956.Message: There is no free space to add new comments to the Lifecycle Log.

PR25.Description: The system's configuration database is missing or is unreadable. This may be due to a user action such as Lifecycle Controller Wipe or a replaced motherboard.
PR25.Resolution: Enable the Collect System Inventory on Restart attribute of the Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. Alternatively, use the Unified Server Configurator utility.

UEFI0251.Description: A memory riser was detected behind an empty processor socket. Memory must be installed behind a populated processor socket in order to be recognized by the system and available for usage. Check to make sure processors and memory are installed in a supported configuration.
UEFI0251.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Populate processors and memory in a supported configuration and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0251.Message: Memory riser %1 is populated behind an empty processor socket.

PCI1320.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1320.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1320.Message: A bus fatal error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

FAN905.Description: Applying fan configuration settings. This may take several seconds.
FAN905.Message: Applying fan configuration settings. This may take several seconds.

SEC0701.Description: This warning message is displayed when using the default username and password (root and calvin). Using the default password causes a severe security risk for iDRAC.
SEC0701.Resolution: To change the password, run the following racadm commands: racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.Password <new password string>.Alternatively, to avoid this warning message run the following racadm command: racadm set iDRAC.Tuning.DefaultCredentialWarning Disable
SEC0701.Message: Warning: Default username and password are currently in use. It is strongly recommended to change the default password immediately.

SWC0062.Description: The destination folder is not present, the destination is full or write-protected.
SWC0062.Resolution: Verify the following and retry the operation:1) Destination folder is present.2) Destination has enough free space.3) Destination is not write-protected.If the problem persists, perform an AC power cycle and retry.

OSD61.Description: The IP Address format is invalid and cannot be validated. The specified IP address may not be a valid IPv4 or IPv6 address.
OSD61.Resolution: Verify the IP address format and retry the operation.

RAC0298.Description: A Root Domain Name must be specified for Active Directory configuration.
RAC0298.Resolution: Root Domain Name must be configured.
RAC0298.Message: Root Domain Name must be configured.
