PWR8574.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is not able to communicate with the iDRAC on the server identified in the message. Therefore the server could not be hard reset. This situation may occur when iDRAC is restarting.
PWR8574.Resolution: Wait for three minutes, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the server and wait for the iDRAC to finish restarting before retying the operation.
PWR8574.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate to the iDRAC, when trying to hard reset the server %1.

PWR2262.Description: The Intel Management Engine is unable to utilize the PECI over DMI facility.
PWR2262.Resolution: Look for the PWR2264 "normal system operation" message in the Lifecycle Log after the PWR2262 entry. It may take 30 seconds for the message to be logged. If the PWR2264 message does not appear, do the following: Disconnect power from the server and reconnect power. Turn on the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR2262.Message: The Intel Management Engine has reported an internal system error.

ISM0023.Description: The feature WMI Information is disabled. It will be enabled when a compatible iDRAC firmware is installed.
ISM0023.Resolution: WMI Information feature requires iDRAC 8 firmware version 2.00.00 or later. Update the iDRAC firmware to the appropriate version to activate the WMI Information feature.
ISM0023.Message: The feature WMI Information is de-activated because the iDRAC firmware version installed is not compatible. It will be activated when the compatible iDRAC firmware is installed.

SEL1404.Message: A platform event trap (PET) was generated.

BAT1006.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1006.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle will start in %2 days.

OSD22.Description: Unable to detach ISO image from the host because either the image is already detached, or iDRAC may not be operating normally.
OSD22.Message: Unable to detach ISO image from the host.

MEM9003.Description: A correctable error was detected in propagation of signals between processor and memory through the Intel SMI 2 memory interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9003.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reseat the memory riser and restart the server. 2) If the issue is not resolved by preceding action, reseat the processor and restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your services provider.
MEM9003.Message: Intel SMI 2 Memory interconnect %1 has a correctable error.

OSD46.Description: Another process (iDRAC GUI /racadm/iDRAC configuration utility) is currently accessing VFlash.
OSD46.Resolution: Wait until the access to VFlash is relinquished and then retry this command.

PWR201.Description: Selecting the Server Based Power Management Mode option sets your power cap to a maximum value, server priorities to a default priority, and then disables the Max Power Conservation Mode.
PWR201.Message: Selecting the Server Based Power Management Mode option sets your power cap to a maximum value, server priorities to a default priority, and then disables the Max Power Conservation Mode. Do you want to continue?

MEM1000.Message: Memory device at location %1 transition to a running state.

SEC0612.Description: The default username and password is currently in use and unauthorized access to the iDRAC may occur because the default values are widely known. This is a severe security risk.
SEC0612.Resolution: To change the credentials using RACADM command, run the following at the command line interface (CLI): "racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.Password <new password string>". Alternately, to disable the default credential in use message, run "racadm config -g cfgractuning -o cfgRacTuneDefCredentialWarningEnable 0".
SEC0612.Message: The default username and password is currently in use. It is recommended to immediately change the default credentials.

VFL0021.Description: The requested operation cannot be performed if one of the vFlash SD cards is in an 'attached' state.
VFL0021.Resolution: Detach the vFlash SD Card partitions by running the racadm command "racadm set iDRAC.vflashpartition.<partition number>.attachstate 0". and retry the operation.
VFL0021.Message: One of the vFlash SD Card partitions is already attached to the host operating system.

PSU0042.Resolution: 1) Remove the power supply input cord and then remove power supply. 2) Re-install the power supply and then re-install the power supply cord. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0042.Message: An output over current fault detected on power supply %1.

CTL12.Description: The controller and attached enclosures are not cabled correctly.
CTL12.Resolution: Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on correct cabling configurations.
CTL12.Message: An invalid SAS configuration has been detected on %1. Details: %2

RAC1179.Description: Unable to complete requested operation because a Type A/A USB cable is connected to the front panel USB port and the iDRAC is emulating a NIC device.
RAC1179.Resolution: To change the USB Management Port mode setting, remove the Type A/A USB cable from the front panel USB port and change the port mode settings.
RAC1179.Message: Unable to complete requested operation because an Type A/A USB cable is connected to the front panel USB port and the iDRAC is emulating a NIC device.

RAC914.Description: The specified value is not within the valid range. To set the LED state to off, enter 0. To set the LED state to on, enter 1.
RAC914.Resolution: Set the numeric value to 0 (Off) or 1 (On).
RAC914.Message: Value specified is invalid: Must be 0 (Off) or 1 (On).

BAT1016.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1016.Message: The %1 battery learn mode has changed to Auto.

RAC0244.Description: This message is displayed when a duplicate vFlash partition name is entered.
RAC0244.Resolution: Enter a unique label name for the partition.
RAC0244.Message: The partition label must be unique.

RAC943.Description: The Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is currently disabled. If the system inventory is not up-to-date, the system configuration profile that is being copied will not have the latest inventory information.
RAC943.Resolution: To get latest inventory information, cancel the current export job, run "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart 1" to enable CSIOR, and re-initiate the export operation.
RAC943.Message: Warning: Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

SWC0321.Description: Could not open the log file for reading.
SWC0321.Message: Unable to open the log for reading.

CPU0702.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.
CPU0702.Resolution: Check system and operating system logs for exceptions. If no exceptions found, remove input power, reinstall the processor, then apply input power.

PCI1312.Message: An EISA fail-safe time-out was detected.

ASR0002.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC). The system powered off per the configured setting.
ASR0002.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0002.Message: The watchdog timer powered off the system.

CMC8516.Description: The I/O module may have taken more time to boot than was expected or the I/O module did not boot.
CMC8516.Resolution: Verify the I/O Module is turned on using CMC Web Interface or RACADM CLI and retry the operation. Otherwise, reinsert the I/O Module and retry the operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support.
CMC8516.Message: The I/O Module %1 did not boot within the expected time.

UEFI0200.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Write Level Coarse Training phase.
UEFI0200.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0200.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RAC0156.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about system voltage.
RAC0156.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0156.Message: Unable to retrieve the voltage information. The system is powered off.

SWC0245.Description: Local configuration using RACADM is disabled. This limits local configuration privileges such as resetting object values.
SWC0245.Resolution: Within group cfgRacTuning set the property cfgRacTuneLocalConfigDisable to 0.
SWC0245.Message: Failed to set object value because local configuration using RACADM is disabled.

SWC0067.Description: The location of the operating system configuration file specified in the operation is not valid.
SWC0067.Resolution: Make sure that the specified source file path is correct and retry the operation.
SWC0067.Message: Unable to import operating system configuration file.

PWR210.Description: The redundancy policy cannot be changed to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.
PWR210.Message: The redundancy policy cannot be changed to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.

RED041.Description: The license required to perform the operation identified in the message is expired or is not available.
RED041.Resolution: Install an iDRAC license that supports the following features: Automatic Update or Server Profile Export and Import. After the appropriate license has been installed, retry the operation.
RED041.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was not created because the required license is not available.

BAR107.Description: The vFlash media reader requires a license to function.
BAR107.Resolution: Obtain the license for vFlash media from your service provider. Install the license and retry the operation.
BAR107.Message: vFlash media reader license not present.

BAR086.Description: The system profile import of Lifecycle Controller configuration data has failed.
BAR086.Resolution: If collect system inventory on reboot (CSIOR) is not enabled, enter and exit System Services in USC to update the database, reboot the system and try the operation again. If the error continues, use the field service repair software to repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download all Dell Update Packages for USC, Diagnostics Driver Packs, and device firmware for all host system devices, install all packages and retry the operation.
BAR086.Message: Unable to Restore The Lifecycle Controller Configuration database.

MEM0700.Message: The persistent correctable memory error rate is at normal levels for a memory device at location %1.

BAR055.Description: Attempted configuration import was not successful for the specified device.
BAR055.Resolution: The system event log captures the values that were not set, and must be reset manually.
BAR055.Message: Previously stored configuration values not applied to Device: %1

SWC8556.Description: The Boot Identity profile identified in the message is in use by the server that has the Service Tag identified in the message.
SWC8556.Message: The Boot Identity profile %1 is in use by the server that has the Service Tag %2.

RAC0265.Description: If VLAN is enabled, specify the VLAN ID and VLAN Priority.
RAC0265.Resolution: Enter a VLAN ID and VLAN Priority.
RAC0265.Message: Specify the VLAN ID and VLAN Priority.

CTL62.Description: Physical disk(s) have been removed from a virtual disk. The virtual disk will be in Failed state during the next system reboot. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL62.Message: %1 on %2 has missing drives and will go offline at boot.

STOR062.Description: One or more physical disks specified are full and cannot be used to create additional virtual disks.
STOR062.Resolution: Make sure all physical disks specified to create a virtual disk have the required amount of free space and retry the operation.
STOR062.Message: One or more physical disks specified are full and cannot be used to create additional virtual disks.

LIC213.Description: This error can occur when:1) License Manager fails to load due to lack of system resources.
LIC213.Message: A system error was detected during License Manager startup.

RAC0293.Description: This error is displayed when LDAP or Active Directory cannot find an associated Certificate Authority (CA) certificate.
RAC0293.Resolution: Upload a valid root Certificate Authority (CA) certificate.
RAC0293.Message: When certificate validation is enabled, a valid root Certificate Authority (CA) certificate must be uploaded. The CA certificate is used to verify the directory server SSL certificate.

RED062.Description: Unable to successfully authenticate. The username or password entered is incorrect, or HTTP server does not support BASIC or Digest authentication types.
RED062.Resolution: Verify username, password and server authentication type. To manually update, retry the operation.
RED062.Message: Unable to successfully authenticate user credentials to the specified repository.

SYS080.Description: Preview of system configuration XML file import operation indicates that no changes will be applied successfully. This is likely due to a mismatch between the actual target system components and component FQDDs specified in the configuration XML file.
SYS080.Resolution: Make sure that the input file is compliant with the system configuration schema published on www.delltechcenter.com/lc and contains valid FQDDs that represent actual components in the target system.
SYS080.Message: Preview of system configuration XML file import operation indicated that no configuration changes will be successful.

PWR2252.Description: The server did not turn on because an NDC or Mezzanine card is incompatible with the I/O Module or PCIe subsystem.
PWR2252.Resolution: Check the release notes for the product and make sure to install compatible components in the server.
PWR2252.Message: Unable to turn on the server because an NDC or Mezzanine card is incompatible with the I/O Module or PCIe subsystem.

SWC0033.Description: Exporting the Server Configuration Profile image file to the network share was successful.
SWC0033.Message: Successfully exported the Server Configuration Profile image file to network share.

PDR74.Description: A user cancelled the copyback operation.

UEFI0234.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Memory Test phase.
UEFI0234.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0234.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

HWC8503.Description: The communication between the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) and the control panel is functioning normally.
HWC8503.Message: Communication to the control panel has been restored.

LC079.Description: The export operation cannot be started because Lifecycle Controller is currently running an instance of Export Message Registry operation.
LC079.Resolution: Wait for the current export process to complete, and then retry the operation.
LC079.Message: Unable to start the export operation because Lifecycle Controller is currently running an instance of Export Message Registry operation.

BAR021.Description: The system profile export could not complete successfully as there is insufficient space on the network share or connectivity was lost.
BAR021.Resolution: >Delete files to free up 384 MB of space on the current network share, or specify another destination that has enough space.

UEFI0078.Description: One or more Machine Check errors occurred in the previous boot.
UEFI0078.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the source of the Machine Check error and resolve the issues.
UEFI0078.Message: One or more Machine Check errors occurred in the previous boot.

BAT1032.Description: The battery temperature is within the normal operating range.
BAT1032.Message: The battery temperature on %1 is normal.

SWC1914.Description: Network Time Protocol configuration is disabled.
SWC1914.Message: Network Time Protocol configuration is disabled.

PWR1008.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1008.Resolution: Review system configuration, upgrade power supplies or reduce system power consumption.
PWR1008.Message: The system performance degraded because power draw exceeds the power threshold.

PDR106.Description: A physical disk identified in the hot-spare that was assigned as a hot spare has been un-assigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically by the storage management software. When one of the disks in a virtual disk fails, data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, The hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. In this situation, assigning a new hot spare to maintain data protection in recommended.
PDR106.Resolution: No response action is required. Assigning a new dedicated hot spare to the virtual disk is recommended.
PDR106.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is unassigned as a dedicated hot-spare.

RED085.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because communication between iDRAC and CMC took more time than expected.
RED085.Resolution: Verify the status of CMC by accessing the CMC and making sure it is functioning and responding and then retry the operation. For more information about troubleshooting a CMC issue, see the CMC User Manual. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RED085.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware, communication with Chassis Management Controller took more time than expected.

PST0081.Description: System is at F1/F2 prompt because the system BIOS was unable to detect a bootable device.
PST0081.Resolution: Make sure a bootable device is attached to the system and enabled in BIOS setup. If device is attached and enabled, remove and reapply power to server. If the problem persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

LOG201.Description: Lifecycle Controller Log corruption was detected during iDRAC boot. The Lifecycle Controller Log was truncated at the point of corruption.
LOG201.Message: Recovered from Lifecycle Controller Log corruption.

UEFI0132.Description: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient base memory. The base memory is memory below 640K.
UEFI0132.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove unused PCIe card(s) to free up option ROM space. 2) Disable unused boot protocol instances (such as PXE, iSCSI, etc.) from applicable PCIe card(s) option ROM configurations. 3) If possible, install and run the Operating System in UEFI boot mode.
UEFI0132.Message: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient base memory.

RAC0683.Description: Unable to perform split mode configuration on enclosure(s).
RAC0683.Resolution: Check the following: 1) The controller must have Real Time Configuration Capability and the associated enclosure(s) must have Split Mode Capability in order to perform the operation. 2)The controller(s) associated with the enclosure(s) support real time configuration. To verify the controller real time configuration support, go to the Controller Properties page, select the required controller and verify the Real Time Configuration Capability value.3)The enclosure(s) supports split mode configuration. To verify the enclosure, go to the Enclosure Properties page, select the required enclosure, and verify the Enclosure Split Mode Capability property value.
RAC0683.Message: Unable to perform split mode configuration on enclosure(s).

STOR061.Description: The initializing virtual disk operation is not supported on the target device.
STOR061.Resolution: For more information about supported operations, see the documentation specific for the targeted RAID controller or the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide.
STOR061.Message: Initializing virtual disk is not supported on the RAID controller.

LC057.Description: The attribute name provided is not valid for the current method.
LC057.Resolution: Retry the operation with a valid AttributeName parameter value.

RAC0606.Description: The selected network connection test operation was successful.
RAC0606.Message: The network connection test operation was successful.

UEFI0063.Description: An attribute cannot be successfully configured because of an issue in the ACI data block.
UEFI0063.Resolution: Check the ACI data block for any invalid configuration data and settings, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0063.Message: Unable to change an attribute because of issues in the Attribute Configuration Interface (ACI) data block.

SWC0059.Description: vFlash partitions are being used by other applications such as Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services or RACADM.
SWC0059.Resolution: Wait until the current operations are complete and retry the operation. For information, see the FAQs section of the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services or RACADM User Guide.

SWC0082.Description: An error occurred while joining the Dell Integrated Data Center Network because the Provisioning Server on Integrated Data Center did not respond. Refer to Integrated Data Center setup instructions to setup the Provisioning Server.
SWC0082.Resolution: Refer to Integrated Data Center Userguide for setup instructions.
SWC0082.Message: Unable to join Integrated Data Center network.

UEFI0089.Description: Incompatible x16 data bus width DIMM is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0089.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0089.Message: Incompatible x16 data bus width DIMM is installed on memory slot: %1.

USR0190.Description: The peak value of the sensor identified in the message is reset.
USR0190.Message: Peak value is reset for %1 sensor.

TMPS0103.Description: <font face="Calibri">Inlet temperature has been above the critical  threshold for duration of 1% or more for the operational time during the last one year.</font>
TMPS0103.Resolution: This condition will occur if the ambient temperature is high. Make sure the ambient temperature of the environment is in normal range.
TMPS0103.Message: Inlet temperature is above critical level for extended duration.

PWR8570.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is not able to communicate with the iDRAC on the server identified in the message. Therefore, the server could not be power cycled. This situation may occur when iDRAC is rebooting.
PWR8570.Resolution: Wait for few minutes, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following: 1) Reset the iDRAC, 2) Perform a Virtual Reseat of the server, 3) Remove and re-insert the server.
PWR8570.Message: Unable to communicate to the iDRAC, when trying to power cycle the server %1.

VLT0215.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0215.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0215.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PST0007.Description: System BIOS has started power on self test.

HWC5032.Description: The fabric type for IOM's on the same chassis fabric must match.
HWC5032.Resolution: Check chassis fabric type in CMC GUI and compare to the type of both IOM's.
HWC5032.Message: A fabric mismatch detected on IO module %1.

STOR16.Description: The configuration of the storage sled in the slot identified in the message is normal.
STOR16.Message: The storage sled %1 configuration is normal.

LC043.Description: Work notes cannot include non-printable or reserved characters, such as &, <, >, /.
LC043.Resolution: Do not use non-printable characters or reserved characters such as &, <, >, and /.
LC043.Message: Work note contains non-printable or reserved characters.

SYS047.Description: The input file is not compliant with the system configuration XML schema.
SYS047.Resolution: Make sure that the input file is compliant with the system configuration schema published on delltechcenter.com/lc in the LC XML Schema Guide.
SYS047.Message: Input file for system configuration XML is not compliant with configuration schema.

PCI3005.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card %1 was successfully updated.

LC061.Description: Jobs, invoke methods, enumerates can now be performed on Lifecycle controller. Lifecycle controller is ready to take provisioning requests.
LC061.Message: Lifecycle controller is ready to take provisioning requests

VFL0003.Description: The partition number identified in the message cannot be queried, because identified partition does not exist.
VFL0003.Resolution: Use a partition number of an existing partition for the requested operation.

CPU9001.Description: A correctable error was detected in propagation of signals between processors.
CPU9001.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Restart the server and verify whether or not the issue persists. 2) If yes, reseat the processors, and then restart the server. 3) If the issue persists, contact your server provider.
CPU9001.Message: CPU interconnect %1 has a correctable error.

RAC0117.Description: The SD card is not present, or communication with the SD card is lost. This could result in reduced functionality and capabilities.
RAC0117.Resolution: This error may occur because: 1. Make sure the SD card is seated correctly. 2. The SD card is invalid. Insert a valid SD card of size greater than 256MB and try again.

PDR1006.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is in the failed array.

SUP017.Description: The specified start time is invalid.
SUP017.Resolution: Start Time should be in the form YYYYMMDDHHMMSS. Or it should be TIME_NOW to specify an immediate update or reboot. Verify the specified start time and retry the action.

PWR8517.Description: Chassis power state transition did not complete successfully. This may be due to one of the following: 1) Unable to turn off one or more servers, 2) A firmware update may be in progress.
PWR8517.Resolution: Check the tracelog for more information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8517.Message: Unable to turn off chassis power.

FAN1001.Description: The enclosure detected that a fan was inserted.

BOOT007.Description: One or more of the Boot Source instance IDs does not belong to the affected Boot Configuration.
BOOT007.Resolution: ChangeBootOrderByInstanceID only accepts Boot Sources from the impacted Boot Configuration. Verify that all source arguments belong to the desired Boot Configuration.
BOOT007.Message: Boot Source does not belong to specified Boot Configuration

VFL0012.Description: The vFlash media is not enabled.
VFL0012.Resolution: Enable the vFlash media by running the command 'racadm set idrac.vFlashSD.Enable 1'.

UEFI0238.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write DQ/DQS Training - Calibration phase.
UEFI0238.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0238.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

UEFI0040.Description: The TXT has been disabled due to an unexpected issue. Check the SEL (System Event Log) for details of the issue.
UEFI0040.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 2) Update the BIOS firmware on the system. For information about the issue, see System Event Log (SEL).
UEFI0040.Message: The TXT feature is disabled because of an unexpected issue.

RAC0664.Description: Exporting the RAID Controller Log will take less than the number of minutes identified in the message. The job identified in the message is created for the RAID Controller Log Export operation.
RAC0664.Resolution: To check the progress of the job click the Job Queue button.
RAC0664.Message: Exporting the RAID Controller Log will take less than %1 minutes. Job ID: #{jobID} is created for the RAID Controller Log Export operation.

BAR113.Description: The Automatic Backup job that was earlier schedule was not successfully created. This could be due to an invalid parameter entered to create the job.
BAR113.Resolution: Using the iDRAC Web UI, select Server Profile from the navigation panel, and then the Automatic Backup tab. Clear Settings and reenter appropriate data, the select Schedule Backup to restart the Automatic Backup jobs. Using the RACADM CLI or WSMAN API, clear the scheduled backup settings and retry the Automatic Backup scheduling operation.
BAR113.Message: Unable to create an Automatic Backup job.

USR8511.Description: Successful login from IP address by Username identified in the message.
USR8511.Message: Login was successful %1 from %2 (username=%3, type=%4, sid=%5)

MEM9015.Description: The memory device identified in the message has encountered a uncorrectable error. System performance may be degraded. The operating system and/or applications may fail as a result.
MEM9015.Resolution: Re-install the memory component identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM9015.Message: Multi-bit memory errors detected on a Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) device %1.

RAC058.Description: The value provided for the specified attribute is not unique. For example, the user name for a user account must be unique.
RAC058.Resolution: Provide a unique value for the specified attribute. For more information about the component being managed, see the DCIM Profile documentation.
RAC058.Message: AttributeValue is not unique for AttributeName %1.

FC013.Description: An incorrect AttributeName parameter name was provided.
FC013.Resolution: Enter the correct AttributeName available for the component in the system. Identify the correct AttributeName from the attribute enumeration response for the component or refer to the FC HBA Profile specification.

UEFI0207.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Command Clock Training - Group 2 phase.
UEFI0207.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0207.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

VDR22.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

CTL75.Description: The controller cache was discarded by the user. Data may have been lost or corrupted.
CTL75.Resolution: If data was corrupted or lost, restore the data to the disk from a backup copy.

SUP0519.Description: The update firmware image operation is unable to process the firmware image provided. The image is invalid or incompatible with the installed component.
SUP0519.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0519.Message: Unable to validate firmware image for %1.

VFL1002.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is IPMI-function ready.

PWR8601.Description: The power buttons for all multinode sleds in the chassis are disabled. The operation to disable the power button is only applicable to the multinode sleds available, and does not affect other servers in the chassis.
PWR8601.Resolution: To enable the chassis power button use the CMC RACADM command line interface (CLI) or CMC Web interface. At the CLI, enter "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisSledPowerButtonEnable 1". Using the Web interface, click Server Overview > Power > Control. Clear the Disable power button for all multinode sleds in the chassis" check box.
PWR8601.Message: The multinode sled power button is disabled.

JCP001.Description: The UEFI automated task related to the job was successfully scheduled.

UEFI0087.Description: Unsupported 4Gb technology DIMM module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0087.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0087.Message: Unsupported 4Gb technology DIMM module is installed on memory slot: %1.

PWR8536.Description: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is enabled.
PWR8536.Message: Server Performance Over Power Redundancy is enabled.

OSD73.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'HashValue' is missing.
OSD73.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "HashValue" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD73.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'HashValue' is missing.

SYS060.Description: Some configuration changes for the component identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) in the configuration job results were not successfully applied.
SYS060.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log and identify the configuration changes that did not complete or retrieve the configuration results using the GetConfigResults() method. Retry those changes that did not complete in a separate import operation.

PCI1319.Description: A high-severity issue was detected in the SSD bay identified in the message.
PCI1319.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the component identified in the message, and then monitor the log for a re-occurrence of the issue. If the issue persists, and occurs during server startup, update the component firmware. If the issue persists and occurs during OS runtime, restart the server and update the OS drivers for the component identified in the message.
PCI1319.Message: A high-severity issue is detected in the SSD bay %1, Slot %2.

HWC5012.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
HWC5012.Message: On screen display (OSCAR) is not functional for the %1.

SWC5004.Description: System Controller (SC) has started functioning again because either a server health issue is resolved or SC has completed a firmware update process.

PSU1002.Description: The enclosure detected that a power supply unit was removed and is no longer functioning in optimal condition.
PSU1002.Resolution: Re-insert the power supply unit into the enclosure. Re-connect the AC power cable and switch on the power supply unit. Contact technical support if the issue persists.

HWC5037.Description: The firmware on the I/O module did not boot. The problem may be because the I/O module is not inserted correctly.
HWC5037.Resolution: Reseat I/O module. If problem persists, contact the service provider.

HWC4018.Description: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between the components identified in the message.
HWC4018.Message: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between %1%2 and %3%4.

CTL13.Description: The controller has flushed the cache and all data in the cache has been lost. This may occur when the system has memory or battery problems that cause the controller to distrust the cache. Although user data may have been lost, this alert does not always indicate that relevant or user data has been lost.
CTL13.Resolution: Verify that the battery and memory are functioning properly.

RAC0690.Description: The iDRAC Service Module is not installed on the operating system of the server.
RAC0690.Resolution: Install the iDRAC Service Module and retry the operation.
RAC0690.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is not installed on the operating system of the server.

PCI3017.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card was successfully updated.

RAC1028.Description: The certificate cannot be downloaded if the certificate type specified is other than "1", "2", or "3".
RAC1028.Resolution: Make sure to specify either "1", "2", or "3" for the certificate type (-t) option, and retry the operation.
RAC1028.Message: Unable to download the specified certificate type.

MEM0701.Description: The memory may not be operational. This an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0701.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM0701.Message: Correctable memory error rate exceeded for %1.

RAC0148.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about the batteries.
RAC0148.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0148.Message: Unable to retrieve the batteries information. The system is powered off.

BAR080.Description: Importing the Lifecycle Controller configuration database from the system profile backup file.

UEFI0104.Description: The DIMM module on memory slot identified in the message is populated out of order in the channel.
UEFI0104.Resolution: Install DIMM modules in sequential order without skipping any slots in the channel. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0104.Message: The DIMM module on memory slot %1 is populated out of order in the DIMM channel.

NIC502.Description: The value of the specified parameter cannot be changed.
NIC502.Resolution: Enable DHCP on the NIC before enabling it for DNS.
NIC502.Message: DHCP is required to be enabled on the NIC before DHCP can be enabled for DNS server or domain name objects.

PWR8556.Description: The Server identified in the message was shutdown due to insufficient power.
PWR8556.Message: Server %1 was shutdown due to insufficient power.

UEFI0101.Description: The total amount of installed memory has exceeded the amount supported by the platform.
UEFI0101.Resolution: Remove memory modules from the system to reduce the total amount of installed memory. For more information on installed memory limit, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0101.Message: Total amount of installed memory has exceeded limit.

LIC009.Description: An upgrade license carries specific information about the license it is replacing. If that information does not match, then the license import is aborted.
LIC009.Resolution: Obtain a new license file with the correct upgrade information.

PDR16.Description: The physical disk is predicted to fail. Many physical disks contain Self Monitoring Analysis and Reporting Technology (SMART). When enabled, SMART monitors the disk health based on indications such as the number of write operations that were performed on the disk.
PDR16.Resolution: Replace the physical disk. Even though the disk may not have failed yet, it is strongly recommended that the disk be replaced. Review other messages for additional information.

OSE1006.Description: The system has successfully booted to diagnostics.

RAC031.Description: The operation cannot be completed because an incorrect username is entered.
RAC031.Resolution: Enter a valid username and retry the operation.
RAC031.Message: Unable to complete the operation because an incorrect username is entered.

SYS149.Description: Initiating iDRAC reset to defaults operation because of a System Erase operation. The iDRAC will restart after firmware default values are restored.
SYS149.Message: The process of resetting iDRAC to default settings is initiated.

CTL115.Description: Operation cannot be completed as key mismatch was detected.
CTL115.Resolution: Resolve encryption key mismatch using controller security related operations like creating security key,modifying security key or delete security key and then retry operation.
CTL115.Message: Unable to do any Secure Drive related operations as keymismatch was detected between peers controller.

VF046.Description: File transfer was not successful. This could be because of network problems or an operational problem with the file server.
VF046.Resolution: Try the download again. If the issue persists, validate that the network share is operational.
VF046.Message: HTTP download operation was not successful.

SWC1928.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-write mode.
SWC1928.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the read-write mode.

SYS084.Description: Export of ePSA Diagnostics results did not complete successfully because the iDRAC internal storage containing the results could not be accessed.
SYS084.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Delete all jobs, 2) Reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and 3) Retry the operation.
SYS084.Message: Export of ePSA Diagnostics results did not complete successfully because the iDRAC internal storage containing the results could not be accessed.

RED070.Description: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup schedule due to invalid input parameters.
RED070.Resolution: Verify the input parameters to the set Automatic Backup schedule method are correct and retry the operation.
RED070.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup schedule.

UEFI0000.Description: A CPU type 0x00, divide by zero exception, (type 0x00) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment. The software attempted to do a mathematical divide by zero, an illegal operation.
UEFI0000.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception.Update or remove the hardware or software.
UEFI0000.Message: CPU Exception Type 0x00: Divide by Zero (Software).

RAC0909.Description: The specified command is missing object name syntax.
RAC0909.Resolution: Specify the correct subcommand object name syntax. See the help text or documentation for valid syntax.
RAC0909.Message: Invalid subcommand syntax: Specify the object name.

BAR029.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware and configuration import is in progress.
BAR029.Message: Restoring Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

PWR8528.Description: The Max Power Conservation Mode can be enabled only when Server Based Power Management Mode is disabled.
PWR8528.Resolution: The Max Power Conservation Mode can be changed when Server Based Power Management mode is disabled. Using the CMC Web UI, navigate to the Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration page, then uncheck the Enable Server Based Power Management checkbox. Retry the operation.
PWR8528.Message: Unable to set Max Power Conservation Mode because the Server Based Power Management mode is enabled.

IOV104.Description: For each adapter assigned to a server, power is allocated when the server is turned on. If the available power is less than the required power, the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) will not power on the adapters associated with the server.
IOV104.Resolution: Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM command line interface, run the command "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerCap <Power cap>" to increase the power cap or add an additional power supply.
IOV104.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to allocate %1 Watt for server-%2 PCIe adapters.

BAT0011.Resolution: Verify the battery installation, check the system logs for thermal related issues.
BAT0011.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is operating normally.

SWC0242.Description: The license is missing or expired. This will result in the loss of functionality that is specific to the features supported by the license.
SWC0242.Resolution: Import an appropriate license to iDRAC. If you do not know which license to install, contact your service provider.
SWC0242.Message: A required license is missing or expired. Obtain an appropriate license and try again, or contact your service provider for additional details.

TMP0133.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0133.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0133.Message: The control panel temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

CTL39.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC0117.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.
SWC0117.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertdownload subcommand.
SWC0117.Message: Invalid syntax. Both -f and -t must be specified.

RAC0140.Description: The firmware update process returned an 'Update Failed' status.
RAC0140.Resolution: Try the firmware update again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, try uploading the firmware through another interface such as Web GUI, RACADM, or DUPs.

VFL0708.Message: SD card is busy with another operation and could not be initialized.

BIOS013.Description: An unknown AttributeName was specified in the operation.
BIOS013.Resolution: Enter the correct AttributeName available in the system. Refer to the enumeration response for desired attribute.

HWC5031.Description: The CMC has powered off the IOM.
HWC5031.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

OSD26.Description: Unable to continue with BootToPXE command because another process is using Lifecycle Controller.
OSD26.Resolution: See ConcreteJob status to make sure that the running process is complete, and then run BootToPXE.
OSD26.Message: Unable to continue with BootToPXE - another command is running.

UEFI0028.Description: The iDRAC is not responding after a recovery system reset was performed. BIOS will continue POST startup with iDRAC in a non functional state.
UEFI0028.Resolution: Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system.
UEFI0028.Message: iDRAC is not responding after a recovery system reset was performed.

PWR8684.Description: The storage sled controller in the slot identified in the message turned on successfully.
PWR8684.Message: Storage sled controller %1 in slot %2 turned on successfully.

PST0000.Description: The BIOS provided a progress code to the iDRAC, but that progress code is not recognized by the current iDRAC firmware.
PST0000.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the iDRAC firmware. 2) Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

TMP0118.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0118.Message: The system inlet temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

BIOS010.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G systems: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
BIOS010.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G systems: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.
BIOS010.Message: Lifecycle Controller is not enabled, cannot create Configuration job.

AMP0319.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes
AMP0319.Message: Chassis power level current is less than the lower critical threshold.

FC011.Description: Configuration job already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job is completed.
FC011.Resolution: Cancel the configuration job or wait for the job to complete. Refer to documentation on job cancellation.
FC011.Message: Configuration job already created, pending data cannot be deleted

SWC0241.Description: To modify this property, set the Power Cap Enable option.
SWC0241.Resolution: Set the Power Cap Enable object and modify the required property.
SWC0241.Message: Power Cap Enable not set. Unable to modify this property

RAC0105.Description: Communication with the Smart Card reader cannot be established, or is lost.
RAC0105.Resolution: This error may occur because:1. Check connection between reader and system.2. There may be an issue with the Smart Card reader. Try reinstalling the reader driver or use a different reader.
RAC0105.Message: The Smart Card reader cannot be detected. Check whether the reader is installed correctly.

SEL1208.Message: A platform event filter action was executed.

OSD65.Description: The ISO file is successfully attached. The next host reboot is scheduled to boot to the ISO file.
OSD65.Message: The ISO file is successfully attached. The next host reboot is scheduled to boot to the ISO file.

PWR8503.Description: This Information is provided to enable checking whether the powercap is lower than the maximum supported powercap limit.
PWR8503.Message: The current value of System Input Power Cap (%1W AC) is less than the upper limit (%1W AC).

SWC0102.Description: The option requested is not available on the interface being used.
SWC0102.Resolution: Refer to the help to get the list of options valid for the interface.
SWC0102.Message: The -m option is not supported by the interface being used.

UEFI0199.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Write Level Fine Training phase.
UEFI0199.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0199.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

CPU0803.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0803.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0803.Message: The power input for CPU %1 voltage regulator module is lost.

HWC4011.Resolution: Check presence, re-install or reconnect, then re-attempt the update. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC4011.Message: Hardware unsuccessfully updated for mezzanine card %1.

HWC2003.Description: The cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC2003.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC2003.Message: The storage %1 cable is not connected, or is improperly connected.

VF037.Description: The attaching partition operation did not complete successfully.
VF037.Message: Attach partition operation did not complete successfully.

RAC0765.Description: The OS IP address cannot be accessed by using the Ping process because an incorrect IP address is entered.
RAC0765.Resolution: Enter a correct IP address, and then retry the operation.
RAC0765.Message: Unable to access the operating system (OS) IP address by using the Ping process because an incorrect IP address is entered.

USR105.Description: The user account used as credentials to access iDRAC is not enabled or configured to perform the operation.
USR105.Resolution: Retry the operation after creating the user account.

RAC0516.Description: Converting physical disk drives to RAID-compatible will overwrite any OS-created RAID arrays.
RAC0516.Resolution: Make sure that there are no OS-configured RAID arrays, and then click OK.
RAC0516.Message: Converting physical disk drives to RAID-compatible will overwrite any OS-created RAID arrays.

MEM8500.Description: A low memory condition was detected. If this condition continues, a failover or a reset may occur. If multiple resets occur, contact your service provider.
MEM8500.Resolution: If multiple resets occur, contact Service.

STOR090.Description: Unable to create a virtual disk because an invalid combination of span count or disks passed was entered for the RAID level selected.
STOR090.Resolution: Enter a span count value (-sc option) or number of disks (-pdkey option) that is appropriate for the RAID level selected. See the PERC Controller Users Guide for valid span count and number of disks required for a raid level. Retry the operation by running the RACADM storage createvd command with the appropriate options.
STOR090.Message: Unable to create a virtual disk because an invalid combination of span count or number of disks was entered for the RAID level selected.

CTL18.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL18.Message: Load Balance and Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.

PSU8508.Description: Unable to set the Power configuration because the PSU firmware update is in progress.
PSU8508.Resolution: Retry the operation after the PSU firmware update is completed.
PSU8508.Message: %1, PSU%2 firmware update is in progress.

RAC0292.Description: This error is displayed when LDAP or Active Directory cannot find its certificate.
RAC0292.Message: A valid certificate is not loaded.

BAT1019.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

VF012.Description: There is no SD card detected.

DIS004.Description: The Auto Discovery process has timed out and stopped. The Auto Discovery process runs for 24 hours from the initial system power on or re-initialization request. Every 90 seconds the Auto Discovery client will attempt to identify and contact the Provisioning Server during this period.
DIS004.Resolution: Check for previous messages in the Lifecycle Controller Log that provide more specific information why the timeout occurred.
DIS004.Message: Auto Discovery 24-hour timeout occurred. Stopping Auto Discovery process.

NIC100.Description: The network link is down. Either the network cable is not connected or the network device is not working.
NIC100.Resolution: Verify that the network port is enabled and if the port has Activity/Speed LEDs, that they are lit. Check the network cable, network cable connections, and the attached network switch.
NIC100.Message: The %1 Port %2 network link is down.

SWC0702.Description: Power capping is disabled and sets recommended limits for the system.

RED029.Description: This task will reboot the system at the scheduled start time.

SWC0277.Description: The syntax for the config command is invalid.
SWC0277.Resolution: Refer to the help text for the 'config' subcommand.
SWC0277.Message: Invalid syntax. The -i option is only valid with -g and -o.

PDR116.Description: The PCIe Solid-State Drive is predicted to fail. Many physical disks contain Self Monitoring Analysis and Reporting Technology (SMART). When enabled, SMART monitors the disk health based on indications such as the number of write operations that were performed on the disk.
PDR116.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.

HWC8510.Description: The heat sinks of the PCIe switches are properly attached.
HWC8510.Message: The heat sinks of the PCIe switches are properly attached.

SYS157.Description: Unable to successfully complete requested options of the System Erase operation. Retrying the System Erase operation may be required.
SYS157.Resolution: Retry the System Erase operation. To retry the System Erase operation using the Lifecycle Controller utility, restart the server and when the company logo is displayed, press <F10>. Select Hardware Configuration > Retire or Repurpose System, check appropriate options, and then retry the operation. Also disable "F1/F2 Prompt on Error" in BIOS settings for System Erase operation to continue without intervention.
SYS157.Message: Unable to successfully complete requested System Erase tasks.

UEFI0271.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the network connection to DHCPv6 server is not established.
UEFI0271.Resolution: Check the network cable connection of the initiator or the DHCPv6 server and retry the operation.
UEFI0271.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the network connection to DHCPv6 server is not established.

DIS016.Description: Provisioning Server responded to iDRAC IP address change.
DIS016.Message: Response received from Provisioning Server to the notification of iDRAC IP address change.

UEFI0035.Description: The BIOS passwords are disabled because the PWRD_EN jumper is removed from the system board.
UEFI0035.Resolution: To enable the BIOS passwords, install the PWRD_EN jumper.
UEFI0035.Message: The BIOS passwords are disabled because the PWRD_EN jumper is removed from the system board.

SWC0251.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0251.Resolution: Enter the index value as specified by the message.
SWC0251.Message: Invalid index value. Only index values %1 - %1 are permitted.

USR8512.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.
USR8512.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct. Retry the operation with valid credentials.

UEFI0166.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because the number of allowable Target Address Decode (TAD) rules exceeded during memory initialization.
UEFI0166.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0166.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

CMC8573.Description: The chassis health is critical or non-recoverable.
CMC8573.Resolution: Review the Chassis log or the Chassis Management Controller(CMC) SEL log for the failure or Export chassis log and SEL log and contact technical support .

RAC0218.Description: A maximum of 4 iDRAC Web GUI sessions can be open at any time.
RAC0218.Resolution: Close one or more sessions before opening another session.
RAC0218.Message: The maximum number of user sessions is reached.

OSD75.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'HashType' is invalid.
OSD75.Resolution: Check the value provided for input parameter "HashType" and retry the operation.
OSD75.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'HashType' is invalid.

PCI3010.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next service window.
PCI3010.Message: A non-fatal IO error detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

ENC27.Description: The enclosure cannot support both SAS and SATA physical disks. Physical disks may be disabled. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
ENC27.Message: SAS or SATA mixing of physical disks is not supported within the %1.

JCP029.Description: Only one Job of the JobType requested can be created or scheduled at any time. A job of the same type already exists in the job queue.
JCP029.Resolution: Wait until the existing job is complete or delete the existing job and then retry the operation.
JCP029.Message: A Job of JobType %1 already exists.

TMP0128.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0128.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0128.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is outside of range.

RAC1007.Description: The job specified in the message cannot be deleted when it is Running, Scheduled, or transitioning from Downloading to Scheduled.
RAC1007.Resolution: Wait until the specified job is completed, or reboot the system to move the job to Completed state. To view the job status, use"racadm jobqueue view -i <Job_ID>".

SWC8506.Description: The Profile identified in the message has been deleted.

BAR093.Description: The attempt to disconnect from the specified CIFS location was not successful.
BAR093.Resolution: If this happens on a backup request, restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller and try the operation again. If this is a restore request the Integrated Remote Access will be restarted during the execution of the request. Only restart the Integrated Remote Access Controller if it does not restart on its own.

PWR2212.Message: The system is in legacy OFF state.

UEFI0116.Description: One or more boot drivers have reported issue(s) via the UEFI Driver Health Protocol.
UEFI0116.Resolution: Check the Driver Health Menu in Boot Manager for details.
UEFI0116.Message: One or more boot drivers have reported issue(s).

ISM0011.Description: The server OS could not start the iDRAC Service Module, because the iDRAC Service Module disabled on iDRAC.
ISM0011.Resolution: Enable the iDRAC Service Module on the iDRAC before starting this service on the server OS, and then retry the operation. To enable the module by using iDRAC GUI: Click Network, click OS to iDRAC Pass-through, and then click the USB NIC option. In the OS IP Address box , type an IP address, and then click Apply. To enable the module by using RACADM command, run the following command at the command line interface: racadm set idrac.servicemodule. ServiceModuleEnable enabled
ISM0011.Message: The server operating system (OS) is unable to start the iDRAC Service Module, because it is set to "disabled" in iDRAC.

SWC1905.Description: RAC Virtual Console configuration has been changed.
SWC1905.Message: RAC Virtual Console configuration has been changed.

RAC0230.Description: This message is displayed when a confirmation is required to initialize the vFlash SD Card.
RAC0230.Resolution: Press OK to initialize the SD Card. This will erase all data. If undesired press Cancel.
RAC0230.Message: This operation erases all data in the SD Card. Do you want to continue?

VLT0300.Description: Low voltages may be the result of a problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. The low voltage may cause the processor to fail to operate.
VLT0300.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0300.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

CTL42.Description: An attempt to hot plug an Enclosure Management Module (EMM) has been detected.
CTL42.Resolution: If the new enclosure and its device are not detected by the operating system, try restarting your system to verify the newly attached enclosure and its sub-components are detected. See the hardware documentation for more information.
CTL42.Message: Enclosure Management Module (EMM) hot plug is not supported on %1.

BAR036.Description: A system profile import did not complete successfully and has left the system in an unusable state. Attempting to setup the environment for normal operation.
BAR036.Message: System Reset or Lifecycle Controller Actions Canceled, System Profile Failure Recovery initiated.

VF040.Description: The downloaded image did not successfully complete the hash verification.
VF040.Resolution: Try the download again. If this issue persists, check the network connectivity.
VF040.Message: Image hash verification was not successful.

PSU0904.Description: In order to meet service requirements the supply must be shut down.
PSU0904.Resolution: Remove input power at the power supply.
PSU0904.Message: Could not power down 240VA on power unit %1.

SYS042.Description: The requested component configuration successfully completed.

BAT1000.Description: The controller cannot communicate with the battery. The battery is absent or improperly connected. A battery with a weak or depleted charge may also cause this message.
BAT1000.Resolution: Verify that the device is present and then check the cables. See the storage hardware documentation to verify cabling. In addition check the connection to the controller battery and the battery health. A battery with a weak or depleted charge may cause this message.

RAC999.Description: DNSFromDHCP6 cannot be enabled if iDRAC IPv6 AutoConfig is disabled.
RAC999.Resolution: Enable IPv6 AutoConfig using "racadm set iDRAC.IPv6.AutoConfig < 1 | Enabled >" command, and retry the operation.
RAC999.Message: The object DNSFromDHCP6 cannot be enabled.

RAC0207.Description: Certificate upload failed possibly due to poor network connection.
RAC0207.Resolution: Try the operation again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, issue a new Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and try again.

TMP0137.Description: The system cooling is working normally.
TMP0137.Message: The system cooling is working normally.

SWC4005.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between iDRAC in slot %1 and CMC.

VDR6.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

CMC8572.Description: The coin cell battery in the CMC located in the slot specified in the message is not working. The battery needs to be replaced.
CMC8572.Resolution: Replace the coin cell battery of the standby CMC
CMC8572.Message: The coin cell battery in CMC %1 is not working.

PDR1024.Description: The installed disk does not meet the array requirements, for example a SATA disk may not operate in an array containing SAS drives.
PDR1024.Resolution: Verify the disk meets the array requirements.
PDR1024.Message: Drive mismatch detected for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

HWC4001.Message: A hardware incompatibility was corrected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and CPU.

UEFI0168.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because a negative Target Address Decode (TAD) offset was calculated during memory initialization.
UEFI0168.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0168.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

RAC0608.Description: The message appears in Job Queue page when the iDRAC firmware update job status is downloading. Communication to the iDRAC will be lost when the iDRAC restarts to complete the firmware update.
RAC0608.Resolution: Reconnect iDRAC communications session after iDRAC is restarted. The iDRAC will be ready for login once the restart is complete.
RAC0608.Message: The iDRAC will restart when the iDRAC firmware update is complete. All current user sessions will be closed.

RAC0801.Description: iDRAC closes all the existing sessions and all configuration settings are set to default values. The iDRAC IP address is set to the default static IP address.
RAC0801.Message: iDRAC has reset to default settings.

STOR311.Description: A drive firmware update was applied but requires a DC power cycle (cold boot) to activate. If the drive is internal to the system performing the update, no further action is required. If the drive is in an external enclosure, the enclosure must be turned off and then turned on in order for the updated drive firmware to activate.
STOR311.Resolution: If the drive is internal to the system performing the update, no further action is required. If the drive is in an external enclosure, the enclosure must be turned off and then turned on in order for the updated drive firmware to activate. After turning off the external enclosure, wait for drives to spin down before turning the enclosure back on. The drive firmware will activate after the enclosure is turned back on.
STOR311.Message: A firmware update was applied to a drive that requires a DC power cycle (cold boot). If the drive is in an external enclosure, the updated firmware will only be activated after a DC power cycle of the enclosure.

RAC0116.Description: The entered IPv6 address does not conform to the addressing standard or the supported IPv6 address range.
RAC0116.Resolution: Enter a valid Destination IPv6 Address.

MEM9012.Description: BIOS logged the major and minor code of a Memory Reference Code (MRC) warning. This information can be reviewed by using a tool which displays raw IPMI SEL data such as IPMIitool with the -vvv option or RACADM with the -E option.
MEM9012.Message: A Memory Reference Code (MRC) warning code is logged.

SWC0266.Description: The SD card may not be inserted/inserted properly.
SWC0266.Resolution: Ensure that the SD card is inserted in the server.
SWC0266.Message: Unable to perform the requested operation. Make sure SD card is inserted.

USR8504.Description: The IP range filter feature is enabled in CMC. The IP address from where the login attempt was made is not in the specified range of IP address that can access the CMC.
USR8504.Resolution: If access needs to be given to this specified IP address, change the IP range address and IP range mask accordingly and retry the operation.
USR8504.Message: The IP address specified is out of range.

VLT0216.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0216.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0216.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is outside of range.

UEFI0141.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This situation is caused by missing LC files.
UEFI0141.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0141.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

PR9.Description: The Part Replacement feature started the firmware update process based on Part Firmware Update attribute settings.

OSE1004.Description: The system OS has successfully booted from the PXE server.

RED056.Description: An internal error occurred because of insufficient memory available on iDRAC.
RED056.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation.
RED056.Message: An internal error occurred. Unable to complete the specified operation.

RAC0764.Description: Selecting a higher SSL encryption enhances the security. However, the cryptography settings for your virtual machine environment (JVM, IcedTea) may require installing the Unlimited Strength Java Cryptography Extension Policy Files to permit usage of iDRAC plugins such as vConsole with this higher level of encryption.NOTE: Using this level of encryption may have import or export implications. For more guidance, contact your legal department.
RAC0764.Message: Selecting a higher SSL encryption enhances the security. However, the cryptography settings for your virtual machine environment (JVM, IcedTea) may require installing the Unlimited Strength Java Cryptography Extension Policy Files to permit usage of iDRAC plugins such as vConsole with this higher level of encryption.NOTE: Using this level of encryption may have import or export implications. For more guidance, contact your legal department.

RED079.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the parameter identified in the message.
RED079.Resolution: Verify the value for the parameter identified in the message is valid and retry the operation.
RED079.Message: The input value entered for the parameter %1 is invalid.

RAC1118.Description: Successfully initiated the update operation specified in the command.
RAC1118.Resolution: To know about the status of a command that is initiated, run the following command:racadm jobqueue view -I <job ID>.
RAC1118.Message: Successfully initiated the update operation specified in the command.

MEM1001.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem continues, contact support.
MEM1001.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to transition to a running state.

SYS014.Description: The value provided for the identified attribute is invalid.
SYS014.Resolution: For more information, refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and provide a valid value for the identified attribute.

CTL103.Description: The Check Consistency Mode value of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL103.Message: The Check Consistency Mode value of %1 is set to %2.

BAR085.Description: The validation of the system profile backup file has failed. The retrieval of system information to validate the backup file has failed.
BAR085.Resolution: Restart the remote access controller, and retry the operation. If the error continues, use the remote access controller firmware to try the operation again.
BAR085.Message: Unable to collect System Information for Import Backup file validation.

SWC0060.Description: One or more vFlash partitions are attached.
SWC0060.Resolution: Use iDRAC Web interface to detach the vFlash partitions and retry the operation.

TMP0103.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0103.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0103.Message: The system board %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SWU8546.Description: The firmware update operation of the Standby CMC was not successful.
SWU8546.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware.

SYS161.Description: The Tech Support Report related data have been deleted from iDRAC non-volatile storage.
SYS161.Message: Tech Support Report related non-volatile storage deleted.

POW003.Description: Host failed to power up because PCI/Mezz cards not installed in Fabric1/Fabric2.This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2253
POW003.Message: Power on permission error, no PCI/Mezz card installed in Fabric1/Fabric2

RED082.Description: The Automatic Update or Automatic Backup feature is disabled.
RED082.Resolution: Enable the correct job schedule type, and then retry the operation. For example, to enable the Automatic Update feature, select the Enable Automatic Update option.
RED082.Message: The requested job cannot be scheduled, because job schedule type such as Automatic Backup or Automatic Update is not enabled.

CTL113.Description: The encryption key for the controller identified in the message does not match its peer.
CTL113.Resolution: Resolve key mismatch by configuring same encryption keys on both the controllers.
CTL113.Message: %1 is operating in Degraded Fault Tolerant Mode because of encryption key setting mismatch with its peer controller.

UEFI0190.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Clock DCC Training phase.
UEFI0190.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0190.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RAC1073.Description: The threshold value of the sensor identified in the message cannot be successfully set because the capability reset the sensor threshold value is not supported.
RAC1073.Resolution: No response action is required. For more information about resetting the threshold level of a sensor, run the "racadm getsensorinfo" command at the command line interface (CLI), and then retry the operation.
RAC1073.Message: Unable to reset the threshold value of sensor %1 because the capability to reset this sensor threshold value is not supported.

SUP0104.Description: The source path needs to be lesser than 64 characters.

SWC0260.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0260.Resolution: Refer the list of objects in the corresponding group.

LC022.Description: The Lifecycle Controller Log was successfully exported to the destination specified.
LC022.Message: Lifecycle Controller Log Export was successful.

STOR074.Description: The requested RAID configuration operation will not be allowed because the RAID controller is currently in HBA mode.
STOR074.Resolution: In order to perform a RAID configuration operation, change the controller mode to RAID and retry the operation. For switching to RAID mode using the F2 System Setup utility, go to Device Settings > "RAID Controller "> Controller Management > Advanced Controller Management > Switch to RAID mode.
STOR074.Message: The requested RAID configuration operation is not allowed because the controller is currently in HBA mode.

RAC979.Description: The custom signing certificate was extracted from the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file and applied to the system configuration.
RAC979.Message: Successfully uploaded the custom signing certificate to iDRAC.

RAC016.Description: The method cannot be run because an invalid attribute name is entered.
RAC016.Resolution: Enter a valid attribute name and retry the operation.
RAC016.Message: Unable to run the method because an invalid attribute name is entered.

UEFI0050.Message: The process of collecting Brand information is started.

PWR8582.Description: Unable to turn on the server identified in the message because the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) is enabled. After MPCM is enabled, the chassis will be in power conservation mode and the CMC cannot process any further server power on operation requests.
PWR8582.Resolution: Disable the Max Power Conservation Mode and retry the operation.
PWR8582.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because Max Power Conservation Mode is enabled.

SWC0012.Description: The operation to retrieve the front panel security settings encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0012.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0012.Message: Unable to retrieve the front panel security settings.

USR0013.Description: The user does not have sufficient privileges to execute the command.
USR0013.Message: Insufficient user privileges to perform operation.

IOID113.Description: The initiator properties of the NIC port could not be configured because either iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is not enabled, or the network controller is not functioning.
IOID113.Resolution: Make sure that the iSCSI or FCoE partition of the network port is enabled. Check whether or not the network controller is working and then retry the operation.
