IOID113.Message: Unable to configure the initiator properties of %1 Port %2.

VDR19.Description: The reconfiguration operation was not completed. This may be due to a user action or a physical disk failure.
VDR19.Resolution: Recreate the virtual disk and restore data from a backup copy.

STOR0110.Description: The specified Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDDs) system component name is invalid.
STOR0110.Resolution: Verify that the correct Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) system component name is specified. See the help text (The help text for the raid subcommand can be obtained by running "racadm help raid") or documentation for valid FQDD system component names.

VLT0209.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0209.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0209.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PCI3002.Description: Either the BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, LOM, or NIC firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3002.Resolution: Update BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, LOM, and mezzanine card firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3002.Message: Failed to program virtual MAC address on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

SWC4012.Description: The system has detected a firmware or software incompatibility between the components identified in the message. A mismatch between component versions may cause the system to not function appropriately.
SWC4012.Resolution: Update the firmware or software of the components identified in the message. For information about the identified components, see the product documentation available at the service provider support site.
SWC4012.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility is detected between %1%2 and %3%4.

PST0006.Description: System BIOS has started initialization multiprocessor support.

SWU8500.Description: This message is displayed when:1. A reboot job is unable to provide a valid reboot ID.2. The WSMAN command to set up a job queue on Lifecycle Controller was not successful.
SWU8500.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the error persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8500.Message: The %1 request to Lifecycle Controller on server %2 was not successful.

PWR8521.Description: The chassis reset operation was completed.

SWU8531.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful, because the Update process was not completed within the firmware update timeout duration.
SWU8531.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware. The firmware update timeout limit is exceeded.

IOID114.Description: The target setting properties of the NIC port identified in the message are successfully configured.
IOID114.Message: The target settings properties of the %1 Port %2 are successfully configured.

CMC8545.Description: A firmware error has occurred causing a CMC failover. The process identified in the message was not detected. The CMC will restart automatically.
CMC8545.Resolution: No response action is required. If multiple failovers occur, contact your service provider.
CMC8545.Message: Detected a missing process failover condition detected. Process = %1.

RAC0660.Description: The file server cannot be accessed because of incorrect credentials.
RAC0660.Resolution: Check the file server credentials and retry the operation.
RAC0660.Message: Unable to access the specified file server location.

STOR1.Description: The controller cannot communicate with a device. The state of the device cannot be determined. There may be a bad or loose cable, or a missing device, or a problem with the driver or firmware.
STOR1.Resolution: See the storage hardware documentation for information on checking the cables. Check for problems with any enclosures attached to the system. Verify that the controller has a supported version of the driver and firmware. Rebooting the system may resolve this problem.
STOR1.Message: A device %1 is in an unknown state.

SYS059.Description: Configuration changes for the component identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) were successfully applied.
SYS059.Resolution: No response action is required. See Lifecycle Log for details.

RFM1021.Description: The removable flash media is installed but improperly configured or failed to initialize.
RFM1021.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.
RFM1021.Message: Removable Flash Media is not IPMI-function ready.

LOG510.Description: The operation cannot be completed because of an unknown issue.
LOG510.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset CMC and then retry the operation.
LOG510.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of an unknown issue in the CMC.

RAC1191.Description: The file import operation has failed because of large file size.
RAC1191.Resolution: The file import operation has timed out, because the file is invalid or is exceeding the permissible size. Retry the operation with a valid file.
RAC1191.Message: Unable to import the specified file to iDRAC.

BAR016.Description: A system profile import operation has been requested.

SWU8559.Description: The firmware downgrade operation is unsuccessful. A downgrade to the firmware version uploaded is not supported.
SWU8559.Resolution: Refer to the platform Owner's Manual for more information or contact your service provider.
SWU8559.Message: The firmware downgrade operation is unsuccessful. A downgrade to the firmware version uploaded is not supported.

ENC24.Description: The controller is not receiving a consistent response from the enclosure. There could be a firmware problem or an invalid cabling configuration. If the cables are too long, they degrade the signal.
ENC24.Resolution: Power down all enclosures attached to the system and reboot . If the problem persists, upgrade the firmware to the latest supported version. Verify the cable configuration is valid. See the storage hardware documentation for valid cabling configurations.

STOR027.Description: Setting the Virtual disk name is not a valid operation on the specified controller.
STOR027.Resolution: Do not specify the virtual disk name and retry the operation.
STOR027.Message: Virtual Disk name is not supported.

PWR8687.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the storage sled controller installed on the server in the slot identified in the message because the server does not have a Mezzanine card. A Mezzanine card position is identified with the following numbers: For quarter-width server, the position number is 1. For half-width server mezzanine C & B maps to position numbers 1 & 2 respectively. For full-width server, Mezzanine C & B on the upper- or left part of the server maps to position numbers 1 & 2 respectively. Mezzanine C & B on the lower- or right part of the server maps to position numbers 3 & 4 respectively.
PWR8687.Resolution: Install a Mezzanine card in the Mezzanine card slot of the server identified in the message, and then retry the operation.
PWR8687.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the storage sled controller installed on server in slot %1 because the server does not have a Mezzanine card.

PWR202.Description: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature forces servers in to a low-power and limited-performance mode, and then disables the ability to turn on additional servers.
PWR202.Message: Enabling the Max Power Conservation Mode (MPCM) feature forces servers in to a low-power and limited-performance mode, and then disables the ability to turn on additional servers.

RAC0127.Description: Size must be a whole number.
RAC0127.Resolution: Enter a whole number for the size field.
RAC0127.Message: The specified size must be a non-fractional numeric value.

BAR009.Description: The vFlash media is not present on the system.
BAR009.Resolution: Insert the appropriate vFlash media in the designated vFlash portal, enable and initialize it, and retry.

JCP010.Description: The method invoked was successfully completed.

PSU0091.Description: The rating of the power supply unit identified in the message should not exceed system power distribution limits.
PSU0091.Resolution: Remove the power supply unit identified in the message and review server product documentation for appropriate configuration.
PSU0091.Message: Power supply unit %1 rating exceeds the system power distribution limits.

SYS148.Description: The BIOS is configured to reset to defaults on the next system restart because of a System Erase operation.
SYS148.Message: BIOS is configured to reset to defaults on next system restart.

USR0007.Description: <font face="Calibri" size="2">UserID closing session from IP Address.</font>

PDR88.Description: When physical drives in spun down power state are configured, the drives should transition to spun up power state.. If the drive is not functioning properly, this transition could fail.
PDR88.Resolution: Replace the physical disk and try again. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
PDR88.Message: Power state change failed on %1. (from %2 to %2)

SWC0101.Description: Racadm is unable to read the available log records at this point. Retry the command.
SWC0101.Message: Unable to read available log records.

RDU8500.Description: The CMC is identified in the message is active.

PWR2203.Message: The system is sleeping with system hardware and processor context lost.

PCI2000.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI2000.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device.
PCI2000.Message: A fatal IO error detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

CMC8529.Description: The user account does not have sufficient privileges to perform the requested operation. Server Administrator privilege is required to perform the requested action.
CMC8529.Resolution: Use a different user account that has Server Administrator privilege, and retry the operation. For more information, contact your system administrator or service provider.
CMC8529.Message: Unable to perform the requested action on the server-%1, because of insufficient privileges.

STOR023.Description: Unable to perform configuration operations because a configuration job for the device already exists.
STOR023.Resolution: Wait for the current job for the device to complete or cancel the current job before attempting more configuration operations on the device.
STOR023.Message: Unable to perform configuration operations because a configuration job for the device already exists.

SWC0306.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0306.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0306.Message: The -a option requires -g and -u to also be specified.

UEFI0244.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) links failed to come up to full operating frequency.
UEFI0244.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0244.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) links are operating in slow speed mode.

SWC8561.Description: Some or all or the specified MAC addresses are removed from the Virtual MAC Address Pool. Some MAC addresses could not be removed because they were not present.
SWC8561.Message: Some or all or the specified MAC addresses are removed from the Virtual MAC Address Pool of Boot Identity profile operations.

UEFI0206.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Command Clock Training - Group 1 phase.
UEFI0206.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0206.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

TMP1003.Resolution: Check whether the thermostat setting is too low and whether the room temperature is too cool.
TMP1003.Message: %1 has crossed the minimum failure threshold.

JCP013.Description: One or more required input parameters needed for the operation are missing.
JCP013.Resolution: Refer to the documentation for the operation being attempted and provide valid values for the identified parameters.

UEFI0119.Description: Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) RAID redundancy was lost. The system BIOS should have prompted the user for the rebuild process.
UEFI0119.Resolution: No additional response action is required if you have followed the instructions on the screen to start the rebuild process.
UEFI0119.Message: The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) RAID redundancy was lost.

TMP0116.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0116.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0116.Message: The %1 temperature is outside of range.

LC076.Description: Unable to perform the Custom Signed Certificate (CSC) certificate delete operation. This may be due to IPMI communications issues.
LC076.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation.
LC076.Message: Unable to perform the Custom Signed Certificate (CSC) certificate delete operation.

FAN1002.Description: The enclosure detected that a fan has failed and the enclosure is no longer functioning in optimal condition..

FC009.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage due to use by another application or operation.
FC009.Resolution: Wait for Lifecycle Controller to complete the current operation. Make sure that the system is: 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
FC009.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

BAT0005.Description: The system has to remain powered on to charge the battery.
BAT0005.Resolution: Allow the PERC RAID controller battery to charge. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

BAT0013.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is present.

LIC007.Description: Each License Manager object has a unique identifier by which it may be accessed. If the user supplied identifier is outside the acceptable range or the object no longer exists in the system, then this error is returned. Most common identifiers are the license entitlement identifier, the device Fully Qualified Device Descriptor, or the import transaction identifier assigned to a license when imported.
LIC007.Resolution: Re-issue this command with correct License Manager object identifier.
LIC007.Message: Invalid entry: Object does not exist or cannot be found.

UEFI0151.Description: A PERC storage adapter is installed in a slot identified by this message but the internal storage slot is empty This configuration is not supported.
UEFI0151.Resolution: Install a compatible storage adapter in the internal storage slot. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0151.Message: A PERC storage adapter is installed in %1 but the internal storage slot is empty. This configuration is not supported.

PWR2209.Message: The system is in an undermined sleep state.

LC038.Description: Lifecycle Controller is locked by another instance of the Hardware Inventory export process. Allow the process to complete before attempting another export operation.
LC038.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Rerun the command after about 2 minutes 2) Reset the iDRAC and rerun the command.
LC038.Message: An instance of Hardware Inventory export is already in progress.

RAC0601.Description: The server encountered an unexpected condition. This may be due to invalid JavaScript Object Notation.
RAC0601.Resolution: Wait for few minutes and refresh the page. If the problem persists, contact service provider.
RAC0601.Message: Unable to retrieve alert recurrence information.

LIC501.Description: The attempted action requires a valid license for certain advanced features installed in the system but the required license is missing or expired.
LIC501.Resolution: Obtain an appropriate license then try again. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC501.Message: A required license is missing or expired.

RAC993.Description: The job ID specified in the message was deleted.

PDR21.Description: A disk has received a SMART alert (predictive failure). The disk is likely to fail in the near future.
PDR21.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk will cause the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.

RAC959.Description: The content of the configuration XML file used for import is invalid because of incorrect modifications or content.
RAC959.Resolution: Correct the modifications to the configuration XML file to be imported or specify the correct file, and retry the operation. Check the Lifecycle Log for more details.
RAC959.Message: Invalid file used for configuration XML file import operation.

UEFI0084.Description: One or more PCI Parity errors (PERR) have occurred.
UEFI0084.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCI device that caused the PERR. Update the identified device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0084.Message: One or more PCI Parity errors (PERR) have occurred.

SWC8532.Description: The starting IP address specified cannot accommodate all the servers. The starting iDRAC IPv4 Address specifies the static IPv4 address of the iDRAC located in the first slot. The static IPv4 address of each subsequent iDRAC is calculated as a slot number increment of this IPv4 address.
SWC8532.Resolution: Make sure there are enough IPv4 addresses for all the iDRACs and then retry the operation.
SWC8532.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to set chassis assigned QuickDeploy IP addresses because the starting IP address cannot accommodate all iDRACs.

VF016.Description: The SD card is not writable.
VF016.Resolution: Check the write-protection tab of the SD card.

ASR0003.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate to the baseboard management controller (BMC). The system powered cycled per the configured setting.
ASR0003.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0003.Message: The watchdog timer power cycled the system.

SWU8545.Description: The firmware update operation of the Standby CMC was not successful.
SWU8545.Message: Unable to update the Standby CMC firmware.

STOR093.Description: The configuration operation cannot be performed because the controller is not available for import process.
STOR093.Resolution: Make sure an operation is not pending on the controller. If an operation is pending, wait for the operation to complete or cancel the pending operation and then retry the operation. Refer to the storage controller documentation for compatibility information.
STOR093.Message: Unable to run the configuration operation because the controller is not available for the import process.

PWR211.Description: The Fresh Air (FA) mode cannot be set because the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is enabled.
PWR211.Message: Unable to set the Fresh Air (FA) mode because the Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is enabled.

BOOT8500.Description: Unable to change the BIOS boot order for the server because of a broken communication between the CMC and iDRAC, or iDRAC is rebooting.
BOOT8500.Resolution: Reset iDRAC or wait until iDRAC reboots, and retry the operation.
BOOT8500.Message: Unable to change the BIOS boot order for the Server %1

RAC995.Description: The hardware inventory cannot be retrieved because another hardware inventory operation may already be in progress or due to an internal error whether or not Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) is enabled or disabled.
RAC995.Resolution: Another hardware inventory operation may already be in progress and must complete before retrying the operation. If no other hardware inventory operation was in progress, make sure to enable Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature, reboot the system, and retry the operation. If CSIOR is already enabled and no other hardware inventory operation was in progress, reboot the iDRAC using "racadm racreset" command and then retry the operation.
RAC995.Message: Unable to retrieve the hardware inventory.

ISM0014.Description: The feature identified in the message is disabled by using one of the iDRAC interfaces.

UEFI0016.Description: Unable to find a Lifecycle Controller partition. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0016.Resolution: Perform the following actions: 1)Reboot the system. 2) Press F2 during boot to enter System Setup. 3) Select iDRAC Settings then Lifecycle Controller. 4) Change Lifecycle Controller back to Enabled. If subsequent failures occur, press and hold the system ID button down for 15 seconds to reset the iDRAC. For more information on how to reset iDRAC, see iDRAC User's Guide.
UEFI0016.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible and is therefore in Recovery mode.

RAC1116.Description: The command could not be successfully run, because an incorrect "restart flag" value was entered in the command.
RAC1116.Resolution: Enter a correct flag value. The recommended values are "true" and "false". Make sure that you have entered the correct value, and then retry the operation.
RAC1116.Message: Unable to run the command, because the restart flag entered is incorrect.

LC031.Description: An internal error occurred while exporting the Hardware Inventory XML file.
LC031.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the command.
LC031.Message: Internal error occurred while exporting inventory.

PDR47.Description: The controller encountered an unrecoverable medium error when attempting to read a block on the physical disk and marked that block as invalid. If the controller encountered the unrecoverable medium error on a source physical disk during a rebuild or reconfigure operation, it punctures the corresponding block on the target physical disk. The invalid block clears on a write operation.
PDR47.Resolution: Back up the data from the disk. Start disk initialization and wait for it to complete, and then restore the data from a backup copy.
PDR47.Message: A block on %1 was punctured by the controller.

SWC0077.Description: iDRAC is unable to initiate the Repurpose or Retire System operation because the iDRAC is not responding or another operation is in progress.
SWC0077.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do one the following: 1) Check if there are other operations running on the iDRAC and wait for the operations to complete, and retry the operation. 2) Restart the server, and retry the operation.
SWC0077.Message: Unable to initiate the Repurpose or Retire System operation.

STOR0501.Description: Unable to create a virtual disk due to unknown reasons.
STOR0501.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation:1) Exit the RAID Configuration wizard.2) Update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version.3) Reboot the system and press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.

PDR104.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message has turned off because the critical temperature threshold of the device was exceeded.
PDR104.Message: The %1 has turned off because the critical temperature threshold is exceeded.

UEFI0034.Description: A CMOS battery loss is detected resulting in an invalid BIOS configuration.
UEFI0034.Resolution: Go to the System Setup to configure system settings, system time and date.
UEFI0034.Message: A CMOS battery loss is detected resulting in an invalid BIOS configuration.

PWR8587.Description: The server cannot be turned on if the chassis enclosure is open.
PWR8587.Resolution: The chassis enclosure is open. Retry the operation after closing the enclosure.
PWR8587.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because the chassis enclosure is open.

VFL0711.Description: An error occurred while initializing the SD card because the SD card write-protection feature is enabled.
VFL0711.Resolution: Move the SD card write-protection tab to the disabled position and try again.
VFL0711.Message: SD card is write-protected and could not be initialized.

PCI5007.Description: The 3.3 Volt Regulator power related issue of PCIe carrier present in the slot identified in the message is resolved.
PCI5007.Message: The auxiliary power-related issue of the PCIe adapter in slot %1 is resolved.

RED064.Description: A scheduled Update from Repository completed and no applicable updates were found.
RED064.Message: The scheduled Update from Repository job completed successfully. Applicable updates were not found.

OSE1005.Resolution: Review system boot configuration, local PXE configuration, and PXE server configuration

CTL107.Description: The Rebuild Rate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL107.Message: The Rebuild Rate of %1 is set to %2.

SWC8508.Resolution: Check if iDRAC is ready and system is running properly. Utilize the RACADM command by running "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until it becomes ready. A Virtual Reseat may be required.
SWC8508.Message: Unable to capture Profile from server in slot %1

UEFI0057.Description: The MCE is logged during Power-on-Self-Test (POST). MCE could have occurred during either the current or the previous POST.
UEFI0057.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify Machine-Check Exception (MCE) event source. Resolve the issue identified in the SEL that caused the MCE. For further information, contact your service provider.
UEFI0057.Message: A Machine-Check Exception (MCE) error has occurred.

PSU1001.Description: The enclosure detected that a power supply unit has failed.
PSU1001.Resolution: Check for other messages related to the state of the power supply unit/enclosure. These may help determine the cause of this event. Contact technical support if the issue still persists.

VLT0302.Description: High voltages may be the result of problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. Elevated voltages may result in damage to the processor or other electronic components inside the system.
VLT0302.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0302.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

SYS156.Description: The requested component erase tasks of the System Erase operation is successfully completed.
SYS156.Message: Erase operations for System Erase tasks successfully completed.

PSU0080.Description: The system does not support mixed voltage power supplies.
PSU0080.Resolution: Review product documentation, change power supply with correct voltage rating.
PSU0080.Message: Power supply %1 voltage rating does not match the system's requirements.

PSU8518.Description: The operation to read the FRU data from the PSU identified in the message did not complete successfully due to internal communication errors.
PSU8518.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the condition persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8518.Message: Unable to access the PSU %1 FRU data.

RAC0276.Description: If the Enable NIC checkbox is cleared, remote access to iDRAC is disabled.
RAC0276.Message: To save the changes and update this page, click Apply.

SWC0265.Description: The option requested is not available on the DRAC being used.
SWC0265.Resolution: Refer to the help to get the list of commands/options valid for the DRAC.
SWC0265.Message: This option is not supported on this type of DRAC.

BAR034.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller(iDRAC) firmware import did not complete successfully.
BAR034.Resolution: Download the firmware for the Integrated Remote Access Controller(iDRAC) and apply it.
BAR034.Message: Unable to Restore Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

RAC0128.Description: A non-specific error has been detected while accessing the vFlash.
RAC0128.Resolution: Try the operation again in a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC before trying the operation again.
RAC0128.Message: An error has occurred in vFlash.

ENC2.Description: An Enclosure Management Module (EMM) was removed.
ENC2.Resolution: Reinsert the Enclosure Management Module (EMM). See the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the EMM.

RAC0268.Description: The NIC is disabled. This may adversely affect the current operation, and might not allow subsequent GUI interactions to this NIC.
RAC0268.Resolution: Enable the NIC before performing the operation.

PDR65.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

USR0151.Description: The VNC client from the IP address identified in the message is logged off.
USR0151.Message: The remote VNC session from the IP address %1 is logging off.

RAC0154.Description: Displayed when a group of redundant power supplies has one or more individual power supplies with bad status.
RAC0154.Resolution: Replace the degraded power supply unit. Check the Power Supplies page for more information.
RAC0154.Message: Non-redundant power mode: Secondary power supply has degraded.

VLT0200.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0200.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0200.Message: The system board %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

PDR66.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR66.Message: %1 that was marked as missing has been replaced.

RED037.Description: The currently installed firmware of the components on the server match with the specified remote repository.
RED037.Message: All components' firmware match with the specified remote repository.

PWR1004.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1004.Resolution: if unintended, review system configuration changes and power policy.
PWR1004.Message: The system performance degraded because power capacity has changed.

RAC0147.Description: Firmware rollback image is missing or is corrupt.

SWC0315.Description: The getconfig subcommand failed to get the object value.

SYS076.Description: The configuration XML file contains a component node that is not supported.
SYS076.Resolution: Make sure the input configuration XML file only specifies supported component. Check the import operation job configuration results for the unsupported XML node.
SYS076.Message: Invalid or unsupported component specified in the input configuration XML file.

RAC057.Description: The Privacy Protocol for the user cannot be enabled because the Authentication protocol is disabled.
RAC057.Resolution: Enable the Authentication Protocol attribute for the identified user ID account, and retry the operation to set the Privacy Protocol to an enabled state.
RAC057.Message: Unable to set Privacy Protocol to an enabled state because the Authentication Protocol attribute is set to None for the user ID: %1

IPA0004.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.

VDR93.Description: This alert message occurs if there are medium errors in the physical drives.
VDR93.Message: %1 bad block medium error is cleared.

RAC050.Description: The country code is not entered in the correct format or does not exist. Refer to ISO 3166 for the correct country code format.
RAC050.Resolution: Enter country code in the correct format as defined in ISO 3166. For example, United States = US.

RAC0278.Description: This warning message appears when IPv6 is disabled.
RAC0278.Resolution: Use IPv4 network to access iDRAC remotely.
RAC0278.Message: Disabling IPv6 prevents access to iDRAC using an IPv6 address.

VFL0716.Description: An error has occurred while initializing SD Card because the SD card is not an approved vFlash SD card.
VFL0716.Resolution: Insert a vFlash SD card and try again.
VFL0716.Message: SD Card is not a vFlash SD Card; the SD card could not be initialized.

BAT1003.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1003.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has completed.

UEFI0233.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - FIFO Reset phase.
UEFI0233.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0233.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC0676.Description: Unable to assign physical disk drives as global hotspare(s). This may be because there are no disk drives available in a ready state or there are no virtual disks present.
RAC0676.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) If there are no disk drives available in ready state, insert additional disk drives and make sure the drives are in ready state. 2) If no virtual disks are present, click <create virtualdisk link> and create at least one virtual disk. 3) If the physical disk drive(s) are in non-RAID mode, convert them to RAID mode by pressing Ctrl+R while restarting the server, and then select the required controller. Press F2 and select the Convert to RAID capable option, and then complete the operation.
RAC0676.Message: Unable to assign physical disk drives as global hotspare(s).

PCI3019.Description: A low-severity issue was detected in the SSD bay identified in the message.
PCI3019.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the component identified in the message, and then monitor the log for a re-occurrence of the issue. If the issue persists, and occurs during server startup, update the component firmware. If the issue persists and occurs during OS runtime, restart the server and update the OS drivers for the component identified in the message..
PCI3019.Message: A low-severity issue is detected in the SSD bay %1, Slot %2.

SYS004.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.
SYS004.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation and retry the operation with a valid value for the identified parameter.

PR10.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference and would apply firmware based on user settings for the system. However, the previous device's firmware update package is not present on the Lifecycle Controller.
PR10.Resolution: Use Unified Server Configurator or Dell update package to update device.
PR10.Message: Firmware update will not be performed. Firmware package is not present for %1

UEFI0017.Description: Unable to locate a file required to run Lifecycle Controller. No Lifecycle Controller functionality is available while in Recovery Mode.
UEFI0017.Resolution: Repair Lifecycle Controller firmware using the Lifecycle Controller Dell Update Package (DUP) or Lifecycle Controller Repair Package via iDRAC. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
UEFI0017.Message: Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible and is therefore in Recovery mode.

PDR59.Description: The disk has a bad block. Data was remapped to another disk block. No data loss has occurred.
PDR59.Resolution: Monitor the disk for other messages or indications of poor health.
PDR59.Message: A bad disk block was reassigned on %1.

HWC1001.Description: The absent device may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

PSU0035.Resolution: Check input power, replace or re-install the power supply. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0035.Message: An over voltage fault detected on power supply %1.

STOR303.Description: Controller mode cannot be changed as the controller has foreign configuration associated with it.
STOR303.Resolution: Clear the foreign configuration and retry the operation.
STOR303.Message: Unable to change controller mode while foreign configuration is present on the controller.

LC081.Description: The Server Screen Shot export operation cannot be completed because of internal firmware issues.
LC081.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart iDRAC by invoking the WS-Man iDRACReset method which is defined in the DCIM_iDRACCardService class (input parameters are not required for this method), and then retry the operation.
LC081.Message: Unable to complete the Server Screen Shot export operation because of internal firmware issues.

SYS092.Description: The iDRAC is collecting information about the server for a Tech Support Report.
SYS092.Message: The iDRAC is collecting information about the server for a Tech Support Report.

PWR8588.Description: The server identified in the message cannot be turned on while a chassis infrastructure firmware update operation is in progress.
PWR8588.Resolution: The chassis infrastructure firmware update is in progress. Retry the operation after the firmware update is complete.
PWR8588.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because a chassis infrastructure firmware update is in progress.

RAC0727.Description: Auto-throttling is enabled for the server based on a request from the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) because the CMC has restarted.
RAC0727.Message: Auto-throttling is enabled for the server.

RAC070.Description: The SSL Web-Server certificate was successfully restored to factory defaults.
RAC070.Message: The SSL Web-Server certificate was successfully restored to factory defaults.

RDU0003.Description: One of more fans have failed or have been removed or a configuration change occurred which requires additional fans.
RDU0003.Resolution: Remove and re-install failed fans or install additional fans.

CMC8538.Description: The length of the CMC firmware version to be sent in the message from local CMC to peer CMC is too long. Under these conditions, CMC version in the message is displayed as 1.0.
CMC8538.Message: Firmware version string is too long.

SWC0140.Message: RAC reset operation initiated successfully. It may take up to a minute for the RAC to come back online again.

HWC8507.Description: The USB device inserted in to the I/O Panel USB port is causing an issue and cannot be used. The USB device may not be operational.
HWC8507.Resolution: Remove the USB device from the I/O Panel USB port, and then retry the operation with another USB device.
HWC8507.Message: The USB device inserted in to the I/O Panel USB port is causing an issue and cannot be used.

VDR54.Description: You have cancelled the virtual disk initialization.

PR36.Description: The system has detected a different firmware version than previously recorded for the indicated device. This may be due to a firmware update, rollback, or part replacement.
PR36.Message: Version change detected for %1 firmware. Previous version:%2, Current version:%3

BAT1015.Description: Diagnostic event for service to determine if there is an ambient temperature problem.

SYS023.Description: There are no pending values to change.
SYS023.Resolution: Ensure there are pending values for the attributes that need to be set and retry the operation.

PST0012.Description: System extended memory test in progress.

PDR33.Description: The controller cannot to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a global hot spare. The disk either failed or was removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.
PDR33.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and installed. Check the cables. Refer to the product documentation and see the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the global hot spare.
PDR33.Message: A dedicated hot spare has been removed. %1

SWU8515.Description: The IOM firmware update operation was not successful. Unable to initiate the Update process.
SWU8515.Message: Unable to update the IOM firmware. Update Initiation was not successful. ErrorCode=0x%1.

SWC1903.Description: RAC SSL Certificate has been changed.
SWC1903.Message: RAC SSL Certificate has been changed.

RAC0687.Description: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.
RAC0687.Resolution: Choose to create a job for the successful operations. View successful pending operations using the Pending Operations button or click Cancel to quit job creation.
RAC0687.Message: Some of the applied pending operations were not created.

BIOS015.Description: A set attribute operation was attempted on a read only attribute.
BIOS015.Message: AttributeValue cannot be changed to read only AttributeName %1.

FAN0002.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.
FAN0002.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan at the next scheduled service window. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0002.Message: Fan %1 RPM is greater than the upper warning threshold.

BIOS029.Description: The BIOS password cannot be configured because an Export Server Profile operation is already running.
BIOS029.Resolution: Wait until the current export operation is completed, and then retry the operation.
BIOS029.Message: Unable to change the BIOS password because an Export Server Profile operation is already running.

RAC1046.Description: Unable to view the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.
RAC1046.Resolution: Configure the Automatic Update feature by running the RACADM command "racadm autoupdatescheduler create" with the desired option settings.
RAC1046.Message: Unable to view the Automatic Update (autoupdate) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.

USR0181.Description: The Quick Sync feature is deactivated because the inactivity timeout limit was reached.
USR0181.Resolution: Press the activate button on the bezel to activate the iDRAC Quick Sync feature.
USR0181.Message: The Quick Sync feature is deactivated because the inactivity timeout limit was reached.

PCI1314.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable re-install the device at the next scheduled service time.
PCI1314.Message: A bus correctable error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

LC002.Description: A general failure occurred while executing the command.
LC002.Resolution: Verify network connectivity. If failure persists, reset the iDRAC to resolve the issue.

BAR007.Description: System profile export operation is successfully completed.

HWC2002.Message: The storage %1 cable or interconnect is connected.

ENC30.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWU8549.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful, because of a firmware image checksum error.
SWU8549.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8549.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Standby CMC and Active CMC. The checksum process was not successful.

OSD36.Description: User has cancelled system services by using the CTRL+E option (iDRAC configuration utility) during POST. This action cancels the WSMAN request to boot to ISO.
OSD36.Resolution: To resolve the issue rerun the command. Do not cancel system services using CTRL+E during POST when system is rebooting to the ISO.
OSD36.Message: Boot to ISO Image has been cancelled by using CTRL+E option on the server.

ENC12.Description: Communication with an enclosure has been restored. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PWR2401.Description: The iDRAC controller detected that the power management firmware did not initialize properly. The system may operate in a performance degraded state.
PWR2401.Resolution: "1) Disconnect system input power, wait one minute, reconnect system input power.2) Re-flash system BIOS.3) Upgrade system BIOS to the latest revision."

SWC0045.Description: The Import operation did not successfully complete. For more information, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0045.Resolution: Exit the Import Server Profile wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0045.Message: Unable to complete the Import operation.

SWC0035.Description: The backup operation did not initialize because the system does not have a service tag.
SWC0035.Resolution: Assign a service tag to the system and retry the operation. To assign the service tag, contact your service provider.
SWC0035.Message: Unable to initialize backup Server Profile operation.

HWC5004.Description: CMC has old firmware and does not recognize the new device which has requested link tuning information. After updating the firmware the CMC will recognize the device.
HWC5004.Resolution: Update the CMC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC5004.Message: A link tuning failure detected on %1.

CMC8506.Description: A command to shut down the CMC was initiated.
CMC8506.Message: A command to shut down the CMC was initiated.

NIC003.Description: An invalid number of arguments was passed to the method.
NIC003.Resolution: Enter all the required command parameters. Check documentation and try again.

SWC0258.Description: Insufficient resources to execute the command.
SWC0258.Resolution: Power Cycle the system and re-enter the command.

PDR19.Description: A disk on the specified controller has received a SMART alert (predictive failure) indicating that the disk is likely to fail in the near future.
PDR19.Resolution: Replace the disk that has received the SMART alert. If the physical disk is a member of a non-redundant virtual disk, then back up the data before replacing the disk. Removing a physical disk that is included in a non-redundant virtual disk causes the virtual disk to fail and may cause data loss.

SWC0078.Description: The server has been successfully removed from Integrated Data Center. All configurations will be restored to Factory defaults.
SWC0078.Message: The server has been successfully removed from Integrated Data Center.

PSU1003.Description: The power supply is not providing any power. This may be because the power supply switch is in the off position or the power supply has failed.
PSU1003.Resolution: Check whether the power switch on the power supply unit is turned off or on. If it is turned off, turn it on. If the problem is not corrected, verify that the power cord is attached and functional. See the storage hardware documentation for more information.

RAC0749.Description: SNMPv3 User cannot be set to None.
RAC0749.Resolution: Set the SNMPv3 User to a value other than None and retry the operation.
RAC0749.Message: SNMPv3 User cannot be set to None.

SWC0039.Description: The backup Server Configuration Profile image partition is not present in the vFlash SD card.
SWC0039.Resolution: A backup Server Configuration Profile is required to import or export a Server Profile. Perform the backup operation and retry import or export operation.
SWC0039.Message: Unable to find the backup Server Configuration Profile image.

STOR039.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because of a mismatch in the number of AttributeName and AttributeValue values specified.
STOR039.Resolution: Specify a valid number of AttributeName and AttributeValue pair values and retry the operation.
STOR039.Message: Mismatch in AttributeName and AttributeValue count.

SEC0031.Description: The chassis is open. System performance may be degraded, and security may be compromised.
SEC0031.Resolution: Close the chassis. Check system logs.
SEC0031.Message: The chassis is open while the power is on.

LOG001.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the method invoked in the operation are missing.
LOG001.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
LOG001.Message: Missing required InstanceID or JobID parameter.

RAC0625.Description: The requested job cannot be scheduled, because job schedule types such as Automatic Backup or Automatic Update is not enabled.
RAC0625.Resolution: Enable the correct job schedule type, and then retry the operation. For example, to enable the Automatic Backup feature, select the Enable Automatic Backup option.
RAC0625.Message: Unable to schedule, because the requested job schedule type is not enabled.

VLT0217.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is within range.

RAC0722.Description: Failed to program the Chassis assigned MAC address for the NIC.Integrated in the specified slot number.
RAC0722.Message: Failed to program the Chassis assigned MAC address for the NIC.Integrated.%1.

UEFI0270.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the network connection to DHCPv4 server is not established.
UEFI0270.Resolution: Check the network cable connection of the initiator or the DHCPv4 server and retry the operation.
UEFI0270.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the network connection to DHCPv4 server is not established.

UEFI0226.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the DDR4 LR-DIMM Transmit Buffer Training phase.
UEFI0226.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0226.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

TMP0204.Resolution: Check system operating environment, fans, and heatsinks.
TMP0204.Message: CPU %1 temperature is outside of range.

RAC0502.Description: Virtual disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off or there are no virtual disks created.
RAC0502.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Check if virtual disks are created.
RAC0502.Message: There are no virtual disks to be displayed.

TMP0131.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0131.Message: The control panel temperature is less than the lower critical threshold.

RAC0626.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because all or some of the schedule parameters entered are incorrect.
RAC0626.Resolution: Enter correct input schedule parameters and retry the operation.
RAC0626.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid schedule parameter is entered.

CMC8509.Description: The extended storage feature is not activated if the media on the secondary CMC is no longer functional.
CMC8509.Resolution: Do one of the following, and retry the operation: 1) In the CMC Web interface, go to Chassis Controller > Flash Media > Configuration and verify if the card on the secondary CMC displays errors. 2) Do a failover and then reprovision the card from the same GUI page. Reprovisioning is only allowed on the card of primary CMC. However, if both the options 1 and 2 fail, the card may be no longer functional.
CMC8509.Message: Unable to activate the extended storage feature on the secondary CMC: %1. The feature will be deactivated.

LC018.Description: The certificate modification operation was successful. Communication to iDRAC will be lost as iDRAC restarts to use the new server certificate.
LC018.Message: Server certificate successfully modified. iDRAC will now restart and be unavailable during restart.

BIOS028.Description: The BIOS password cannot be simultaneously configured by using plain text and a hash.
BIOS028.Resolution: Wait until the current password configuration process is completed and retry the operation.
BIOS028.Message: Unable to change the BIOS password using plain text because the password is currently being configured using a hash.

UEFI0180.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Write Leveling error was detected.
UEFI0180.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0180.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

SYS009.Description: Length of string for specified attribute exceeded the maximum length allowed.
SYS009.Resolution: Check Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and retry the command with string value length less than maximum length allowed.
SYS009.Message: String exceeds maximum length for attribute: %1

CMC8602.Description: The Chassis group identified in the message is deleted. This chassis was the leader of the group.

VFL0713.Resolution: Detach the partitions and try again.
VFL0713.Message: One or more partitions are currently attached; the SD card could not be initialized.

HWC1102.Description: The peripheral sled identified in the message is installed in the unsupported slot identified in the message.
HWC1102.Resolution: Install the Storage sled in a supported slot and retry the operation. For information about the supported sleds and slots, see the User's Guide available at the support site.
HWC1102.Message: The %1 is installed in an unsupported slot %2.

VRM0010.Description: The virtual media could not be disconnected. Possible reason is that it might be in use.
VRM0010.Message: Unable to disconnect Virtual Media devices.

STOR304.Description: Controller mode cannot be changed as the controller has virtual disk or hotspare associated with it.
STOR304.Resolution: Delete the Virtual Disks and/or Hotspares and retry the operation.
STOR304.Message: Unable to change controller mode while Virtual Disks and/or Hotspares are present on the controller.

PCI1350.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1350.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1350.Message: A PCI system error was detected on a component at slot %1.

VDR28.Description: A user has caused a mirrored virtual disk to be split. When a virtual disk is mirrored, its data is copied to another virtual disk to maintain redundancy. After being split, both virtual disks retain a copy of the data. Because the mirror is no longer intact, updates to the data are no longer copied to the mirror.
VDR28.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR28.Message: A virtual disk and its mirror have been split.

CTL31.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC1018.Description: This occurs when an incorrect syntax is used or an incorrect object is specified during the command invocation.
RAC1018.Resolution: Make sure to use the correct syntax and correct object names, and retry the operation. For information related to the corresponding group, see RACADM help or the RACADM User's Guide.
RAC1018.Message: The specified object or syntax is invalid.

BAR077.Description: The collection and export of host system firmware images was not successful.
BAR077.Resolution: Apply Dell Update Packages for all devices and software, and try the operation again. If the error continues, repair the Lifecycle Controller and apply the packages again, and retry the operation.
BAR077.Message: Unable to collect the Firmware images.

SWC8600.Description: The profile version must be compatible with the server generation and Lifecycle Controller firmware version.
SWC8600.Resolution: Make sure that profile versions are compatible with target servers when attempting application of profiles to servers.
SWC8600.Message: The selected profile was not applied to %1.

SWC0274.Description: The value of specified parameter is invalid.
SWC0274.Resolution: Enter the same command with a legal value to the object.
SWC0274.Message: Invalid syntax. An object value must be specified.

PCI1310.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1310.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1310.Message: A PCI system error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

LC051.Description: There can only be one Server Profile Export job at a time.
LC051.Resolution: Wait for the existing Server Profile Export job to run and complete or cancel it, before retrying the operation.
LC051.Message: Cannot create multiple Server Profile Export jobs.

CTL72.Description: There is too much foreign configuration data to be imported in one attempt.
CTL72.Resolution: Import these foreign configurations in multiple attempts.
CTL72.Message: The foreign configuration overflow has occurred on %1.

RAC0759.Description: A running Tech Support Report job has been cancelled.
RAC0759.Resolution: Click Job Queue button to view the status of the cancelled job.
RAC0759.Message: A running Tech Support Report job has been cancelled.

IOV112.Description: Chassis infrastructure firmware is not valid and must be reinstalled.
IOV112.Resolution: Update the Chassis Infrastructure firmware. Using Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM, run the command "racadm fwupdate -g -u -a <TFTP server IP Address> -d mainboard.bin -m main_board" to upload the latest firmware version to the Chassis Infrastructure Mainboard.
IOV112.Message: Chassis Infrastructure firmware is not valid.

LC058.Description: The attribute value specified in the AttributeValue array is not valid for the corresponding specified attribute.
LC058.Resolution: Retry the operation with a valid attribute value for the corresponding specified attribute.
LC058.Message: Invalid AttributeValue parameter value for corresponding AttributeName value, %1.

RED016.Description: The remote share location that has the file(s) or ISO image did not mount correctly.
RED016.Resolution: 1. Verify that the path to the share is correct and that the parameters to the call are correct. 2. Verify that there are no network connectivity issues. 3. Verify that the mount point exists.

STOR035.Description: Unable to perform operation because either the number of storage objects specified is insufficient or the storage objects are not in a required state to perform this operation.
STOR035.Resolution: Check the number and state of storage objects and retry the operation.
STOR035.Message: Unable to perform operation because either the number of storage objects specified is insufficient or the storage objects are not in a required state to perform this operation.

LC009.Description: There were insufficient parameters specified for this command.
LC009.Resolution: Confirm that the parameters provided are correct. For a list of parameters for this method refer to the Lifecycle Controller User Guide.

SUP009.Description: Because of the size of the driver pack, the update process removes the older version of the driver pack from the system before installing the newer version. For that reason, the driver pack update cannot be deleted.
SUP009.Resolution: Wait for the Driver Pack update to complete. To revert to the previous version of the update, download and update the firmware to the version desired.
SUP009.Message: Driver pack update in progress - Delete failed.

SYS044.Description: Unable to collect the configuration information for one or more components. An internal error occurred while processing component information.
SYS044.Resolution: Enable Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) using Lifecycle Controller and restart the system. Make sure that inventory collection is complete before retrying the operation. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
SYS044.Message: Unable to export one or more component configurations.

DIS105.Description: The network share folder cannot be accessed, because an unsupported or invalid share type is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS105.Resolution: Enter a valid sharetype in DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC using (-s <0 or 1>) where 0 = NFS, 2 = CIFS.
DIS105.Message: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access the network share folder, because an invalid sharetype value is specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

UEFI0183.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Early Vref Centering initialization.
UEFI0183.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0183.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

PWR221.Description: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is already disabled.
PWR221.Message: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is already disabled.

BIOS026.Description: The status of the Password cannot be set to locked, because currently there is a System Password change is pending.
BIOS026.Resolution: Wait until the pending System Password change is applied or delete the pending System Password change and retry the operation.
BIOS026.Message: Password status cannot be set to locked when a System Password change is pending.

BAR083.Description: System profile backup file validation failed because the host system model information does not match the value stored in the file.
BAR083.Resolution: Obtain a valid host system backup image and try the operation again. Reboot the remote access controller and try the operation again. If the error continues, download a new remote access controller firmware image and try the operation again.
BAR083.Message: Host System Model does not match the Backup file System Model information.

SUP007.Description: The iDRAC communication channel is open and being used by another process; this can be caused by an open session of USC locally on the server.
SUP007.Resolution: If USC is in use, wait until USC has exited and retry the action. Otherwise retry after 30 seconds to check if network connectivity caused this error.

SWC0133.Resolution: Specify either the connect or the disconnect option with the subcommand.

AMP0322.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0322.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes
AMP0322.Message: Chassis power level current is outside of range.

VDR38.Description: A user renamed a virtual disk. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PDR26.Description: A drive has entered the online state. This may be because the system just started or could be because a problem with the drive has been corrected.

SYS154.Description: Initiating secure erase operation on secure erase-capable drives for the controller identified in the message.
SYS154.Message: Initiating secure erase operation on secure erase-capable drives for controller: %1.

USR0015.Description: The specified user does not exist.
USR0015.Resolution: Verify the existing users and enter a valid username.
USR0015.Message: The specified user does not exist.

BAT1002.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1002.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has started.

IOV105.Description: An error by the Chassis Infrastructure slot management detected an error which may prevent the physical assignment/unassignment or power off of a slot. The errors may be caused by PCIE training timeouts, false hot plug signals, or installation of an unsupported PCIe adapter card. For a list of supported PCIe adapter cards contact your service provider.
IOV105.Resolution: Make sure that supported adapters are used and installed correctly in the PCIe slot.
IOV105.Message: Unable to manage PCIE adapter %1 located in %2 %3.

CTL102.Description: The controller identified in the message is enabled by a user action.

VLT0201.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0201.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0201.Message: The system board %1 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

RAC0698.Description: Unable to modify USB management settings because the USB device is currently in use.
RAC0698.Resolution: Wait for the current USB operations to complete and retry the operation.
RAC0698.Message: Unable to modify USB management settings because the USB device is currently in use.

BAT0019.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0019.Resolution: Check the battery to confirm presence.

SWC8564.Description: The Boot Identity profile from the server identified in the message cannot be cleared because there is no response from the server iDRAC. A MAC Address conflict is possible if the server retains virtual MAC Address values and they are also allocated to another server.
SWC8564.Resolution: Make sure that the server is not used until the Persistence Policy settings are returned to default values and the Virtual MAC Address settings have been cleared. Persistence Policy settings can be reset to default values by resetting the server iDRAC to factory default settings. If the iDRAC cannot be reset to default values, contact your service provider before attempting to use the server.
SWC8564.Message: Unable to clear the Boot Identity profile from the server in slot %1 because there is no response from the server iDRAC.

OSE1009.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. Verify the media in the CDROM is bootable. See system video for additional information

LC052.Description: There can only be one Server Profile Import job at a time.
LC052.Resolution: Wait for the existing Server Profile Import job to run and complete or cancel it, before retrying the operation.
LC052.Message: Cannot create multiple Server Profile Import jobs.

CPU0822.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is configured correctly.

LC069.Description: The certificate does not exist for export or delete operation.

RFM1032.Description: The card is write-protected by the physical latch on the SD card. IDSDM cannot use a write-protected card.
RFM1032.Resolution: if unintended, remove the media and disable write protection.
RFM1032.Message: Removable Flash Media is write protected.

PSU0044.Description: The power supply is operating but the system cannot get status information.
PSU0044.Resolution: If problem persist, remove and re-install power supply.
PSU0044.Message: Cannot obtain status information from power supply %1.

RAC0106.Description: Communication with the Smart Card reader is established and a Smart Card is inserted, but there are problems reading the Smart Card.
RAC0106.Resolution: This error may occur because:1. Make sure the Smart Card is seated correctly.2. Smart Card is invalid. Insert a valid Smart Card and try again. 3. Check connection between reader and system.4. There may be an issue with the Smart Card reader. Try reinstalling the reader driver or use a different reader.
RAC0106.Message: The Smart Card cannot be detected. Insert the Smart Card correctly.

LC083.Description: The Redfish Event service cannot deliver notifications to the IP Address identified in the message because of network communication issues.
LC083.Resolution: Make sure that the server is connected to the network and retry the operation. If the issue persists, delete the subscription and then subscribe by using an IP that is connected to the network.
LC083.Message: The Redfish Event service cannot deliver notifications to %1 because of network communication issues.

PDR95.Description: The attempt to update the physical disk has failed. This is due to too much activity on the bus, a bad update package, or a bad disk.
PDR95.Resolution: Retry the update. If the update fails a second time, verify the update package is valid. If the update package is valid, replace the failing disk. Contact technical support if the problem persists.

PDR3.Description: The RAID Controller may not be able to read/write data to the physical disk drive indicated in the message. This may be due to a failure with the physical disk drive or because the physical disk drive was removed from the system.
PDR3.Resolution: Remove and re-insert the physical disk drive identified in the message and make sure the physical disk drive is inserted properly. If the issue persists, replace the physical disk drive.

PWR1003.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1003.Resolution: If unintended, review system configuration changes and thermal policy.
PWR1003.Message: The system performance degraded because cooling capacity has changed.

AMP0311.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is within range.

BAR033.Description: A Lifecycle Controller internal data import operation did not complete successfully.
BAR033.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Download and apply the Dell Update Package for the Unified Server Configurator (USC). 2) Run System Services to update the database if CSIOR is not enabled. 3) Reboot the system and retry the operation. If these response actions do not resolve the issue, download the Field Service Repair software and repair the Lifecycle Controller. Download and install all the DUPs for USC, diagnostics, driver packs, and device firmware of all the devices of the host system.
BAR033.Message: Unable to Restore Lifecycle Controller data.

RAC913.Description: The management system could not login to the iDRAC.
RAC913.Resolution: Verify whether the username and password given for the iDRAC are correct.
RAC913.Message: Unable to login to RAC using the specified address

OSD56.Description: An ISO is already connected using Remote File Share (RFS). The connection might have been initiated from iDRAC GUI, racadm, or Remote Services API.
OSD56.Resolution: Disconnect the Remote File Share (RFS) using iDRAC GUI, racadm, or Remote Services API and then retry the operation to connect the ISO again.
OSD56.Message: An ISO is already connected using Remote File Share (RFS).

UEFI0221.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Read Voltage Training phase.
UEFI0221.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0221.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

BAT0014.Description: The PERC RAID controller battery may report absent due to disconnect or thermal exceptions.
BAT0014.Resolution: 1) Verify the PERC RAID controller battery installation for the associated bay. 2) If installed, reseat or reconnect the battery and cables. 3) Check the system logs for thermal related issues.
BAT0014.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is absent.

SYS170.Description: The SHA256 Hash value and the clear text value for an iDRAC user password cannot be used at the same time for a password configuration operation.
SYS170.Resolution: Make sure that the user password is configured using either the clear text or the SHA256 Hash, but not both.
SYS170.Message: The SHA256 Hash value and the clear text value for an iDRAC user password cannot be entered together.

RAC055.Description: The user name for the user account cannot be cleared because the user account is enabled in the configuration XML file.
RAC055.Resolution: Retry the operation after disabling the user account in the configuration XML file.
RAC055.Message: User name cannot be cleared because the user account is enabled in the input configuration XML file.

IOV121.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has changed the PCIe ride-through timeout to the value identified in the message. PCIe adapters will remain turned on for the number of seconds specified by the ride-through timeout value after the server they are assigned to is turned off. Note: A value of zero equals infinite number of seconds.
IOV121.Message: PCIe ride-through time out has changed from %1 to %1 seconds.

IOV114.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter (VA) identified in the message has been assigned to the server identified in the message.

SYS153.Description: The non-volatile cache of the controller identified in the message is being erased.
SYS153.Message: Deleting hardware cache data for controller: %1.

RAC991.Description: The "jobqueue" command cannot be run, because the existing update jobs are transitioning to one of these states: "New", "Downloading", or "Running".
RAC991.Resolution: Wait until the existing update jobs are completed before retrying the operation. To monitor the status of the existing jobs, use the "racadm jobqueue view" command.

STOR072.Description: The configuration operation could not be performed because it requires iDRAC Service Module (ISM) service to be present and running in the server Operating System.
STOR072.Resolution: Make sure the iDRAC Service Module (ISM) service is running on the server Operating System and then retry the operation. Refer to the iDRAC User Guide for installing and starting ISM.
STOR072.Message: iDRAC Service Module (ISM) is either not present or not running on the server OS.

PWR8500.Description: The chassis power state from the configuration database and the current state are different. The current chassis power state will be updated in the configuration database. This is to insure the chassis power state will be the same if the CMC is rebooted or a CMC failover occurs. Note that the numerical value of the state is intended for technical support use.
PWR8500.Message: Chassis power state updated to %1 from %2.

CPU0806.Description: System performance may be degraded or the system may fail to operate.
CPU0806.Resolution: Review product documentation for proper configuration and installation procedures.
CPU0806.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is incorrectly configure.

SUP0101.Description: Unable to get the update status.
SUP0101.Message: Unable to get firmware update status.

ASR0108.Message: The system returned from an OS watchdog timer event.

SEL9902.Description: Software on the system has logged an event that cannot be determined. You may need to review this event using a tool which displays raw data such as Ipmitool with the -vvv option or Racadm with the -E option.

USR0016.Description: Unable to obtain the session info from RAC.
USR0016.Message: Unable to get session info from the RAC.

CTL117.Description: Operation failed because invalid securitykey was passed.
CTL117.Resolution: Provide valid securitykey for the operation.

CTL110.Description: The Patrol ReadRate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL110.Message: The Patrol Read Rate of %1 is set to %2.

SWC0038.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to export the file to the network share because the destination folder is read-only or inaccessible.
SWC0038.Resolution: Remove the write protection on the destination folder and verify the folder is accessible, then retry the operation. If the problem persists, check network settings and retry.
SWC0038.Message: Unable to export the file to the network share.

VF025.Resolution: To perform a write operation on this partition, change its access type to read-write and try this operation again.

RED007.Description: The Update Package security signature cannot be verified.
RED007.Resolution: Re-acquire the Update Package from the service provider.
RED007.Message: Unable to verify Update Package signature.

SWC0130.Description: The Trap needs to be set for the particular index for the testtrap to go through.
SWC0130.Resolution: Set cfgIpmiPetAlertEnable in cfgIpmiPet group using config subcommand for the corresponding index.
SWC0130.Message: Trap at specified index is not currently enabled.

FCD8500.Description: The server specified in the message must be turned off or the server slot must be empty before changing the FlexAddress configuration.
FCD8500.Resolution: Turn off the server and retry the operation.
FCD8500.Message: Unable to apply the %1 configuration. The affected servers (slot %2) are not turned off.

TMP0115.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0115.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0115.Message: The %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PWR8504.Description: The chassis power button press is detected but the button has been disabled.
PWR8504.Resolution: The chassis power button is disabled. To enable the chassis power button use the CMC RACADM command line interface, CMC Web interface. Using the command line, enter "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerButtonEnable 1". Using the Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration. Clear the Disable Chassis Power Button check box.
PWR8504.Message: Chassis power button is pressed, but the button is disabled.

UEFI0061.Description: The request to change one or more attribute(s) is being processed.
UEFI0061.Message: The request to change attributes is being processed.

SYS061.Description: Some configuration changes for the component identified by the Fully Qualified Device Descriptor (FQDD) in the configuration job results were not successfully applied.
SYS061.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log and identify the configuration changes that did not complete or retrieve the configuration results using the GetConfigResults() method. Retry those changes that did not complete in a separate import operation.

VDR9.Description: A consistency check operation on a virtual disk has started.
