STOR054.Description: The controller or the firmware on the controller does not support the CacheCade feature.
STOR054.Resolution: Refer to the specific controller users guide for more information.

SUP0121.Message: Firmware update in progress [%1 percent complete]

VRM0020.Description: Racadm tool failed to obtain the data.
VRM0020.Message: Unable to determine current Remote Image state.

STOR042.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because the attribute value specified is not supported in the current configuration.
STOR042.Resolution: Specify a value for the attribute identified in the message by using one of the possible values currently available for that attribute.

PWR8559.Description: Power cycle initiated for the I/O module in the slot identified in the message.
PWR8559.Message: Power cycle initiated for I/O Module %1.

SWC0215.Description: The process to disable the file share has started. Use the -s option to know more about the status.
SWC0215.Resolution: If required check the status using the -s option.
SWC0215.Message: Disable Remote File Started. Please check status using -s option to know Remote File Share is ENABLED or DISABLED.

PDR98.Description: An error occurred while performing an action on the disk.
PDR98.Resolution: Check the disk is present or replace the disk.

RAC0663.Description: Resetting the selected PERC controller's configuration will delete all the virtual disks (VDs) and unassign hot-spares from the associated controller.
RAC0663.Message: Resetting the selected PERC controller's configuration will delete all the virtual disks (VDs) and unassign hot-spares from the associated controller.

TMP5.Description: You have changed the value for the maximum temperature probe warning threshold. This alert is provided for informational purposes.
TMP5.Message: The temperature probe maximum warning value was changed on %1.

UEFI0085.Description: One or more chipset errors have occurred.
UEFI0085.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the chipset error. Do one of the following: 1) Turn off the input power to the system and turn on again. 2) Update the PCIe device firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0085.Message: One or more chipset errors have occurred.

SWC0316.Description: The value for index must be greater than zero.
SWC0316.Resolution: Enter a positive value for index.
SWC0316.Message: The index must be greater than 0.

RAC0257.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the Alternate DNS IPv4 address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0257.Resolution: Enter a valid Alternate DNS Server Address. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0257.Message: The Alternate DNS Server Address is invalid. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].

CMC8502.Description: CMC is unable to access the specified server's IPv6 information. Unable to display the specified server's Launch iDRAC link on the CMC Web interface.
CMC8502.Resolution: Enable IPv6 for the specified server using the CMC command line or CMC Web GUI interface, so that the link to launch iDRAC is displayed on the CMC Web interface. For the command line options or navigation for Web interface, see the Troubleshooting section in the CMC User's Guide.
CMC8502.Message: Unable to access the IPv6 information of the server.

PSU0002.Description: System performance and power redundancy may be degraded or lost.
PSU0002.Resolution: Remove and re-install the power supply at the next service window. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0002.Message: A predictive failure detected on power supply %1.

SWC0252.Description: Invalid number of arguments were passed to the command.
SWC0252.Resolution: Refer the help text for the command, and enter the required parameters.
SWC0252.Message: No options were specified. The subcommand requires options to be used.

OSD34.Description: Unable to continue with BootToPXE command because the system has an ISO image attached. Detach the ISO image before continuing with BootToPXE.
OSD34.Resolution: Run the DetachISOImage command and then run BootToPXE.
OSD34.Message: Unable to continue with BootToPXE - ISO image is attached to the system.

SWC0298.Description: The specified object value cannot be configured if local configuration is disabled or smart card logon is enabled. If smart card logon is enabled, serial, SSH, telnet and IPMIoverLAN is disabled by force and cannot be enabled.
SWC0298.Resolution: Enable Local Configuration (through GUI) or Disable Smart Card Logon to change the value.
SWC0298.Message: The specified object value cannot be configured if local configuration is disabled or smart card logon is enabled. If smart card logon is enabled, serial, SSH, telnet and IPMIoverLAN is disabled by force and cannot be enabled.

RAC0249.Description: The vFlash partition is in-use by another process. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0249.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.
RAC0249.Message: One or more partitions are in-use by another process.

SWC0076.Description: Lifecycle Controller detected that the iDRAC internal storage partitions identified in the message were not made available by BIOS during the boot process.
SWC0076.Resolution: No response action required. If the issue occurs consistently during system startup, restart the iDRAC and then restart the system. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC0076.Message: The following iDRAC internal storage partitions present in the system were not mounted during the system startup: %1

RED092.Description: The firmware for the component identified in the message was updated successfully to the firmware version identified in the message.
RED092.Message: The %1 firmware updated successfully. Previous version: %2, Current version: %3

RDU8508.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.
RDU8508.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8508.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover since the other CMC is non-functional.

STOR018.Description: This operation did not detect any foreign drives. This may be because no foreign drives are present or the only foreign drives are in a secured locked state.
STOR018.Resolution: If the only foreign drives present are in a secured locked state, run a secure erase operation on the drives to securely erase data or unlock these drives and retry the operation. Otherwise the operation was not successful because there are no foreign drives.

NIC501.Description: Autoconfig assigns values to the network components.
NIC501.Resolution: Disable Autoconfig and then modify the value.
NIC501.Message: The requested object is not allowed to be configured if Auto Config is enabled.

RDU8522.Description: The standby CMC identified in the message became the active CMC.

IOV013.Description: Unable to assign a virtual adapter (VA) to a server that is already assigned a VA, because a server may be assigned only one VA.
IOV013.Resolution: Unassign the server's current virtual adapter (VA) and retry the operation. To unassign the VA using RACADM, run the following command "racadm setpciecfg".
IOV013.Message: Unable to assign a virtual adapter (VA) to a server that is already assigned a VA, because a server may be assigned only one VA.

RAC0303.Description: This error message is displayed when Virtual Console feature is unavailable.
RAC0303.Resolution: Enable Virtual Console and ask the administrator to grant Access Virtual Console privilege.
RAC0303.Message: Virtual Console is disabled or you do not have the Access Virtual Console privilege.

SUP0525.Description: Unable to verify the digital signature of the Update Package.
SUP0525.Resolution: Download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0525.Message: Unable to verify the digital signature of the Update Package.

RAC0622.Description: The certificate file is invalid for one of the following reasons: 1) CA Certificate is corrupted, expired, or does not have signing privileges. 2) CA private key does not match with CA Certificate being uploaded.
RAC0622.Resolution: Make sure the CA certificate and private key are correct and retry the operation. The certificate can be validated using the OpenSSL tools.
RAC0622.Message: An invalid certificate file is uploaded.

SYS141.Description: The Lifecycle Controller data is deleted because of a System Erase operation.

SWC8617.Description: The request by the WS-Man method identified in the message for the server in slot identified slot is unsuccessful.
SWC8617.Resolution: Make sure that iDRAC is ready and system is functioning properly. Run the RACADM command "racadm getversion" to list all the servers and make sure the iDRAC version is displayed. If the iDRAC is listed as Not Ready then wait until iDRAC is ready for use. A Virtual Reseat may be required.
SWC8617.Message: Server Profiles: request %1 for server in slot %2 was unsuccessful. Returned fault: %3.

RAC1177.Description: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC and accessible from the iDRAC.
RAC1177.Resolution: No response action is required. To attach the USB device to the server instead of the iDRAC, remove the USB device from the front panel USB port, change the USB Management Port mode settings and then reinsert the USB device.
RAC1177.Message: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC.

UEFI0126.Description: The primary SD card is in write-protected mode.
UEFI0126.Resolution: No response action is required if this is intentional.
UEFI0126.Message: The primary SD card is in write-protected mode.

OSD66.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'OSName' is missing.
OSD66.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "OSName" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD66.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'OSName' is missing.

RAC0126.Description: The label field is empty. A label is required to create an empty partition.
RAC0126.Resolution: Enter a label that contains one to six alphanumeric characters.
RAC0126.Message: The label value is invalid. Expected range: 1-6 alphanumeric characters.

RAC1057.Description: Rollback operation did not complete successfully. The component identifier (FQDD) specified in the operation is not valid or does not have a Rollback firmware image available.
RAC1057.Resolution: Run the RACADM command "racadm swinventory" to see the list of Rollback firmware images available and the corresponding component identifier (FQDD).
RAC1057.Message: Rollback operation did not complete successfully. The component identifier specified is not valid or does not have a rollback firmware image available.

VDR45.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC0907.Description: The System ID LED was successfully set to on.

RAC0655.Description: The Replicate Lifecycle Controller Log in OS Log and Auto System Recovery Action features are disabled in the iDRAC Service Module because the OpenManage Server Administrator is installed on the server operating system.
RAC0655.Message: The Replicate Lifecycle Controller Log in OS Log and Auto System Recovery Action features are disabled in the iDRAC Service Module because the OpenManage Server Administrator is installed on the server operating system.

CTL104.Description: The Enhanced Auto Import Foreign Config status of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL104.Message: The Enhanced Auto Import Foreign Config value of %1 is set to %2.

LOG007.Description: This message is generated after a series of sequential duplicate events. Log entry count is the number of times the previous message was repeated.
LOG007.Message: The previous log entry was repeated %1 times.

STOR0104.Description: No virtual disk data to display. The system is powered off, physical disks are not present on the system, or virtual disks are not created.
STOR0104.Resolution: Check if the server has power, physical disks are available, and virtual disks are created.

CTL105.Description: The Patrol Read attribute identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message for the controller identified in the message.
CTL105.Message: The Patrol Read attribute %1 is set to %2 for %3.

SUP0108.Description: The firmware update is in progress and another update cannot be done.
SUP0108.Resolution: Wait for the update operation to conclude and then re-try.
SUP0108.Message: A firmware update operation is already in progress.

MEM0600.Message: Memory device was added at location %1.

RAC059.Description: When the Network Time Protocol (NTP) feature is enabled, the iDRAC will get time from the configured NTP server. Directly configuration of the iDRAC time is disabled when NTP is enabled.
RAC059.Resolution: Disable Network Time Protocol (NTP) and retry the operation.
RAC059.Message: Unable to configure iDRAC time because Network Time Protocol (NTP) is enabled.

BIOS021.Description: The old BIOS password specified in the change BIOS password operation was incorrect.
BIOS021.Resolution: Retry the operation with correct old BIOS password.

UEFI0222.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Round Trip Training phase.
UEFI0222.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0222.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC1194.Description: The server firmware is up to date and matches the catalog definitions.
RAC1194.Message: Successfully compared the firmware versions on the server to the versions defined in the specified catalog. The server firmware is up to date and matches the catalog definitions.

VDR51.Description: The consistency check completed on the virtual disk after making corrections.
VDR51.Message: The consistency check process made corrections and completed on %1.

ASR0107.Description: The operating system or an application failed to respond to a pre-notification with-in the timeout period. (IPMI sensor type code 11h - offset 07h)
ASR0107.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0107.Message: The OS watchdog timer pre-timeout interrupt was initiated.

PR23.Description: The specified job is ready to start. It is waiting for scheduling from job control. This message is no longer in use in Lifecycle Controller 2.0 as the job control functionality handles this operation.

RAC1128.Description: Any operation involving remote share (CIFS) cannot continue if the location (-l option) is not specified. The -u and -p options represent the user name and password for the remote share, and -l represents the location of the remote share.
RAC1128.Resolution: Make sure to specify the location (-l option) of the remote share along with the user name and password, and retry the operation. To view the list of options that can used for the required subcommand, run the RACADM command "racadm help <subcommand>".
RAC1128.Message: The -l option must be specified if -u and -p options are used.

RAC1133.Description: The BIOSRTDRequested attribute was modified successfully. The BIOS reset to default values operation is pending a server restart.
RAC1133.Resolution: To apply the BIOS default values, restart the server. After the server has restarted, the default BIOS values will be accessible from the iDRAC.
RAC1133.Message: BIOSRTDRequested value is modified successfully. The BIOS reset to default values operation is pending a server restart.

SUP0520.Description: The firmware update operation for the component did not complete due to an internal error.
SUP0520.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0520.Message: Unable to update the %1 firmware to version %2.

PR8.Description: The indicated device has been removed from the system, is no longer functioning, or has been disabled.
PR8.Resolution: If the part is present, make sure it is properly installed. Ensure that the device has not been disabled in the system BIOS or other configuration utility. Contact technical support if the device is still non functional.

OSD42.Description: There was an error while copying the ISO image from the network share to the VFlash.
OSD42.Resolution: 1) Make sure the network connection is working. 2) Make sure the Dell VFlash doesn't have any hardware issues by accessing it through the iDRAC GUI.
OSD42.Message: Downloading ISO File to VFlash failed.

BOOT009.Description: No Boot Sources could be found for the desired Boot Configuration.
BOOT009.Resolution: Verify that Boot Sources for the indicated Boot Configuration are displaying when enumerating DCIM_BootSourceSetting. Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
BOOT009.Message: Boot Sources cannot be found for this Boot Configuration

VDR8.Description: This message occurs when a physical disk in the disk group was removed or when a physical disk included in a redundant virtual disk fails. Because the virtual disk is redundant (uses mirrored or parity information) and only one physical disk has failed, the virtual disk can be rebuilt.
VDR8.Resolution: Configure a hot spare for the virtual disk if it is not already configured. Rebuild the virtual disk. If a physical disk was removed from the disk group, either replace the disk or restore the original disk.

HWC7004.Description: Server health changed to a critical state from either a normal or warning state.
HWC7004.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7004.Message: Server %1 health changed to a critical state from either a normal or warning state.

LIC207.Description: The license has expired. This could result in the loss of functionality that is specific to the features supported by the license.
LIC207.Resolution: Obtain and import a replacement license.

HWC0002.Description: The vFlash SD Card is either not present or not correctly inserted.
HWC0002.Resolution: Insert the vFlash SD card or reinsert the vFlash SD card, and retry the operation.
HWC0002.Message: Unable to detect vFlash SD card.

RED004.Description: The job cannot be run because of an unknown issue.
RED004.Resolution: Check the uniform resource identifier (URI), target path and make sure the repository server is available.
RED004.Message: The job cannot be run because of an unknown issue.

PDR112.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message is approaching the warranted wear-out limit.
PDR112.Message: The %1 has reached %2 of warranted device wear-out limit.

LNK0005.Description: Error occurred while communicating with the DHCP server because the network settings are not configured correctly or the DHCP server could not be contacted.
LNK0005.Resolution: Verify if the network cable is connected and network configuration settings are correct, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the network interface controller (NIC) firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
LNK0005.Message: Unable to connect to DHCP server.

LC070.Description: The configuration XML file used for the import operation does not exist on the specified network share.
LC070.Resolution: Make sure the input configuration XML file for the operation exists on the network share.
LC070.Message: Unable to find the configuration XML import file.

PSU0001.Resolution: Remove and re-install the power supply. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

RED066.Description: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates are staged to run after the next system restart.
RED066.Resolution: A system restart is required to apply the staged updates.
RED066.Message: The recurring scheduled update from repository job completed and updates are staged to run after the next system restart.

PWR8575.Description: A Virtual Reseat for the server identified in the message is initiated. A Virtual Reseat is the same as removing and inserting a server.
PWR8575.Message: Initiated the Virtual Reseat of server %1.

RAC0248.Description: This message is displayed when trying to delete a vFlash partition.
RAC0248.Resolution: Press OK to delete this partition of the SD Card. This action will erase all the data in this partition. If undesired press Cancel.
RAC0248.Message: This operation deletes the partition permanently. Do you want to continue?

FC005.Description: The number of AttributeName and AttributeValue array elements are not equal.
FC005.Resolution: Provide equal number of array elements for AttributeName and AttributeValue parameters. For more information about input parameters, see FC HBA Profile specification.
FC005.Message: The number of AttributeName array elements does not match the AttributeValue array element count.

PCI5009.Description: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected that a PCIe adapter was removed from a server which was turned-on. This may cause the server operating system to stop responding or to function in an improper manner.
PCI5009.Resolution: Perform a 'Power Cycle' operation on the associated server. Restarting the operating system will not resolve this issue. Only remove PCIe adapters when the associated server is turned-off.
PCI5009.Message: The PCIe adapter in the PCIe slot%1 was removed from the slot while the server%2 was turned-on.

UEFI0092.Description: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit.
UEFI0092.Resolution: Check the total number of ranks in each channel to make sure it does not exceed the maximum allowed limit. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0092.Message: The number of DIMM ranks has exceeded the maximum allowed ranks per channel limit.

VLT0210.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0210.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0210.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is outside of range.

RED071.Description: Unable to get the Automatic Backup schedule information because the schedule is not configured.
RED071.Message: Unable to get the Automatic Backup schedule information.

SUP0107.Description: The file path provided as a parameter is too long.
SUP0107.Resolution: Shorten the length of the string given as file path by either moving the file or renaming the folders along the path.

LC045.Description: The CreateConfigJob operation is currently running. The current operation and system restart must complete before the operation can be attempted again.
LC045.Resolution: Wait for the CreateConfigJob operation that is currently running to complete before requesting another operation.
LC045.Message: An instance of CreateConfigJob is already running.

SWC0301.Description: The IP address provided is not valid.
SWC0301.Message: The specified IP address is not valid.

VLT0227.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0227.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0227.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SEC0040.Description: Operating system generated critical stop IPMI event. (Sensor type code = 20H)
SEC0040.Resolution: Check video and operating system logs for additional information
SEC0040.Message: A critical stop occurred during OS load.

PR18.Description: The Part Replacement feature has detected a firmware difference between the current and previous components. Depending on the Part Firmware Update setting value this may cause a firmware update to the replaced part.
PR18.Message: Firmware version difference detected for device: %1

CMC004.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the parameter identified in the message is invalid.
CMC004.Resolution: Enter a valid parameter and retry the operation. For information about valid parameters, see the CMC Profile document available on the support site.
CMC004.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the parameter %1 is invalid.

RAC0246.Description: The contents of a read-only partition cannot be modified.
RAC0246.Resolution: Make sure the partition is writable before attempting to change its contents.

SWC0243.Description: SSL Certificate is regenerated successfully and the Web server is restarted.
SWC0243.Message: Certificate regenerated successfully and webserver restarted

USR0176.Description: The Front Panel USB Port Over Current condition is cleared for the port identified in the message.
USR0176.Message: The Front Panel USB Port Over Current condition is cleared for the attached device Disk.USBFront.%1.

VRM0009.Description: No virtual media was found to disconnect.
VRM0009.Message: No Virtual Media devices are currently connected.

JCP020.Description: Existing jobs cannot be scheduled while an Export Server Profile or Import Server Profile job is running.
JCP020.Resolution: Retry the job scheduling operation after the export or import operation is completed.
JCP020.Message: Cannot schedule jobs while export or import operations are running.

RSI0002.Description: The Remote Service database is currently not available.
RSI0002.Message: The remote service is currently not available

CMC8534.Description: Unable to turn on the server specified in the message, because the available power is lesser than the requested power.
CMC8534.Resolution: In the CMC Web interface, verify the available power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, retry the operation. Otherwise, increase the power cap value.
CMC8534.Message: Unable to turn on the server %1 because the power requirement request exceeds the power cap value.

RED036.Description: Firmware updates are available for component identified in the message in the specified remote repository and it is recommended to update to the firmware available in the repository.
RED036.Resolution: Update the component firmware to the version available in the specified remote repository.

UEFI0129.Description: The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) has encountered an unknown issue. This may be because new error codes are coming from the IDSDM firmware and the system BIOS or the iDRAC firmware need to be updated to process correctly.
UEFI0129.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the system BIOS. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. 3) Reseat or replace the SD card media. Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0129.Message: The Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) has encountered an unknown issue.

SEC0004.Description: The LAN is disconnected. Network performance may be degraded.

SUP0103.Description: The specified TFTP server is not reachable.
SUP0103.Resolution: Check if the TFTP server is alive.
SUP0103.Message: TFTP IP address is not reachable.

PWR2403.Description: The iDRAC controller established communication to the power management firmware. System performance will return to normal.
PWR2403.Message: iDRAC communication with power management firmware has been restored.

CMC8576.Description: The RAC CA Certificate is changed.
CMC8576.Message: The RAC CA Certificate is changed.

RAC0607.Description: The integrated NICs in the system do not support OS to iDRAC Pass-Through.
RAC0607.Resolution: Make sure the integrated NICs are enabled from BIOS setup and support OS to iDRAC Pass-Through, then retry the operation. To access BIOS setup, press F2 during system startup. For more information about OS to iDRAC Pass-Through, see iDRAC7 Users Guide.
RAC0607.Message: Unable to perform OS to iDRAC Pass-Through with the current system configuration.

STOR0107.Description: No EMMs data to display. The system is powered off, no enclosure EMMs are present, or the EMMs are not connected to the enclosures.
STOR0107.Resolution: Check if the server has power, EMMs are available, and EMMs are connected to the enclosure.
STOR0107.Message: EMMs are not connected to enclosures or data about EMMs is unavailable.

ASR8500.Description: Watchdog timer is disabled. The watchdog timer is an internal mechanism used to monitor the health of the Chassis Management Controller. The watchdog timer could be disabled as part of a troubleshooting operation and can be enabled by restarting the Chassis Management Controller.

RAC1051.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid value for the option identified in the message.
RAC1051.Resolution: Retry with a correct value for the option identified in the message. For more information, view the help details by running the RACADM command "racadm help systemconfig backup".
RAC1051.Message: Unable to configure the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings. The option %1 is either invalid or not provided.

HWC1005.Description: The storage adapter may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.

SEC0006.Description: The fan area is open. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0006.Resolution: Close the fan area. Check system logs.

SWC8530.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to set the server administrator access to the iDRAC root user. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or the iDRAC is rebooting
SWC8530.Resolution: If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8530.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to set administrator access to the iDRAC root user.

BOOT017.Description: The boot device(s) specified in the source argument used in the operation cannot be enabled or disabled. This behavior applies to BCV devices and one-time boot.
BOOT017.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on validity of operation for the boot device specified. For more information on the operation, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
BOOT017.Message: Source argument does not support enable or disable mode.

CMC8557.Description: The code number specified in the message is displayed after a firmware error occurs before a failover .
CMC8557.Message: The system health failover is requested. Code %1.

RAC926.Description: The value given for the recurrence interval is invalid. It has to be a value from 0 to 365.
RAC926.Resolution: Change the argument of r to a value from 0 to 365 and then run the same command.
RAC926.Message: The recurrence interval needs to be an integer from 0 to 365.

CTL78.Description: This alert message occurs if controller firmware is flashed.

PDR1106.Message: Drive %1 is in the failed array.

AMP0316.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0316.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0316.Message: System level current is outside of range.

VDR59.Description: This alert message occurs if virtual disk security has failed.

PWR2211.Message: The system is in legacy ON state.

STOR096.Description: A virtual disk cannot be created because the disk space size value entered for the virtual disk is less than the lower limit value (100 MB).
STOR096.Resolution: Enter a value (the -size option) equal or higher than 100 MB, and then retry the operation.
STOR096.Message: Unable to create a virtual disk because the disk space size value entered for the virtual disk is less than the lower limit value (100 MB).

RAC0214.Description: Login page is missing a password.

UEFI0088.Description: Unsupported 8Gb technology DIMM module is installed on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0088.Resolution: Remove the unsupported DIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0088.Message: Unsupported 8Gb technology DIMM module is installed on memory slot: %1.

PWR8674.Description: Unable to change the value of the Allow 110 VAC Operation property because it is not supported in NEBS configuration PWR or PSU.
PWR8674.Message: Unable to change the value of Allow 110 VAC Operation property because it is not supported in NEBS configuration PWR or PSU.

PST0008.Description: System BIOS has started System Management Mode (SMM) initialization.

SEL1211.Description: The time stamp on system event log events may not correlate to the system time. (IPMI sensor type code 12h - offset 05h)
SEL1211.Resolution: Cycle system input power, if problem persists call support.
SEL1211.Message: The time-stamp clock could not be synchronized.

RAC0639.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'minute' while scheduling a job.
RAC0639.Resolution: Enter a correct value from 0 to 59, and then retry the operation.
RAC0639.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid 'minute' value is entered.

NIC023.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in iDRAC.
NIC023.Resolution: Retry the action. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
NIC023.Message: Cannot perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

UEFI0210.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Receive Buffer Vref Training phase.
UEFI0210.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0210.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SWC0288.Description: The object specified in the message in the group specified in the message is not configured.
SWC0288.Resolution: Configure the object specified in the message in specified group, before performing a config to file action.
SWC0288.Message: Object %1 in %2 group must be specified. Line: %3

MEM1008.Message: Memory device at location %1 is offline.

UEFI0117.Description: Card identification signature is not present on Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card 1.
UEFI0117.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Check the IDSDM or the SD card media. 2) Try reseat or replace the SD card media. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0117.Message: Card identification signature is not present on Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card 1.

LIC211.Description: License import/delete/expiration resulted in a feature set change.
LIC211.Message: The iDRAC feature set has changed.

CMC8605.Description: The chassis health state is no longer OK and is currently the state identified in the message. Actions should be taken to resolve any outstanding issues so that the chassis health state will return to OK.
CMC8605.Resolution: Review the Chassis log or the Chassis Management Controller(CMC) SEL log for any outstanding issue(s) and resolve any issues found by performing the recommended response action for each issue found. If the issue persists, export the chassis log and CMC SEL log and contact your support provider.
CMC8605.Message: The chassis health state is no longer OK and is currently %1.

PCI1342.Description: System performance may be degraded. The device has failed to respond to a transaction (master/target abort or completion timeout).
PCI1342.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1342.Message: A bus time-out was detected on a component at slot %1.

TMP1004.Description: The enclosure temperature sensor identified in the message is operating within the upper and lower configured temperature thresholds.
TMP1004.Message: The temperature sensor %1 is now within configured threshold values.

CTL56.Description: The text for this alert is generated by the controller and can vary depending on the situation. This text is from events in the controller event log that were generated while Storage Management was not running.
CTL56.Resolution: See the hardware documentation for more information.

HWC2008.Description: The fabric type for the IOM and mezzanine cards must match. Once an IOM or mezzanine card is inserted into the chassis, the fabric type is then set for the CMC and the CMC will ensure that all subsequent IOM's and mezzanine cards match.
HWC2008.Resolution: Check chassis fabric type in CMC GUI and compare to the type of IOM or mezzanine card.
HWC2008.Message: A fabric mismatch detected for mezzanine card %1.

VF004.Description: The value of the input parameter identified in the message is not a valid value.
VF004.Resolution: Refer the iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller User Guides for the required input parameters for this method.

VFL0014.Description: The vFlash SD card is not initialized. Either the card is not properly formatted or it may not be supported.
VFL0014.Resolution: Format the vFlash SD card by running the command "racadm vflashsd initialize". Make sure that the card is supported by contacting your service provider for a list of supported SD card types.
VFL0014.Message: The vFlash SD card is not initialized.

RED084.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because of an issue in the communication between iDRAC and CMC.
RED084.Resolution: Verify the status of CMC by accessing the CMC and making sure it is functioning and responding and then retry the operation. For more information about troubleshooting a CMC issue, see the CMC User Manual. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RED084.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware because of an issue in the network communication between iDRAC and CMC.

RAC0768.Description: iDRAC firmware is recently updated and iDRAC is still in the process of initializing. It is recommended to wait a few minutes before logging in so that the iDRAC initialization process can fully complete.
RAC0768.Resolution: Wait a few minutes to log in to iDRAC. Some iDRAC features may not be available for use if log in is continued at this time.
RAC0768.Message: iDRAC is currently initializing. Try logging in to iDRAC after few minutes because iDRAC is initializing after a recent firmware update process.

IOID005.Description: The Storage Initiator Persistence Policy setting is changed to the restart type identified in the message.
IOID005.Message: Storage Initiator Persistence Policy setting is changed to %1.

RAC0104.Description: An invalid PIN was entered. Too many log in attempts with a Smart Card login can result in a user being locked out of the system.
RAC0104.Resolution: 1. Enter a valid Smart Card PIN and try again.2. Use a different Smart Card.

RED039.Description: Settings for an Automatic Server Profile Backup, Automatic Update, or other recurring operations identified in the message were cleared. The recurring operation identified in the message is deleted.
RED039.Message: Settings for a recurring operation of type %1 were cleared.

UEFI0203.Description: A failing memory buffer has been identified on the memory riser identified in the message.
UEFI0203.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0203.Message: A failing memory buffer has been detected during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

PDR78.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR78.Message: %1 state changed from Non-RAID to READY.

PWR203.Description: The System Input Power Cap value cannot be set to less than or equal to 13300 W, because the Extended Power Performance feature is enabled.
PWR203.Resolution: Enter a Power cap value greater than 13300 W, and then retry the operation.
PWR203.Message: Unable to set the System Input Power Cap value to less than or equal to 13300 W (45381 BTU/h), because the Extended Power Performance feature is enabled.

BAR089.Description: A problem has been detected with the installation of the Unified Server Configurator (USC). This needs to be corrected before a valid Backup file can be created.
BAR089.Resolution: Obtain the Dell update package for the Unified Server Configurator and apply it. Then perform a Backup operation to save this data, for later restore.
BAR089.Message: Lifecycle Controller needs to be updated.

RED006.Description: The Update Package cannot be successfully downloaded.
RED006.Resolution: Check the network connection and access to the update package from the iDRAC.

OSE0005.Description: Graceful shutdown request to an agent via the BMC did not occur due to a system hardware or software exception.
OSE0005.Resolution: review operating system logs and system video for additional information

LIC010.Description: A license is not imported to the iDRAC when one of the following conditions exists:1) The license is not for the iDRAC.2) The target system may not be upgraded to the product class specified by the license (for example, user may not upgrade from an express product class to an enterprise product class).
LIC010.Resolution: Verify this system may be upgraded to the product class specified by the license. If this system cannot be upgraded to the product class specified, obtain a new license file.
LIC010.Message: Import failed: This license is not for the specified device.

PR33.Description: The platform system motherboard was replaced.

PCI1354.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next scheduled service time.
PCI1354.Message: A bus correctable error was detected on a component at slot %1.

UEFI0186.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the DC Detection phase.
UEFI0186.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0186.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

SUP0517.Description: The firmware image specified in the operation did not apply successfully. An internal error may have occurred.
SUP0517.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, download the latest update package from your service provider, and retry the operation.
SUP0517.Message: Unable to update the %1 firmware to version %2.

JCP018.Description: A new job cannot be created until the existing Export job is completed or the job is deleted. There can only be one Export Server Profile job running at a time.
JCP018.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation after the Export Server Profile job is completed. 2) Delete the scheduled Export job and retry the operation.
JCP018.Message: Cannot create new jobs until the existing Export job is completed or the job is cancelled.

LC016.Description: A required method argument was missing.
LC016.Resolution: Include all the parameters required for the command. Check Lifecycle Controller Profile documentation and try again.

RFL2008.Description: The Internal Dual SD Card redundancy feature was disabled. The SD card identified in the message is disabled.
RFL2008.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is disabled.

BAR054.Description: The attempt to clean up after an unsuccessful Backup/Restore of a system profile operation has not been successful. The Lifecycle Controller/System Services related operations may not execute as expected until the system is properly restored to a functional configuration.
BAR054.Resolution: Enter the iDRAC configuration utility. Select the System Services option in the main selection screen. Choose the Cancel Lifecycle Controller Actions / Cancel System Services operation and follow the directions to ensure this operation is performed. If Cancel Lifecycle Controller Actions / Cancel System Services is not available, remove power from the system, wait 1 minute and reapply power. If the issue persists, contact your technical service provider.
BAR054.Message: System Reset or Lifecycle Controller Actions Canceled, System Profile Failure Recovery unsuccessful.

STOR020.Description: The controller key cannot be set because a key is already present.
STOR020.Resolution: Delete the current key and retry the operation.
STOR020.Message: A controller key is already present.

SUP0105.Description: The firmware image provided by the user is not valid.

BAR112.Description: Server Profile backup file validation failed because the target system identifier information does not match the value stored in the file. The Server Profile file may be from another system or the iDRAC may need to be restarted to acquire the system identifier information accurately.
BAR112.Resolution: Obtain a valid Server Profile file for the target system and try the operation again. If the problem reoccurs, restart the iDRAC and try the operation again.
BAR112.Message: The system identifier in the Server Profile file does not match the target system.

PSU0033.Resolution: Check the system operating environment, including airflow and inlet temperature. Check system logs for temperature and thermal component failures.
PSU0033.Message: The temperature for power supply %1 is outside of range.

CTL101.Description: The controller identified in the message is disabled by a user action.

RAC022.Description: Unable to set values for User Password, IPMILan, IPMISerial or User Admin Privilege because the User Name is not configured.
RAC022.Resolution: Set User Name before attempting to set values of other identified attributes.
RAC022.Message: Unable to set values for User Password, IPMILan, IPMISerial or User Admin Privilege because the User Name is not configured.

SYS087.Description: When the configuration XML file specified in the Preview operation is imported to the system, a system reboot will occur to apply the configuration changes.
SYS087.Message: A system reboot will occur when the previewed configuration XML file is imported to the system.

SWC0312.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0312.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0312.Message: Invalid syntax. The -u option is not valid with any other options.

OSE1002.Description: The system OS has successfully booted from C:

DIS103.Description: The network share folder cannot be accessed by using the credentials specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.
DIS103.Resolution: Verify whether or not the following are correctly entered in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC, and then retry the operation: 1) Network share name. 2) The IP address of the network share folder. 3) The username and password (-u <username> & -p <password>)
DIS103.Message: The AutoConfig operation is unable to access a network share folder, because incorrect credentials are specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

STOR8.Description: High Availability RAID is not supported by this firmware release. This event may occur during the upgrade process.
STOR8.Message: Detected two RAID controllers in integrated slots. This configuration is not currently supported and the second controller will not be powered on.

SWU8556.Description: The sled network uplink on the sled identified in the message could not be configured. The servers on the sled may not have expected network connectivity.
SWU8556.Resolution: Perform a Virtual Reseat operation, and then retry the operation. To virtually reseat a server 1) Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components, and then select slot for the component identified in the message and apply the Virtual Reseat or 2) Run the following RACADM command at the command line interface: "racadm serveraction -f -m sled-<slot number> reseat".
SWU8556.Message: Unable to configure the sled network uplink on sled %1.

BAT1008.Description: The controller battery cannot maintain cached data for the required period of time. For example, if the required period of time is 24 hours, then the battery cannot maintain cached data for 24 hours.
BAT1008.Resolution: Verify the battery health is good. See the storage hardware documentation to verify battery health. Contact technical support.
BAT1008.Message: Write policy on %1 was changed to Write Through.

STOR026.Description: A configuration job was not created because there are no pending configuration changes.
STOR026.Message: A configuration job was not created because there are no pending configuration changes.

BOOT002.Description: Unable to allocate required memory to perform the operation
BOOT002.Resolution: Power cycle system and reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.

USR0152.Description: Could not successfully connect to the remote VNC session, because an incorrect VNC password was entered from the IP address identified in the message.
USR0152.Resolution: Enter the correct VNC password and retry the operation.
USR0152.Message: Unable to connect the remote VNC session, because an incorrect VNC password was entered from the IP %1.

SYS031.Description: The configuration is being applied to a component.

CTL4.Description: You have disabled the controller alarm. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

FAN903.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode cannot be enabled because an unsupported fan is present in the Chassis.
FAN903.Resolution: Insert a fan that is supported by the Chassis, and then retry the operation. For a list of fans that are supported by Chassis, see the Chassis Management Controller Users Guide.
FAN903.Message: Cannot enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode because an unsupported fan is inserted in the Chassis.

BAR039.Description: The license required for operation is not present.
BAR039.Resolution: Use supported vFlash media and licensing for this feature, and try the operation again.

VDR41.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SYS164.Description: The System Erase operation attempted to access Lifecycle Controller internal storage that is already being accessed by another function. Exclusive access to the internal storage is required for the System Erase operation. The System Erase operation attempts Lifecycle Controller internal storage access for 10 minutes. After the timeout the current job completes with an unsuccessful status.
SYS164.Resolution: Check the server and make sure that it is not in BIOS POST startup processing or stopped in the POST phase of startup. PWR8686.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware identified in the message to the supported latest available version and retry the operation. For information about the supported firmware versions, refer to the Chassis Management Controller user's Guide available at the support site.

BOOT006.Description: One or more of the Boot Source instance ID's does not contain valid data.

SYS064.Description: The input file for the import configuration operation contains invalid XML data at the line specified.

SWU8506.Description: Completed the Firmware update operation for the CMC identified in the message..

IOV115.Resolution: Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM command line interface, run the command "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerCap <Power cap>" to increase the power cap or add an additional power supply.

RDU0013.Resolution: Check the event log for power supply failures. Review system configuration and power consumption.

BAR111.Resolution: If the managed system does not turn off during Import, turn off the system and retry the operation. If the managed system turned off, restart the Remote Access Controller and retry the operation. If the export was to a network share verify the connection and try the operation again. If the export destination was the vFlash media, insert a new SD card and try the operation again.

PWR8509.Description: Unable to change the server power priority because Server Based Power Management mode is enabled.
PWR8509.Resolution: The server power priority can be changed once Server Based Power Management mode is disabled. Using the CMC Web UI, navigate to the Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration page, then uncheck the Enable Server Based Power Management checkbox. Retry the operation.
PWR8509.Message: Unable to change the server power priority because Server Based Power Management mode is enabled.

PWR8501.Description: Power allocation succeeded for Virtual infrastructure.
PWR8501.Message: Successfully set Virtual Infrastructure Device power to %1 WDC

RAC0667.Description: This setting will be applied after the server has been turned off and turned on again. This may result in loss of configuration and/or access physical disk drive(s) or virtual disk(s) being marked offline. This may also result in some disk(s) being identified as foreign disks. Foreign physical disk drive(s) or virtual disk(s) can be imported or cleared.
RAC0667.Message: This setting will be applied after the server has been turned off and turned on again. This may result in loss of configuration and/or access to physical disk drive(s).

SUP0120.Message: Preparing for firmware update. Please wait...

PDR1.Description: This message is generated after a copyback stops on a physical disk during a rebuild operation.
PDR1.Resolution: Wait for rebuild to finish, then copyback should resume.

USR8503.Description: The Active Directory authentication was not successful for the specified username.
USR8503.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used in the operation are correct.
USR8503.Message: Domain user authentication was not successful. Reason code = %1

RAC029.Description: The operation cannot be completed because necessary dependency values are not found in the input.
RAC029.Resolution: Refer to the Dell Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide and Profile Documents available at the support site, and then retry the operation.
RAC029.Message: Unable to complete the operation because necessary dependency values are not found in the input.

IOV010.Description: Unable to assign the PCIe slots because a license is required to assign more than two PCIe slots to a server. Non-licensed systems are allowed only two slots per server.
IOV010.Resolution: Import a license that allows assignments of more than two PCIe slots per server. For more information about licenses, contact your service provider.
IOV010.Message: Unable to assign the PCIe slot(s) because a license is required to assign more than two PCIe slots to a server.

VF034.Description: The specified partition access type is not a valid type.
VF034.Resolution: Try a partition access type that is supported.

SEC0045.Message: Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) is operating correctly.

LOG506.Description: The requested operation cannot be started because the ExportChassisLog operation is already running.
LOG506.Resolution: Wait for the current ExportChassisLog operation to complete and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
LOG506.Message: Unable to start the requested operation because the ExportChassisLog operation is already running.

SWC0116.Description: The syntax of the setniccfg command is invalid.
SWC0116.Resolution: Refer the help text for setniccfg subcommand.
SWC0116.Message: The -s option requires IP address, subnet mask, and gateway.

PWR205.Description: The Server Performance Over Power Redundancy (SPOPR) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.
PWR205.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR205.Message: The Server Performance Over Power Redundancy (SPOPR) feature cannot be enabled because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.

RED013.Description: The DUP specified is not compatible with the target device.
RED013.Resolution: Download and use the DUP that matches the device being targeted.
RED013.Message: The DUP specified is not compatible with the target device.

UEFI0011.Description: A CPU general protection (type 0x0D) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0011.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

FAN8501.Description: Disabling Enhanced Cooling Mode allows for reduced power consumption by reducing the maximum speed of the blowers while still providing sufficient blade airflow.

JCP006.Description: One or more of the specified values for creating a job are invalid or an internal error has occurred when scheduling the job.
JCP006.Resolution: Use the correct value for the job attribute and retry the operation.

PSU0032.Resolution: Check the system operating environment, including airflow and inlet temperature. Check system logs for temperature and thermal component failures.
PSU0032.Message: The temperature for power supply %1 is in a warning range.

SWC0046.Description: Unable to initiate Import operation since another Import operation is already in progress.
SWC0046.Resolution: Wait until current Import operation is complete before initiating a new Import operation.

SYS119.Description: The OS collector cannot be exposed to the host server because of communication issues between the iDRAC and server OS.
SYS119.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and server OS.
SYS119.Message: Unable to expose the OS Collector to the server OS.

PCI1316.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1316.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1316.Message: A bus uncorrectable error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

FAN904.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode cannot be enabled because the Maximum Power Conservation Mode is enabled.
FAN904.Resolution: Disable the Maximum Power Conservation Mode, and then retry the operation. To disable the mode by using CMC Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Configuration. To disable the mode using the RACADM utility, run the command "racadm config -g cfgThermal -o cfgThermalEnhancedCoolingMode 0".
FAN904.Message: Cannot enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode because the Maximum Power Conservation Mode is enabled.

PCI5006.Description: The power related issue of the PCIe device in the slot identified in the message is resolved.
PCI5006.Message: The power-related issue of the PCIe adapter in slot%1 is resolved.

CBL0003.Description: The backplane cable identified in the message is disconnected or no cable is detected.
CBL0003.Resolution: Reconnect or replace the cable identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

CMC8535.Description: Unable to turn on the server specified in the message because of an internal CMC error.
CMC8535.Resolution: Reboot CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, reseat the server and retry the operation.
CMC8535.Message: Unable to turn on High Power Management for the server %1

STOR019.Description: The passphrase specified does not follow the passphrase character criteria of the controller character.
STOR019.Resolution: Enter a passphrase that meets the passphrase character criteria of the controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR019.Message: The specified passphrase is not valid.

SYS078.Description: Unable to retrieve the system configuration XML file from the network share for the requested preview operation. This may be due to issues with network accessibility.
SYS078.Resolution: If the configuration XML file is on an NFS share, make sure that the network share is accessible from iDRAC. If the configuration XML file is on a CIFS share, make sure that the network share is accessible from iDRAC using the share credentials specified. Test the network share access using the Test Network Connection method. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
SYS078.Message: Unable to retrieve the system configuration XML file from the network share for preview.

SWC1922.Description: The user identified in the message has successfully modified the server configuration by using Quick Sync.
SWC1922.Message: User %1 has successfully modified the server configuration by using Quick Sync.

SYS174.Description: The Tech Support Report (TSR) cannot be exported because of an issue while connecting to the network share using the provided credentials or other network share parameters.
SYS174.Resolution: Make sure the entered sharetype, sharename, IP address, username and password are valid and retry the operation. The network share connectivity can be tested by using the Test Network Connection feature of the iDRAC.
SYS174.Message: Unable to access network share for exporting Tech Support Report (TSR).

SWC0016.Description: The operating system driver pack is missing or not accessible.
SWC0016.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation.
SWC0016.Message: Unable to initialize OS Deployment wizard.

SEC0604.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0604.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

USR8509.Description: The login attempt with details specified in the message was not successful.
USR8509.Resolution: Contact the administrator and ensure the username and password credentials used are correct. Retry the operation with valid credentials.
USR8509.Message: Login was not successful (username=%1, ip=%2, error=0x%3, type=%4)

RDU0030.Description: The storage voltage of the device identified in the message is redundant.
RDU0030.Message: The storage voltage of %1 is redundant.

STOR076.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because at least one other pending operation was found on the RAID controller. This operation needs exclusivity because it involves changing RAID backplane topology.
STOR076.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending operations, allow the job to complete, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR076.Message: Enclosure configuration mode (Split/Unified) cannot be changed because there are already pending operations.

PSU0910.Description: The system did not respond correctly to a power down request.
PSU0910.Message: Soft power control failure detected on power unit %1.

DKM1000.Resolution: Check for network connectivity. Review network, server, and client configuration.
DKM1000.Message: A network problem detected. Cannot contact key management server.

SYS081.Description: Successfully previewed system configuration XML file import operation.
SYS081.Message: Successfully previewed system configuration XML file import operation.

PWR8665.Description: The property chassis power button is either enabled or disabled as identified in the message.

PST0003.Description: System BIOS has started chipset initialization.

HWC5014.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
HWC5014.Message: %1 is not functional and is powered off.

RAC044.Description: Some event filter settings were not updated due to problems encountered processing the input parameters.
RAC044.Resolution: Verify the input parameters provided and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC044.Message: Unable to update some event filter settings.

UEFI0169.Description: Memory could not be interleaved because low memory (i.e. memory below the 4GB boundary) cannot be split evenly across processor sockets during memory initialization.
UEFI0169.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure interleaving can be supported. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0169.Message: Unable to configure memory interleaving on DIMM modules on memory slots: %1.

CTL60.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL60.Message: A user has discarded data from the %1 cache.

SWC0083.Description: The iDRAC has been successfully removed from Integrated Data Center network per user action. The iDRAC will now be set to Factory defaults. The iDRAC will be able to show up in an Integrated Data Center only when it is rediscovered.
SWC0083.Message: The iDRAC is successfully removed from the Integrated Data Center network.

SWU8525.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful. The update process was not completed within the firmware update timeout duration.
SWU8525.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWU8525.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware on the server in slot %1. The firmware update timeout limit is exceeded.

PSU0911.Message: Soft power control restored on power unit %1.

SUP0515.Description: Lifecycle Controller was unable to authenticate the Update Package digital signature. The Update Package will not be applied unless it has a valid digital signature.
SUP0515.Resolution: Download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0515.Message: Unable to authenticate the Update Package signature.

RAC023.Description: Unable to enable the User or set values for IPMILan, IPMISerial, or User Admin Privilege because the User Password is not configured.
RAC023.Resolution: Set User Password before attempting to enable the other identified attributes.
RAC023.Message: Unable to enable the User or set values for IPMILan, IPMISerial, or User Admin Privilege because the User Password is not configured.

RAC0742.Description: A Secure Erase operation on a PCIe SSD overwrites all blocks in an encrypted way and all the data on the PCIe SSD device will be permanently lost. The changes will happen after reboot of the system or loss of power to the drive.
RAC0742.Message: The Secure Erase command will be executed on the selected PCIe SSD disk drives(s) only after the reboot of the system or loss of power to the disk drives(s).

SWC0313.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0313.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0313.Message: Invalid syntax. The -h option is not valid with any other options.

PDR82.Description: Security on a secure encrypted disk was activated.

PWR8675.Description: AC power supply is detected in the NEBS configuration.
PWR8675.Message: AC power supply is detected in the NEBS configuration.

BAT0015.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.
BAT0015.Resolution: Check the battery at the next service window.

PDR1107.Message: Rebuild is in progress for drive %1.

SWC0074.Description: The export operation of SupportAssist collection cannot be started because the current version of iDRAC firmware does not support the operation.
SWC0074.Resolution: Update iDRAC firmware to the latest version and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC0074.Message: Unable to start operation with the current iDRAC version.

SWC0270.Description: Local Configuration using RACADM may be disabled.
SWC0270.Resolution: Check if the Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled and enable it through GUI.
SWC0270.Message: Unable to clear the SEL. Possible reason may be that Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled.

PSU0907.Resolution: Remove input power at the power supply.
PSU0907.Message: An interlock power down error was corrected for power unit %1.

RAC1054.Description: Successfully cleared the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.
RAC1054.Message: Successfully cleared the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings.

SWC1912.Description: User ID Access Right has been changed.
SWC1912.Message: User ID %1 User Access Right has been changed.

BIOS016.Description: A set attribute operation was attempted on a disabled attribute.
BIOS016.Message: AttributeValue cannot be changed for disabled AttributeName %1.

RAC0507.Description: The requested information cannot be displayed, because the system did not find any matching resource. This occurs because the system is turned off, resource is not present, or the resource is removed or deleted. For example, resources such as physicals disks, vFlash SD card, SSL certificate or custom signing certificate.
RAC0507.Resolution: Do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Turn on the system. 2) Make the resource available.
RAC0507.Message: Unable to find the requested resource.

SWC0079.Description: iDRAC entered into Dell Integrated Data Center Troubleshooting Mode
SWC0079.Message: iDRAC entered into Integrated Data Center Troubleshooting Mode.

STOR7.Description: The storage monitoring instrumentation detected a burst of events from underlying storage controllers. To overcome this overload condition, all the outstanding events have been purged and a fresh inventory will be performed automatically.
STOR7.Message: The storage management instrumentation is performing an inventory refresh operation.

SWC8620.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate with the iDRAC in server slot identified in the message.
SWC8620.Resolution: Reset the server iDRAC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8620.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to communicate with the iDRAC in server slot %1.

HWC0009.Description: The vFlash SD card is missing or not inserted correctly. iDRAC is not able to enable vFlash SD card.
HWC0009.Resolution: Reinsert the vFlash SD card and retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
HWC0009.Message: Unable to enable vFlash SD card.

RAC1019.Description: Some objects have dependencies on other objects that are required to perform a task. The specified object is not available because of such dependencies.
RAC1019.Resolution: Verify the object dependency using "racadm help <device class>.<groupname>.<objectname>", and retry the operation. For example, racadm help NIC.VndrConfigGroup.1.VirtWWPN.
RAC1019.Message: The specified object is not supported for the current system configuration.

VFL0721.Description: The SD card Initialization did not complete within the maximum process allotted time.
VFL0721.Message: Error occurred while initializing the SD Card due to a timeout.

VDR17.Description: A physical disk included in the virtual disk failed.
VDR17.Resolution: Replace the failed physical disk. Identify the failed physical disk by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. Rebuild the physical disk. When finished, restart the virtual disk format operation.

LIC012.Description: This error may occur if: 1) The license was deleted by another user. 2) The license that is being imported may have been deleted from the temporary storage before the import operation completed.3) At start-up, License Manager does not find the license assigned to the device. This may occur if a power outage occurs before a license delete operation completes.
LIC012.Message: The license file does not exist.

LIC003.Description: System resources may be unavailable at the time command is issued.
LIC003.Resolution: Re-issue the command. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC003.Message: License Manager was unable to create and/or allocate the required resources.

SYS046.Description: An error occurred while copying the system configuration XML file from the network share.
SYS046.Resolution: If the file is being copied from an NFS share, make sure that it is accessible from iDRAC. If the file is being copied from a CIFS share, make sure that it is accessible from iDRAC using the share credentials provided. Test the network share access using the Test Network Connection method. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
SYS046.Message: Unable to import the system configuration XML file from the network share.

HWC4017.Description: The system has detected an unsupported hardware component. A hardware incompatibility is detected between the components identified in the message.
HWC4017.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Review system documentation for the hardware components identified in the message. 2) Replace unsupported components with supported components.
HWC4017.Message: A hardware incompatibility is detected between %1%2 and %3%4.

SWC0146.Message: Last ASR screen was cleared successfully

HWC2012.Description: The fabric type on the server does not match that of the IO module.
HWC2012.Resolution: Check chassis fabric type in CMC GUI and compare to the type of IOM or mezzanine card.
HWC2012.Message: A fabric mismatch detected on fabric %1 with server in slot %2.

SWC0004.Description: The operation to add a work note to the Lifecycle Log encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0004.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0004.Message: Unable to add a work note to the Lifecycle Log.

PWR8592.Description: The request to turn on or turn off the chassis was issued before the previous power operation was completed.
PWR8592.Resolution: Retry the operation after the current operation is complete.
PWR8592.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on or turn off the chassis because another chassis power operation is in progress.

SEC0005.Description: A removable component may have been tampered with, or installed incorrectly, or does not meet system requirements.
SEC0005.Resolution: Check removable hardware components for correct installation. Review installation documentation.

SYS070.Description: The configuration changes that require system reboot into the UEFI environment on the system did not complete for all components.
SYS070.Message: Configuration changes that require system reboot were not applied.

SUP023.Description: Duplicate/Invalid JobID was provided as input for scheduling.
SUP023.Resolution: Verify the job ID and retry the action. Retrieve all open jobs by issuing the GetAllJobs command.
SUP023.Message: Duplicate JobID provided as inputs for scheduling.

SWC8536.Description: The add key operation did not complete successfully for the slot identified in the message due to the key being invalid or corrupt.
SWC8536.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8536.Message: Unable to add key for slot %1 of service account, due to corrupt key.

SWC0262.Description: The IPMI drivers or the RAC controller may not be installed.
SWC0262.Resolution: Check if the required modules are installed.
SWC0262.Message: Unable to perform operation. Please make sure RAC controller and appropriate IPMI drivers are installed.

OSD29.Description: Driver Pack configuration file not found in Lifecycle Controller. Driver Pack may be unusable.
OSD29.Resolution: Update the Driver Pack using USC or DUP and then rerun the command.
OSD29.Message: Driver Pack configuration file not found in Lifecycle Controller. The Driver Pack might be corrupt.

SWC0156.Message: CSR file downloaded from RAC successfully

PR2.Description: The specified device configuration is different from the previous device configuration.

RAC0640.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'hour' while scheduling a job.
RAC0640.Resolution: Enter a correct value from 0 to 23, and then retry the operation.
RAC0640.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid 'hour' value is entered.

RAC0636.Description: The requested network file share cannot be accessed, because an invalid proxy password is entered.
RAC0636.Resolution: Enter a valid proxy password, and then retry the operation.
RAC0636.Message: Unable to access the network file share, because an invalid proxy password is entered.

VLT0212.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0212.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat hard disks in the bay. Reconnect all cables attached to the bay.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0212.Message: The disk drive bay %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

RAC0741.Description: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on the selected PCIe SSD disk drive(s), because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0741.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0741.Message: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on the selected PCIe SSD disk drive(s), because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

STOR0503.Description: Existing RAID configuration was successfully erased.

ENC3.Description: The physical disk enclosure is either hotter or cooler than the maximum or minimum allowable temperature range.
ENC3.Resolution: Check for factors that may cause overheating or excessive cooling. For example, verify that the enclosure fan is working. You should also check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source.
