Make sure the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot or too cold. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information.

FAN8503.Description: The Chassis was turned off because more than two Chassis internal fans stopped functioning. The fans with issues are identified in the CMC Hardware (System Event Log) and Chassis Logs.
FAN8503.Resolution: Make sure that the Chassis internal fans are functioning. At the command line interface (CLI), enter the following command to identify fans that are not functioning: "racadm getsel". Using the CMC Web GUI, select the chassis, click the Logs tab, and then select Hardware Log. Reinsert or replace fans that are not functioning correctly.
FAN8503.Message: The Chassis was turned off because more than two internal fans stopped functioning.

BAR100.Description: An error occurred accessing license data. Cannot collect license data to copy to Server Profile backup file.
BAR100.Resolution: Refer to License Management documentation for re-installation of license(s) instructions and retry the operation.

IOV2008.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) could not successfully connect to the PCIe subsystem.
IOV2008.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Perform an AC Power Cycle operation on the Chassis by disconnecting the chassis from AC power, wait for 30 seconds, and then reconnect AC power. 2) Turn on at least one server. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Server Overview->Power->Control and select the Power On Server option. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
IOV2008.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to communicate with the PCIe subsystem.

RAC1060.Description: The system inventory information may not be current because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.
RAC1060.Resolution: To enable the CSIOR feature, run the RACADM command "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart 1". Then restart the server to cause system inventory information to be collected.
RAC1060.Message: System inventory may not be current because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

ENC6.Description: The controller is unable to communicate with an enclosure. There are several reasons for communication loss. For example, there may be a bad or loose cable. An unusual amount of I/O may also interrupt communication with the enclosure. In addition, communication loss may be caused by software, hardware, or firmware problems, bad or failed power supplies, and enclosure shutdown.
ENC6.Resolution: Check for problems with the cables. See the Cables attached correctly section for more information on checking the cables. You should also check to see if the enclosure has degraded or failed components. To do this, select the enclosure object in the tree view and click the Health subtab. The Health subtab displays the status of the enclosure components. Verify that the controller has the supported driver and firmware versions installed and that each Enclosure Management Modules (EMMs) are running the same version of supported firmware.

RED044.Description: The license required to perform the operation identified in the message either has expired or was removed and the iDRAC was unable to create the next job in the sequence.
RED044.Resolution: Install an iDRAC license that supports the following features: Automatic Update or Server Profile Export and Import. After the appropriate license has been installed, retry the operation.
RED044.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was unable to create a job because the required license is not available now.

LC036.Description: The Lifecycle Controller has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote command.
LC036.Resolution: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the Lifecycle Controller by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system.

BAT1018.Description: The temperature of the battery is high. This may be due to the battery being charged.
BAT1018.Resolution: If the battery is being charged, then charging the battery should be stopped until the battery cools down and charging should be resumed. If this is not case, then some other condition exists and should be investigated.

RAC927.Description: The recurrence value was successfully modified to the specified value.

RAC948.Description: A test event notification for the specified message ID was not sent to the configured destination.
RAC948.Resolution: Make sure to the use a valid message ID, set the required notification filter, and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC948.Message: Unable to send the notification for the specified event to the configured destination.

SYS050.Description: The system configuration XML file for the import configuration operation is not compliant with schema nesting checks. Only RAID controllers can have nested Component nodes up to a maximum nesting depth of three.
SYS050.Resolution: Make sure that the system configuration XML file is compliant with the system configuration schema published on delltechcenter.com/lc in the LC XML Schema Guide. Only RAID controllers can have nested Component nodes.
SYS050.Message: The system configuration XML file for import configuration is not compliant with schema nesting checks.

CMC8578.Description: The Remote Access Controller (RAC) SSL Certificate and key is changed.
CMC8578.Message: The Remote Access Controller (RAC) SSL Certificate and key is changed

CBL0005.Description: The backplane connector identified in the message is incorrectly connected to the motherboard SATA controller.
CBL0005.Resolution: Make sure the cable identified in the message is cabled correctly. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0005.Message: Backplane %1 %2 connector incorrectly connected to the motherboard SATA controller.

RDU0015.Description: The system may power down or operate in a performance degraded state.
RDU0015.Resolution: Check the event log for power supply failures. Review system configuration and power consumption and upgrade or install power supplies accordingly.
RDU0015.Message: The power supplies are not redundant. Insufficient resources to maintain normal operations.

PDR110.Description: The reliability of the PCIe solid state device identified in the message degraded. Data loss is possible.
PDR110.Resolution: Back up the data on the device, and contact your service provider for further instructions.

HWC5002.Description: The fabric type for the IOM and mezzanine cards must match. Once an IOM or mezzanine card is inserted into the chassis, the fabric type is then set for the CMC and the CMC will ensure that all subsequent IOM's and mezzanine cards match.
HWC5002.Resolution: Check chassis fabric type in CMC GUI and compare to the type of IOM or mezzanine card.

PST0256.Description: System BIOS detected a functional or configuration issue during system POST. Check the system video screen for more information. The system event log may contain additional details.
PST0256.Resolution: Check system video and review event log for additional information.

OSD21.Description: Booting to ISO has failed. Either BIOS was unable to boot to the ISO image or the provider did not get a response in 5 minutes from BIOS on successful boot to ISO image.
OSD21.Resolution: 1) Make sure that a POST error did not result in user interaction (Press F1 to continue or F2 to run BIOS setup). 2) Reset iDRAC and rerun the command.
OSD21.Message: Unable to boot to ISO image.

MEM0020.Message: Memory device at location %1 is enabled.

SWC0051.Description: Unable to retrieve license information due to an iDRAC communication error.
SWC0051.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0051.Message: Unable to retrieve iDRAC license information.

MEM1009.Message: Memory device at location %1 failed to transition to offline.

SUP0110.Description: The firmware update is being uninitialized.
SUP0110.Message: Uninitializing firmware update services. Please wait...

SEC0041.Description: TXT initialization cannot be completed because system configuration may have changed.
SEC0041.Resolution: Check system hardware inventory for TPM presence, clear and reconfigure TPM and TXT in BIOS setup menu.
SEC0041.Message: BIOS is unable to configure the Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT).

STOR0502.Description: No RAID controller is installed on the system.
STOR0502.Resolution: Install the RAID controller and do the following: 1) Reboot the system.2) Press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller.3) Retry RAID configuration.
STOR0502.Message: Unable to launch RAID Configuration wizard.

MEM1205.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed.
MEM1205.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>
MEM1205.Message: Memory mirror redundancy is lost. Check memory device at location(s) %1.

SWC0134.Message: The RAC log was cleared successfully

SYS123.Description: An unexpected issue has occurred. This could be because the application encountered an unexpected exception or was terminated by a user. This issue could also be because the application was running in an unsupported OS.
SYS123.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the OS Collector on the iDRAC to the most recent version available, and then retry the operation.
SYS123.Message: OS Collector: An unexpected issue has been encountered.

BIOS027.Description: The attribute identified in the message cannot be set, because the password is currently being reset by using plain text. The BIOS password cannot be simultaneously configured by using plain text and a hash.
BIOS027.Resolution: Wait until the current password configuration process is completed, and then retry the operation.
BIOS027.Message: Unable to change the BIOS password because the password is currently being configured using plain text. Unable to set the attribute %1.

LC065.Description: The static IPv4 information for the iDRAC represented by the related iDRACCard Attributes must be configured correctly.
LC065.Resolution: Configure the iDRAC static IP address information by setting the related iDRACCard Attributes. The related attributes that must be configured are the following:: 1) In the IPv4 group: Address, NetMask, Gateway, DNS1 2) In the NIC Static group: DNSDomainName.
LC065.Message: The iDRAC static IP address information is not fully configured. The missing attribute InstanceID is %1.

MEM0002.Description: The memory is operational. This is an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0002.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0002.Message: Parity memory errors detected on a memory device at location %1.

SYS169.Description: The iDRAC Service Module installed on the operating system is not up to date and does not support the Technical Support Report.
SYS169.Resolution: Make sure the operating system (OS) is a supported OS for the Technical Support Report feature and the latest iDRAC Service Module software is installed on the OS.
SYS169.Message: The iDRAC Service Module installed on the operating system is not up to date and does not support the Technical Support Report feature.

SWC4011.Description: A firmware or software incompatibility was automatically corrected between the network device in the Server identified in the message and the Chassis Management Controller (CMC).
SWC4011.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility is automatically corrected between the %1%2 in Server-%3 and the Chassis Management Controller (CMC).

PWR8671.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature cannot be enabled because the requested power exceeds the Chassis subsystem power limit for IO Modules, Blowers and Servers.
PWR8671.Resolution: Make sure the system operates within the subsystem Connector Limit for the components specified. To review power budget information select Chassis Overview -> Power -> Budget Status. Turn off unused components within the subsystem to make power available to set Enhanced Cooling Mode.
PWR8671.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to set the Enhanced Cooling Mode because the requested power %1 AC Watts exceeds the subsystem power limit %2 AC Watts for IO Modules, Blowers and Servers.

RAC944.Description: A configuration job cannot be created if Lifecycle Controller is disabled.
RAC944.Resolution: Run "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1" to enable Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation.
RAC944.Message: Unable to create the configuration job.

SWC1911.Description: User ID Password has been changed.
SWC1911.Message: User ID %1 User Password has been changed.

RAC964.Description: The operation cannot be performed because of an internal error.
RAC964.Resolution: Wait for some time before retrying the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

SWC0305.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0305.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0305.Message: The -p option requires -u to also be specified.

RAC1166.Description: The Configuration XML file preview operation was successfully initiated after it was invoked by the user name identified in the message.
RAC1166.Message: Successfully initiated Configuration XML file preview operation that was invoked by %1.

UEFI0218.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Write Timing Centering 2D Training phase.
UEFI0218.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0218.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

SWC0253.Description: Unable to allocate memory to perform the operation, see the inserted comment.
SWC0253.Resolution: Power Cycle the system and re-enter the command.
SWC0253.Message: Unable to allocate memory needed to perform operation.

RAC922.Description: The specified path (specified with the l parameter) for the remote share is too long. This path should be less than 256 characters in length.
RAC922.Resolution: Try the same command with a different remote share location, which is less than 256 characters in length.

MEM8000.Description: Errors are being corrected but no longer logged.
MEM8000.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>
MEM8000.Message: Correctable memory error logging disabled for a memory device at location %1.

PWR8557.Description: The current Power Cap setting cannot be enforced. This may be the result of changing the redundancy mode or by changing the PSUs. The power cap setting must be increased to be usable.
PWR8557.Resolution: Increase the Power Cap value. To increase the Power Cap do one of the following: 1) Using CMC Web interface: Select "Chassis Overview" -> Power -> Configuration and then adjust System Input Power Cap values. 2) Run the following RACADM command at the command line interface: "config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisPowerCap <value>".Try setting the power cap above the lower bound displayed on the power configuration page.
PWR8557.Message: The System Input Power Cap is too low to be enforced using the current Power Supply configuration.

JCP012.Description: The requested operation requires memory or file space allocation. The operation failed due to lack of memory or file space in the iDRAC.
JCP012.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
JCP012.Message: The operation failed due to an internal iDRAC error.

PST0065.Description: System BIOS is configuring PCI devices.

RAC0228.Description: SD Card needs to be formatted to make it usable. The card must be initialized.
RAC0228.Resolution: Click Initialize to initialize the card and make it usable.
RAC0228.Message: SD Card is detected with an unrecognized format. Click Initialize to initialize the card.

VRM0012.Description: The Virtual Media server is already connected.
VRM0012.Message: The Virtual Media image server is already connected.

RAC0695.Description: Unable to perform security key operations on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0695.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0695.Message: Unable to perform security key operations on the selected controller, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

UEFI0110.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Write DQ/DQS initialization.
UEFI0110.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0110.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

SWC8614.Description: The setting identified in the message is not recognized because the profile is not in a usable format or contains settings that are no longer supported.
SWC8614.Resolution: Recreate the profile or use a different profile.
SWC8614.Message: Legacy profile setting: %1 is not recognized.

VLT0204.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0204.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0204.Message: The system board %1 voltage is outside of range.

OSD064.Description: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is abruptly stopped either by the user or the installation infrastructure.
OSD064.Message: The process of installing an operating system or hypervisor is abruptly stopped either by the user or the installation infrastructure.

SYS166.Description: The collection of OS and Application Data did not start within the allocated time.
SYS166.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) Make sure the OS does not have any firewall setting to block USB device enumeration, and then retry the operation. 3) Make sure the OS is not configured to attach USB devices as read-only, and then retry the operation. 4) Make sure the OS is supported by the OS Collector application. 5) Reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation. 6) For more information about the collection of OS and application data, see the iDRAC8 User's Guide.
SYS166.Message: The collection of OS and Application Data did not start within the allocated time.

RAC1059.Description: The requested firmware rollback operation could not be performed because another firmware update job is running or being scheduled.
RAC1059.Resolution: Wait until the existing firmware update jobs are completed or scheduled before retrying the operation. To monitor the status of the existing jobs, run the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view". If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and then retry the operation after the iDRAC has finished restarting.
RAC1059.Message: Rollback operation could not be performed because another firmware update job is running.

AMP0313.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0313.Message: System level current is less than the lower critical threshold.

PWR8530.Description: Max Power Conservation Mode is disabled.
PWR8530.Message: Max Power Conservation Mode is disabled.

UEFI0192.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Clock Alignment phase.
UEFI0192.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0192.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RAC0171.Description: Certificate upload failed because the certificate has expired.
RAC0171.Resolution: Certificate has expired. Try creating a new Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and then upload the certificate.
RAC0171.Message: Certificate upload failed: Certificate has expired.

LC041.Description: The length of the Console name exceeds the maximum length allowed or the file operation error encountered.
LC041.Resolution: Change the name of a console to a name less than 32 characters.

SUP0522.Description: Write protection is enabled for the BIOS image and local BIOS update is disabled.
SUP0522.Resolution: To flash the BIOS locally, enable local BIOS update by selecting System Setup.
SUP0522.Message: Unable to update the BIOS firmware because write protection is enabled.

NIC011.Description: Configuration job already created on the specified target. No further command is allowed until the existing job is completed.
NIC011.Resolution: Cancel the configuration job or wait for the job to complete. Refer to documentation on job cancellation.
NIC011.Message: Configuration job already created, pending data cannot be deleted

BAR078.Description: The collection and export of Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC)firmware was not successful.
BAR078.Resolution: Apply the integrated remote access controller firmware, manually set the configuration attributes, and try the operation again.
BAR078.Message: Unable to collect the Integrated Remote Access Controller firmware.

NIC017.Description: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration.
NIC017.Resolution: Remove AC power from system and after restoring AC power, retry the operation.
NIC017.Message: Unable to delete vFlash pending one-time boot configuration

PCI3009.Message: PCIe is operating normally on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

SYS195.Description: The OEM ID Module installation process completed with no errors.
SYS195.Message: The OEM ID module is successfully installed.

SWC0254.Description: Local Configuration using RACADM may be disabled.
SWC0254.Resolution: Check if the Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled and enable it through GUI.
SWC0254.Message: Unable to perform requested operation. If the operation attempted was to configure DRAC, possible reason may be that Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled.

SYS096.Description: The required Dell Diagnostics firmware package is not installed or cannot be found in the iDRAC internal storage.
SYS096.Resolution: Install the Dell 64bit uEFI Diagnostics firmware package, and then retry the operation. The Dell Diagnostics can be installed using the Dell 64bit uEFI Diagnostics Dell Update Package (DUP).
SYS096.Message: Unable to complete the diagnostics operation because the required Dell Diagnostics firmware package is not installed.

IOV1001.Description: The requested operation was successfully executed.
IOV1001.Message: The requested operation was successfully executed.

LC071.Description: Unable to export or import server configuration XML because the Lifecycle Controller version on the target does not support this feature.
LC071.Resolution: Update the Lifecycle Controller version on the target system to a version that supports the export and import server configuration XML feature, and retry the operation.
LC071.Message: The Lifecycle Controller version does not support the export or import of the Server Configuration XML file.

RAC1141.Description: The iDRAC firmware rollback operation was initiated.
RAC1141.Message: The iDRAC firmware rollback operation was initiated.

UEFI0047.Description: One or more keys in the keyboard is stuck and not functional.
UEFI0047.Resolution: Make sure that the key is not stuck in the keyboard and retry the operation.
UEFI0047.Message: One or more keys in the keyboard is stuck and not functional.

RAC942.Description: The system configuration profile import operation is initiated. No other operations can be performed on the system while the system configuration server profile is being imported from the system configuration profile.
RAC942.Resolution: Monitor the job status using "racadm jobqueue view -i <Job ID>".
RAC942.Message: Successfully initiated the import operation. This operation may take several minutes to complete and may cause multiple system restarts while device firmware and configuration are applied.

PSU8502.Description: The input voltage of the PSU specified in the message does not match the input voltage of the PSUs already present in the chassis.
PSU8502.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the power configuration "Allow 110 VAC Operation" setting and make sure it is enabled. 2) Check if the input voltage of all the PSUs are the same. 3) If the input voltage of the PSU specified in the message is not the same, then remove the unmatched PSU.
PSU8502.Message: The PSU in slot %1 detected 110 VAC input voltage and does not match chassis configuration.

SWC0103.Description: The specified log does not take in the -e option.
SWC0103.Message: The -E option is not valid for the specified log.

STOR081.Description: The job could not be created because the reboot type selected for the job creation and the reboot type required for pending operations do not match.
STOR081.Resolution: Change the reboot type for job creation and retry the operation.
STOR081.Message: The job could not be created because the reboot type selected for the job creation and the reboot type required for pending operations do not match.

SYS024.Description: Unable to complete the operation because attribute dependency checking did not complete successfully. This attribute is dependent on a related attribute that has an incorrect value. The related attribute is the parent in a parent-child value dependency relationship and has an affect on what values the child attribute can have.
SYS024.Resolution: Make sure the dependency related attribute has the correct value and retry the operation. For more information on attribute dependency, Refer to the Dell Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Quick Start Guide and Profile Documents available at the support site.
SYS024.Message: Unable to complete the operation because attribute dependency checking did not complete successfully.

JCP004.Description: The job's time window expired and the job failed to complete
JCP004.Resolution: Retry the action and increase the time window so that the job can complete.

MEM0005.Description: The memory is operational. This is an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0005.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0005.Message: Persistent correctable memory error limit reached for a memory device at location(s) %1.

STOR10.Description: The RAID controller was detected, however it is unable to turn on. Access to shared storage will not be available.
STOR10.Message: Access to shared storage will not be available, because the RAID controller is unable to turn on.

SYS083.Description: Unable to export ePSA Diagnostics results because iDRAC internal storage could not be accessed.
SYS083.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Delete all jobs, 2) Reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and 3) Retry the operation.
SYS083.Message: Unable to export ePSA Diagnostics results because iDRAC internal storage could not be accessed.

SYS072.Description: The import of system configuration XML did not complete as the operation took too long.
SYS072.Resolution: Delete all jobs, reset iDRAC by pressing the System ID button for at least 15 seconds, and retry the operation.
SYS072.Message: System configuration XML import operation timed-out.

CPU0800.Message: CPU %1 voltage regulator module is present.

RED093.Description: Lifecycle Controller is not enabled and must be enabled in order for scheduled jobs to be created.
RED093.Resolution: Enable Lifecycle Controller and retry the operation. Lifecycle Controller can be enabled by using the F2 System Setup by pressing F2 during server startup, then select iDRAC Settings > Lifecycle Controller and enable the Lifecycle Controller feature. Retry the operation after the server restarts.
RED093.Message: The requested job cannot be scheduled because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

UEFI0128.Description: Both the primary and secondary SD cards are in write-protected mode.
UEFI0128.Resolution: No response action is required if this is intentional.
UEFI0128.Message: Both the primary and secondary SD cards are in write-protected mode.

SEC0600.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0600.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

RAC0643.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'month' while scheduling a job.
RAC0643.Resolution: Enter a correct numerical value in the following format: Day [1 to 31] of every [1 to 12] month(s). For example, Day 4 of every 11 months. Retry the operation.
RAC0643.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid 'month' value is entered.

SEC0602.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0602.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

SYS163.Description: The iDRAC environment has changed and the iDRAC must be restarted to apply the changes requested. Normal operation will return after the restart has completed. One exception is, the iDRAC has been reset to its default settings. In this case additional setup is required to use the iDRAC. For more information, see the iDRAC User's Guide.
SYS163.Message: The iDRAC is restarting to complete the System Erase operation. Do not restart server until the iDRAC restarts.

BAR088.Description: The maximum number of partitions are already in use.
BAR088.Resolution: Delete partitions and free up 384MB of space on the current vFlash media or obtain new vFlash media.
BAR088.Message: No partitions available on vFlash media.

PCI5002.Description: A PCIe card carrier that does not contain a PCIe card is inserted in the PCIe slot identified in the message.
PCI5002.Message: A PCIe card carrier that does not contain a PCIe card is inserted in the PCIe slot%1 .

SWC0289.Description: The specified object value is invalid.
SWC0289.Resolution: Configure the specified object and assign a valid value.
SWC0289.Message: Invalid value in config file. Group: %1, Object: %2, Value: \"%3\", Line [%4}

RAC974.Description: The value specified for the wait time (w) option is invalid. The valid range is 300 to 3600 seconds.
RAC974.Resolution: Make sure to specify a valid wait time (-w) option and retry the command. The range of supported values are 300 to 3600 seconds.

ENC40.Description: The controller detected a new enclosure. This is due either to a hot plug of an enclosure, or a power state change of an enclosure. In addition, this message is generated if the daisy chain order of the enclosures changes.
ENC40.Message: A new enclosure was detected on %1.

PWR8578.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on the iDRAC because power required is less than available power.
PWR8578.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Go to, the Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field, view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis. Remove and reinsert the server when enough power is available.
PWR8578.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on the iDRAC on server-%1 because power required is less than available power.

MEM9009.Description: A correctable error was detected in the propagation of signals on the Intel DDR memory interconnect identified in the message.
MEM9009.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reseat all DIMMs on the memory riser, 2) Reseat the memory riser, and 3) Restart the server. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
MEM9009.Message: Intel DDR Memory interconnect %1 has a correctable error.

OSD53.Resolution: Remove the write protect from the SD card and then proceed

UEFI0208.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Command Clock Training - Group All phase.
UEFI0208.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0208.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

NIC013.Description: An unknown AttributeName was entered for the operation.
NIC013.Resolution: Enter the correct AttributeName available in the system. Refer to the enumeration response for desired attribute.

VLT0203.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0203.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions2) Reduce system to minimum configuration, inspect and re-install system cables. 3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0203.Message: The system board %1 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SYS017.Description: The job did not complete successfully.
SYS017.Resolution: Verify the reason for the unsuccessful completion of the job by inspecting the Lifecycle Log entries related to the job. Correct the underlying cause of the unsuccessful completion and retry the operation.

PSU0906.Description: In order to meet service requirements the supply must be shut down.
PSU0906.Resolution: Remove input power at the power supply.
PSU0906.Message: An interlock power down error detected on power unit %1.

PSU0037.Resolution: Check for fan blockage. If not replace the power supply.
PSU0037.Message: Fan failure detected on power supply %1.

SWC0105.Description: The command does not take in the -m option.
SWC0105.Resolution: Refer the help text for getraclog command.
SWC0105.Message: Invalid -m option. Try --more or refer help for proper usage

OSD2.Resolution: 1) Rerun the command. 2) Reset iDRAC and run the command.

USR0033.Description: The IPMI over LAN login attempt was ended by the IPMI client before success or failure.
USR0033.Message: Login for %1 from %2 using %3 was incomplete.

SWC0006.Description: The view As Shipped hardware inventory operation encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0006.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0006.Message: Unable to display the As Shipped hardware inventory.

RAC0211.Description: Firmware update has failed. This may be due to a corrupt firmware image, poor network connection, or another issue.
RAC0211.Resolution: Download a new firmware image and try loading the firmware again.

RAC0688.Description: Applying this configuration operation will also apply all existing pending operations on the controller identified in the message.
RAC0688.Resolution: Click Create Job button to create the configuration job. Click Cancel to quit job creation.
RAC0688.Message: Applying this configuration operation will also apply all existing pending operations on the %1. #{View Pending Operations link}

ENC33.Description: Data redundancy has been restored to an enclosure that previously suffered a loss of redundancy.
ENC33.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

RAC983.Description: The Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file is passphrase protected, and the passphrase provided is invalid.
RAC983.Resolution: Specify the correct passphrase for the file using -p option.
RAC983.Message: Invalid passphrase provided for the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file.

PDR39.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR39.Message: A blink operation has initiated on %1.

SWU8522.Description: The firmware update operation is not successful.
SWU8522.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the original source, and then retry the operation.
SWU8522.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC on the server in %1 firmware: ErrorCode=0x%2.

STOR0108.Description: No temperature data to display. The system is powered off, no enclosure temperature probes are present in the system, or the temperature probes are not connected to the enclosures.
STOR0108.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosure temperature probe is available, and temperature probe is connected to the enclosure.
STOR0108.Message: Temperature probes are not connected to enclosures or data about temperature is unavailable.

HWC0013.Description: The USB drive is disconnected or is not readable.
HWC0013.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the USB drive and retry the operation. If the problem persists, restart the system and retry.
HWC0013.Message: Unable to copy the file to USB drive.

PR11.Description: A valid license for this feature is not present.
PR11.Message: A required license for the Part Replacement feature is not present, replacement action(s) will not be performed.

CMC8548.Description: The active Chassis Management Controller is not connected to an external network for more than 25 seconds. A failover is performed if the standby CMC is connected to the external network.
CMC8548.Resolution: Make sure that the external network cable is connected to the active CMC and the network switch. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8548.Message: The active Chassis Management Controller is no longer connected to an external network.

SYS162.Description: The server will be turned on to enter UEFI System Services Manager (SSM). The storage-related erase operations selected, if any, will be processed by SSM.
SYS162.Message: Turning on the server to perform System Erase tasks.

ENC31.Description: The system was unable to download firmware to the enclosure. The controller may have lost communication with the enclosure. There may have been problems with the data transfer or the download media may be corrupt.
ENC31.Resolution: Attempt to download the enclosure firmware again. If problems continue, verify that the controller can communicate with the enclosure. Make sure that the enclosure is powered ON. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on checking the cables.

RAC0682.Description: Enabling iDRAC Direct USB Configuration XML allows any USB key containing a correctly formatted configuration XML file to reconfigure the server when plugged into the USB management port identified by the wrench icon. This may include operations on RAID configurations, user accounts, and alert settings.
RAC0682.Message: Enabling iDRAC Direct USB Configuration XML allows any USB key containing a correctly formatted configuration XML file to reconfigure the server when plugged into the USB management port identified by the wrench icon. This may include operations on RAID configurations, user accounts, and alert settings.

ISM0030.Description: Unable to complete iDRAC Hard Reset operation because this feature is not supported on this platform.
ISM0030.Resolution: Refer to the platform User's Guide documentation for information about whether the iDRAC Hard Reset feature is available.
ISM0030.Message: Unable to complete the iDRAC Hard Reset operation because this feature is not supported on this platform.

VF029.Description: The user account credentials provided for this vFlash operation do not have the correct privileges. Virtual Media Access privilege is required to perform vFlash SD Card media operations.
VF029.Resolution: Use a different user account the has Virtual Media Access privilege.

UEFI0174.Description: A memory population violation has been detected on the identified DIMM slot.
UEFI0174.Resolution: Quad Rank and Octal Rank DIMM modules cannot be mixed on a channel. Populate memory modules in a supported configuration. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0174.Message: A Quad Rank DIMM module is installed on memory slot %1 after an Octal Rank DIMM module.

SWC1926.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync interface is enabled.
SWC1926.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync interface is enabled.

CMC8569.Description: The server slot specified in the message is enabled for DVD drive mapping. The DVD drive can be mapped to this server slot.
CMC8569.Message: The server slot %1 is enabled for DVD drive mapping.

SWC0127.Description: The file may be write protected and hence could not be edited.
SWC0127.Resolution: Check if the file is write protected.
SWC0127.Message: Unable to open file for writing.

SUP011.Description: The specified Job ID was not found in the job queue.
SUP011.Resolution: Verify the job ID and retry the action. Retrieve all open jobs by issuing the GetAllJobs command.

ENC25.Description: The enclosure or an enclosure component is in a Failed or Degraded state.
ENC25.Resolution: Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. See the storage hardware documentation for more information. Contact technical support.

BAR010.Description: The Backup partition creation operation did no complete successfully.
BAR010.Resolution: Make sure that the vFlash media is not write-protected. Enable and initialize the vFlash media, retry backup. If that fails Try new vFlash media or use the Network Share option(s).
BAR010.Message: Unable to create Backup partition on vFlash media.

UEFI0103.Description: One or more memory initialization error have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0103.Resolution: Replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0103.Message: One or more memory initialization errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

STOR025.Description: The pending configuration cannot be deleted because the configuration job is already scheduled.
STOR025.Resolution: Delete the current configuration job for the device to stop pending configuration changes.
STOR025.Message: Unable to delete any pending configuration because the configuration job is already scheduled.

OSD51.Description: There are pending System Services tasks on the host system that are preventing the execution of this method.
OSD51.Resolution: Reboot the host system. The system will automatically enter System Services and complete the pending tasks.
OSD51.Message: Reboot the system to run pending System Services Tasks.

STOR0507.Description: The RAID controller does not have sufficient number of initialized physical disks or adequate disk space to create the requested virtual disk.
STOR0507.Resolution: Connect additional physical disks to the RAID controller, initialize the physical disks, and retry the operation. To initialize the physical disks, reboot the system and select Option ROM during system startup.
STOR0507.Message: Insufficient physical disk space on selected RAID controller.

RAC0281.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IP Subnet Mask does not conform to the required format.
RAC0281.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Subnet Mask. Expected range: 0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255.
RAC0281.Message: The IP Subnet Mask is invalid. Expected range: 0.0.0.0 - 255.255.255.255.

FAN0018.Description: Enhanced Cooling Mode is not supported by the type of fan identified in the message.
FAN0018.Resolution: Replace the fan identified in the message with another fan which supports Enhanced Cooling Mode.
FAN0018.Message: Enhanced Cooling Mode is not supported for fan %1.

CMC8554.Description: An internal network error occurred. If none of the external sources have an issue, the CMC may have a hardware issue. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8554.Resolution: Reseat the network cable and check the connectivity to the outbound switch.

CPU0006.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.
CPU0006.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0006.Message: Unrecoverable CPU complex error detected on CPU %1.

SUP0533.Description: The file cannot be downloaded from FTP share due to network issues.
SUP0533.Resolution: Check network connection and retry download. If the issue persists, reconfigure the network settings and retry.
SUP0533.Message: Unable to download the update package files from the FTP server.

LIC503.Description: The currently installed license does not support the feature for the requested operation. The operation requires a valid license to enable specific features in the system. Since the required license is missing or expired, the features that are being accessed during the operation are disabled.
LIC503.Resolution: Acquire and install the license to enable the required feature, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support or see product documentation for more information.
LIC503.Message: Unable to complete the current operation. The currently installed license does not support the following features: %1.

AMP0306.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0306.Message: Disk drive bay %1 current is less than the lower warning threshold.

IPA0001.Description: Invalid parameters passed to the function.
IPA0001.Message: Invalid NIC IP address parameter specified.

PCI3020.Description: A low-severity issue is detected in the component identified in the message.
PCI3020.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the component identified in the message, and then monitor the log for a re-occurrence of the issue. If the issue persists, and occurs during server startup, update the component firmware. If the issue persists and occurs during OS runtime, restart the server and update the OS drivers for the component identified in the message.
PCI3020.Message: A low-severity issue is detected in a component of the bus %1, device 0, function %2.

STOR060.Description: The requested operation is not supported on the specified storage controller.
STOR060.Resolution: For more information about supported operations, see the documentation specific for the targeted storage controller.
STOR060.Message: Configuration operations are not supported on the specified storage controller.

SYS134.Description: The report size is more than the 30MB allowed size which will cause a truncated, partial report to be generated.
SYS134.Resolution: Remove older log entries so that the final zip archive size can be reduced.
SYS134.Message: OS Collector: Zip archive size exceeded the limit.

SWC0072.Description: SupportAssistcollectioncannot be exported to the destination folder.
SWC0072.Resolution: Verify the following and retry the operation: 1) Destination folder is present. 2) Destination folder has sufficient free disk space. 3) Destination folder is not write-protected. If the issue persists, perform an AC power cycle operation, and then retry the operation.
SWC0072.Message: Unable to export the SupportAssist collection to destination folder.

STOR300.Description: The requested operation could not be completed because at least one other pending operation was found on the RAID controller. This operation needs exclusivity because it requires a server reboot for changes to apply.
STOR300.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Create a job to complete the pending operations, allow the job to complete, and then retry the operation. 2) Cancel any pending operations on the RAID controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR300.Message: Unable to change the controller mode because there are already pending operations.

RAC0277.Description: This warning message appears when IPv4 is disabled.
RAC0277.Resolution: Use IPv6 network to access iDRAC remotely.
RAC0277.Message: Disabling IPv4 prevents access to iDRAC using an IPv4 address.

VFL0018.Description: The requested operation is currently in progress.
VFL0018.Resolution: Wait for the requested operation to complete.
VFL0018.Message: The requested operation is in progress.

HWC5006.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.

SWC0032.Description: Exporting the Server Configuration Profile image file to the USB drive was successful.
SWC0032.Message: Successfully exported the Server Configuration Profile image file to the USB drive.

PDR1023.Message: Rebuild completed for drive %1 in disk drive bay %2.

OSD69.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is missing.
OSD69.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ShareType" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD69.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ShareType' is missing.

SWC0043.Description: The Import Server Profile operation has completed with errors. For more information, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0043.Resolution: Exit the Import Server Profile wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0043.Message: Import Server Profile operation completed with errors.

BAT0010.Description: The system has to remain powered on to charge the battery.
BAT0010.Resolution: Allow the PERC RAID controller battery for the associated bay to charge. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
BAT0010.Message: The storage battery for disk drive bay %1 is low.

VLT0211.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is within range.

BAR004.Description: Hardware Inventory data is being collected and copied into the backup file.

STOR049.Description: The controller is in Local Key Management mode.
STOR049.Message: Controller is in Local Key Management mode.

SWU8541.Description: The PSU firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8541.Resolution: Make sure that the PSU firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8541.Message: Unable to update the PSU firmware, because the Image file is not accessible. ErrorCode=0x%1.

HWC2000.Message: The %1 cable or interconnect is connected.

RED023.Description: The Lifecycle Controller is unable to access internal storage currently in use by another operation.
RED023.Resolution: Make sure all other Lifecycle Controller operations are finished and retry the operation. Using the iDRAC Web UI, select Server and then Job Queue, check the job queue for unfinished jobs and wait for the jobs to finish before retrying the operation. Also, check whether there are update packages being executed in the server OS and wait for these operations to finish before retrying the operation. For remote web services API access, make sure that the GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus method returns Ready status, and then retry the operation. If OS Deploy has been enabled then boot the server into LC UI to clear. Always exit LC UI using "Exit" and not by removing power.
RED023.Message: Lifecycle Controller in use. This job will start when Lifecycle Controller is available.

OSD065.Description: The Operating System/Hypervisor installation did not complete successfully. The system may be unable to boot into the operating system/hypervisor because of the incomplete installation.
OSD065.Resolution: Check the installation logs of operating system or hypervisor, resolve any issues identified, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
OSD065.Message: Operating System/Hypervisor Installation did not complete successfully.

CTL41.Description: An error involving a single bit has been encountered during a read or write operation. The error correction algorithm has corrected this error.

RED075.Description: The Automatic Backup schedule operation could not be successfully created because the Automatic Backup schedule configuration already exists.
RED075.Resolution: Check the Automatic Backup schedule to verify if it is accurate or delete the existing schedule and retry the operation.
RED075.Message: An Automatic Backup schedule already exists.

SUP021.Description: Diagnostics and USC updates are direct updates and cannot be scheduled
SUP021.Resolution: Do not schedule USC or Diagnostics Jobs.
SUP021.Message: Diagnostics, Driver Pack or Lifecycle Controller update is a direct update and cannot be scheduled.

STOR089.Description: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.
STOR089.Resolution: To apply the configuration operation immediately, create a configuration job using the --realtime option. To create the necessary real-time job, run the jobqueue command. For more information about jobqueue command, run the racadm help jobqueue command.
STOR089.Message: The storage configuration operation is successfully completed and the change is in pending state.

RAC1145.Description: The value entered for the -t option is invalid.
RAC1145.Resolution: Check help text for the list of valid log types and retry the operation by entering a valid log type.
RAC1145.Message: The entered log type is invalid.

SWC8538.Description: The Public Key (PK) SSH Authentication key file delete operation did not complete successfully because the Chassis Management Controller is unable to access the configuration database.
SWC8538.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8538.Message: Unable to delete key for slot %1 of service account, due to problem saving key file.

RAC951.Description: Up to 256 characters are allowed for a work note.
RAC951.Resolution: Do not exceed 256 characters in the work note, and retry the operation.
RAC951.Message: The number of characters entered for the work note exceeds the supported limit.

SUP0106.Description: There is no firmware image present at the specified path.
SUP0106.Resolution: Check if the firmware image is present at the specified path.
SUP0106.Message: Unable to locate firmware image file in specified path.

TMP1002.Description: The enclosure is too hot. A variety of factors can cause the excessive temperature. For example, a fan may have failed, the thermostat may be set too high, or the room temperature may be too hot.
TMP1002.Resolution: Check for factors that may cause overheating. For example, verify that the enclosure fan is working. You should also check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source. Make sure the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information.
TMP1002.Message: %1 has exceeded the maximum failure threshold.

RED002.Description: Package has been successfully downloaded. The Job Scheduler will schedule it at the time specified.
RED002.Resolution: Schedule the job if it is not already scheduled.

USR0182.Description: Server information has been accessed by using the iDRAC Quick Sync feature.
USR0182.Message: Server information has been accessed by using the iDRAC Quick Sync feature.

VLT0230.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0230.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the mezzanine card.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0230.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

UEFI0242.Description: The Partial Memory Mirroring feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the requested size.
UEFI0242.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure the requested Partial Mirror size can be supported. For more information, see platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0242.Message: Unable to enable the requested Partial Mirror size of %1GB due to the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the requested size. %2GB was allocated instead.

SUP019.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G systems: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
SUP019.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G systems: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.

SEL1406.Message: The platform generated a SNMP trap.

RED027.Description: The temporary storage is full. The uploaded files must be installed to clear space for additional uploads.
RED027.Resolution: Select and install the currently uploaded files before uploading additional files.
RED027.Message: Insufficient space to upload the requested file.

RAC978.Description: The Lifecycle Controller firmware version on the target system does not support the configuration XML file import or export operations.
RAC978.Resolution: Update to the latest Lifecycle Controller firmware and retry the operation.
RAC978.Message: Unsupported Lifecycle Controller firmware version detected.

SWC0217.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0217.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0217.Message: The -c option requires -u to also be specifed.

CTL99.Description: The security key assigned to the controller identified in the message is deleted.
CTL99.Message: Security key assigned to %1 is deleted.

DIS112.Description: The AutoConfig operation is using the file identified in the message.
DIS112.Message: The AutoConfig operation is using the %1 file.

RAC018.Description: All the tasks in the Job were attempted, but some did not complete successfully.
RAC018.Resolution: Examine source of the errors by inspecting the results from the Job execution, and after resolving the issues, retry the operation. Job results can be retrieved from the Lifecycle Log or the WSMan API.
RAC018.Message: The Job is completed but with errors..

UEFI0048.Description: The Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) operation is not performed during this restart because Lifecycle Controller firmware could not be accessed or run properly.
UEFI0048.Resolution: Repair Lifecycle Controller using the Update Package. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.
UEFI0048.Message: The Collect System Inventory on Restart (CSIOR) operation is not performed during this restart because Lifecycle Controller is not functioning.

VFL0017.Description: The file system on the specified vFlash media partition could not be recognized. Data on the partition may be corrupted.
VFL0017.Resolution: Format the vFlash SD Card using the 'racadm vflashsd initialize' command and retry the operation.
VFL0017.Message: Unable to perform the vFlash media operation because the vFlash media partition is corrupted.

MEM1014.Message: Memory device at location %1 is in a power save state.

SUP030.Description: The value of the ProxySupport parameter must be TRUE if the Proxy IP and User Credentials need to be provided for the operation requested.
SUP030.Resolution: Do not specify Proxy IP and User Credential parameters if the ProxySupport parameter is FALSE.
SUP030.Message: Proxy IP and User Credential pare valid only if the ProxySupport parameter is TRUE.

PWR8555.Description: The request to turn on the component identified in the message was not successful because insufficient power is available at the identified priority for the component.
PWR8555.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis.
PWR8555.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to turn on %1-%2 at priority %3 because of insufficient power. Minimum power needed is %4 AC Watt, but only %5 AC Watt is available.

CMC8505.Description: IPv4 and IPv6 are disabled on the specified server and the CMC is unable to display the link to launch iDRAC web interface.
CMC8505.Resolution: Enable IPv4 or IPv6 for the specified server using the CMC command line or CMC Web GUI interface, so that the link to launch iDRAC is displayed on the CMC Web interface. To enable the NIC for DHCP using RACADM, enter "racadm setniccfg -m server-<slot number> -d" where <slot number> is the server identified in the message. To enable the NIC using the Web interface, click Server Overview > select the identified server, go to Setup > select the Enable IPv4 check box and/or the Enable IPv6 check box.
CMC8505.Message: Unable to access server: %1 because both IPv4 and IPv6 are disabled. NIC Enabled = %2.

SUP0115.Description: The rac cannot be reset, while the firmware update is in progress.
SUP0115.Resolution: Wait for the firmware update to finish.
SUP0115.Message: A firmware update is currently in progress. Unable to reset the RAC at this time.

CPU0002.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is inserted correctly, if the processor is removable. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0002.Message: CPU %1 has failed the built-in self-test (BIST).

PCI1318.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1318.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1318.Message: A fatal error was detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

PDR58.Description: A user attempted to replace a disk with another disk that is using an incompatible technology. For example, replaced one side of a mirror with a SAS disk when the other side of the mirror is using SATA technology.
PDR58.Resolution: Refer to the hardware documentation for information on replacing disks.

RAC1068.Description: The minimum non critical threshold value identified in the message cannot be set, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum non critical threshold value.
RAC1068.Resolution: Check the maximum non critical threshold level using an appropriate RACADM command. For example, to view the maximum non critical threshold value of a sensor, run the 'racadm getsensorinfo' command at the command line interface, and then retry the operation. For more information about other RACADM commands, run the racadm help command.
RAC1068.Message: Unable to set minimum non critical threshold value of %1, because the value entered is greater than, or equal to the maximum non critical threshold value.

RAC0614.Description: The specified password was incorrect for the PKCS#12 file.
RAC0614.Resolution: Make sure to use the correct password for the PKCS#12 file. If the PKCS#12 file is encrypted with a password, add it in required password box. Leave the password box empty if the file was not encrypted with a password.

RAC987.Description: After initiating the firmware update job, the time taken to complete it depends on size of the update file.
RAC987.Resolution: This firmware update job may take several minutes to complete depending on the component or firmware being updated. To view the progress of the job, use the "racadm jobqueue view" command.
RAC987.Message: Firmware update job for %1 is initiated.

HWC1013.Description: The USB cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC1013.Resolution: If removal was unintended, check presence, then re-install or reconnect.

SWC0002.Description: The Part Replacement policy configuration operation encountered an unexpected error while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0002.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0002.Message: Unable to set Part Replacement policies.

UEFI0275.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the TCP connection timed out when connecting to the iSCSI target.
UEFI0275.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure the iSCSI target system is online with the firewall configured to allow TCP access. 2) Make sure the server network infrastructure is configured to allow access to the iSCSI target. 3) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, make sure the iSCSI initiator settings (iSCSI, DHCP, VLAN, initiator/target IP addresses) are configured correctly. 4) Retry the operation.
UEFI0275.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the TCP connection timed out when connecting to the iSCSI target.

CMC8550.Description: If the chassis health status changes, new status is logged. The possible states are Invalid, Other, Unknown, Healthy, Non-critical, Critical, and Non-recoverable.

BOOT016.Description: The input source argument value referring to the boot device is incorrect or empty. The boot device identifier must match the InstanceID for the BootSourceSetting instance that represents the boot device.
BOOT016.Resolution: Use the correct source argument value for the boot device and retry the operation.
BOOT016.Message: Input source argument value for the boot device is incorrect or not found among the boot devices on the system.

RDU8521.Description: The active CMC has been removed from the chassis. If standby CMC is present, it will become active.
RDU8521.Resolution: Reinstall the CMC that was removed.
RDU8521.Message: CMC%1: active CMC has been removed

STOR0511.Description: Unable to change the encryption key due to an internal error.
STOR0511.Resolution: Exit Lifecycle Controller, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem persists, update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.
STOR0511.Message: Unable to change the encryption key.

STOR068.Description: The requested RAID configuration operation did not succeed because the Lifecycle Controller version on the target server does not have the necessary capabilities.
STOR068.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Controller version on the target server and update it with the latest version available.
STOR068.Message: Unable to perform the requested RAID configuration because the Lifecycle Controller version on the server does not have the necessary capabilities.

PST0132.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with CMOS memory during system POST. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception Code 84)
PST0132.Resolution: Check system event log for CMOS battery exceptions. Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

VF049.Description: The initializing SD card operation did not complete successfully.
VF049.Message: Initialize media operation did not complete successfully.

SWC4010.Description: The current CMC firmware does not support the ARI Mode advanced features available in the network device on the server identified in the message.
SWC4010.Resolution: Update the CMC firmware to the latest version and to enable access to the advanced features available in the network device.
SWC4010.Message: %1%2 in Server-%3 requires a version of Chassis Management Controller (CMC) firmware 5.0 or later for using the NParEP (ARI mode) functions.

CPU0703.Description: System event log and OS logs may indicate that the exception is external to the processor.
CPU0703.Resolution: 1) Check system and operating system logs for exceptions. If no exceptions are found continue. 2) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 3) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 4) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SWC0717.Description: For security reasons, the local configuration is disabled. Enable local configuration from the iDRAC Web interface
SWC0717.Resolution: Enable iDRAC local configuration from iDRAC Web interface.
SWC0717.Message: iDRAC Local Configuration is disabled. iDRAC Settings are accessed in read-only mode.

SWC5002.Resolution: Check system logs for minor errors.
SWC5002.Message: %1 upgrade was successful but encountered minor errors.

SUP0501.Description: The catalog file is not in the supported XML format, or the catalog file is corrupted.
SUP0501.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) If the catalog file is customized, recreate the file using Repository Manager, and retry the operation. 2) Update the catalog file from the service provider's FTP server and retry the operation. 3) Update the catalog file from the System Update Utility media or from the System Build Update Utility media and retry the operation. For more information, see Lifecycle Controller User's Guide.

VDR100.Description: The virtual disk identified in message cannot be used because of missing features on the current controller. The features may be missing because they are not available in the firmware version on the controller or the necessary licenses are not installed.
VDR100.Resolution: Update the controller firmware and license to match the peer controller.
VDR100.Message: %1 is unavailable because of incompatibilities with the current controller.

RAC1114.Description: The configuration XML preview operation was successfully initiated and has generated a job with the job ID identified in the message.
RAC1114.Resolution: Monitor the status of the preview operation job by running the racadm command "racadm jobqueue view -i <job ID>".
RAC1114.Message: Configuration XML file preview operation job is initiated. Job ID = %1

SWC0144.Message: Certificate successfully uploaded to the RAC. The RAC will now reset to enable the new certificate and may be offline temporarily.

STOR003.Resolution: Refer to the RAID profile to determine required parameters.

FCD8503.Description: Chassis already has the feature identified in the message activated. Only one instance of a feature can be activated at a time. If the feature must be activated on the new card, it must be deactivated before activating.
FCD8503.Message: The feature is activated in the chassis: %1

CMC8540.Description: The CMC specified in the message is turned on because of a CMC insertion or due to chassis AC power on.

NIC016.Description: A set attribute operation was attempted on a disabled attribute.
NIC016.Message: AttributeValue cannot be changed for disabled AttributeName %1.

ASR0103.Description: The operating system or an application failed to communicate within the timeout period. The system was powered down. (IPMI sensor type code 23h offset - 02h event 3:0 - 4h)
ASR0103.Resolution: Check the operating system, application, hardware, and system event log for exception events.
ASR0103.Message: The OS watchdog timer powered down the system.

CMC8547.Description: A firmware error occurred causing the failover. If this condition continues, a failover will result. If multiple failovers occur, contact Service.
CMC8547.Resolution: No response action is required. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8547.Message: Missing kernel module %1. Failover condition detected

SWU8520.Description: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC identified in the message is not successful.
SWU8520.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the original source, and then retry the operation.
SWU8520.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is not successful.

HWC1201.Description: The sled identified in the message is removed from the slot identified in the message.
HWC1201.Message: The sled %1 is removed from slot %2.

ISM0004.Description: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully started communication with iDRAC.
ISM0004.Message: The iDRAC Service Module has successfully started communication with iDRAC.

TMP0112.Description: Ambient air temperature is too cool.
TMP0112.Message: The %1 temperature is less than the lower warning threshold.

BAT1037.Description: A battery is detected on the Controller identified in the message.
BAT1037.Message: A battery is detected on the Controller %1.

PDR40.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
PDR40.Message: The blink operation has ceased on %1.

TMP0302.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature cannot be enabled because the necessary power or fan configuration is not available.
TMP0302.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the available power and the fan configuration. 2) If the required power for Enhanced Cooling mode is not available, remove other chassis components which are not being used in order to obtain sufficient power. 3) If the fan configuration does not support Enhanced Cooling Mode, replace unsupported fans with supported ones. 4) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
TMP0302.Message: Unable to set Enhanced Cooling Mode because the required power or fan configuration is not available.

VDR1.Description: A storage component such as a physical disk or an enclosure has failed. The failed component may have been identified by the controller while performing a task such as a rescan or a check consistency.
VDR1.Resolution: Replace the failed component. You can identify which component has failed by locating the component that has a red "X" for its status. Perform a rescan after replacing the failed component.

RAC0101.Description: The data returned is not in a known format.
RAC0101.Resolution: This error may occur because:1. Smart Card is invalid. Insert a valid Smart Card and try again. 2. Check connection between reader and system.3. There may be an issue with the Smart Card reader. Try reinstalling the reader driver or use a different reader.
RAC0101.Message: The inserted Smart Card is not valid or the Smart Card reader is not supported.

TMP0127.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0127.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0127.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

CTL92.Description: The controller identified in the message licensed features do not match its peer.
CTL92.Resolution: Update the license on the peer controller.
CTL92.Message: %1 is not operating in Fault Tolerant Mode because of an incompatible license setting on its peer controller.

SWC0029.Description: Status of backup Server Profile operation could not be retrieved because an unrecoverable error occurred while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0029.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation. To reset the iDRAC, hold the System ID button down for 15 seconds or longer and wait for 90 seconds for the iDRAC to restart. For more information on the error, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0029.Message: Unable to retrieve status of backup Server Profile operation.

SWC0065.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to copy the OS drivers from the OS driver pack.
SWC0065.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following:1) Update the system with the latest operating system driver packs using the Firmware Update feature and retry the operation. 2) Reboot the system, press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation..
SWC0065.Message: Unable to retrieve the drivers for the selected operating system.

SEC0043.Description: TXT POST cannot be completed because system configuration may have changed.
SEC0043.Resolution: Check system hardware inventory for TPM presence, clear and reconfigure TPM and TXT in BIOS setup menu.
SEC0043.Message: BIOS Authenticated Code Module detected an Intel Trusted Execution Technology (TXT) problem during POST.

PCI1360.Description: System performance may be degraded, or system may fail to operate.
PCI1360.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1360.Message: A bus fatal error was detected on a component at slot %1.

SWC0293.Description: The specified object is not present in the iDRAC.
SWC0293.Message: The specified object is not recognized by iDRAC.

STOR0101.Description: No RAID controller data to display. The system is powered off, no RAID controller is present in the system, or the RAID controller is not connected to the system.
STOR0101.Resolution: Check if the server has power, RAID controller is available, and that a RAID controller is connected to the system.

SWC0214.Message: Makes a remote ISO image available to the server

STOR029.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the specified physical disk is not found.
STOR029.Resolution: Provide a valid physical disk FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) and retry the operation.

PDR18.Description: A physical disk assigned as a hot spare was unassigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically unassigned by Storage Management. Storage Management unassigns hot spares were used to rebuild data. Once the data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, the hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. Assign a new hot spare to maintain data protection in this situation.
