PDR18.Resolution: Although this alert is provided for informational purposes, you may need to assign a new hot spare to the virtual disk. See Protecting Your Virtual Disk with a Hot Spare for more information.

TMP8503.Description: The NIC adapter in the slot identified in the message may have temperature related issues. The device temperature suggests degraded cooling or possibly a fan not functioning correctly on the adapter card (if adapter card has a fan).
TMP8503.Resolution: The cooling system may have issues. Contact your authorized Customer Service representative for further assistance.
TMP8503.Message: Temperature of NIC adapter in slot %1 is greater than normal operating range possibly due to an issue in the cooling system or a fan that is no longer functioning correctly.

VDR4.Description: This message is generated after a virtual disk was created on a controller.

RAC0290.Description: The user name value does not accept spaces.
RAC0290.Resolution: Do not enter spaces in the user name. If desired, use underscores.
RAC0290.Message: The user name cannot have spaces.

PWR214.Description: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is enabled.
PWR214.Resolution: Disable Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) and retry the operation.
PWR214.Message: Cannot enable the Extended Power Performance (EPP) mode because Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is enabled.

RAC0753.Description: Reset iDRAC to apply the pending new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset old certificate will be active. A manual reset of iDRAC is needed for the new certificate to take into effect.
RAC0753.Resolution: Click the Reset iDRAC link to reset iDRAC.
RAC0753.Message: Reset iDRAC to apply the pending new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset the old certificate will be active.

RAC1034.Description: This operation will cause the server to shutdown immediately. This may result in the applications losing data.
RAC1034.Resolution: Before continuing, exit all the programs running on this server, and make sure that there is no inbound and outbound traffic associated with this server. Inability to do so may prevent all the servers in the chassis from accessing the shared-storage devices for up to two minutes. To continue the operation, enter a -f at the end of command "racadm serveraction powerdown -f", and then retry.
RAC1034.Message: This action will ungracefully turn off the server.

RAC992.Description: The job ID specified in the message is invalid or was already deleted.
RAC992.Resolution: To monitor the current set of the jobs, use the "racadm jobqueue view" command.

SWC1925.Description: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the Disabled mode.
SWC1925.Message: The iDRAC Quick Sync access feature is set to the Disabled mode.

VDR36.Description: Virtual disk initialization is in-progress. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

PR19.Description: The specified job has completed successfully.

PSU8520.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement feature is supported and fully operational.
PSU8520.Message: Enhanced Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is fully supported.

HWC7012.Description: Server <number> health changed to a non-recoverable state.
HWC7012.Resolution: Review System Log or front panel for additional information.
HWC7012.Message: Server %1 health changed to a non-recoverable state.

SWC0311.Description: The syntax of the getconfig command is invalid.
SWC0311.Resolution: Refer the help text for getconfig subcommand.
SWC0311.Message: Invalid syntax. The -g option is only valid with -i and -o options.

PWR2005.Message: The OS run-time software initiated a hard reset.

UEFI0098.Description: The memory Built-In Self-test (BIST) has detected one or more errors on the DIMM installed on memory slot: <slot number>. As a result, the corresponding DIMM has been disabled.
UEFI0098.Resolution: Replace the DIMM module identified in the message. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0098.Message: The memory Built-In Self-test (BIST) has detected one or more errors on the DIMM installed on memory slot: %1. As a result, the corresponding DIMM has been disabled.

PR27.Description: The system ran out of memory while attempting to perform an operation. This has been deprecated.
PR27.Resolution: Retry the operation. If more than one operation was attempted retry them one at a time.

CTL76.Description: The controller encountered errors while applying the configuration on the physical disks. The configuration command applied has not taken effect.
CTL76.Resolution: Re-issue the failed configuration command or try with a different set of physical disks. Contact technical support if the problem persists.
CTL76.Message: A configuration command could not be committed to disk on %1

RAC0285.Description: The user name cannot be empty when creating a user account.

UEFI0213.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Basic Read DQ/DQS Training phase.
UEFI0213.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0213.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

PWR2255.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is configured in Max Power Conservation Mode and is unable to grant power on permission to the server.
PWR2255.Resolution: Disable the Max Power Conservation Mode on the chassis and retry the operation. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Chassis Overview>Power>Configuration and then uncheck the Max Power Conservation Mode field.
PWR2255.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is configured in Max Power Conservation Mode and is unable to grant power on permission to the server.

SWC0284.Description: Local Configuration using RACADM may be disabled.
SWC0284.Resolution: Check if the Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled and enable it through GUI.
SWC0284.Message: Failed to set the object value. Possible reason may be that Local Configuration using RACADM is disabled.

STOR064.Description: Unable to create the requested virtual disk because the physical disks specified did not have the same block size.
STOR064.Resolution: Verify that the physical disks selected for creating the virtual disk have the same block size and retry the operation. The block size can be determined by reviewing the physical disk inventory and checking the BlockSize property for each physical disk.
STOR064.Message: One or more physical disks specified for creating a virtual disk do not have the same block size.

LC066.Description: The Export Certificate operation is already running and may take a few minutes to complete.
LC066.Resolution: Wait until the current operation is complete and then retry the operation.
LC066.Message: The Export Certificate operation is currently running.

RAC0713.Description: Server failed to power up due to fabric mismatch.
RAC0713.Resolution: Ensure that the hardware compatibility between the IO Module (IOM) and the Mezzanine (Mezz) card is correct. Check the M1000e Hardware Manual for correct component compatibility.
RAC0713.Message: Server failed to power up due to fabric mismatch.

SWC0317.Description: The value for -c must be greater than zero.
SWC0317.Resolution: Enter a value greater than zero, for the option -c.
SWC0317.Message: The number of records to display must be greater than zero.

FAN0001.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.
FAN0001.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0001.Message: Fan %1 RPM is less than the lower critical threshold.

RAC0560.Description: RAC Software Initialization error. Monitoring data will not be available for PERC and Network Cards

IOV117.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter(VA) identified in the message has been unassigned/unmapped from the server identified in the message.

PSU8519.Description: The Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) feature is suspended due to the configuration or the type of PSU present. The feature is enabled, but suspended until a supported PSU configuration is in place.
PSU8519.Resolution: Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is not supported by the current power supply configuration. Verify the PSUs are supported. Replace the unsupported PSUs.
PSU8519.Message: Enhanced Dynamic Power Supply Engagement (DPSE) is not supported by the current power supply configuration and is suspended.

SWC8514.Description: Unable to delete the user name identified in the message.
SWC8514.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.

SWC0081.Description: Dell Integrated Data Center mode enabled.

RAC0763.Description: Unable to configure the port number that is entered because the port number is already in use.
RAC0763.Resolution: Enter a port number that is not already in use and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0763.Message: Unable to configure the port number that is entered because the port number is already in use.

RDU8516.Description: A failover has been requested from the RACADM command line interface.
RDU8516.Message: CMC%1: failover initiated by RACADM interface.

SWC0302.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0302.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0302.Message: The -s option is not valid with any other option.

IOV120.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has enabled PCIe ride-through mode. PCIe adapters will remain turned on for the number of seconds specified by the ride-through timeout value after the server they are assigned to is turned off.

PSU1007.Description: A device has been failed and the system is no longer functioning in optimal condition.

JCP036.Description: The job (installation- or configuration job) identified in the message is successfully deleted on iDRAC.
JCP036.Message: The (installation or configuration) job %1 is successfully deleted.

RAC982.Description: The PKCS12 file provided is invalid, because it may not be in the correct format.
RAC982.Resolution: For more details, contact the Certificate Authority.
RAC982.Message: Invalid Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file detected.

SWU8558.Description: Invalid firmware: The uploaded firmware image validation was unsuccessful.
SWU8558.Resolution: Use a valid firmware image and retry the operation.
SWU8558.Message: Invalid firmware: The uploaded firmware image validation was unsuccessful.

CMC8533.Description: Unable to read the header of the extended FRU information. This can occur if there is a problem in the communication between the CMC and the server.
CMC8533.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the server. The CMC will retry the read operation of the FRU information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8533.Message: Unable to read the FRU information, status = %1

RAC010.Description: The input value for the attribute being set contains characters that are not allowed.
RAC010.Resolution: Retry the operation using valid input characters. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

RAC802.Description: iDRAC time has been set through Network Time Protocol (NTP).
RAC802.Message: iDRAC time is set using Network Time Protocol.

LC080.Description: The Export Server Screen Shot operation successfully exported the server screen shot file.
LC080.Resolution: Download the encoded Base64 format server screen shot file, decode the Base64 file and then save it as a *.png file.
LC080.Message: The Export Server Screen Shot operation successfully exported the server screen shot file.

SWC8526.Description: Unable to delete Chassis Group member identified in the message. Another user may have deleted the member before the operation or the group may have been disbanded.
SWC8526.Resolution: Make sure the member identified in the message exists as a member of the Chassis Group. Use the CMC web interface to select the lead chassis, select the setup tab, and then select the group administration sub tab and check if the member exists. If the member exists, restart the group leader and retry the operation.
SWC8526.Message: Unable to delete Chassis Group member %1 (%2)

VF031.Description: The specified partition label is not a valid label.
VF031.Resolution: Try a label that complies with the standards for an OS volume label.

RAC0649.Description: Unable to process the request, because data is not entered or not selected in one or more mandatory fields.
RAC0649.Resolution: Make sure to enter or select data in all the mandatory fields, and then retry the operation.

LC028.Description: Hardware Inventory information is not retrievable due to an internal error.
LC028.Resolution: Try one of the following: 1) Try the operation again 2) AC power cycle system 3) apply the latest firmware update packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
LC028.Message: Unable to retrieve Hardware Inventory information.

RAC1178.Description: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC and a configuration XML import operation is in progress.
RAC1178.Resolution: Wait until the configuration XML import operation has completed before attempting another operation. Verify the status of the configuration XML import operation by running the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view".
RAC1178.Message: A USB device is attached to the iDRAC and a configuration XML import operation is in progress.

RDU8510.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.
RDU8510.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8510.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover, CMC firmware versions are different

PDR7.Description: A physical disk has reported an error condition and may be degraded. The physical disk may have reported the error condition in response to a check consistency or other operation.
PDR7.Resolution: Replace the degraded physical disk. Identify the disk that is degraded by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. Perform a rescan after replacing the disk.

DH005.Resolution: Close other iDRAC sessions and activities. Try again.
DH005.Message: CA Cert is corrupted, expired, or does not have signing privileges.

RAC0511.Description: Physical disks cannot be displayed. This error may occur if the host system is powered off, physical disks are removed, or incorrect filters are applied.
RAC0511.Resolution: 1. Check if the host system is powered off or shutdown. 2. Check if the physical disks are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane. 3. Check if correct filters are applied. 4. Check that the Storage Enclosure is on. 5. verify that the adapter cables are properly connected and there are no bent pins.
RAC0511.Message: There are no physical disks to be displayed.

VF053.Description: CreatePartitionUsingImage method cannot be completed because the URI and Share Type entered do not match.
VF053.Resolution: Make sure that the URI and Share Type match, and then retry the operation.
VF053.Message: Unable to CreatePartition because the URI and Share Type entered do not match.

VDR99.Description: The virtual disk identified in the message cannot be used because of an ID conflict with another virtual disk.
VDR99.Resolution: Power cycle the system chassis to restore the virtual disk. If this does not correct the problem then contact your service provider.
VDR99.Message: %1 is unavailable because of an ID conflict in the fault-tolerant pair.

VDR95.Description: This alert message occurs if the virtual disk has bad blocks.
VDR95.Resolution: Replace the disk in the Virtual disk, generating this alert and restore from backup. You may have lost data.
VDR95.Message: Unable to log block %1.Bad block table on %2 is full.

RAC0711.Description: Unknown power on response from the CMC.
RAC0711.Resolution: Try resetting the CMC. Also try resetting the server.
RAC0711.Message: Unknown power on response from the CMC.

USR0150.Description: The VNC client is connected from the IP address identified in the message to the iDRAC VNC Server.
USR0150.Message: Opening a remote VNC session from IP address %1.

SWC0238.Description: The key specified by the public key is too long.
SWC0238.Resolution: Request for a valid public key from the system and re-try the command.

VF019.Resolution: Check all the partitions, delete the ones that are not necessary and try this operation again.
VF019.Message: Not enough space on SD card

SEL1513.Description: The iDRAC communication link to Chassis Controller is restored. Any issues related to network communication between Chassis Controller and iDRAC, incorrectly seated Chassis Controller, or unavailability of Chassis Controller is now resolved successfully.
SEL1513.Message: The status of Chassis Controller has changed from critical to OK.

UEFI0074.Description: The system BIOS logs this message after detecting a change in Secure Boot policy settings. Such a change may result from user configuration or a system BIOS update. Changes to the following settings trigger this message: 1) Secure Boot (Enable/Disable) 2) Secure Boot Policy (Standard/Custom) 3) Platform Key 4) Key Exchange Keys 5) Authorized Signature Database (db) 6) Forbidden Signature Database (dbx).
UEFI0074.Resolution: Review the Secure Boot policy settings in System Setup > System BIOS > Security Settings page. If policy changes were expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise, modify the Secure Boot policy settings as needed.
UEFI0074.Message: The Secure Boot policy has been modified since the last time the system was started.

PCI5004.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected an issue in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in the slot identified in the message.
PCI5004.Resolution: Make sure that: 1) The PCIe adapter used is supported by the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). For a list of supported adapters, contact your service provider. 2) The adapter is not damaged. 3) The power requirement of adapter is not more than the power allocated to the slot. 4) The adapter is properly inserted in the slot.
PCI5004.Message: A power fault issue is detected in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in PCIe slot%1.

RAC989.Description: Only Windows-based Update Package (.exe extension), iDRAC Firmware (.d7 extension), Personality Module Firmware (.pm extension), Lifecycle Controller firmware repair package (.usc) are supported for the firmware update operation.
RAC989.Resolution: The file used for the operation is invalid. For the list of supported files, use "racadm help update". For the correct version of the file specific to the system, contact the service provider.
RAC989.Message: Unable to apply the %1 firmware update.

STOR14.Description: Peripheral sled initialization is not successful with following possible reasons: 1) FRU is not functioning. 2) Sled internal components are not responding. 3) Component power state is not good. 4) Hardware configuration errors.
STOR14.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check system log for further information about the issue, 2) Remove and re-insert the peripheral sled identified in the message or virtual reseat the sled, 3) Reset the CMC and wait for a few minutes for the CMC to finish restarting. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
STOR14.Message: The peripheral sled in slot %1 initialization is not complete.

SUP0502.Description: iDRAC is unable generate the inventory file or the inventory file received from iDRAC is faulty. For more information about the failure, see Lifecycle Log.
SUP0502.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2.) Wait for five seconds. 3.) Reconnect the power cord and turn on the system. 4) Press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller, and retry the operation. If the problem continues to persist, update iDRAC firmware to the latest version, and retry the operation. Else, contact the service provider.

LIC906.Description: The license file is not present or accessible from the network share location.
LIC906.Resolution: Verify the license file is located on the network share and file access permissions are correct, then retry the operation.
LIC906.Message: License file is not accessible on the network share.

RAC005.Description: The name value pairs do not match in the input specified in the method invocation parameters.
RAC005.Message: Mismatch in AttributeName and AttributeValue count.

CTL47.Description: The Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM) is malfunctioning. Data loss or data corruption may occur. The DIMM must be replaced immediately.
CTL47.Resolution: Replace the DIMM immediately. The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to your hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM.

PDR1101.Description: The controller detected a failure on the disk and has taken the disk offline.
PDR1101.Resolution: Remove and reseat the failed disk. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

PWR8510.Description: Unable to set the chassis power identified in the message.
PWR8510.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8510.Message: Unable to set chassis power property %1.

SEL1500.Message: The chassis management controller (CMC) is redundant.

SYS126.Description: Application data source was not found. An issue occurred while collecting Application Data because of an unknown exception.
SYS126.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS126.Message: OS Collector: Unable to collect Application Data.

UEFI0056.Description: The PCIe error is logged during Power-on-Self-Test (POST). The error could have occurred during either the current or the previous POST.
UEFI0056.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the PCIe device that is not functioning correctly, and then update the device firmware.

PDR8.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

CTL57.Description: The controller was reset to factory default configuration settings.
CTL57.Message: The factory default settings were restored on %1.

VF045.Description: File transfer was not successful. This could be because of network problems or an operational problem with the file server.
VF045.Resolution: Try the download again. If the issue persists, validate that the network share is operational.
VF045.Message: FTP download operation was not successful.

ENC7.Description: You have enabled the enclosure alarm. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

SWC0017.Description: An unrecoverable error occurred while retrieving the drivers.
SWC0017.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists, exit Lifecycle Controller and perform an AC power cycle.
SWC0017.Message: Unable to retrieve the drivers for the selected operating system.

PSU8507.Description: The PSU identified in the message has been disengaged or removed. Insufficient power is available.
PSU8507.Resolution: Insert a PSU in the slot identified in the message.
PSU8507.Message: Insufficient power available because PSU in the slot %1 is not present..

IOID112.Description: The initiator properties of the NIC port identified in the message are successfully configured.
IOID112.Message: The initiator properties of the %1 Port %2 are successfully configured.

RAC0254.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv4 Gateway Address does not conform to the required format
RAC0254.Resolution: Enter a valid Gateway Address. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0254.Message: The Gateway Address is invalid. Expected range: [0.0.0.0 or 1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].

SYS094.Description: The Tech Support Report collection job could not be started, because a report collection job is already running on the server.
SYS094.Resolution: Wait until the current Tech Support Report operation is complete and then retry the operation.
SYS094.Message: The iDRAC is unable to start the Tech Support Report job, because a report collection job is already running on the server.

BAT0017.Description: System settings may be preserved if input power is not removed from the power supplies.

RED086.Description: The Chassis firmware cannot be updated because the Chassis Management at Server (CMAS) attribute is incorrectly set. The CMAS attribute must be set to Monitor and Configure on the CMC in order to update CMC firmware from and iDRAC.
RED086.Resolution: Make sure that the Chassis Management at Server attribute is set to Monitor and Configure, and then retry the operation. To set the correct attribute using Chassis Management Controller (CMC) GUI, navigate to Chassis Overview, then Setup, then General, and then click on the Chassis management at Server attribute to select the correct value.
RED086.Message: Unable to update the Chassis firmware, Chassis Management at Server is not set to Monitor and Configure.

RAC040.Description: One or more required parameters needed for the method invoked in the operation are missing.
RAC040.Resolution: Verify that all required parameters are provided. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

PDR1022.Message: Drive %1 in disk drive bay %2 is no longer in the failed array.

OSD35.Description: Lifecycle Controller is disabled on the system, so none of the remote operating system deployment commands will work. Make sure Lifecycle Controller is enabled before running any command.
OSD35.Resolution: Reboot the system and enable System Services by pressing CTRL+E option when prompted to do so in the POST. This launches the iDRAC configuration utility where Lifecycle Controller can be enabled.

SW0725.Description: iDRAC7 is busy and does not respond to iDRAC7 configuratorIPMI requests.
SW0725.Resolution: Try AC power cycling the server or upgrade the iDRAC firmware.

PST0083.Description: System is at the BIOS Boot Menu.

LIC015.Description: This error occurs when the Lifecycle Controller restore operation is interrupted before it completes. This can occur due to a power outage or when a system is rebooted before the operation is completed.
LIC015.Resolution: Repeat the Lifecycle Controller restore operation. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
LIC015.Message: The License Manager database restore operation failed.

RAC0724.Description: Quick Sync Firmware is successfully updated.
RAC0724.Message: Quick Sync Firmware is successfully updated.

UEFI0137.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This issue is caused by missing LC files.
UEFI0137.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0137.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

SYS053.Description: Configuration changes specified in the system configuration XML file were successfully applied.
SYS053.Message: Successfully imported and applied system configuration XML file.

SWC0063.Description: The share name and login credentials provided are incorrect.
SWC0063.Resolution: Enter the correct share name and login credentials, and retry the operation.
SWC0063.Message: Unable to authenticate the login credentials and share name.

NIC010.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G systems: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
NIC010.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing on the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G systems: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.
NIC010.Message: Lifecycle Controller is not enabled, cannot create Configuration job.

RAC1129.Description: The BootOnce object could not be modified, because the FirstBootDevice object is set to either F10, F11, or BIOS.
RAC1129.Resolution: Configure the FirstBootDevice object to values other than F10, F11, or BIOS and retry the set operation for the BootOnce object. For more information about possible FirstBootDevice values, run the RACADM command "racadm help idrac.serverboot.firstbootdevice".
RAC1129.Message: Unable to modify the BootOnce object.

LC003.Description: An error occurred while trying to set the firmware update mode.
LC003.Resolution: Verify that the firmware version supports this mode. Also confirm that the command and parameters are correct. The parameter choices are: 1) Disable (default) 2) Allow version upgrade only 3) Match firmware of replaced part.
LC003.Message: Failed to change the firmware update mode.

RAC0748.Description: The BIOS watchdog must be disabled if Automatic System Recovery option is enabled.
RAC0748.Resolution: Make sure the BIOS watchdog timer is disabled before enabling the Automatic System Recovery option.
RAC0748.Message: The BIOS watchdog timer must be disabled if the Automatic System Recovery option is enabled.

SYS025.Description: There are no pending configurations to be deleted.

HWC2011.Description: The riser blade cable may be necessary for proper operation. System functionality may be degraded.
HWC2011.Resolution: Check presence, then re-install or reconnect.
HWC2011.Message: The riser board cable or interconnect is not connected, or is improperly connected.

FAN8502.Description: The current CMC firmware did not detect the blower identified in the message.
FAN8502.Resolution: Make sure that CMC is using the latest firmware, and then retry the operation.
FAN8502.Message: Unable to detect the blower %1 because the blower may not be optimally operating.

UEFI0043.Description: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the processor does not support TXT.
UEFI0043.Resolution: Install a TXT-capable processor and retry the operation.
UEFI0043.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the processor does not support TXT.

UEFI0272.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the BIOS cannot obtain the initiator information from DHCPv4 server.
UEFI0272.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Check the configuration of DHCPv4 server. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable DHCP and configure the initiator information manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0272.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the BIOS cannot obtain the initiator information from DHCPv4 server.

UEFI0217.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Basic Write DQ/DQS Training phase.
UEFI0217.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0217.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

PR15.Description: The configuration changes requested have not passed the device specific verification check and will not be applied.
PR15.Message: Unable to verify configuration changes for device: %1

USR0031.Description: Unsuccessful login for the username, IP address, and interface identified in the message.
USR0031.Resolution: Make sure the login credentials are valid and retry the operation.
USR0031.Message: Unable to log in for %1 from %2 using %3.

RAC0100.Description: Communication with the Smart Card has been lost.
RAC0100.Resolution: Insert a valid Smart Card and try again.
RAC0100.Message: The Smart Card is removed. Further communication is not possible.

RAC053.Description: One or more attributes being set are dependent on OS to iDRAC pass-through being enabled.
RAC053.Resolution: Enable OS to iDRAC pass-through and retry the previous command.
RAC053.Message: OS to iDRAC pass-through is disabled.

SWC0056.Description: Unable to export the file to the USB drive because it does not have the specified folder, does not have enough free space, or is read-only.
SWC0056.Resolution: Make sure that the USB drive contains the folder specified, has enough free space, or is not read-only. If the problem persists, reboot the system and retry the operation.
SWC0056.Message: Unable to export the file to the USB drive.

SUP0527.Description: The Update Package does not have this system in the supported platform list.
SUP0527.Resolution: Download the latest Update Package from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0527.Message: The Update Package is not supported for this system.

SEC0611.Message: An Out-of-band password violation was corrected.

SWU8516.Description: iDRAC firmware update operation was not successful. The firmware Image file could not be transferred.
SWU8516.Resolution: Make sure the iDRAC firmware Image file is available in the given path and retry the operation.
SWU8516.Message: Unable to update the iDRAC firmware on the server in slot %1. Transfer is not successful. ErrorCode=0x%2.

MEM1004.Message: Memory device at location %1 is powered off.

PDR60.Description: The reason for the error can vary depending on the situation. The firmware error code is indicated in the message.
PDR60.Resolution: Verify the health of attached devices. Review the Lifecycle log for significant events. Replace faulty hardware, if required. Make sure the cables are attached securely. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information on checking the cable connections.

MEM1214.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed.
MEM1214.Resolution: Review system logs for memory exceptions. Re-install memory at location <location>

BAR022.Description: The host system is powering up to perform component firmware and configuration restoration.
BAR022.Message: System powering up to perform component updates.

UEFI0109.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during write leveling initialization.
UEFI0109.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0109.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

SWU8514.Description: The IOM infrastructure firmware update operation is not successful.
SWU8514.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source folder, and then retry the operation.
SWU8514.Message: Unable to update the IOM infrastructure firmware of slot %1. ErrorCode=0x%2.

ENC8.Description: You have disabled the enclosure alarm.

RFL2005.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is operating normally.

USR0173.Description: The Front Panel USB port switched automatically from iDRAC to operating system.
USR0173.Message: The Front Panel USB port switched automatically from iDRAC to operating system.

RAC0149.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about the fans.
RAC0149.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0149.Message: Unable to retrieve the fan information. The system is powered off.

STOR041.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because an invalid value for the attribute identified in the message is specified.
STOR041.Resolution: Specify a valid value for the attribute identified in the message and retry the operation.

SWC1910.Description: User ID Name has been changed.
SWC1910.Message: User ID %1 User Name has been changed.

SWC0236.Description: The specified public key was deleted from iDRAC.

UEFI0265.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 address is invalid.
UEFI0265.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the Initiator IP address field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0265.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 address is invalid.

BAR049.Description: The automatic Host System power up request has erred and the system will not power up after the Integrated Remote Access Controller has restarted.
BAR049.Resolution: As indicated by the job status, wait for restore to complete. After the status displays Complete or Failed, wait for a few minutes for the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) to restart. After restart, power on the Host System using iDRAC.
BAR049.Message: Automatic Host System power up setup failed.

RAC0767.Description: The USB NIC IP address identified in the message cannot be assigned to the OSBMC device because IP address setting conflicts with existing network interface IP.
RAC0767.Resolution: Enter an unique IP address for OSBMC USB NIC that is not the same as another NICs IP address, and then retry the operation. For information about supported IP addresses, refer to the iDRAC Users Guide available at the support site.
RAC0767.Message: Unable to assign USB NIC IP address %1 to the OSBMC device because IP address setting conflicts with existing network interface IP.

PCI1300.Description: The front panel diagnostic was pressed, and the system may be halted as a result. The interrupt was user induced.
PCI1300.Resolution: Reset the system to continue operation.
PCI1300.Message: A front panel diagnostic interrupt was detected.

BAT1009.Description: The controller battery health has returned to normal.
BAT1009.Message: Write policy on %1 was changed to Write Back.

SEC0003.Description: The processor area is open. A drive may be added or removed. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0003.Resolution: Close the processor area. Check system logs.

LIC205.Description: The License Manager sets a maximum time period that its database may be locked. If that timeout exceeds, it releases the lock conditions and reports the error. The user must assume that the Lifecycle Controller backup or restore operation failed and should repeat the operation.
LIC205.Resolution: Repeat the backup or restore operation.
LIC205.Message: License Manager database lock timeout has been exceeded.

CTL29.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL29.Message: The Patrol Read rate has changed for %1.

OSD59.Description: Disconnecting ISO using Remote File Share (RFS) operation did not complete successfully.
OSD59.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
OSD59.Message: Unable to disconnect from ISO using Remote File Share (RFS).

SWC0267.Description: Unable to edit the SD card, since it is write protected.
SWC0267.Resolution: Check if the SD card is write protected. If yes, disable the write protection.
SWC0267.Message: Unable to perform the requested operation. Make sure a non write protected SD card is inserted.

SYS043.Description: The current configuration of the system components (BIOS, RAID, NIC, iDRAC, and so on) was written to a system configuration XML file and successfully copied to the specified location.
SYS043.Message: Successfully exported system configuration XML file.

SWC8520.Description: Unable to modify the user name specified in the message.
SWC8520.Resolution: Make sure: 1) The login credentials for the operation have user config administration privilege, 2) The user name given is valid. If the issue persists, restart the CMC and retry the operation.
SWC8520.Message: Unable to modify user name from %1 to %2: %3-%4

SYS175.Description: Selective Export / Import could not find any matches for the FQDDs specified.
SYS175.Resolution: Make sure that only valid FQDDs are entered as input to the Target parameter, and then retry the operation
SYS175.Message: Unable to find a device configuration for the FQDD entered.

HWC5036.Description: The IOM module performance may be impact.
HWC5036.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
HWC5036.Message: A failure is detected on IO module %1.

UEFI0042.Description: Unable to enable the TXT feature because Trusted Platform Module (TPM) configuration is invalid.
UEFI0042.Resolution: Go to System Setup > System Security page, select the "On with pre-boot measurement" option for TPM Security, and click the "Activate" option under TPM command. Restart the system, go to System Setup > System Security page, and then enable TXT.
UEFI0042.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because Trusted Platform Module (TPM) configuration is invalid.

AMP0315.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0315.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes.
AMP0315.Message: System level current is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SWU8523.Description: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC identified in the message is successful.
SWU8523.Message: The firmware update operation of the iDRAC on the server in slot %1 is successfully completed.

STOR0111.Description: The specified reference key is invalid.
STOR0111.Resolution: Verify that the correct reference key is specified. See the help text or documentation for valid reference keys.

PST0126.Description: System is currently booting to an UEFI compatible operating system. No more POST codes will be generated in this boot sequence.
PST0126.Message: Giving control to UEFI aware OS.

SWC8517.Description: Successfully modified the password for the User identified in the message.

LOG509.Description: The command cannot be run because the value of the parameter identified in the message exceeds the maximum length identified in the message.
LOG509.Resolution: Enter a value for the parameter identified in the message that is equal to or less than the maximum allowed characters.
LOG509.Message: Unable to run the command because the parameter value of %1 exceeds the maximum allowed number of %2 characters.

VDR40.Description: This message is generated after the reconfiguration of a virtual disk resumes.

JCP002.Description: The Lifecycle Controller is not able to schedule a job at this time because of an internal error.
JCP002.Resolution: Wait up to three minutes and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system and enumerate DCIM_Lifeycle Job to view the list of jobs that are currently scheduled.

HWC8509.Description: The heatsinks are critical for providing cooling to the PCIe switches. If a PCIe switch stops functioning due to improper cooling, the PCIe subsystem may no longer function correctly and data loss may occur.
HWC8509.Resolution: Immediately turn off the Chassis by pressing the Chassis power button or removing chassis input power. The Chassis can be turned off remotely by running the following RACADM command "racadm chassisaction -m chassis nongraceshutdown". After turning off, contact your service provider.
HWC8509.Message: One or more PCIe switch heatsinks are not properly attached.

SYS145.Description: vFlash SD Card data is deleted because of a System Erase operation.
SYS145.Message: vFlash SD Card data is deleted.

VDR43.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
VDR43.Message: Dedicated hot spare unassigned physical disk %1.

SWC0205.Message: Upload an SSL key to the RAC

VFL1005.Description: The media is being prepared or is under maintenance. If the problem persists, reinstall the card.
VFL1005.Resolution: Please wait for the media to be ready.
VFL1005.Message: Removable Flash Media %1 is not ready.

FC014.Description: The AttributeValue parameter is invalid due to one of the following: 1) The length of new AttributeValue is not within the minimum length and maximum length range or does not comply with the governing regular expression 2) Value of new AttributeValue is not within the lower bound and upper bound range limits 3) The value is not one of the possible values.
FC014.Resolution: For valid attribute values, see the FC HBA Profile specification.
FC014.Message: Invalid AttributeValue parameter content for corresponding AttributeName %1.

USR0175.Description: The USB device attached to the port identified in the message is drawing more current than is supported by the port.
USR0175.Resolution: Reinsert the USB device in the Front Panel USB Port and retry the operation. If the issue persists, use a different USB device.
USR0175.Message: The Front Panel USB Port Over Current is detected for the attached device on Disk.USBFront.%1.

SWC0209.Message: Connect or disconnect image server connections

UEFI0076.Description: A Corrected Machine Check error(s) has occurred.
UEFI0076.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the Corrected Machine Check (CMC) errors. Resolve the issue identified in the SEL that caused the CMC.
UEFI0076.Message: One or more Corrected Machine Check(CMC) errors have occurred.

RFL2003.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is online.

UEFI0099.Description: The Memory Mirroring feature cannot be enabled because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.
UEFI0099.Resolution: Check the DIMM population and hardware configuration to make sure the Memory Mirroring feature can be supported. For more information, see platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0099.Message: Unable to enable the Memory Mirroring feature because the current DIMM population or hardware configuration does not support the feature.

VLT0303.Description: High voltages may be the result of problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. Elevated voltages may result in damage to the processor or other system electrical components. The system may power down.
VLT0303.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0303.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper critical threshold.

CTL70.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL70.Message: Attempted to import an orphan drive on %1.

LIC201.Description: This license is going to expire. An expired license could result in the loss of functionality that is specific to the features supported by the license.
LIC201.Resolution: Purchase a new license to prevent interruption of licensed features.
LIC201.Message: License %1 assigned to device %2 expires in %3 days.

RAC965.Description: Any operation involving remote share (CIFS) cannot continue if the location (-l) is not specified. The u and p options represent the user name and password for the remote share, and -l represents the location of the remote share.
RAC965.Resolution: Make sure to specify the location (-l) of the remote share along with the user name and password, and retry the operation. To view the list of options that can used for the required subcommand, use the racadm help <subcommand> command.
RAC965.Message: The -l option must be specified if -u and -p are used.

UEFI0058.Description: Uncorrectable Memory Error has occurred because a Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) is not functioning.
UEFI0058.Resolution: Check the System Event Log (SEL) to identify the non-functioning DIMM, and then replace it.
UEFI0058.Message: An uncorrectable Memory Error has occurred because a Dual Inline Memory Module (DIMM) is not functioning.

ISM0017.Description: The BMC watchdog auto-recovery action is changed from the original action identified in the message to the new action identified in the message.
ISM0017.Message: The BMC watchdog auto-recovery action is changed from %1 to %2.

PWR8583.Description: To enable 110V operation, the Allow 110VAC Operation feature must be enabled. If the feature is not enabled, the server turn-on operation will not be processed.
PWR8583.Resolution: On the Power Configuration page, in the Web UI, select the Allow 110VAC Operation for power supplies and retry the operation. Using the RACADM utility, run the following command, "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisAllow110VACOperation 1".
PWR8583.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on server-%1 because unacknowledged 110V PSUs are present.

SYS051.Description: Sometimes, the operating system on the server may not allow a graceful shutdown or may not complete within the specified graceful shutdown timeout. This error indicates that the system could not be shutdown within the time specified. The default timeout value is 5 minutes and the maximum value allowed is 1 hour.
SYS051.Resolution: Retry the operation with a longer specified graceful shutdown timeout or with the system shutdown option.
SYS051.Message: The system could not be shut down within the specified time.

PR20.Description: The specified job is in progress.

CTL109.Description: The Reconstruct Rate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL109.Message: The Reconstruct Rate of %1 is set to %2.

SWC0143.Message: SSL key successfully uploaded to the RAC.

RAC0627.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested recurrent Automatic Backup job is already scheduled.
RAC0627.Resolution: Delete the current scheduled job, and then retry to create a new Automatic Backup job with a new schedule.
RAC0627.Message: Unable to schedule, because the requested recurrent Automatic Backup job is already scheduled.

USR0020.Description: The specified session id does not exist and is invalid.

USR0008.Description: The Default Login Warning feature is disabled. No warning is provided if any local user is configured with default credentials,
USR0008.Message: The Default Login Warning feature is disabled.

VLT0207.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0207.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0207.Message: The memory module %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

NIC012.Description: No changes to BIOS attribute data are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration.

CMC8575.Description: The RAC SSL Certificate is changed.
CMC8575.Message: The RAC SSL Certificate is changed.

AMP0320.Description: Product documentation contains information on correct configuration. The failure could also be caused by a faulty component or related cabling. System performance may be degraded.
AMP0320.Resolution: Review system power policy, check system logs for power related failures, and review system configuration changes
AMP0320.Message: Chassis power level current is greater than the upper warning threshold.

PWR2264.Description: The Intel Management Engine has recovered the ability to utilize the PECI over DMI facility.
PWR2264.Resolution: If the PWR2262 "internal system error" was logged within the previous 30 seconds, ignore the message. No response action required.
PWR2264.Message: The Intel Management Engine has reported normal system operation.

RAC056.Description: The Authentication Protocol attribute for the user account identified in the message cannot be disabled because the Privacy Protocol attribute is enabled. The Privacy Protocol for the user account is not set to None.
RAC056.Resolution: Disable the Privacy Protocol attribute for the identified user ID account by setting the value to None, and retry the operation to set Authentication Protocol attribute to None.
RAC056.Message: Unable to set the Authentication Protocol attribute to None because the Privacy Protocol attribute is enabled for user ID: %1

RAC1144.Description: No configuration results information is available for the job ID identified in the message because the job ID is invalid or is not present in the job queue and a related Lifecycle Log entry is not found.
RAC1144.Resolution: Check the job ID identified in the message and retry the operation with a valid job ID. To check valid job IDs in the current job queue, using RACADM, run the command "racadm jobqueue view".
RAC1144.Message: The Job: %1 is invalid or is not present in the job queue and a related Lifecycle Log entry is not found.

SWC0052.Description: An error occurred while retrieving the operating system drivers.
SWC0052.Resolution: Exit the OS Deployment wizard and update the system with the latest operating system driver packs available from the service provider and retry the operation. For more information, see the Lifecycle Controller user's guide.
SWC0052.Message: Unable to continue with OS Deployment operation.

RED028.Description: Update files were not selected, therefore the installation did not proceed.
RED028.Resolution: Select one or more update files to install.

RAC0751.Description: The value for information or warning threshold should not be less than lower critical threshold value.
RAC0751.Resolution: Enter a threshold value that is greater than the lower warning or critical threshold values and retry the operation.
RAC0751.Message: The threshold value entered is less than the lower warning or critical threshold.

VF044.Description: File transfer was not successful. This could be because of network problems or an operational problem with the file server.
VF044.Resolution: Try the download again. If the issue persists, validate that the network share is operational.
VF044.Message: TFTP download operation was not successful.

RAC0648.Description: The request cannot be processed, because the length of string entered for one of the input parameter is more than the specified length.
RAC0648.Resolution: Enter a string not more than 4095 characters in length, and then retry the operation.

MEM0007.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.
MEM0007.Resolution: Review product documentation for supported memory configurations
MEM0007.Message: Unsupported memory configuration; check memory device at location %1.

FAN0003.Description: The fan is not performing optimally. The fan may be installed improperly or may be failing.
FAN0003.Resolution: Remove and re-install the fan. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
FAN0003.Message: Fan %1 RPM is greater than the upper critical threshold.

SWC0125.Description: The CSR file could not be generated.

IOV106.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to power on adapter. Possible reasons for power failures are: 1) Adapter not an approved adapter. 2) Adapter not fully inserted in the slot 3) Auxiliary power cable not connected (applicable to slot 1 - 3 only). 4) Adapter is damaged.
IOV106.Resolution: Make sure a supported PCIe device is used and that it is properly inserted in the PCIe slot. For a list of supported devices, contact the service provider.
IOV106.Message: Unable to power on PCIe adapter %1 in %2 %3.

UEFI0147.Description: The system hardware or cabling configuration is invalid.
UEFI0147.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Make sure the system cables, risers, and CPU configuration are installed correctly. 2) Reseat each PCIe riser and reconnect the cables. For more information, see the system Owner's Manual.
UEFI0147.Message: The system hardware or cabling configuration is invalid.

SYS129.Description: Unable to complete XML transform on the data collected because the collected data is in an unexpected format.
SYS129.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) If the issue persists, reinstall the latest OS Collector on the iDRAC, and then retry the operation.
SYS129.Message: OS Collector: Unable to complete XML transform on the data collected.

IOV123.Description: The PCIE Slot or PERC Virtual Adapter(VA) identified in the message has been unassigned/unmapped from the extension of the server slot identified in the message.
IOV123.Message: %1 %2 is unassigned/unmapped from extended server slot %3.

SYS074.Description: Unable to apply configuration changes because another configuration job is in progress.
SYS074.Resolution: Wait until the current configuration job is complete and retry the operation.
SYS074.Message: Unable to apply configuration changes because another configuration job is in progress.

RAC0642.Description: The job could not be successfully scheduled, because an invalid value is entered for 'day' of a month while scheduling a job.
RAC0642.Resolution: Enter a correct numerical value in the following format: Day [1 to 31] of every [1 to 12] month(s). For example, Day 4 of every 11 months. Retry the operation.
RAC0642.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid value is entered for the 'day' of a month.

LNK0003.Description: Cannot connect to the DNS server because of network issues or there is no response from the DNS server.
LNK0003.Resolution: Verify that the server is connected to the network and retry the operation.
LNK0003.Message: Unable to connect to the DNS server.

VDR21.Description: This message is generated after a consistency check completes on a virtual disk.

STOR099.Description: The FQDD cannot be found because an invalid FQDD is entered or an operation is pending on the FQDD identified in the message.
STOR099.Resolution: Do the following and then retry the operation: 1) Make sure the FQDD entered is valid. 2) Make sure an operation is not pending on the FQDD identified in the message. For more information refer to the RACADM Command Line Reference Guide.
STOR099.Message: Unable to find the FQDD %1 because an invalid FQDD is entered or an operation is pending on the specified FQDD.

BAT1029.Description: The controller battery cannot recharge. The battery may have already recharged the maximum number of times or the battery charger may not be working.
BAT1029.Message: The battery on %1 can no longer recharge.

RAC930.Description: Racadm is currently unable to obtain the inlet temperature data. This happens if there is no data populated in the temperature tables or if the instrumentation does not return valid values.
RAC930.Resolution: Wait for the instrumentation to populate the thermal tables. Retry the operation. If the problem persists, contact the service provider.
RAC930.Message: Unable to export the inlet temperature data.

SYS056.Description: Waiting for the system to shut down before applying configuration changes.
SYS056.Message: Waiting for the system to shut down.

SYS067.Description: Some or all configuration actions during the import of configuration XML operation did not complete successfully. The configuration action details are logged into the Lifecycle Log.
SYS067.Resolution: Export the Lifecycle Log and identify the configuration changes that did not successfully complete. Resolve any issues with the configuration XML content and retry the import operation.
SYS067.Message: Unable to complete application of configuration XML file values.

STOR0105.Description: No enclosure data to display. The system is powered off, enclosures are not present on the system, or enclosures are not connected to the RAID controllers.
STOR0105.Resolution: Check if the server has power, enclosures are available, and enclosures are connected to the RAID controllers.

HWC4002.Description: A hardware incompatibility was detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and other hardware. An iDRAC or BMC firmware update is needed.
HWC4002.Resolution: Update the BMC/iDRAC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC4002.Message: A hardware incompatibility detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and other hardware.

SWC0061.Description: Write-protection is enabled on the vFlash SD card.
SWC0061.Resolution: Remove the write-protection on the vFlash SD card and retry the operation.

PST0064.Description: System BIOS is displaying power on splash screen.

CMC003.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the parameter identified in the message is missing.
CMC003.Resolution: Enter the missing parameter and retry the operation. For information about the parameters, see the CMC Profile document available on the support site.
CMC003.Message: Unable to complete the operation because the parameter %1 is missing.

RAC074.Description: The iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation cannot be completed because a vflash partition creation operation is in progress.
RAC074.Resolution: Wait for the vFlash partition creation process to complete and retry the operation.
RAC074.Message: Unable to perform the iDRAC reset to factory defaults operation because a vFlash partition creation operation is in progress.

CPU0008.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.
CPU0008.Resolution: if unexpected, check presence, and system setup (BIOS) configuration.

PWR2205.Message: The system is in a soft-off state.

BAR056.Description: The configuration import was successful for the specified device.

SEC0606.Description: This may apply to a physical or remote access attempt.
SEC0606.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.
SEC0606.Message: The network boot password violation detected.

RAC0160.Description: Certificate upload failed because the certificate could not be validated.
RAC0160.Resolution: Certificate may be corrupt. Try creating a new Certificate Signing Request (CSR) and then upload the certificate.
RAC0160.Message: Certificate upload failed: Cannot validate the certificate.

SWC8522.Description: Successfully completed a configuration sync with the member identified in the message.
SWC8522.Message: Chassis Group Leader update of member %1 configuration successful.

HWC8502.Description: The internal cable that connects the I/O panel to the system board is properly connected.
HWC8502.Message: The I/O panel cable is connected.

SWC0722.Description: iDRAC is processing a previous reset to default command.
SWC0722.Message: Error occurred while resetting to defaults. The reset command was not accepted.

SWC8608.Description: The CMC was unable to perform the operation described in the message because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller of the server is disabled.
SWC8608.Resolution: Make sure that iDRAC on the server identified in the message is operating and that Lifecycle Controller is enabled, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform a virtual reseat of the server and retry the operation. To perform a virtual reseat of the server, on CMC Web interface, select Chassis Overview -> Troubleshooting -> Reset Components. On the Reset Components page, select Virtual Reseat from the drop-down menu for the server identified in the message.
SWC8608.Message: Server Profiles: unable to access server: %1 for operation [%2] because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller of the server is disabled.

UEFI0010.Description: A CPU stack-segment fault (type 0x0C) exception occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment.
UEFI0010.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

SWC8616.Description: The server identified in the message cannot be accessed remotely by iDRAC because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller for of the server is disabled.
SWC8616.Resolution: Make sure that the iDRAC on the server identified in the message is operating properly and that Lifecycle Controller is enabled, and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, perform a virtual reseat of the server and retry the operation. The server can be virtually reseated by using the CMC Web GUI interface and selecting Chassis Overview > Troubleshooting > Reset Components and then selecting Virtual Reseat from the drop down menu.
SWC8616.Message: Server in slot %1 is not ready to be accessed remotely because of one or more of the following reasons: 1) iDRAC is not ready. 2) Lifecycle Controller for of the server is disabled.

LC035.Description: This method is not supported in this version of Firmware.
LC035.Resolution: Update the iDRAC firmware to a version that supports this method.
LC035.Message: As-Shipped Hardware Inventory Export method is not supported.

STOR077.Description: A Patrol Read State change operation cannot be performed if the Patrol Read Mode is not set to Manual.
STOR077.Resolution: Change the Patrol Read Mode to Manual before performing a Patrol Read State change operation.
STOR077.Message: Unable to change Patrol Read State since Patrol Read Mode is not set to Manual.

BAR102.Description: Unable to import license data from the backup Server Profile.
BAR102.Resolution: Refer to iDRAC User Guide documentation license installation instructions and retry the operation.

STOR043.Description: One or more physical disk drives selected for the operation are part of a virtual disk that is not Secondary RAID Level 0.
STOR043.Resolution: This operation is not supported unless the previous virtual disk on the selected physical disk drives are deleted first. To perform the operation, delete any virtual disk on the selected physical disks drives and retry the operation.
STOR043.Message: One or more selected physical disk drives are part of virtual disk that is not Secondary RAID Level 0.

STOR067.Description: The operation did not succeed since the selected controller does not support creating uneven span RAID10 virtual disks.
STOR067.Resolution: The selected controller is not capable of creating an uneven span RAID10 virtual disk. Specify the proper span length and span depth combination for creating RAID10 virtual disk on the selected controller, and then retry the operation.
STOR067.Message: Controller does not support uneven span RAID10 virtual disks.

RDU8509.Description: For failover to occur, the standby CMC needs to be present, at the same version as the primary and healthy. During failover, the active CMC resets and the standby CMC becomes active. This message is logged when the standby CMC is absent, unhealthy or at a different firmware version.
RDU8509.Resolution: Check the status of the standby CMC and make sure the firmware version matches the primary CMC. Then reseat the CMC and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RDU8509.Message: CMC%1: cannot failover, chassis is in non-redundant state

PST0001.Description: System BIOS detected the system is turned on.

RAC0692.Description: Unable to assign and un-assign physical disk drives as global hotspare(s), because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0692.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0692.Message: Unable to assign and un-assign physical disk drives as global hotspare(s), because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

SWC0248.Description: The specified command has invalid syntax.
SWC0248.Resolution: Verify that the correct command syntax is specified. See the help text or documentation for valid commands.

PSU0039.Description: Insufficient amount of current to keep power supply operating at a normal levels.
PSU0039.Resolution: 1) Remove and re-install the power supply input cord. 2) Check power distribution or PSU input source for anomalies. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0039.Message: An under current fault detected on power supply %1.

UEFI0245.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization failed to configure all installed processors to the maximum common frequency.
UEFI0245.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0245.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) link initialization error detected.

MEM9001.Description: The memory interconnect is functioning normally.

PWR2257.Description: The target power allocation override has been enabled or disabled as identified in the message.
PWR2257.Message: The target power allocation override is %1. The target power allocation (AC) is %2 Watts.

BAR079.Description: The collection and export of Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration was not successful.
BAR079.Resolution: Apply the integrated remote access controller firmware, manually set the configuration attributes, and try the operation again.
BAR079.Message: Unable to collect the Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration.

SUP006.Description: The DUP is being downloaded and the update cannot be deleted while the download is in progress
SUP006.Resolution: Wait until the update package is downloaded and retry the action. The download can take more than 5 minutes depending on network speed and size of the update package.

RAC0602.Description: The value for alert recurrence must be within the range 0-365.

RAC1014.Description: The SNMPv3 privacy protocol cannot be configured to AES or DES mode if SNMPv3 authentication protocol state is set to "None".
RAC1014.Resolution: To configure the SNMPv3 Privacy Protocol for a specified iDRAC user, change the SNMPv3 Authentication Protocol to either MD5 or SHA state using "racadm set idrac.users.<index>.SNMPv3AuthenticationType <value>".
RAC1014.Message: The SNMPv3 privacy protocol cannot be configured to AES or DES mode if SNMPv3 authentication protocol state is set to "None".

VFL0013.Description: The request could not be successfully completed, because the vFlash SD Card is in read-only mode. Write operations cannot be performed on the card.
VFL0013.Resolution: Change the access mode on the vFlash SD Card to read-write.
VFL0013.Message: The vFlash SD Card is in read-only mode.

RAC1175.Description: The user configuration cannot be modified, because modification is not allowed at index 1.
RAC1175.Message: Unable to change the user configuration because modifying the user configuration at index 1 is not allowed.

PDR72.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes

LIC013.Description: The license includes features not supported in this firmware release.
LIC013.Resolution: Update the firmware to the latest version.
LIC013.Message: These license features are not supported by this firmware version.

SWC0003.Description: An unrecoverable error occurred while communicating with iDRAC.
SWC0003.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists:1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord.2) Wait for five seconds.3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0003.Message: Unable to display the Lifecycle log.

PCI3007.Message: Link Tuning or FlexAddress data successfully obtained.

RAC0752.Description: The value for information or warning threshold should not be greater than upper critical threshold value.
RAC0752.Resolution: Enter a threshold value that is lower than the upper warning or critical threshold values and retry the operation.
RAC0752.Message: The threshold value entered is greater than the upper warning or critical threshold.

STOR044.Description: One or more physical disks specified to create virtual disk (VD) is not valid because it is not part of the same disk group.
STOR044.Resolution: Enumerate existing virtual disks to find the physical disks of the same disk group. Specify physical disks that are of the same disk group and retry the operation.
STOR044.Message: All physical disks specified are not part of the same disk group.

VDR50.Description: The background initialization task encountered errors that cannot be corrected. The virtual disk contains physical disks that have unusable disk space or disk errors that cannot be corrected.
VDR50.Resolution: Review other messages to identify whether the physical disk that has errors. If the virtual disk is redundant, you can replace the physical disk and continue using the virtual disk. If the virtual disk is non-redundant, you need to recreate the virtual disk after replacing the physical disk. After replacing the physical disk, run a consistency check to verify the data.
VDR50.Message: Background Initialization (BGI) completed with uncorrectable errors on %1.

STOR0505.Description: Unable to delete the existing virtual disks for unknown reasons.
STOR0505.Resolution: Exit the RAID Configuration wizard and retry the operation. If the problem persists do the following: 1) Reboot the system. 2) Press the <F10> key to re-enter Lifecycle Controller. 3) Retry the operation.

BAR053.Description: Restoring device firmware on the device identified in the message.

OSD62.Description: The command cannot be run because an invalid firmware image file name is entered.
OSD62.Resolution: Make sure that a valid firmware image file is entered. The file must not contain any file path components such as forward slash (/) or period (.).
OSD62.Message: Unable to run the command because an invalid firmware image file name is entered.

SWC0158.Message: User CA certificate successfully uploaded to the RAC.

UEFI0086.Description: Unsupported Small Outline Dual In-line Memory Module (SODIMM) memory is installed on the RDIMM memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0086.Resolution: Remove the unsupported SODIMM module from the identified memory slot and replace it with a supported module. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0086.Message: Unsupported Small Outline Dual In-line Memory Module (SODIMM) memory is installed on RDIMM memory slot: %1.

SWC4013.Description: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between the components identified in the message.
SWC4013.Message: A firmware or software incompatibility was corrected between %1%2 and %3%4.

RAC0510.Description: This error occurs if Lifecycle log events have not occurred recently.
RAC0510.Message: There are no events to be displayed.

LC024.Description: Unable to retrieve Lifecycle Controller Log records because of an issue internal to the firmware.
LC024.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Try the operation again 2) AC power cycle the system 3) apply the latest firmware update packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.
LC024.Message: Unable to retrieve Lifecycle Controller Log records.

SWC0132.Description: Either the destination Ip address is not reachable or the required values are not configured.
SWC0132.Resolution: Check for the connectivity to the configured Ip address.
SWC0132.Message: Unable to send test trap. Please make sure that your trap has been configured correctly and connectivity to the destination endpoint exists.

TMP0138.Description: Disabling the C1E state in servers with processors that have their Thermal Design Power (TDP) value set to equal to or greater than 155 Watt results in increased fan speed during high CPU workloads.
TMP0138.Message: The C1 Enhance (C1E) state is disabled in the server. Increased fan speeds can be expected during high CPU workload.

LC077.Description: The new certificate will not be in-use until iDRAC has been restarted
LC077.Message: Certificate imported successfully. Reset iDRAC to apply new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset old certificate will be active

SUP024.Description: The InstanceID value provided for update operation is invalid.
SUP024.Resolution: Enumerate inventory, copy the InstanceID value and provide that value for the update operation
SUP024.Message: InstanceID value provided for the update operation is invalid

RAC1053.Description: Unable to view the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.
RAC1053.Resolution: Configure the Automatic Backup feature by running the RACADM command "racadm systemconfig backup" with the desired option settings.
RAC1053.Message: Unable to view the Automatic Backup (autobackup) feature settings because the feature has not been configured.

SYS010.Description: The input value for the specified attribute is not valid.
SYS010.Resolution: Refer to Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation and provide valid attribute value for the specified attribute.
SYS010.Message: Invalid character in value for attribute: %1

RED045.Description: The necessary user access rights for performing the operation identified in the message were removed or the username was removed and the iDRAC is unable to create the next job in the sequence.
RED045.Resolution: Use a username that has the necessary access rights and retry the operation.
RED045.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was unable to create a job because the necessary user access rights are not available now.

IOV008.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) was unable to reset the PCIe subsystem into factory default mode.
IOV008.Resolution: Turn off the chassis, turn on the chassis, and then retry the operation.
IOV008.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to put PCIe subsystem into factory default mode.

RAC0223.Description: The Subject line in the email contains invalid characters.
RAC0223.Resolution: Invalid character. Enter a valid value as mentioned in the online help.
RAC0223.Message: Enter an alphanumeric value or a valid symbol for the following (see the online help for more information):

RAC994.Description: The jobs cannot be deleted if they are in one of these states: "Scheduled" or "Running". However, all jobs in one of these states: "Completed" or "Failed" will be deleted.
RAC994.Resolution: To monitor the job status, use the "racadm jobqueue view -i <job ID>", and delete the jobs one at a time using the "racadm jobqueue delete -i <job ID>" command.
RAC994.Message: Unable to run the "jobqueue delete --all" command.
