MEM0010.Resolution: If unexpected, review system logs for power or thermal exceptions.
MEM0010.Message: Memory device at location %1 is overheating.

UEFI0248.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. A resource allocation was forced because resources were not requested for the identified processor. .
UEFI0248.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0248.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected on processor %1.

RAC961.Description: Another import operation cannot be started if an import operation that was performed earlier has some pending or committed configuration changes.
RAC961.Resolution: Wait until the configuration changes are applied before starting another import operation. Use the racadm jobqueue view command to check the status of the current import operation.
RAC961.Message: A pending or committed system configuration change exists.

PR4.Description: The current component firmware version is lower than the previous component firmware version.
PR4.Message: Older version of firmware found on device: %1

TMP1000.Description: The enclosure is too hot. A variety of factors can cause the excessive temperature. For example, a fan may have failed, the thermostat may be set too high, or the room temperature may be too hot.
TMP1000.Resolution: Check for factors that may cause overheating. For example, verify that the enclosure fan is working. You should check the thermostat settings and examine whether the enclosure is located near a heat source. Make sure the enclosure has enough ventilation and that the room temperature is not too hot. Refer to the enclosure documentation for more diagnostic information.

PWR8681.Description: The firmware identified in the message does not support the PCIe reassignment operation.
PWR8681.Resolution: Update the firmware identified in the message to the supported latest available version. See the latest iDRAC User Guide for information on the versions that support the PCIe reassignment.
PWR8681.Message: The %1 firmware in the server slot %2 does not support additional PCIe slots.

SWC0225.Description: The syntax of the command is incorrect.
SWC0225.Resolution: Refer to the help for remote image command.
SWC0225.Message: Invalid syntax. The -d option is not valid with -l.

LC044.Description: The Lifecycle Controller system configuration wipe operation is currently running. The operation deletes user information from system hardware and resets BIOS, iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller to default settings. The current operation and system restart must complete before the operation can be attempted again.
LC044.Resolution: Wait for the Lifecycle Controller system configuration wipe operation that is currently running to complete before requesting another operation.
LC044.Message: An instance of Lifecycle Controller system configuration wipe is already running.

RAC981.Description: A passphrase is required only for passphrase protected certificate, which is specified using the value of 3 for the -t option.
RAC981.Resolution: If the file being uploaded is passphrase protected, specify the file type as 3 using the -t option. If the file is not passphrase protected, retry the command, without specifying the -p option.
RAC981.Message: The type of certificate specified does not require a passphrase.

PDR1116.Description: The controller detected a drive removal
PDR1116.Resolution: If unintended, verify drive installation. Remove and reseat the indicated disk. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SWU8502.Description: The specified Lifecycle Controller operation is successfully submitted and the operation will be executed on the basis of scheduling criteria.
SWU8502.Message: A %1 request was submitted to the Lifecycle Controller on server %2.

NIC004.Description: The value for the specified parameter is invalid.
NIC004.Resolution: Verify that parameter values passed to the method are entered as they appear in the enumeration and parameter data type matches the documentation.

LIC202.Description: This error can occur when:1) Platform table has invalid value for default license feature set and permissible license upgrade path. In this case, the system sets the default licensed feature set to Basic Management and does not restrict the license upgrade path.2) License Manager fails to load due to lack of system resources.
LIC202.Message: A system error was detected during License Manager startup.

NIC516.Message: Static IP configuration enabled and modified successfully

SEL1304.Description: PXE is one way to boot a system from the network. (IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 02h)
SEL1304.Resolution: Check network and PXE server configuration.

RAC0146.Resolution: Try the operation after a few minutes. If the problem persists, reset iDRAC and repeat the operation.

PDR38.Description: A user has initiated a clear operation on a physical disk.

IOV116.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected a power fault in an PCIE AUX power cable after the adapter was powered on. A power fault may be caused by a loose cable connection to the adapter or between the cable and the AUX cable harness.
IOV116.Resolution: Make sure AUX power cable identified in the message is fully plugged into the adapter and the AUX cable harness.
IOV116.Message: PCIE AUX power cable %1.was disconnected while powered on.

SWC0050.Description: Unable to initiate Import operation since iDRAC is not responding.
SWC0050.Resolution: Retry the Import operation using a valid backup image file and the correct passphrase. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait for five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.

RAC958.Description: The import or export operation cannot be started because a job is already running.
RAC958.Resolution: Wait for the currently running job to complete and then retry the operation. The currently running job can be an update, backup, export or other job type. To view the status of currently running job using the RACADM command line interface, run the racadm jobqueue view command.
RAC958.Message: Unable to start the import or export operation because a job is already running.

LC055.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because the number of AttributeName input parameters provided to the method exceeded the number of attributes available in iDRAC.
LC055.Resolution: Retry the operation with an input parameter array that matches the available attributes in iDRAC.
LC055.Message: The operation did not complete successfully because of an invalid attribute array.

LIC901.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.
LIC901.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

CPU0025.Description: System is unable to boot or may run in a degraded state.
CPU0025.Resolution: Check presence and reinstall the terminator.

RED034.Description: A firmware update operation is currently in progress.
RED034.Resolution: Check the firmware update job status. Wait for the current job to complete.

SYS058.Description: Running Lifecycle Controller Automated Task Execution application in Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) environment to apply configuration changes.

NIC014.Description: AttributeValue may be invalid because of the following causes: 1) Length of new AttributeValue is not within minLength and maxLength 2) Value of new AttributeValue is not within LowerBound and UpperBound 3) Value of new Attributevalue is not one of the possible values.
NIC014.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on valid attribute values.

CTL59.Description: There may be a problem with the enclosure. Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. To verify the health of the enclosure, select the enclosure object in the tree view. The Health sub-tab displays a red X or yellow exclamation point for enclosure components that are failed or degraded. See the enclosure documentation for more information.
CTL59.Resolution: There may be a problem with the enclosure. Verify the health of the enclosure and its components. To verify the health of the enclosure, select the enclosure object in the tree view. The Health sub-tab displays a red X or yellow exclamation mark for enclosure components that are failed or degraded. See the enclosure documentation for more information.

RAC039.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.
RAC039.Resolution: Verify the value for the specified parameter. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

SWU8560.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful because of a unrecognized image error.
SWU8560.Resolution: Obtain a valid firmware image from your service provider and retry the operation.
SWU8560.Message: The firmware update process of Active CMC and Standby CMC was not successful because of a unrecognized image error.

SWC1923.Description: The server configuration cannot be modified by using Quick Sync because invalid credentials are entered.
SWC1923.Resolution: Make sure that correct user name and password are entered, and then retry the operation.
SWC1923.Message: Unable to modify the server configuration by using Quick Sync because invalid credentials are entered.

LOG002.Description: The value provided for the specified parameter is invalid.
LOG002.Resolution: To provide the correct value for the specified parameter, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

SYS180.Description: The TTY log data of the storage controller identified in the message cannot be exported because an issue was encountered while communicating with the controller.
SYS180.Resolution: While exporting the TTY log, make sure that the server is not in BIOS POST, and then retry the operation. Use GetRemoteServicesAPIStatus() invoke method and check for output parameter RTStatus and ensure it shows 0 (ready status) and then retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset iDRAC, and retry the operation.
SYS180.Message: There was an issue encountered when attempted to export TTY Log data for the storage controller %1.

VLT0301.Description: Low voltages may be the result of a problem with the voltage regulator or a problem with the processor. When the critical threshold is crossed, the processor will fail to operate. The system may power down.
VLT0301.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) Make sure the processor is seated correctly. 3) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0301.Message: CPU %1 %2 voltage is less than the lower critical threshold.

RDU0012.Description: The current power operational mode is non-redundant because of a power supply exception, a power supply inventory change, or a system power inventory change. The system was previously operating in a power redundant mode.
RDU0012.Resolution: Check the event log for power supply failures. Review system configuration and power consumption.

RED060.Description: The specified repository catalog is either not supported or the structure is incorrect. Only Windows Update Packages are supported by iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller for the operation. If the structure is incorrect, either the expected elements are not present, or unexpected elements are present in the catalog XML file. The catalog XML file should be generated by the Repository Manager tool.
RED060.Resolution: Check the repository catalog file name and contents. Rebuild the catalog XML file using Repository Manager by selecting Windows Update Packages only, and retry the operation.
RED060.Message: The specified repository catalog is not supported.

UEFI0131.Description: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient shadow memory. The option ROM shadow memory is located between C0000h and F0000h.
UEFI0131.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Remove unused PCIe card(s) to free up option ROM space. 2) Disable unused boot protocol instances (such as PXE, iSCSI, etc.) from applicable PCIe card(s) option ROM configurations. 3) If possible, install and run the Operating System in UEFI boot mode.
UEFI0131.Message: Unable to load one or more option ROMs because of insufficient shadow memory.

NIC009.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage because it is use by another application or operation.
NIC009.Resolution: Wait for the current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator utility 2) Not waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
NIC009.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

RAC0684.Description: Unable to perform split mode configuration on the selected enclosures, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.
RAC0684.Resolution: To enable Lifecycle Controller, reboot the server. During server startup, press F2 to enter System Setup. Go to iDRAC Settings -> Lifecycle Controller, select Enable, and save the changes. Retry the operation after the server has restarted.
RAC0684.Message: Unable to perform split mode configuration on the selected enclosures, because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

BAT1034.Description: One or more battery properties were modified.
BAT1034.Message: The battery properties for %1 have changed.

LOG507.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of lack of memory or file space in the CMC.
LOG507.Resolution: Reset the CMC and retry the operation.
LOG507.Message: Unable to allocated required CMC resources.

OSE1000.Description: The system OS has successfully booted from A:

UEFI0140.Description: The System Service Mode (SSM) cannot be entered because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This situation is caused by missing LC partitions.
UEFI0140.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0140.Message: Unable to enter System Service Mode (SSM) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

SWC8558.Description: No specified MAC addresses were deleted because they were not present in MAC Address Pool.
SWC8558.Message: No specified MAC addresses were deleted because they were not present in MAC Address Pool of Boot Identity profile operations.

RAC1064.Description: Unable to initiate the requested SystemErase operation because another SystemErase job is already in progress.
RAC1064.Resolution: To check the job status, run the RACADM command "racadm jobqueue view" and retry the operation after the current SystemErase operation has completed.
RAC1064.Message: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation because another instance of SystemErase job is already in progress.

CTL106.Description: The Background Initialization Rate of the controller identified in the message is set to the value identified in the message.
CTL106.Message: The Background Initialization Rate of %1 is set to %2.

CTL95.Description: The controller identified in the message has stopped operating in a fault tolerant mode.
CTL95.Resolution: This situation may resolve itself in a few minutes. If the situation does not resolve itself or this message is repeated, contact your service provider.
CTL95.Message: %1 has left the fault tolerant pair.

FC012.Description: No changes to component attribute data are available between the previous configuration and the current configuration.

UEFI0158.Description: The iDRAC request to reset BIOS to default settings cannot be completed.
UEFI0158.Resolution: Restart the system and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0158.Message: Unable to complete the iDRAC request to reset BIOS to default settings.

VF026.Description: This partition index has already been used.
VF026.Resolution: This partition index has already been used. Try a different index.

RAC0263.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the Alternate IPv6 DNS Server address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0263.Resolution: Enter a valid Alternate IPv6 DNS server address.
RAC0263.Message: The Alternate IPv6 DNS Server Address is invalid.

CTL3.Description: You have enabled the controller alarm. This alert is provided for informational purposes.

BIOS023.Description: An unrecoverable error occurred in the operation while communicating with iDRAC.
BIOS023.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue continues, reset the iDRAC.
BIOS023.Message: Cannot perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

VDR97.Description: The Patrol Read task has encountered an error such as a bad disk block and remapped data to correct the error.
VDR97.Message: Patrol Read corrected a media error on %1.

RAC0561.Description: iDRAC lost connection with CMC proxy component that enables agent free monitoring of PCIe slots. Agent free monitoring will not be supported for Chassis PCIe slots while this connection is not functioning.
RAC0561.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check the Lifecycle Log for the subsequent RAC0562 communications restored message that will indicate the link was re-established automatically. 2) If there is no subsequent RAC0562 message in the Lifecycle Log, restart the iDRAC. The iDRAC can be restarted by using the RACADM command line utility and entering "racadm racreset". 3) After the iDRAC has restarted, if the communications link is still not functioning, restart the CMC and check the Lifecycle Log for this link error after the CMC has restarted. 4) If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0561.Message: iDRAC to CMC communication link is not functioning for agent free monitoring of chassis PCIe slots.

RAC0675.Description: Results are not available for the search criterion entered.
RAC0675.Resolution: Enter another criterion and retry the operation.
RAC0675.Message: Results are not available for the search criterion entered.

SWC0213.Message: Disable the Virtual Console from a local Console

SUP0526.Description: Unable to continue the firmware update because the catalog file or the update package is corrupt.
SUP0526.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, download the latest Update Package or Catalog file from your service provider and retry the operation.
SUP0526.Message: Unable to continue with firmware update.

SYS139.Description: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.
SYS139.Resolution: Retry the operation after the server has finished starting and POST has completed.
SYS139.Message: Unable to start the collection of OS and Application Data because the server is in POST and has not finished startup.

SWC0232.Description: Remote RACADM commands are not supported on the current iDRAC.
SWC0232.Resolution: If remote RACADM is a necessity, upgrade the iDRAC version.
SWC0232.Message: Remote RACADM commands are not supported on this iDRAC. To upgrade your iDRAC version, contact your service provider.

HWC4000.Description: A hardware incompatibility was detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and Processor(s). An iDRAC or BMC firmware update is needed.
HWC4000.Resolution: Update the BMC/iDRAC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.
HWC4000.Message: A hardware incompatibility detected between BMC/iDRAC firmware and CPU.

STOR006.Description: The operation could not be completed because of an issue with the management controller (either the iDRAC or the Chassis Management Controller (CMC)) that is managing the storage.
STOR006.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.

VDR30.Description: A user changed the write policy for a virtual disk.
VDR30.Resolution: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

DIS005.Description: Message was sent successfully from Auto Discovery to Provisioning Server to request certificate.
DIS005.Message: Auto Discovery communicated successfully with Provisioning Server %1.

RAC0284.Description: This is the time span (in seconds) within which login attempts from an IP address with excessive failures are rejected. The default value is 3600 seconds (1 hour).
RAC0284.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Blocking Fail Penalty Time. Expected range: 10-65535.
RAC0284.Message: IP Blocking Fail Penalty Time is invalid. Expected range: 10-65535.

OSD67.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'IPAddress' is missing.
OSD67.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "IPAddress" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD67.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'IPAddress' is missing.

CTL25.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL25.Message: Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.

BAR023.Description: The process is entering the component update phase of the restore operation.

JCP000.Description: A new job with the ID identified in the message is created.
JCP000.Message: A new job with ID %1 is created.

STOR11.Description: The current hardware configuration is setup correctly for High Availability. However, the current firmware does not provide this functionality and one of the cards will be kept in a powered down state until High Availability capable firmware is installed.
STOR11.Message: The currently detected hardware configuration is High Availability Ready. However, the current software solution does not yet support high availability.

RAC0613.Description: An internal error occurred because of an invalid file.
RAC0613.Resolution: Make sure to upload the required file in the correct format and retry the operation.

OSD77.Description: The method cannot be invoked because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is missing.
OSD77.Resolution: Provide the missing parameter "ResetType" in the method invocation and retry the operation.
OSD77.Message: Unable to invoke the method because the mandatory input parameter 'ResetType' is missing.

LC020.Description: The contents of the PKCS12 parameter was not valid because: 1) not a valid PKCS12 file 2) not a valid pfx file 3) did not contain a certificate that matched the private key in the file.
LC020.Resolution: Validate that the PKCS12 content was Base64 encoded. OpenSSL can be used to create or validate a PKCS12 encoding.
LC020.Message: PKCS12 decrypt of the certificate could not complete.

MEM9016.Description: The memory device identified in the message may not be operational. This an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM9016.Resolution: Re-install the memory component identified in the message. If the issue persists, contact your service provider. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM9016.Message: Correctable memory error rate exceeded for Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM)%1.

USR0021.Description: The session could not be closed. A possible reason is that the session does not exist.
USR0021.Message: Unable to close session with the specified ID

PDR75.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes

SEL0014.Description: The System Event Log (SEL) was cleared by the username identified in the message from the IP address identified in the message.
SEL0014.Message: The System Event Log (SEL) was cleared by %1 from %2.

PWR8678.Description: The power property identified in the message is changed as identified in the message.
PWR8678.Message: The value of the property %1 is %2.

TMP0105.Message: The system board %1 temperature is within range.

CMC002.Description: The operation cannot be successfully completed because of an unknown issue.
CMC002.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation. 2) Reset CMC and retry the operation.
CMC002.Message: Unable to complete the operation because of an unknown issue.

CMC8571.Description: The coin cell battery in the primary CMC is not working. The battery needs to be replaced.
CMC8571.Resolution: Replace the coin cell battery in the primary CMC.
CMC8571.Message: The coin cell battery in the primary CMC is not working.

SWU8555.Description: Active and Standby CMC firmware update process is initiated.
SWU8555.Message: Active CMC and Standby CMC firmware updates have been initiated.

CTL50.Description: The NVRAM has corrupt data. The controller is unable to correct the situation.

PSU502.Description: The server was already down, when the user gave a power off request.

RAC0158.Description: The Kerberos keytab is needed by the iDRAC to authenticate itself to the Kerberos (Active Directory) server. It is created on the AD server, and issued for the iDRAC. Its like a password, and therefore should be kept secret.
RAC0158.Resolution: The Kerberos keytab file may be corrupt. Upload a valid Kerberos keytab file.

LC060.Description: Lifecycle controller is currently performing tasks and another task cannot be scheduled until the previous task finishes.
LC060.Resolution: Wait until Lifecycle controller finishes performing current tasks and host system to finish POST.
LC060.Message: Lifecycle controller is currently not ready to take provisioning requests

PWR8551.Description: This will be logged when a Virtual Infrastructure Device power allocation is configured.
PWR8551.Message: Successfully set Virtual Infrastructure Device power to %1 DC Watt.

UEFI0027.Description: A license change for the system or a component in the system requires a system reset in order for the new license to take effect.
UEFI0027.Resolution: Wait for the BIOS to reset the system.
UEFI0027.Message: The system must be restarted for the new license to become effective.

OSD33.Description: The system has an older version of BIOS that does not support this method. Install the latest version of BIOS to use this method.
OSD33.Resolution: Update the BIOS to version 1.2 or later and then rerun the command.
OSD33.Message: Installed BIOS version does not support this method.

PDR117.Description: The PCIe solid state device identified in the message has turned off because the critical temperature threshold of the device was exceeded.
PDR117.Resolution: Contact your service provider for further instructions.
PDR117.Message: The %1 has turned off because the critical temperature threshold is exceeded.

SUP0117.Message: Firmware rollback initiated successfully. The iDRAC will now reset to complete the firmware rollback operation.

SWC8513.Description: The user name identified in the message was successfully deleted.

UEFI0273.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv4 server is invalid.
UEFI0273.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Reconfigure the DHCPv4 server root path option, and note that server name must be specified. 2) Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings > Connection Settings page, disable Target Info via DHCP and configure the parameters manually. Retry the operation.
UEFI0273.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI target configuration data obtained from DHCPv4 server is invalid.

PST0139.Description: System BIOS detected a failure with the Keyboard Controller. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST exception code 8B)
PST0139.Resolution: Remove and reapply input power. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SWC8624.Description: The network communication session between CMC and I/O Aggregator (IOA) cannot be started because the IOA did not respond.
SWC8624.Resolution: Power-cycle the IOA and retry the operation.
SWC8624.Message: The network communication session between CMC and I/O Aggregator cannot be started on %1.

SWC8563.Description: The Boot Identity profile identified in the message is cleared from the server identified in the message.
SWC8563.Message: Boot Identity profile %1 is cleared from server in slot %2.

OSD58.Description: The connect ISO operation using Remote File Share (RFS) did not complete successfully.
OSD58.Resolution: Verify all the parameters are correct. If the problem persists. then reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
OSD58.Message: Unable to connect an ISO using Remote File Share (RFS).

CPU0001.Description: The processor temperature increased beyond the operational range. Thermal protection shut down the processor. Factors external to the processor may have induced this exception.
CPU0001.Resolution: Review logs for fan failures, replace failed fans. If no fan failures are detected, check inlet temperature (if available) and reinstall processor heatsink.
CPU0001.Message: CPU %1 has a thermal trip (over-temperature) event.

PCI3004.Description: Either the BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, or mezzanine card firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3004.Resolution: Update BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, and mezzanine card firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3004.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card %1 failed to support Link Tuning or FlexAddress.

USR0017.Description: There are no active sessions on the iDRAC for the specified user.
USR0017.Message: No active sessions currently exist for the specified user.

HWC5008.Resolution: Contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
HWC5008.Message: Console is not available for the %1.

ISM0016.Description: The BMC watchdog reset time is changed to a value identified in the message.
ISM0016.Message: The BMC watchdog reset time is changed to %1 seconds.

UEFI0133.Description: Unable to perform PXE boot because the VLAN settings conflict with that of the iSCSI device settings.
UEFI0133.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Go to System Setup and change the VLAN configuration for the PXE device to match that of the iSCSI device. Either both devices must be configured with VLAN enabled or both devices must be configured with VLAN disabled. 2) Change the PXE device interface setting to use a different NIC interface than the NIC interface used by the iSCSI device.
UEFI0133.Message: Unable to perform PXE boot because the VLAN settings conflict with that of the iSCSI device settings.

PCI1362.Description: System performance may be degraded. The bus is not operating at maximum speed or width.
PCI1362.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next scheduled service time.
PCI1362.Message: Bus performance degraded for a component at slot %1.

RAC1130.Description: The requested operation could not be successfully completed because of an unsupported version of BIOS, USC, and/or iDRAC firmware.
RAC1130.Resolution: Verify whether or not a correct version of BIOS, Lifecycle Controller, and/or iDRAC firmware is installed. For more information on the appropriate firmware version required, refer to the RACADM Command Line Reference Guide. Also check if there is a limitation in terms of platforms such as monolithic or modular, and then retry the operation.
RAC1130.Message: Unable to complete the operation. This feature is not supported on the currently-used platform.

VFL0009.Description: Unable to access the vFlash media, because another operation is currently using the vFlash media.
VFL0009.Resolution: Wait until the vFlash media is available for the requested operation, and then retry the operation.
VFL0009.Message: vFlash media is currently in use by another operation.

LNK8501.Description: The network connection of the identified server to the external network is restored.
LNK8501.Message: The network connection of server in slot %1 IOM in slot %2 port %3 is restarted.

SWC0118.Description: The syntax of the sslcertupload command is invalid.
SWC0118.Resolution: Refer the help text for sslcertupload subcommand.

SWC0149.Description: The requested SNMP test trap alert was successfully sent.

RAC968.Description: The configuration XML file cannot be imported from a client location when using Firmware RACADM.
RAC968.Resolution: When using Firmware RACADM, make sure to import the configuration XML file from a remote share only.
RAC968.Message: Importing the configuration XML file from a local share is not supported when using Firmware RACADM.

RAC025.Description: Unable to set static values for DNS1 or DNS2 when DNS from DHCP is Enabled.
RAC025.Resolution: Disable DNS from DHCP to set values for DNS1 or DNS2.
RAC025.Message: Unable to set values for DNS1 or DNS2 attributes because DNS from DHCP is Enabled.

RFM1024.Description: At boot, the Card Identification (CID) signature of the card is different from the Non-volatile (NV) storage value or the card is the destination of a copy operation that is in-progress.
RFM1024.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.

SEL9900.Description: The current software version cannot decode this event. The source of the event may come from a source that is not compatible with this software or the event may have been added after the release of this software. You may need to review this event using a tool which displays raw data such as Ipmitool with the -vvv option or Racadm with the -E option.

PWR2263.Description: User continued after receiving power supplyoversubscription warning (F1/F2).
PWR2263.Message: User ignored Power Supply Oversubscription Warning.

RAC0619.Description: The message appears in Firmware Rollback page when the iDRAC firmware rollback action completed successfully.
RAC0619.Resolution: Reconnect iDRAC communications sessions after iDRAC is restarted. The iDRAC will be ready for login once the restart is complete.
RAC0619.Message: The iDRAC firmware rollback will cause an iDRAC restart and all current user sessions will be closed.

STOR017.Description: The virtual disk specified is not compatible with the requested operation or a specified operation parameter is not appropriate for the virtual disk type specified.
STOR017.Resolution: Make sure the operation parameters are appropriate for the virtual disk type. Specify a compatible virtual disk for the requested operation and retry the operation.
STOR017.Message: The specified Virtual Disk is not valid for the operation.

SWU8554.Description: Local CMC firmware update process is initiated.
SWU8554.Message: Local CMC firmware update has been initiated.

SYS171.Description: The import operation cannot be completed successfully because the SHA1v3Key and the MD5V3Key values must both be supplied.
SYS171.Resolution: The SHA1v3Key and the MD5V3Key values must be entered together for an import operation.
SYS171.Message: Unable to successfully complete the import operation because not all hash password values have been entered.

UEFI0148.Description: The SAS cable for the primary SAS expander daughter card is missing or misconfigured.
UEFI0148.Resolution: Check the cable configuration.For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0148.Message: The SAS cable %1 for the primary SAS expander daughter card is missing or misconfigured.

USR8510.Description: Successful login by Username identified in the message.

UEFI0249.Description: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization encountered a programmatic error. A requested resource could not be allocated. Resource was forced to maximum possible value instead.
UEFI0249.Resolution: Reseat all processors in the system and ensure all processors are matching. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0249.Message: Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) initialization error detected.

PDR5.Description: A physical disk has been removed from the disk group. This alert can also be caused by loose or defective cables or by problems with the enclosure.
PDR5.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) If a physical disk was removed from the disk group, either replace the disk or restore the original disk. Identify the disk that was removed by locating the disk that has a red "X" for its status. 2) Perform a rescan after replacing or restoring the disk. 3) If a disk was not removed from the disk group, then check for cable problems. Refer to product documentation for more information on checking the cables. 4) Make sure that the enclosure is powered on. 5) If the problem persists, check the enclosure documentation for further diagnostic information.

VF028.Description: This partition is detached and attempts to detach it will fail.

RAC0224.Description: A partial string used to construct a complete error message.

SUP0109.Description: The firmware update cannot proceed without the TFTP IP address.
SUP0109.Message: A TFTP IP address has not been specified but is required.

LOG502.Description: The command cannot be run because the method parameter identified in the message is missing.
LOG502.Resolution: Enter all the parameters required in the command, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the Chassis Record Log Profile.
LOG502.Message: Unable to run the command because the method parameter %1 is missing.

UEFI0229.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Receive Enable Training - Calibration phase.
UEFI0229.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0229.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

RAC1132.Description: The firmware could not be successfully updated, because one or all of the following values are incorrect:a. logon IDb. IP address of TFTP or FTP serverc. Full path of the firmware file.
RAC1132.Resolution: Run the racadm command "racadm help <subcommand>" to get more details about the various options applicable for this command and the values accepted by the command.
RAC1132.Message: Unable to update the firmware. The value entered for an option is invalid.

MEM0003.Description: The memory is operational. This is an early indicator of a possible future uncorrectable error.
MEM0003.Resolution: Re-install the memory component. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
MEM0003.Message: Stuck bit memory error detected on a memory device at location %1.

BAT1005.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1005.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle has been postponed.

VFL0002.Description: The status of vFlash SD Card or the vFlash media partition cannot be obtained, because some of the iDRAC services are busy.
VFL0002.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, restart the iDRAC and retry the operation. If the issue continues to persist, contact your service provider.
VFL0002.Message: Unable to query the vFlash media status.

RAC014.Description: The method cannot be run because an invalid attribute name is entered.
RAC014.Resolution: Enter a valid attribute name and retry the operation.
RAC014.Message: Unable to run the method because an invalid attribute name is entered.

CMC8518.Description: the Double height server identified in the message is detected in the top slot. However, the bottom slot is also responding which should not occur if a double height server is inserted.
CMC8518.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove the server identified in the message. 2) Restart the CMC and wait for the CMC to complete the start up process. 3) Reinsert the server identified in the message. If the problem persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8518.Message: Detecting Double height server in slot %1 but the iDRAC in bottom slot %1 is also responding.

RAC1062.Description: Unable to initiate the requested SystemErase operation. The component identifier specified is not valid.
RAC1062.Resolution: Run the RACADM command "racadm help systemerase" to see the list of supported components.
RAC1062.Message: Unable to initiate the SystemErase operation. The component identifier specified is not valid.

RAC0279.Description: An invalid IPMI encryption key was entered.
RAC0279.Resolution: Enter a valid encryption key of up to 40 characters. Odd number of characters and blank spaces are not allowed.
RAC0279.Message: Invalid Encryption Key. Expected format: 0 to 40 characters, even number of characters and no blank spaces are allowed.

RAC0135.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while detaching the vFlash partition.
RAC0135.Message: An error has occurred while detaching a partition.

PSU0019.Message: The input power for power supply %1 has been restored.

LIC017.Description: This error can occur when the license file: 1) Signature is not valid. 2) Data is not in the correct format. 3) Missing needed data. 4) Contains unknown data.5) Has not been unzipped.
LIC017.Resolution: Download the license file, unzip and import the license.
LIC017.Message: The license file is corrupted, has not been unzipped, or is not a valid license file.

PCI3016.Description: Either the BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, or mezzanine card firmware is out of date and does not support FlexAddress.
PCI3016.Resolution: Update BIOS, BMC/iDRAC, and mezzanine card firmware. If problem persists please contact customer support.
PCI3016.Message: Device option ROM on mezzanine card failed to support Link Tuning or FlexAddress.

RAC0509.Description: The server is currently unable to handle the request due to temporary overloading or server maintenance.
RAC0509.Resolution: Wait for few minutes and refresh the page. If the issue persists, contact service provider.
RAC0509.Message: The server is temporarily unavailable. Try again after sometime

SWC8619.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to process inventory data from the server in the slot identified in the message. This can happen if: 1) There is a communications issue between the CMC and the iDRAC on the server identified in the message. 2) Incorrect firmware is installed on network cards. 3) Incorrect firmware is installed on the server iDRAC. 4) There is no free temporary storage in the CMC.
SWC8619.Resolution: Do the following and retry the operation: 1) Make sure the latest firmware is installed on the network cards and iDRAC on the server identified in the message. 2) Reset the Chassis Management Controller. 3) Reset the server iDRAC. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8619.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to process data from the server in slot %1.

BAR026.Description: The configuration is being set for each component.

RAC0910.Description: The specified command is missing group and object name syntax.
RAC0910.Resolution: Specify the correct subcommand group and object name syntax. See the help text or documentation for the valid syntax.
RAC0910.Message: Invalid subcommand syntax: Specify group and object name.

SEL1204.Description: The operating system or BIOS detected an unknown event. (IPMI sensor type code 12h - offset 02h)
SEL1204.Resolution: Reduce system to minimum supported configuration. If issues persists, contact support.
SEL1204.Message: An unknown system hardware failure detected.

ENC22.Description: The enclosure has a bad sensor. The enclosure sensors monitor the fan speeds, temperature probes, and so on.
ENC22.Resolution: Refer to the storage hardware documentation for more information.

SWC8507.Description: A new Profile identified in the message has been created.

STOR033.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because an invalid value is specified for Start/Until Time.
STOR033.Resolution: Enter a valid Start/Until Time and retry the operation. For more information about the Start/Until Time, see the RAID Profile specification.
STOR033.Message: Invalid parameter value for Start/Until Time.

RAC0719.Description: Not able to connect to remote file share. Virtual media devices are already in use.
RAC0719.Resolution: Stop existing Virtual Media sessions and retry the operation.
RAC0719.Message: Not able to connect to remote file share. Virtual media devices are already in use.

SWU8543.Description: The firmware update operation of CMC was not successful. The Image file was not accessible.
SWU8543.Resolution: Make sure that the CMC firmware image file is available at the location specified in the operation, and then retry the operation.
SWU8543.Message: Unable to update the Active CMC firmware. The Image file was not accessible.

PWR8552.Description: There is insufficient power for the component identified in the message to turn on.
PWR8552.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to distribute power. Using the CMC Web UI, go to Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis. Contact your service provider for information on the power required for the component identified in the message.
PWR8552.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to turn on %1-%2 because of insufficient power.

SWC1920.Description: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is enabled.
SWC1920.Message: The Chassis Management at Server Mode is enabled.

MEM0022.Description: The memory may not be seated correctly, misconfigured, or has failed. Memory size is reduced.
MEM0022.Resolution: If unexpected, check presence, then re-install.
MEM0022.Message: Memory device at location %1 is absent.

PSU0038.Message: Power supply %1 fan is operating normally.

OSE1007.Resolution: Review system boot configuration and boot media. See system video for additional information

DIS100.Description: The AutoConfig operation is successfully completed by the iDRAC using the AutoConfig import file specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

RAC046.Description: The event notification selected is not supported for the event filter specified.
RAC046.Resolution: Refer to the iDRAC User Guide and Lifecycle Controller documentation and retry the operation with a valid event notification selection on the specified filter.
RAC046.Message: Unsupported event notification for the event filter specified.

PWR2261.Description: The iDRAC experienced an issue initializing the Current Monitor. The system motherboard may need replacement.
PWR2261.Message: Current Monitor initialization issue observed, IMON Revision %1, CPLD IMON MFR Revision %2.

PDR86.Description: The number of blocks on the disk that exhibit an error has exceeded the capacity of the drive to remap. Any future writes to bad sectors will be unrecoverable.
PDR86.Message: Bad block table on %1 is full.

UEFI0235.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Memory Buffer Write Leveling Training - Calibration phase.
UEFI0235.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0235.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

UEFI0044.Description: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the processor does not support TXT.
UEFI0044.Message: Unable to enable the TXT feature because the motherboard chipset does not support TXT.

ISM0007.Description: The iDRAC Service Module ended communication with iDRAC over the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel. This is because either iDRAC is being restarted or the OS to iDRAC Pass-through configuration is being changed. The iDRAC Service Module will continue to try connecting to iDRAC.
ISM0007.Message: The iDRAC Service Module communication with iDRAC has ended.

RED097.Description: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is for a component that is not in the target system inventory.
RED097.Resolution: Identify and download the firmware version that corresponds to the component being updated in the target system inventory, and retry the operation. For a list of supported firmware versions, refer to the iDRAC User's Guide available on the support site.
RED097.Message: Unable to complete the firmware update operation because the specified firmware image is for a component that is not in the target system inventory.

PST0005.Description: System BIOS has started copying image from flash to system memory.

VLT0205.Message: The system board %1 voltage is within range.

SYS045.Description: An error occurred while copying the system configuration XML file to the network share.
SYS045.Resolution: If the file is being exported to an NFS share, make sure that it is accessible from iDRAC. If the file is being exported to a CIFS share, make sure that it is accessible from iDRAC using share access credentials with the appropriate privileges.
SYS045.Message: Unable to copy the system configuration XML file to the network share.

STOR309.Description: The command cannot be run because multiple targets must not be entered as input in the Blink/Unblink Target method.
STOR309.Resolution: Enter only one target FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor), and then retry the operation.
STOR309.Message: Unable to run the command because multiple targets must not be entered as input in the Blink/Unblink Target method.

RAC0152.Description: While the system is powered off it is unable to retrieve information about power supplies.
RAC0152.Resolution: Turn the system on to view this information.
RAC0152.Message: Unable to retrieve the power supply information. The system is powered off.

SYS093.Description: The iDRAC is exporting the Tech Support Report to the specified destination.
SYS093.Message: The iDRAC is exporting the Tech Support Report.

UEFI0202.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Health Check phase.
UEFI0202.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0202.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

SWC0324.Description: There are no records to display. This might be a result of the log being cleared.
SWC0324.Message: There are no records available to display.

SEC0001.Description: The drive bay is open. A drive may be added or removed. System performance may be degraded.
SEC0001.Resolution: Close the drive bay. Check system logs.

LC075.Description: Deleting the custom signed certificate should regenerate a new unique certificate . Reset iDRAC to apply new certificate. Until iDRAC is reset old certificate will be active
LC075.Message: The Custom Signed Certificate (CSC) is deleted successfully. iDRAC will now restart and be unavailable during restart

VDR14.Description: A user cancelled the consistency check operation for a virtual disk.
VDR14.Message: The consistency check on %1 was cancelled.

IOV118.Description: The Fabric identified in the message is not up and a chassis power cycle is required.
IOV118.Resolution: Power cycle the chassis. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) RACADM command line interface, run the command "racadm chassisaction powercycle".

RAC0657.Description: The file name cannot be blank when performing the Backup Server Profile operation.
RAC0657.Resolution: Enter an appropriate file name, and then retry the operation.
RAC0657.Message: The file name field must not be blank.

IOV002.Description: CMC could not successfully allocate resources because of the following reasons: 1) The chassis manager is unable to allocate required resources. 2) The chassis manager or chassis infrastructure firmware is rolled back to an earlier version. 3) There is an issue with the internal communications between chassis components.
IOV002.Resolution: Make sure the firmware for the various chassis components are compatible with each other. If this is the case, do the following: 1) Turn off the chassis, by pressing the chassis Power Button, 2) run the following CMC RACADM command "racadm racresetcfg". If the problem persists, contact your technical service provider.
IOV002.Message: Unable to create or allocate the required resources.

RAC036.Description: The value of the specified attribute is dependent on the value of another attribute. The current value dependency is invalid. The other attribute value must be changed before the specified attribute value can be set.
RAC036.Resolution: Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation for the specified attribute dependency on another attribute value and retry the operation.

RAC0271.Description: Locking the user account prevents them from gaining access to iDRAC.
RAC0271.Resolution: Press OK to lock this user account. This action will prevent future access for this user. If undesired press Cancel.

SEL1207.Message: An entry was removed from auxiliary log.

SWC0299.Description: The Email Address provided is invalid.
SWC0299.Message: The Destination Email Address is invalid.

UEFI0266.Description: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on the connection identified in the message because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 subnet mask address is invalid.
UEFI0266.Resolution: Go to System Setup > Network Settings > iSCSI Device Settings page, make sure there is no typographical error in the Initiator Subnet Mask field, and retry the operation.
UEFI0266.Message: Unable to perform iSCSI boot on connection %1 because the iSCSI initiator IPv4 subnet mask address is invalid.

SEC0610.Description: This may apply to a remote access attempt.
SEC0610.Resolution: Check system logs for intrusion attempts, and ensure strong password policies.

UEFI0182.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. A corrected Early Vref Centering error was detected.
UEFI0182.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0182.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

SWU8529.Description: The iKVM firmware update operation was not successful, because the firmware Image file could not be transferred to the target.
SWU8529.Resolution: Make sure that the iKVM firmware Image file is available at the specified location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8529.Message: Unable to update the iKVM firmware, because the Image file was not transferred to the iKVM target.

OSD15.Description: Unable to mount the network share using the credentials specified in the command because either the username or password is incorrect.
OSD15.Resolution: Rerun the command with the correct username and password.
OSD15.Message: Mount network share failed - incorrect username or password.

VF013.Description: The SD card is locked by another operation.
VF013.Resolution: Rerun the command after about 2 minutes

RAC0673.Description: To export operating system (OS) and application data, the OS Collector utility must be run on the server OS. A virtual USB device labeled DRACRW has appeared in the server OS. After the OS Collector utility execution has completed, return to this page to complete exporting the Tech Support Report (TSR).
RAC0673.Resolution: Invoke the OS Collector utility in the OS and wait for execution completion. Then return to this page to complete exporting the Technical Support Report (TSR).
RAC0673.Message: OS Collector must be run on the server OS in order to export OS and Application Data. A virtual USB device labeled DRACRW has appeared in the server OS. This device contains the OS Collector utility, go to the Server OS and run the version of the utility appropriate to the OS type. After the OS Collector utility execution has completed, return to this page to finish exporting the Technical Support Report (TSR).

ENC5.Description: One or more of the enclosure components has failed. For example, a fan or power supply may have failed. Although the enclosure is currently operational, the failure of additional components could cause the enclosure to fail.
ENC5.Resolution: Identify and replace the failed component. To identify the failed component, select the enclosure in the tree view and click the Health subtab. Any failed component will be identified with a red X on the enclosure's Health subtab. Alternatively, you can select the Storage object and click the Health subtab. The controller status displayed on the Health subtab indicates whether a controller has a failed or degraded component. See the enclosure documentation for information on replacing enclosure components and for other diagnostic information.

BAT1007.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
BAT1007.Message: The battery on %1 learn cycle will start in %2 hours.

BAR069.Description: The system profile export did not complete successfully because there is insufficient space on the vFlash media.
BAR069.Resolution: Delete partitions and free up 384 MB of space on the current vFlash media, or use new vFlash media.

SWC8531.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to set the administrator role for the iDRAC root user. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or iDRAC is rebooting.
SWC8531.Resolution: If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8531.Message: Chassis Management Controller unable to set iDRAC administrator role for root user account.

SWU8551.Description: The firmware update process of Active CMC was not successful, because of a firmware image checksum error.
SWU8551.Resolution: Reacquire the Image file from the source location, and then retry the operation.
SWU8551.Message: Unable to update the firmware of Active CMC. The checksum process was not successful.

VME0003.Description: Virtual Console session fails to start.
VME0003.Resolution: Retry the Virtual Console session initiation.
VME0003.Message: Virtual Console session fails to start.

VFL1017.Message: Media is present for Removable Flash Media %1.

UEFI0121.Description: The primary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.
UEFI0121.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Install a SD card media in the primary SD card slot. 2) Reseat or replace the SD card media. 3) If write-protected mode is expected, then no response action is required.
UEFI0121.Message: The primary SD card is missing, not responding, or in write-protected mode.

RAC1027.Description: A test event was generated and the alert was successfully sent to the destination.
RAC1027.Resolution: Verify if the alerts were received by the configured destination. Otherwise, reconfigure the destination and retry the operation.
RAC1027.Message: Successfully sent the alert for the specified event to the configured destination.

LIC905.Description: The LicenseName value is greater than the allowed max length of 64.
LIC905.Resolution: Correct the length of the LicenseName value and retry the operation.
LIC905.Message: The LicenseName value cannot exceed 64 characters.

PCI1321.Description: A high-severity issue is detected in the component identified in the message.
PCI1321.Resolution: Remove and reinsert the component identified in the message, and then monitor the log for a re-occurrence of the issue. If the issue persists, and occurs during server startup, update the component firmware. If the issue persists and occurs during OS runtime, restart the server and update the OS drivers for the component identified in the message.
PCI1321.Message: A high-severity issue is detected in a component of the bus %1, device 0, function %2.

PWR222.Description: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is already enabled.
PWR222.Message: The Extended Power Performance (EPP) feature is already enabled.

FCD8531.Description: The CMC is not responding. The chassis has the factory-programmed service tag.
FCD8531.Message: Unable to activate the %1. The chassis service tag is unavailable.

TMP0134.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or cool.
TMP0134.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0134.Message: The control panel temperature is outside of range.

RAC0113.Description: Data entered is not an integer value in the valid range of numbers.
RAC0113.Resolution: Enter a Remote Syslog Port number. Expected range: [1-65535 or 0x1-0xFFFF]
RAC0113.Message: Remote Syslog Port value is invalid: Valid range is 1-65535 or 0x1-0xFFFF.

BAR082.Description: Remote access controller firmware and configuration import in progress.

STOR010.Description: The operation cannot be completed because the RAID level entered is not supported by the controller.
STOR010.Resolution: Enter a valid RAID level and retry the operation.
STOR010.Message: RAID level not supported on controller.

PSU1005.Description: The enclosure detected that a power supply unit was switched on.

PSU0036.Description: This failure may be the result of an electrical issue with cables or subsystem components in the system.
PSU0036.Resolution: 1) Remove and re-install the power supply.2) Check cables and subsystem components in the system for damage. 3) If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
PSU0036.Message: An over current fault detected on power supply %1.

RAC024.Description: Unable to VLAN is Disabled so cannot set VLAN Priority because VLAN is Disabled.
RAC024.Resolution: Enable VLAN to set VLAN Priority.
RAC024.Message: Unable to VLAN is Disabled so cannot set VLAN Priority because VLAN is Disabled.

BAR076.Description: The collection and export of Lifecycle Controller Configuration Database failed.
BAR076.Resolution: Enter System Services in USC, and select Exit and Reboot to reset and update the database. If the error continues repair the Lifecycle Controller, apply the Dell Update Packages for USC, diagnostics, device firmware and driver pack and retry the operation.
BAR076.Message: Unable to collect the Configuration database.

SWC0086.Description: The Public IP access feature has been enabled in iDRAC by the Integrated Data Center solution. The iDRAC can now be managed via the Public IP interface.
SWC0086.Message: The Integrated Data Center Public IP mode is enabled.

NIC506.Description: The requested operation requires the DNS registration to be enabled.
NIC506.Message: The requested object requires DNS registration to be enabled.

BIOS009.Description: Lifecycle Controller cannot gain access to internal storage because of use by another application or operation.
BIOS009.Resolution: Wait for the current Lifecycle Controller operation to complete. Verify that the system is 1) Not currently in Lifecycle Controller Unified Server Configurator utility 2) Waiting for user intervention at F1/F2 POST error 3) Not in any of the device or controller Option ROMs and retry the operation.
BIOS009.Message: Lifecycle Controller is currently in use.

FSD000.Description: The customer has authorized the specified debug capabilities on this iDRAC. (This should occur in response to a request from Dell tech support.) Each debug capability represents a certain action Dell engineers can perform to debug iDRAC.
FSD000.Message: Debug authorized by customer; debugcaps: %1, was authorized by: %2, at %3 for the period: %4 to %5.

HWC2014.Resolution: Make sure the hardware is installed correctly. Refer to the product documentation for correct configuration and installation procedures.

SEL0010.Description: When the event log is full, additional events are not written to the log or older events will be overwritten and lost. (IPMI sensor type code 10h - offset 05h)
SEL0010.Resolution: Backup and clear log at the next maintained time.
SEL0010.Message: System event log (SEL) is almost full.

RAC043.Description: Some event filter settings were not updated due to problems encountered processing the input parameters.
RAC043.Resolution: Verify the input parameters provided and retry the operation. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
RAC043.Message: Unable to update some event filter settings.

SUP015.Description: One of the parameters specified received a NULL value that prevented the action from completing.
SUP015.Resolution: Correct the parameter value and retry the command.
SUP015.Message: Input parameters values should not be NULL.

RAC0159.Description: Certificate upload failed because there is no pending Certificate Signing Request (CSR) or private key.
RAC0159.Resolution: Upload failed due to no pending Certificate Signing Request (CSR). Try creating a new CSR and then upload the certificate.
RAC0159.Message: Certificate upload failed: No pending CSR or private key.

RAC966.Description: Any operation involving remote share (CIFS) cannot continue if user name, password, or both are not specified. The u and p options represent the user name and password for the remote share.
RAC966.Resolution: Make sure to specify both user name and password for the remote share, and retry the operation. To view the list of options that can used for the required subcommand, use the racadm help <subcommand> command.
RAC966.Message: Unable to continue with the operation because the user name or password is not specified.

TMP0129.Message: Disk drive bay temperature is within range.

PWR1007.Description: To avoid shutdown, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1007.Resolution: Review system configuration, upgrade power supplies or reduce system power consumption.
PWR1007.Message: The system performance degraded because power exceeds capacity.

TMP0202.Resolution: Check system operating environment, fans, and heatsinks.
TMP0202.Message: CPU %1 temperature is greater than the upper warning threshold.

RED076.Description: Unable to create the Automatic Update schedule because an input parameter is invalid..
RED076.Resolution: Verify the values for all the input parameters are correct and retry the operation.
RED076.Message: Unable to create an Automatic Update schedule, because an invalid parameter is entered.

RAC1169.Description: The RACADM "config" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.
RAC1169.Resolution: Run the RACADM "racadm set" command to configure the iDRAC configuration parameters. For more information on the set command, run the RACADM command "racadm help set".
RAC1169.Message: The RACADM "config" command will be deprecated in a future version of iDRAC firmware.

RAC1013.Description: For any iDRAC user, SNMPv3 authentication protocol can be changed to "None" only if the SNMPv3 privacy protocol state is set to "None".
RAC1013.Resolution: Change the SNMPv3 privacy protocol state to 'None' using "racadm set iDRAC.Users.<index>.SNMPv3PrivacyType none", and retry the operation.
RAC1013.Message: The SNMPv3 authentication protocol state cannot be set to None if the SNMPv3 privacy protocol state is set to None.

PWR8572.Description: The server identified in the message can be shutdown only if the server is turned on.
PWR8572.Message: Unable to shutdown the server %1 because the server is off.

RAC1159.Description: The data cannot be retrieved from iDRAC because Lifecycle Controller is disabled or a DUP update is in progress.
RAC1159.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Check if a DUP fw update is progress and wait until it is finished. 2) Make sure the Lifecycle Controller is Enabled. To enable Lifecycle Controller, run the command 'racadm set LifeCycleController.LCAttributes.LifecycleControllerState 1'. 3) Retry the operation.
RAC1159.Message: Unable to get the requested data from iDRAC.

UEFI0195.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Read Training phase.
UEFI0195.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0195.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RAC0251.Description: The vFlash partitions are attached. Therefore, the current operation cannot proceed.
RAC0251.Resolution: Detach the partitions and try again.
RAC0251.Message: One or more partitions are currently attached.

UEFI0257.Description: Cannot boot to Service Partition because the target Service Partition was not found in the boot list.
UEFI0257.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, do one of the following and retry the operation: 1) Update the system BIOS. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0257.Message: Unable to boot to Service Partition because the target Service Partition was not found in the boot list.

UEFI0123.Description: The secondary SD card has now become the primary SD card.
UEFI0123.Resolution: Check the screen display or the Lifecycle Log for prior messages. If the switch is expected, then no response action is required.
UEFI0123.Message: The secondary SD card has now become the primary SD card.

DKM1002.Message: Key management server certificate problem detected.

SYS194.Description: The Collection of System Inventory successfully completed by Lifecycle Controller firmware.
SYS194.Message: The Collection of System Inventory successfully completed.

RAC984.Description: iDRAC is unable to extract the custom signing certificate and the private key from the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file.
RAC984.Resolution: Check if the specified file and passphrase are valid, and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC984.Message: Unable to upload the Public Key Cryptography Standards version 12 (PKCS12) file.

UEFI0243.Description: The Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) channel identified in the message is operating at a degraded width. This allows continued uptime although indicates an error condition requiring further investigation. This maybe an early indication of upcoming memory riser failure.
UEFI0243.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0243.Message: Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) operating at reduced width on memory riser %1.

ISM0006.Description: The iDRAC Service Module could not successfully communicate with iDRAC, because the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel is not configured in the USB-NIC mode.
ISM0006.Resolution: Make sure that the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel is configured only in the USB-NIC mode, and then retry the operation. To enable the OS-to-iDRAC Pass-through channel, run the following command in the order they are listed: 1) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.PTMode usb-p2p 2) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.UsbNicIpAddress <ip address> 3) racadm set idrac.os-bmc.adminstate enabled
ISM0006.Message: The iDRAC Service Module is unable to communicate with iDRAC using the OS to iDRAC Pass-through channel.

PDR108.Description: The physical disk identified in the message that had been assigned as a hot spare has been unassigned and is no longer functioning as a hot spare. The physical disk was unassigned by a user or automatically by the storage management software. When one of the disks in a virtual disk fails, data is rebuilt onto the hot spare, The hot spare becomes a member of the virtual disk and is no longer assigned as a hot spare. In this situation, assigning a new hot spare to maintain data protection in recommended.
PDR108.Resolution: No response action is required. Assigning a new global hot spare is recommended.
PDR108.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is unassigned as a global hot spare.

CTL48.Description: The controller has physical disks that were moved from another controller or have been removed and replaced on the current configuration. These physical disks contain virtual disks that were created on the current or other controller. See the storage hardware documentation for Import Foreign Configuration and Clear Foreign Configuration for more information. Foreign configuration is seen when a controller is replaced.
CTL48.Resolution: Import or clear the detected foreign configuration using a configuration tool or utility.
CTL48.Message: A foreign configuration was detected on %1.

PCI1304.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, if device is removable, re-install the device.
PCI1304.Message: An I/O channel check error was detected.

STOR0510.Description: Unable to apply the RAID controller encryption because RAID controller is not responding.
STOR0510.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, reboot the system or update the RAID controller firmware to the latest version and retry the operation.

RAC1140.Description: The file name cannot be specified when the Technical Support Report (TSR) is exported to a remote share.
RAC1140.Resolution: Run the command without using the -f option. For more information on exporting Technical Support Report (TSR), run the command 'racadm help techsupreport export'.
RAC1140.Message: File name is not required to export the Technical Support Report (TSR) to a remote share.

RDU8519.Description: The communication between the primary and standby CMCs was lost. This may occur when the CMC identified in the message is restarting, or a firmware update operation is in progress. If the issue persists, a failover will occur.
RDU8519.Resolution: Wait for 10 minutes for: 1)Firmware update operations to complete and 2) The CMC to finish restarting. If the communication is not reestablished, remove and reinsert the CMC.
RDU8519.Message: Unable to communicate with peer CMC %1.

PWR209.Description: The redundancy policy cannot be changed to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.
PWR209.Resolution: Disable Extended Power Performance and retry the operation.
PWR209.Message: Unable to change the redundancy policy to either Power Supply Redundancy or No Redundancy because the Extended Power Performance is enabled.

SYS077.Description: Unable to perform the preview operation because the specified system configuration XML file does not exist on the remote share.
SYS077.Resolution: Make sure the configuration XML file to be previewed exists on the remote share before retrying the operation.
SYS077.Message: Unable to perform the preview operation because the specified file does not exist on the remote share.

SWU002.Description: The expander or storage enclosure processor firmware update did not complete successfully.
SWU002.Resolution: Check the Storage Enclosure Backplane type and the Firmware version and make sure they are appropriately matched, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual
SWU002.Message: The backplane firmware update did not complete successfully.

SWC0303.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0303.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0303.Message: The -r option is not valid with any other option.

RAC0243.Description: There was a conflict with a concurrent session. Another user may have logged inusing a separate browser or RACADM.
RAC0243.Resolution: There was a conflict with a concurrent session. Refresh the page to see the currently available options.
RAC0243.Message: Partition failed: A partitioning conflict has occurred with another session.

PST0196.Description: System BIOS detected an invalid memory population. Reinstall the memory to match the supported population. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video. (BIOS POST Exception code C4)
PST0196.Resolution: Re-install memory to match supported memory configuration.

SWC0041.Description: The specified source file location is incorrect.
SWC0041.Resolution: Make sure that the specified source file location is correct and retry the operation.
SWC0041.Message: Unable to copy the backup Server Configuration Profile.

SWU8504.Description: The specified Lifecycle Controller operation is successfully submitted and the operation will be executed on the basis of scheduling criteria.
SWU8504.Message: Successfully scheduled the %1 operation on the server %2.

TMP0109.Description: Ambient air temperature is too warm or one or more fans may have failed.
TMP0109.Resolution: Check system operating environment and review event log for fan failures.
TMP0109.Message: The memory module %1 temperature is greater than the upper critical threshold.

PSU0803.Description: Insufficient power in chassis to power on server.
PSU0803.Resolution: Utilize the Chassis Management Controller web interface to check available power and server power requirements. If sufficient power is available, retry the operation.
PSU0803.Message: Insufficient power in chassis to power on server.

IOV007.Description: For each adapter assigned to a server, power is allocated when the server is turned on. If the available power is less than the required power, the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) will not power on the adapters associated with the server.
IOV007.Resolution: To release the required power, turn off one or more servers by pressing the Power Button on the individual server units.
IOV007.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to allocate power to one or more PCIe adapters in the Chassis Infrastructure component.

CTL19.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL19.Message: Abort CC on Error, Copyback, and Load Balance has changed for %1.

STOR037.Description: Unable to complete the requested operation because one or more input parameters identified in the message are not specified.
STOR037.Resolution: Enter all the required parameters and retry the operation.

RAC0604.Description: The system inventory may not be up-to-date because the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled. The CSIOR feature retrieves detailed system inventory information during system startup and stores this information on iDRAC.
RAC0604.Resolution: Enable CSIOR, restart the system and retry the operation. To enable CSIOR, press F2 (System Setup) during system startup, navigate to iDRAC Settings >Lifecycle Controller, and select the Enabled option for Collect System Inventory on Restart.
RAC0604.Message: System inventory may not be up-to-date because Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) is disabled.

PDR107.Description: The physical disk drive identified in the message is assigned as a global hot-spare.
PDR107.Message: The physical disk drive %1 is assigned as a global hot-spare.
