PST0142.Description: BIOS Memory testing failed. Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce system configuration to minimum memory configuration. This exception occurred early in system power on, thus the system may not display video.
PST0142.Resolution: Compare system memory installation to supported system memory configurations. Reduce system configuration to minimum memory configuration.

UEFI0149.Description: The PERC storage adapter identified in this message is not supported by the installed storage backplane.
UEFI0149.Resolution: Install a compatible storage adapter.For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0149.Message: The PERC storage adapter in %1 is not supported by the installed storage backplane.

RAC1176.Description: The Certificate Signing Request (CSR) message cannot be generated because all the attributes in the iDRAC.Security group are not configured.
RAC1176.Resolution: Make sure that all the attributes in the iDRAC.Security group are configured. To get the list of attributes, run the following command "racadm get iDRAC.Security".
RAC1176.Message: Unable to generate the Certificate Signing Request (CSR) message because all the attributes in the iDRAC.Security group are not configured.

IOV107.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) has detected the removal of a PCIe adapter card while it was powered on.
IOV107.Resolution: Power down the affected server(s) and then power on the server(s). Note: OS reboot only will not correct this issue.
IOV107.Message: PCIe adapter %1 in slot %2 was removed while powered on.

UEFI0046.Description: An issue in observed in the previous invocation of TXT SINIT Authenticated Code Module (ACM) because the TXT information stored in the TPM chip may be corrupted.
UEFI0046.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Update the BIOS firmware. 2) Go to System Setup > System Security page, click the "Clear" option under TPM command. Restart the system, go to System Setup > System Security page, click the "Activate" option under TPM command, and then enable TXT.
UEFI0046.Message: An issue is observed in the previous invocation of TXT SINIT Authenticated Code Module (ACM) because the TXT information stored in the TPM chip may be corrupted.

RAC0630.Description: The job cannot be scheduled, because the requested network file share type is not supported.
RAC0630.Resolution: Enter a correct network file share type, and then retry the operation.
RAC0630.Message: Unable to schedule, because an invalid network file share type is entered.

SWC0304.Description: The syntax of the fwupdate command is invalid.
SWC0304.Resolution: Refer the help text for fwupdate subcommand.
SWC0304.Message: The -g option requires -u to also be specified.

MEM8001.Message: Persistent correctable memory error logging enabled for a memory device at location %1.

RAC0138.Description: The retrieved certificate came back as a null or empty document.
RAC0138.Message: A valid certificate is not loaded.

SWC0034.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to export the file to the network share because it has insufficient free space.
SWC0034.Resolution: Make sure that the network share has sufficient free space then retry the operation. If the problem persists, check network settings and retry the operation.
SWC0034.Message: Unable to export the file to the network share.

RED051.Description: The update package file download was not successful. This could be due to the following: 1) The update package file is missing, 2) The host address, share, user name, and password information are correct but the file name was invalid, 3) The network file share could not be mounted, or 4) The network file share disconnected before the transfer was complete.
RED051.Resolution: Check the network connection and access to the update package from the iDRAC.
RED051.Message: The network file transfer of an update package was not successful.

SYS181.Description: The collect OS and Application Data operation cannot be completed because the OS Collector is not installed on the iDRAC.
SYS181.Resolution: Install OS Collector on the iDRAC and retry the operation. To install the OS Collector using the iDRAC Web UI, get the latest OC Collector update package and then select the Update and Rollback link from the iDRAC Web UI home page and upload the install package.
SYS181.Message: Unable to collect OS and Application Data because the OS Collector is not installed on the iDRAC.

HWC4015.Description: CMC has old firmware and does not recognize the new device which has requested link tuning information. After updating the firmware the CMC will recognize the device.
HWC4015.Resolution: Update the CMC firmware. If the problem persists, contact support.

TMP0300.Description: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is enabled.
TMP0300.Message: The Enhanced Cooling Mode feature is enabled.

UEFI0107.Description: One or more memory errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message. The error occurred during Read DQ/DQS initialization.
UEFI0107.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the issues persist, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0107.Message: One or more memory errors have occurred on memory slot: %1.

DIS106.Description: The AutoConfig import file operation could not be successfully completed, because the shutdown type (-d) specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC is incorrect.
DIS106.Resolution: Enter a valid shutdown type in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC using (-d <0 or 1>) where 0 = Graceful shutdown and 1 = Forced shutdown.
DIS106.Message: Unable to start the AutoConfig file import operation, because an invalid shutdown type was specified in the DHCP scope option field where the VendorID=iDRAC.

UEFI0004.Description: A CPU invalid opcode exception (type 0x06) occurred in the pre-boot UEFI environment. The software attempted to execute invalid code.
UEFI0004.Resolution: Recently installed hardware or updated software may cause this exception. Update or remove the hardware or software.

PWR1005.Description: To avoid exceeding the user defined capacity, system performance has been degraded.
PWR1005.Resolution: If unintended, review system configuration changes and power policy.
PWR1005.Message: The system performance degraded because of user-defined power capacity has changed.

UEFI0136.Description: The CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) operation cannot be executed because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible. This issue is caused by missing LC partitions.
UEFI0136.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Restart the system and retry the operation. 2) Update the iDRAC firmware. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
UEFI0136.Message: Unable to execute CSIOR (Collect System Inventory on Restart) because the Lifecycle Controller (LC) firmware was not accessible.

PR28.Description: The device that the job was intended for is no longer detected. This could be due to the device being removed, disabled, or a failure.
PR28.Resolution: If the device was removed, reinsert the device and retry the operation. If the device was disabled, re-enable the device and retry the operation.
PR28.Message: Unable to locate device in current configuration.

MEM7000.Message: The memory riser mismatch was corrected.

SWC0249.Description: The specified parameter needs to be given with its legal value.
SWC0249.Resolution: Enter the proper index preceded by -i.
SWC0249.Message: Invalid syntax. The requested subcommand requires -i %1 to be specified.

BAR096.Description: The current BIOS firmware installed on the system does not have Backup and Restore feature support.
BAR096.Resolution: Obtain the System BIOS firmware with Backup and Restore support, update the system and try the operation again.

PCI3008.Resolution: Cycle input power, update component drivers, remove and re-install the device at the next service window.
PCI3008.Message: A non-fatal PCIe error detected on a component at bus %1 device %2 function %3.

VLT0224.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0224.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the memory module.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0224.Message: The memory module %1 voltage is less than the lower warning threshold.

FAN911.Description: The attempt to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode (ECM) was not successful because ECM is already enabled or Gen3 fans are not present in the Chassis.
FAN911.Resolution: Check whether or not the Enhanced Cooling Mode (ECM) is already enabled. Make sure there are Gen3 fans in the Chassis and retry the operation.
FAN911.Message: The attempt to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode was not successful.

PDR30.Description: The controller cannot to communicate with a disk that is assigned as a global hot spare. The disk either failed or was removed. There may also be a bad or loose cable.
PDR30.Resolution: Verify that the disk is healthy and installed. Check the cables. Refer to the product documentation and see the Cables Attached Correctly section for more information on checking the cables. If necessary, replace the disk and reassign the global hot spare.

RAC0283.Description: This is the time span (in seconds) within which IP Blocking Fail Count failures must occur to trigger the IP Blocking Penalty Time. The default value is 3600 seconds (1 hour).
RAC0283.Resolution: Enter a valid IP Blocking Fail Window. Expected range: 10-65535.
RAC0283.Message: IP Blocking Fail Window is invalid. Expected range: 10-65535.

RAC0678.Description: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on the PCIe SSD disk drives.
RAC0678.Resolution: Make sure PCIe SSD disk drives are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane and retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC0678.Message: Unable to perform Prepare to Remove or Secure Erase operations on PCIe SSD disk drives.

CTL23.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL23.Message: Copyback and Auto Copyback on Predictive Failure has changed for %1.

CPU0011.Resolution: Review System Event Log and Operating System Logs. If the issue persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
CPU0011.Message: Uncorrectable Machine Check Exception detected on CPU %1.

RAC1115.Description: The command could not be successfully run, because of insufficient privileges for the username supplied.
RAC1115.Resolution: Make sure that you have appropriate privileges, and then retry the operation.
RAC1115.Message: Unable to run the command, because of insufficient user privileges.

PWR8579.Description: A request to reset the CMC identified in the message is initiated. If a second CMC is present, a failover to the other CMC will occur as a result.
PWR8579.Message: Request to reset the CMC %1 is initiated.

LIC903.Description: One or more parameters were not specified for the invoked method.
LIC903.Resolution: To provide the correct parameters, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.

PCI5008.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) could not successfully connect to the PCIe switch board.
PCI5008.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Perform an AC Power Cycle operation on the Chassis by disconnecting the chassis from AC power, waiting for 30 seconds, and then reconnecting AC power. 2) Power on at least one server. Using the Chassis Management Controller (CMC) web interface, select Server Overview->Power->Control and then click the Operation field and select the Power On Server operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PCI5008.Message: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to communicate with the PCIe switch board.

SWC8539.Description: The Public Key (PK) SSH Authentication key file delete operation is successfully completed for the slot identified in the message.
SWC8539.Message: The key delete operation successfully completed for slot %1 of service account.

RAC1012.Description: Unable to change the auto-negotiation state for the current NIC selection mode, because the iDRAC NIC is in dedicated mode.
RAC1012.Resolution: Change the iDRAC NIC mode to shared mode using "racadm set idrac.nic.selection <value>", and retry the operation.
RAC1012.Message: Unable to change the auto-negotiation state for the current NIC selection mode.

PDR1105.Message: Drive %1 is in the critical array.

OSD28.Description: Hash verification on the ISO image has failed. The hash value specified in the command is either incorrect or the ISO image has been changed.
OSD28.Resolution: 1) Verify that the hash value specified in the command is correct. 2) Make sure that the ISO has not been changed 3) Replace the ISO image on the share and rerun the command.
OSD28.Message: Hash verification on the ISO image failed.

FC016.Description: A set attribute operation was not successful because the attribute is disabled.
FC016.Message: Unable to change the attribute value of the disabled attribute %1.

JCP019.Description: A new job cannot be created until the existing Import Server Profile job is complete or deleted. Only one Import Server Profile job can be running at any given time.
JCP019.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1) Retry the operation after the Import Server Profile job is complete. 2) Delete the scheduled Import Server Profile job and retry the operation.
JCP019.Message: Cannot create new jobs until the existing Import System Profile job is completed or cancelled.

FC010.Description: For 11G systems: System Services must be enabled to perform the requested operation. System Services has been disabled through the iDRAC configuration utility accessed by pressing CTRL+E on boot up or through a remote operation. For 12G systems: Lifecycle Controller must be enabled to perform the requested operation. Lifecycle Controller has been disabled by pressing F2 Setup, selecting iDRAC Configuration, and selecting Lifecycle Controller Settings on boot up or through a remote operation.
FC010.Resolution: For 11G systems: Use the iDRAC configuration utility to enable the System Services by pressing the CTRL+E option on boot up at the targeted system. For 12G systems: Use F2 Setup, select iDRAC Configuration, and select Lifecycle Controller Settings, to enable the Lifecycle Controller on boot up of the targeted system.
FC010.Message: Unable to create Configuration job because Lifecycle Controller is not enabled.

RAC0677.Description: No physical disk drives in ready state, virtual disks, or PCIe SSD drives are available to perform operations on.
RAC0677.Resolution: Do one of the following: 1. If there are no disk drives available in ready state, insert additional disk drives and make sure the drives are in ready state. 2. If no virtual disks are present, click <create virtualdisk link> and create at least one virtual disk. 3. If PCIe SSD drives are inserted into the enclosure or attached to the backplane.
RAC0677.Message: No physical disk drives in ready state, no virtual disks are created, and no PCIe SSD drives are available to perform operations on.

UEFI0062.Description: One or more attributes were successfully changed.
UEFI0062.Message: One or more attributes are successfully changed.

LOG503.Description: The command cannot be run because the value of the parameter identified in the message is not valid.
LOG503.Resolution: Enter all the parameters required in the command as per the enumeration, and then retry the operation. For more information, see the Chassis Record Log Profile.
LOG503.Message: Unable to run the method because the parameter %1 is not valid.

PCI2003.Message: The component at slot %1 recovered from a fatal IO error.

CTL61.Description: The controller has detected a change in the storage configuration between since its last shut down. This can generally happen if some configured physical disks are removed from the system when the system was shutdown.
CTL61.Resolution: Shut down the system. Re-insert the removed physical disks and re-start the system.
CTL61.Message: Physical disks found missing from configuration during boot time on %1.

CTL80.Description: The controller identified in the message has an issue as displayed in the message.
CTL80.Resolution: To resolve this issue, see Troubleshooting section in the Dell Shared PowerEdge RAID Controller (SPERC8) documentation.
CTL80.Message: %1 experienced the following warning during startup: %2.

SEL1209.Description: System policies or permissions may prevent the action from executing. If configured, the system will not execute the action on a platform event (power down, cycle, interrupt, send alert).
SEL1209.Message: The platform event filter action failed.

RFL2009.Description: The Internal Dual SD Card redundancy feature was enabled. The SD card identified in the message is enabled.
RFL2009.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is enabled.

RDU0032.Description: The system has multiple redundant voltage lines. One or more of these voltage lines is no longer available.
RDU0032.Resolution: 1) Turn system off and remove input power for one minute. Re-apply input power and turn system on. 2) If the issue still persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.

SYS188.Description: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file has a file size of zero, which is not valid.
SYS188.Resolution: Make sure the import configuration file is valid before retrying the operation.
SYS188.Message: Unable to perform the import operation because the specified file has a file size of zero, which is not valid.

USR0184.Description: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature has been disconnected and the feature is not available.
USR0184.Resolution: Connect a bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature. Press the activate button to enable the Quick Sync feature.
USR0184.Message: A bezel with the iDRAC Quick Sync feature has been disconnected and the feature is not available.

BOOT018.Description: The Boot Control List specified in the operation is read-only and cannot be modified.
BOOT018.Resolution: Refer to the documentation on validity of operation for the Boot Control List specified. For more information on the operation, see Lifecycle Controller-Remote Services documentation.
BOOT018.Message: Specified Boot Control List is read-only

FAN1000.Description: The enclosure detected that a fan was removed and the enclosure is no longer functioning in optimal condition..
FAN1000.Resolution: Re-insert the fan into the enclosure. Contact technical support if the issue persists.

LOG006.Description: This message is generated while performing a Test Event action. Performing a Test Event action logs an event in the Lifecycle Log with the user specified message ID. It may also generate events through SNMP, email, or other event notification sources if they are enabled. The test event does not indicate that there is a hardware or software problem. It provides a mechanism for users to test their event processing applications.
LOG006.Message: Test event generated for message ID %1.

SWC8601.Description: The source profile is not correct in form or content.
SWC8601.Resolution: Recreate source profile or choose a different one.
SWC8601.Message: Quick Deploy Profile unable to apply profile %1 to server %2

PR5.Description: Some or all configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to the current device. This may be due to firmware version or other differences in the part.
PR5.Resolution: Check the device's configuration and ensure that the new configuration is correct for the system.
PR5.Message: The configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to device: %1

CTL40.Description: An error involving multiple bits has been encountered during a read or write operation. The error correction algorithm recalculates parity data during read and write operations. If an error involves only a single bit, it may be possible for the error correction algorithm to correct the error and maintain parity data. An error involving multiple bits, however, generally indicates data loss. In some cases, if the multi-bit error occurs during a read operation, then the data on the disk may be ok. If the multi-bit error occurs during a write operation, then data loss has occurred.
CTL40.Resolution: Replace the Dual In-line Memory Module (DIMM). The DIMM is a part of the controller battery pack. Refer to the storage hardware documentation for information on replacing the DIMM. You may need to restore data from backup.

RED038.Description: An Automatic Server Profile Export or Automatic Update task identified in the message has been added.
RED038.Message: A recurring task of type %1 is added.

UEFI0020.Description: The Lifecycle Controller feature is enabled.
UEFI0020.Message: The Lifecycle Controller feature is enabled.

RAC0654.Description: Unable to perform operations on the iDRAC Service Module (iSM) because the iSM is not installed on the server operating system. All fields in the iDRAC GUI iSM page are disabled.
RAC0654.Resolution: Make sure that the iDRAC Service Module is installed on the server operating system, and then retry the operation.
RAC0654.Message: No operations can be performed on the iDRAC Service Module.

RAC1182.Description: The server instrumentation can not provide any information related to power because PMBus capability is not present or the PSU(s) with PMBus capability have been removed.
RAC1182.Message: Unable to retrieve information for the Power group or attribute because the server is not PMBus capable.

SEL1300.Description: System setup displays the system boot order. The local video screen may also show additional information. (IPMI sensor type code 1eh - offset 00h)
SEL1300.Resolution: Check system boot settings. Check mass storage controller configuration settings is applicable.

MEM8502.Description: An ECC memory condition was detected on the primary CMC and a failover was initiated.
MEM8502.Resolution: Reseat the primary CMC and initiate a failover back to the primary CMC. If the problem persists and multiple failovers occur, contact your service provider..
MEM8502.Message: ECC Memory error rate failover condition detected.

PWR8655.Description: CMC could not successfully turn on the component identified in the message, because of insufficient power available.
PWR8655.Resolution: Make sure there is sufficient power available, and then retry the operation. To view the available power, on the CMC Web interface, click Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. The available power is displayed in the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field. To increase available power, add more PSUs or remove unused components from the Chassis.
PWR8655.Message: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to turn on the component %1-%2 because of insufficient power. The minimum required power is %3 AC Watts, but only %4 AC Watts is available.

SYS172.Description: A Remote Diagnostic operation has been interrupted because the server was restarted during the operation.
SYS172.Resolution: Make sure that there are no diagnostic operations in progress before restarting the server or wait for the Remote Diagnostic operation to complete.
SYS172.Message: A Remote Diagnostic operation has been interrupted.

OSD63.Description: The DetachDrivers invoke method cannot be run because the driver files are not attached.
OSD63.Message: Unable to run the DetachDrivers invoke method because the driver files are not attached.

PSU8512.Description: The firmware update operation for the PSU identified in the message did not complete, because of internal communication errors.
PSU8512.Resolution: Retry the firmware update operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PSU8512.Message: Unable to update the firmware for the PSU in slot %1. Error=0x%2 (%3)

RED018.Description: Reinstall or Rollback not supported for this device.
RED018.Resolution: 1. Update the device directly using the update methods since rollback is not supported for this device. 2. Verify that the target specified in the command is correct.
RED018.Message: Reinstall or Rollback not supported for this device.

RAC061.Description: The IPMI Watchdog can not be enabled at the same time as the OS Watchdog.
RAC061.Resolution: Disable the OS Watchdog before enabling IPMI Watchdog.
RAC061.Message: Unable to set the IPMI Watchdog because the OS Watchdog is already enabled..

LOG005.Description: The operation did not complete successfully because of an unknown error in iDRAC.
LOG005.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the issue persists, reset the iDRAC.
LOG005.Message: Cannot perform the operation due to an unknown error in iDRAC.

BAR075.Description: The collection and export of system information failed.
BAR075.Resolution: Restart the remote access controller, and retry the operation. If the error continues, use the remote access controller firmware to try the operation again.

VF014.Description: Enabling vFlash was not successful because the vFlash feature is not disabled.
VF014.Resolution: The vFlash is enabled and any attempt to enable it will not be successful.

VF003.Description: The required input parameter identified in the message is missing.
VF003.Resolution: Refer the iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller User Guides for the required input parameters for this method.

VFL1006.Description: At boot, the Card Identification (CID) signature of the card is different from the Non-volatile (NV) storage value or the card is the destination of a copy operation that is in-progress.
VFL1006.Resolution: If unintended, reinstall the flash media.

UEFI0194.Description: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect initialization during the Fine Command Training phase.
UEFI0194.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the memory riser and 3) Restart the system. For more information, see the platform Owner's Manual.
UEFI0194.Message: An error occurred during Scalable Memory Interconnect (SMI) initialization on memory riser %1.

RAC0136.Description: A separate message will provide more detail about this error which was detected while attaching the vFlash partition.
RAC0136.Message: An error has occurred while attaching a partition.

SWC0309.Description: The platform does not support the specified functionality of fwupdate.
SWC0309.Message: The -p option is not supported with the interface being used.

VF005.Description: A partition with no image was created.

UEFI0081.Description: Memory size has changed from the last time the system was started. No action is required if memory was added or removed.
UEFI0081.Resolution: If the change is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise, check the DIMM population inside the system and memory settings in System Setup for configuration changes. For more information, see the platform Owners Manual.
UEFI0081.Message: Memory size has changed from the last time the system was started.

RED040.Description: The job identified in the message was created by an Automatic Server Profile Backup, Automatic Update, or other recurring operation.
RED040.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 created a job %2.

SWC0264.Description: The resources required for the execution are in use by another process
SWC0264.Resolution: Wait for the process to release the resources and try again.
SWC0264.Message: Resource currently in use by another process. Please retry again later.

CTL64.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.
CTL64.Message: Attempted to import Unsupported Virtual Disk type RAID%1 on %2.

RAC971.Description: The import or export operation cannot continue if the value specified for the file type is incorrect. The correct value for the file type is "xml" or "ini".
RAC971.Resolution: Make sure to specify either "xml" or "ini" for the file type (-t) option. If no file type is specified, "ini" is used as default.

PSU0802.Description: The power supply redundancy policy on the system has been set.
PSU0802.Message: The power supply redundancy policy on the system has been set.

JCP003.Description: The Job did not complete successfully.
JCP003.Resolution: Retry the operation, and if necessary, make sure that valid parameters are provided for the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
JCP003.Message: The Job did not complete successfully.

RAC0610.Description: Different values were entered for passpharse and confirm passpharse field.
RAC0610.Resolution: Values entered in passphrase and confirm passphrase fields must be the same.
RAC0610.Message: The passphrase and confirm passphrase values entered do not match.

SEC0607.Message: The network boot password violation was corrected.

RAC0286.Description: When creating a user account, the New Password and Confirm New Password fields cannot be empty.
RAC0286.Resolution: Enter valid passwords for New Password and Confirm New Password.
RAC0286.Message: New Password and Confirm New Password fields cannot be empty.

BAT1025.Description: The controller was unable to recover data from the cache. This may indicate data loss has occurred.
BAT1025.Resolution: Verify that the battery is charged and in good health. See the hardware documentation for more information. When the battery charge is unacceptably low, the battery cannot maintain cached data. Data loss may also have occurred, restoring data from backups may be needed. Verify whether the battery has met its recharge limit. The battery may need to be recharged. Contact technical support if the issue persists.
BAT1025.Message: %1 is unable to recover cached data from the Battery Backup Unit (BBU).

VDR57.Description: A disk media error was detected while the controller was completing a background task. A bad disk block was identified. The disk block has been remapped.
VDR57.Resolution: Consider replacing the disk. If you receive this alert frequently, ensure to replace the disk. It is recommended to routinely back up your data.
VDR57.Message: Background Initialization in %1 corrected medium error.

BAR035.Description: The Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) Configuration import did not complete successfully.
BAR035.Resolution: Manually reset the Integrated Remote Access Controller (iDRAC) configuration.
BAR035.Message: Unable to Restore Integrated Remote Access Controller configuration.

RAC0297.Description: The Domain Controller Address be specified for Active Directory configuration.
RAC0297.Resolution: Enter a valid Domain Controller Address.
RAC0297.Message: Specify a Domain Controller Address must be configured.

SEL1501.Description: An action or failure has taken place that breaks CMC redundancy. This includes loss of network connection, hardware failures, firmware update, firmware mismatch between CMC's, CMC reset, and unplugging a CMC.
SEL1501.Resolution: Check CMC network cables and network connections. Check that CMC firmware versions match.
SEL1501.Message: Chassis management controller (CMC) redundancy is lost.

PCI3011.Message: The component at bus %1 device %2 function %3 recovered from a non-fatal IO error.

RED043.Description: The operation identified in the message is currently disabled.
RED043.Resolution: Enable the operation identified in the message and retry the operation. To enable the Automatic Server Profile Backup operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoBackup 1". To enable the Automatic Update operation, run the following racadm command: "racadm set lifecycleController.lcattributes.AutoUpdate 1".
RED043.Message: A recurring operation of type %1 was not created because the operation type is disabled.

LOG203.Description: This message is generated while archiving Lifecycle Log. All the older messages are archived and can be retrieved using the export Lifecycle Log feature.
LOG203.Message: Lifecycle Log archived up to Log Sequence number %1.

SWC8528.Description: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to update the IDRAC "root" user password. This can happen if the communication to the iDRAC from CMC is non-functional or if the password entered is not valid.
SWC8528.Resolution: Make sure the password is valid. If communications with the iDRAC is not functioning, reset the iDRAC and retry the operation after a few minutes. Run the RACADM command "racadm ping server-<slot number> " to check the communications. If the communications are not functional, restart the iDRAC by performing a Virtual Reseat of the server using the RACADM command "racadm racreset -m server-<slot id>".
SWC8528.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to update the iDRAC root password.

SYS088.Description: Applying the changes defined in the configuration XML file will take approximately the estimated time identified in the message.
SYS088.Message: Estimated time for applying configuration changes is %1 seconds.

SWC8515.Description: Successfully modified privileges of User identified in the message.

OSD23.Description: Cannot continue with DetachISOImage because another command is in the process of exposing the ISO image and booting to it.
OSD23.Resolution: See the ConcreteJob status to make sure that the current running process is complete and then run DetachISOImage.
OSD23.Message: Unable to continue with DetachISOImage - another command is in the process of exposing the ISO Image and booting to it.

BAR045.Description: The host system is powering down to facilitate the import of the Integrated Remote Access Controller system profile.
BAR045.Message: Powering down the Host System for Integrated Remote Access Controller Restore.

SWC0231.Description: The partition image type specified is not available on local racadm.
SWC0231.Message: Partition of type \"image\" not supported on local racadm.

RAC1192.Description: The Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is currently disabled. If the system inventory is not up-to-date, the system configuration profile that is being copied will not have the latest inventory information.
RAC1192.Resolution: To get latest inventory information, cancel the current job, run "racadm set LifecycleController.LCAttributes.CollectSystemInventoryOnRestart 1" to enable CSIOR, and re-initiate the operation.
RAC1192.Message: The Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature is disabled.

SYS8500.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) sent messages to delay power throttling to all capable servers in the chassis. This was done because the CMC firmware was updated or a failover was initiated. If specific server errors are shown in the message, verify that the iDRAC and Lifecycle Controller firmware versions on those servers is updated to the most current version available.
SYS8500.Resolution: If no errors are shown, no response is required. If errors are listed in the message, navigate to the named servers and make sure that IDRAC and Lifecycle Controller firmware versions are the latest available.

RAC0624.Description: The requested operation could not be completed, because an incorrect job type or job ID is entered.
RAC0624.Resolution: Enter the correct job type or ID, and then retry the operation.
RAC0624.Message: Unable to find the requested job type or ID.

PWR8594.Description: The available power is not sufficient to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode feature.
PWR8594.Resolution: Make sure there is enough power supply to enable the Enhanced Cooling Mode feature. Go to, the Chassis Overview > Power > Power Budget Status. In the Total Input Power Available For Allocation field view the available power. To add more power, insert more PSUs or remove unused components from the chassis.
PWR8594.Message: Chassis Management Controller is unable to set the Enhanced Cooling Mode because the requested power %1 AC Watt is more than available power %2 AC Watt.

PDR101.Description: This alert message occurs if there are arrays not protected with a global hot spare.
PDR101.Message: Global Hot Spare %1 does not cover all arrays.

CTL17.Description: This alert is provided for informational purposes.

ISM0013.Description: The feature identified in the message is enabled by using the one of the iDRAC interfaces.

SWC8615.Description: A profile was successfully generated from a server.

RAC0115.Description: The IPv4 address does not conform to the addressing standard or the supported IPv4 address range.
RAC0115.Resolution: Enter the Destination IP Address value between [1.0.0.0 - 223.255.255.255 excluding: 127 (first octet), 0 or 255 (last octet)].
RAC0115.Message: The Destination IP Address value is invalid.

RAC0621.Description: The message appears in Job Queue page when the iDRAC firmware update job status is completed. Communication to the iDRAC will be lost .
RAC0621.Resolution: The iDRAC will be ready for login once the restart is complete.
RAC0621.Message: Successfully completed the iDRAC firmware update. All current user sessions will be closed.

UEFI0130.Description: The system time and data are invalid.
UEFI0130.Resolution: Go to the System Setup to set the current time and date.
UEFI0130.Message: The system time and date are invalid.

SWC0229.Description: Insufficient arguments passed to the command.
SWC0229.Resolution: Refer the help text for vflashpartition command.
SWC0229.Message: Some Necessary tag(s) are missing: -i -o -e -t -f & -s must be specified for create partition.

RAC0261.Description: This error message is displayed to indicate that the IPv6 gateway address does not conform to the required format.
RAC0261.Resolution: Enter a valid IPv6 gateway address.

UEFI0152.Description: This is a test BIOS and must not be used in production environment.
UEFI0152.Resolution: Do not use this BIOS in production.
UEFI0152.Message: This BIOS is for testing purpose only.

CBL0007.Description: The backplane cables identified in the message need to be connected to the correct backplane bays.
CBL0007.Resolution: Make sure the cables identified in the message are cabled correctly. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CBL0007.Message: Backplane %1 %2 cable and backplane %1 %2 cable are swapped.

CMC8521.Description: The Mezz card 1 FRU for the server specified in the message is not functioning or CMC is unable to read it.
CMC8521.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Reset iDRAC of the specified server or virtual reseat the server. 2) Reset CMC and wait for a few minutes. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
CMC8521.Message: The Mezz card 1 FRU for the server %1 is not functioning.

VLT0232.Description: System hardware detected an over voltage or under voltage condition.If multiple voltage exceptions occur consecutively the system may power down in failsafe mode.
VLT0232.Resolution: 1) Review system logs for power supply exceptions.2) Reseat the mezzanine card.3) If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to the product documentation to choose a convenient contact method.
VLT0232.Message: The mezzanine card %1 %2 voltage is greater than the upper warning threshold.

RAC0665.Description: RAID Controller Log data is being collected. This operation will take less than the number of minutes identified in the message.
RAC0665.Resolution: Do not log off from the application until the log data collection process is completed.
RAC0665.Message: RAID Controller Log data is being collected. This operation will take less than %1 minutes.

SWU8537.Description: The LKVM firmware update operation was not successful, because the IP address of the active CMC that is provided to the LKVM is invalid.
SWU8537.Resolution: Make sure the CMC IP address entered is valid, and then retry the Update operation.
SWU8537.Message: Unable to update the LKVM firmware, because the IP address provided is invalid. ErrorCode=0x%1.

STOR028.Description: The requested operation cannot be completed because the specified virtual disk is not found.
STOR028.Resolution: Provide a valid virtual disk FQDD (Fully Qualified Device Descriptor) and retry the operation..

PST0084.Description: System started the Automated Task application.

UEFI0262.Description: An issue is observed initializing DDR (double data rate) on the memory riser identified in the message. A possible cause is the DIMM modules are incorrectly seated in the slots.
UEFI0262.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM modules and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory modules identified in the message.
UEFI0262.Message: Unable to initialize DIMM modules on memory riser %1 because of a DDR training error.

PWR8516.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action requested.
PWR8516.Resolution: Check the tracelog for more information. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
PWR8516.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action requested..

SWC8621.Description: The Chassis Management Controller (CMC) is unable to process inventory data from the server slot identified in the message. This can happen if there is no free temporary storage in CMC.
SWC8621.Resolution: Restart the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). To restart the CMC, start an SSH session to the CMC and enter the command "racadm racreset". Wait for the CMC to finish restarting and check if the inventory data is collected. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
SWC8621.Message: The Chassis Management Controller is unable to process inventory data from the server in slot %1.

STOR053.Description: The system could not obtain a controller key from the Dell Key Management Server.
STOR053.Resolution: For more information about obtaining a key, see Dell Key Manager or Lifecycle Controller Remote Services Guide available at dell.com/support/manuals.
STOR053.Message: The controller key is not present. The key must be retrieved from the Dell Key Management Server.

BAR003.Description: The Backup partition is being created for storing the backup file.

UEFI0069.Description: A CMOS checksum error has occurred resulting in an invalid BIOS configuration. BIOS configuration is reset to default settings.
UEFI0069.Resolution: Go to the System Setup and configure the desired settings. Save and exit to apply the settings.
UEFI0069.Message: A CMOS checksum error has occurred. CMOS is reinitialized.

SWC8551.Description: The boot identity profile cannot be applied because the profile identified in the message is in use by the server in the slot identified in the message.
SWC8551.Resolution: Clear the boot identity of server identified in the message to apply another profile. Using the CMC GUI, navigate to the Boot Identity page, Boot Identities are cleared using "Clear Identity" option provided "Boot Identity Profiles" tab.
SWC8551.Message: Unable to apply the boot identity profile because the profile %1 is already in use by the server in slot %2.

PWR2402.Description: The iDRAC controller cannot communicate with the power management firmware due to an problem with the interface to the power management engine or with the power management engine itself. The system may operate in a performance degraded state.
PWR2402.Resolution: Check the Lifecycle Controller Log (LC Log) and make sure that there are no subsequent log entries indicating that Communication with power management firmware has been restored. If this log entry is not present then do one of the following: 1) Disconnect system input power, wait one minute, reconnect system input power. 2) Re-flash system BIOS. 3) Upgrade system BIOS to the latest revision.
PWR2402.Message: iDRAC is unable to communicate with power management firmware.

PWR8602.Description: The power buttons for all multinode sleds in the chassis are enabled. The operation to enable the power button is only applicable to the multinode sleds available, and does not affect other servers in the chassis.
PWR8602.Resolution: To disable the chassis power button use the CMC RACADM command line interface (CLI) or CMC Web interface. At the CLI, enter "racadm config -g cfgChassisPower -o cfgChassisSledPowerButtonEnable 0". Using the Web interface, click Server Overview > Power > Control. Select the "Disable power button for all multinode sleds in the chassis" check box.
PWR8602.Message: The multinode sled power button is enabled.

UEFI0106.Description: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on the memory slot identified in the message.
UEFI0106.Resolution: Remove input power to the system, reseat the DIMM module and restart the system. If the correctable error persists, then replace the faulty memory module identified in the message.
UEFI0106.Message: One or more memory correctable training errors have occurred on memory slot: %1

RFL2007.Message: Internal Dual SD Module %1 is writable.

PR17.Description: Some of the configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to the current device. This may be due to firmware version or other differences in the part.
PR17.Resolution: Check the device's configuration and ensure that the new configuration is correct for the system.
PR17.Message: Some of the configuration values stored for the previous device could not be applied to device: %1

PWR8522.Description: The chassis power cycle operation was initiated.

STOR021.Description: Operation cannot be completed because a controller key is not present.
STOR021.Resolution: Set an appropriate controller key and retry the operation.
STOR021.Message: The controller key is not present.

SYS189.Description: There is no cached copy of OS and Application data in the iDRAC flash storage.
SYS189.Resolution: Collect the OS and Application Data either manually or automatically using the iDRAC Services Module (ISM) tools and then retry the operation.
SYS189.Message: Cached OS and Application Data is not available in the iDRAC.

SYS055.Description: The configuration specified in the system configuration XML file was applied, but there were some errors. The Lifecycle Controller Log contains the details of the component configurations that did not complete successfully.
SYS055.Resolution: Review the Lifecycle Controller Log and identify the configuration changes that did not complete successfully. Retry those changes in a separate operation.
SYS055.Message: Import of system configuration XML file operation completed with errors.

SEC0702.Description: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is enabled.
SEC0702.Message: The Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS) mode is enabled.

SYS065.Description: An internal error occurred opening the input configuration XML file. An iDRAC reset is required.
SYS065.Resolution: Reset iDRAC and retry the operation.
SYS065.Message: Input file for import configuration operation cannot be found or opened.

PST0080.Description: System is at the F1/F2 prompt because the system BIOS detected an issue other than "No bootable devices".
PST0080.Resolution: Check post display screen for details. Press F1 to continue boot, or press F2 to go to setup.
PST0080.Message: An issue was detected. System at boot F1/F2 prompt. Requires entry to continue.

OSE0001.Description: The system halted due to an exception while the operating system was running. This is a kernel panic or bug check event.
OSE0001.Resolution: Review operating system logs and system video for additional information

SWC0044.Description: Lifecycle Controller is unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation. For more information, see the Lifecycle Log.
SWC0044.Resolution: Retry the operation. If the problem persists, do the following: 1) Turn off the system and disconnect the power cord. 2) Wait five seconds. 3) Reconnect the power cord, turn on the system, and retry the operation.
SWC0044.Message: Unable to retrieve the status of the Import Server Profile operation.

RAC0906.Description: Unable to perform the requested operation.
RAC0906.Resolution: Try again later. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method.

OSD54.Description: vFlash allows only 16 partitions to be created
OSD54.Resolution: Make sure that there are less than 16 partitions before creating another partition on vFlash.

PSU0005.Description: The operating requirements for the power supply may be found in product documentation or on the power supply itself.
PSU0005.Resolution: Verify the input power is within the operating requirements for the power supply.
PSU0005.Message: The power input for power supply %1 is outside of the allowable range, but it is attached to the system.

SUP0504.Description: The catalog file in the update repository is not digitally signed.
SUP0504.Resolution: Use a repository that has the catalog file from a trusted source and retry the operation. If the catalog is from a trusted source, click OK to proceed without digital signature verification.
SUP0504.Message: Unable to authenticate the catalog file in the update repository.

LC040.Description: Unable to allocate required memory to perform the operation.
LC040.Resolution: Power cycle system and retry the operation. If the problem persists, reapply firmware packages for Lifecycle Controller and iDRAC.

RAC0766.Description: The USB NIC IP address identified in the message cannot be assigned to the OSBMC device because only Link Local IP address can be allowed.
RAC0766.Resolution: Enter appropriate Link Local IP address, and then retry the operation. For information about supported IP addresses, refer to the iDRAC Users Guide available at the support site.
RAC0766.Message: Unable to assign USB NIC IP address %1 to the OSBMC device because only Link Local IP address can be allowed.

LNK0004.Description: Unable to connect to FTP server due to a network error.
LNK0004.Resolution: Check the network connection, network configuration settings, and retry. If the problem persists, restart the FTP server.
LNK0004.Message: Unable to connect to FTP server.

PDR41.Description: The clear command did not complete on the physical disk. This means that some data was not cleared and may be recoverable.
PDR41.Message: The clear operation on %1 was cancelled.

HWC8508.Description: A device causing an issue in the I/O panel USB port is removed.
HWC8508.Message: A device causing an issue in the I/O panel USB port is removed.

UEFI0055.Description: The debranding process cannot be completed because of the reasons identified on the computer screen.
UEFI0055.Resolution: Check the screen display for details of the failure. Retry the debrand process again, or update the system BIOS and then retry.
UEFI0055.Message: Unable to complete the debranding operation because of the issue(s) displayed earlier.

SWC0071.Description: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully exported to the network share folder.
SWC0071.Message: The SupportAssist collection has been successfully exported to the network share folder.

SYS168.Description: The requested System Erase job cannot complete because there was another job or System Services task already in progress.
SYS168.Resolution: Wait for the job or System Services task in progress to complete before initiating a System Erase job.
SYS168.Message: Unable to complete the System Erase job because another operation is in progress.

PSU0908.Description: The power supply is installed correctly but an input source is not connected or is not functional.
PSU0908.Resolution: Verify the input source is attached to the power supply. Verify the input power is within the operating requirements for the power supply.

SYS020.Description: The value provided for the required attribute is invalid.
SYS020.Resolution: The value specified is not valid. Refer to the Lifecycle Controller Remote Services documentation for more information.

SUP0532.Description: The repository contains corrupt Update Packages.
SUP0532.Resolution: Enter another repository location that contains the desired Update Packages and retry the operation.
SUP0532.Message: The repository contains corrupt Update Packages.

PSU0006.Description: The power supply identified in the message must be supported by the platform. Generally, multiple power supplies in the server should have the same feature set and power rating.
PSU0006.Resolution: Review server product documentation for supported power supplies and power supply configurations.

RAC1123.Description: Fibre Channel (FC) objects are not available if Fibre Channel devices are not installed in the server, or if some iDRAC services are busy.
RAC1123.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Power off and remove AC or DC power from the server. 2) Make sure the Fibre Channel devices are correctly installed in the server. 3) Restart the server to allow the Collect System Inventory On Restart (CSIOR) feature to update the server inventory. 4) Retry the operation. If the issue persists, contact your service provider.
RAC1123.Message: Unable to perform the operation because Fibre Channel (FC) attributes are not available in the current server configuration.

RAC0911.Resolution: Try again later. If the problem persists, contact technical support. Refer to your product documentation to choose the contact method that is convenient for you.
RAC0911.Message: Data about version details is unavailable.

SWC8504.Description: The Profile identified in the message was renamed and the description for the Profile was edited.
SWC8504.Message: %1 Profile renamed to %2 and description edited.

UEFI0154.Description: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.
UEFI0154.Resolution: If the absence of license is expected, no action is necessary. Otherwise do one of the following: 1) Reload the license. 2) Remove input power from the system, wait for 30 seconds, and re-apply input power. Turn on the system. 3) Update the iDRAC firmware.
UEFI0154.Message: Unable to find the Dell Processor Acceleration Technology (DPAT) Enterprise license after three consecutive boots. The Dell Controlled Turbo BIOS setup configuration is being reverted to default because of the absent license.

PCI5005.Description: Chassis Management Controller (CMC) detected an issue in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in the slot identified in the message.
PCI5005.Resolution: Make sure that: 1) The PCIe adapter used is supported by the Chassis Management Controller (CMC). For a list of supported adapters, contact your service provider. 2) The adapter is not damaged. 3) The adapter is properly inserted in the slot.
PCI5005.Message: An auxiliary power fault issue is detected in the PCIe adapter that was turned on in PCIe slot%1.

PWR8519.Description: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned off.
PWR8519.Message: Unable to perform the chassis power action because the chassis is already turned off.

UEFI0120.Description: Both of the Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card media are missing, or not responding.
UEFI0120.Resolution: Make sure both the SD card media are properly installed and retry the system start up. If the issue persists, replace the SD card media.
UEFI0120.Message: Both of the Internal Dual Secure Digital Module (IDSDM) SD card media are missing, or not responding.

UEFI0215.Description: An error occurred during DDR memory initialization during the Basic Write Level Training phase.
UEFI0215.Resolution: Do the following: 1) Remove input power to the system, 2) Reseat the DIMM module and 3) Restart the system. If the issue persists, then replace the faulty memory module(s) identified in the message.
UEFI0215.Message: An error occurred during DDR memory channel initialization on memory slots: %1.

PCI2001.Message: The component at bus %1 device %2 function %3 recovered from a fatal IO error.

PR7.Description: The specified device was added to the system.

POW005.Description: Host failed to power up because CMC MPCM mode is enabled. This messages has been replaced by Message ID PWR2255
POW005.Resolution: Disable MPCM mode to power up.
POW005.Message: Power on permission error, CMC is in MPCM mode.

PWR8562.Description: Unable to power on the server before the power on timer has expired. This happens if the server did not show power on status change within 30 seconds after the power on operation was initiated. This issue may also occur when iDRAC is rebooting.
PWR8562.Resolution: The Server may need more time to power on. Wait for ten seconds and check the power status. If the server was not powered on, retry the operation. If the issue persists, remove and reinsert the server, wait for the iDRAC to complete startup, and retry the operation.
PWR8562.Message: Unable to power on the server %1 before power on timer expired.

Description: This registry defines the iDRAC messages for Redfish
Name: iDRAC Message Registry
